Vocabulary last modified: 2020-07-01

subtitle: Rock types and non-rock observations used to describe geological sites and samples.

Namespace: http://linked.data.gov.au/def/lithotype

Concepts

1.1 Non Rock Observation

  • Procedural observations that indicate missing, processed, incorrect, or contaminated sample
  • Concept URI token: non-rock-observation

1.1.1 Coked coal

  • Child of: non-rock-observation

  • Coke is a grey, hard, and porous fuel with a high carbon content and few impurities, made by heating coal in the absence of air

  • Concept URI token: coked-coal

1.1.2 Composite Coal Sample

  • Child of: non-rock-observation

  • A collection of mulitple samples, combined to form a representative sample

  • Concept URI token: composite-coal-sample

1.1.3 Contamination

  • Child of: non-rock-observation

  • Foreign material introduced to a sample or observation

  • Concept URI token: contamination

1.1.4 Core Loss

  • Child of: non-rock-observation

  • An unidentifiable interval in core due to loss of rock during the coring and retrieval process

  • Concept URI token: core-loss

1.1.5 Fill

  • Child of: non-rock-observation

  • Disturbed rock that has settled in place of the interval intended to be sampled, thereby rendering correct identification impossible

  • Alternate labels: Back Fill, Fill / Spoil, Land Fill, Spoil,

  • Concept URI token: fill

1.1.6 Lost Rock

  • Child of: non-rock-observation

  • Rock that has been lost in the process of obtaining rock sample before identification can be performed

  • Concept URI token: lost-rock

1.1.7 Mine Dump

  • Child of: non-rock-observation

  • Material deliberately discarded during mining operations

  • Alternate labels: Dump, Waste Dump,

  • Concept URI token: mine-dump

1.1.8 Mine Workings

  • Child of: non-rock-observation

  • Material disturbed during the operation of a mine

  • Concept URI token: mine-workings

1.1.9 Not Logged

  • Child of: non-rock-observation

  • A sample of rock collected but not logged

  • Concept URI token: not-logged

1.1.10 Stope

  • Child of: non-rock-observation

  • Material from an excavation in a mine working or quarry in the form of a step or notch.

  • Concept URI token: stope

1.1.11 Vein

  • Child of: non-rock-observation

  • A lithological observation of a distinct sheetlike body of crystallised minerals within a rock.

  • Concept URI token: vein

1.1.12 Void

  • Child of: non-rock-observation

  • A natural void in the rock. E.g. Vugs, Geode, Carbonate dissolution

  • Concept URI token: void

1.2 Rock

  • A rock is a naturally-occurring solid aggregate of one or more minerals, mineraloids or, in some cases, organic material. Sediments are the unconsolidated equivalent of these. Other related materials, including some man-made materials, are included within this categorisation, along with the major classifications for meteorites.

  • Alternate labels: Basement Undifferentiated, Basement, Unidentified rock, Unidentified, Unknown rock, Unknown,

  • Concept URI token: rock

1.2.1 Artificial material

  • Child of: rock

  • Materials that have been created by man, or natural materials altered in composition or structure by man.

  • Alternate labels: Anthropogenic material

  • Concept URI token: artificial-material

1.2.1.1 Asphalt (processed)

  • Child of: artificial-material

  • A sticky, black and highly viscous liquid or semi-solid form of petroleum, found in natural geological deposits, ore produced by distillation of petroleum, coal, etc.

  • Concept URI token: asphalt-processed

1.2.1.1.1 Tar (processed)

  • Child of: asphalt-processed

  • A carbon-rich bitumen, produced from coal, wood, petroleum, or peat.

  • Concept URI token: tar-processed

1.2.1.2 Bonded aggregate

  • Child of: artificial-material

  • A composite material of rock and/or sand particles bonded by a cement, usually lime cement or bitumen.

  • Concept URI token: bonded-aggregate

1.2.1.2.1 Portland cement concrete

  • Child of: bonded-aggregate

  • A man-made, intimate mixture of an aggregate (sand and gravel), water, and portland cement, which will harden to a rocklike mass.

  • Concept URI token: portland-cement-concrete

1.2.1.2.2 Tarmac

  • Child of: bonded-aggregate

  • A form of concrete with rock particles bonded by bitumen rather than a lime cement.

  • Concept URI token: tarmac

1.2.1.3 Cement

  • Child of: artificial-material

  • A binder, a substance used for construction that sets, hardens, and adheres to other materials to bind them together.

  • Concept URI token: cement

1.2.1.4 Ceramics

  • Child of: artificial-material

  • Inorganic nonmetallic solid materials with high melting temperatures, high hardness and poor conductivity.

  • Alternate labels: Ceramic (man-made)

  • Concept URI token: ceramic-man-made

1.2.1.4.1 Clay brick

  • Child of: ceramic-man-made

  • Oblong blocks of ceramic formed by firing illite-rich clays, used for building.

  • Concept URI token: clay-brick

1.2.1.4.2 Ferrite (ceramic)

  • Child of: ceramic-man-made

  • A synthetic ceramic compound consisting of a mixed oxide of iron and one or more other metals (such as barium, manganese, nickel, and zinc) which has ferrimagnetic properties and is used in high-frequency electrical components such as aerials.

  • Concept URI token: ferrite-ceramic

1.2.1.5 Glass (man-made)

  • Child of: artificial-material

  • A non-crystalline amorphous solid, most usually silicate glass derived from silicate-sand.

  • Concept URI token: glass-man-made

1.2.1.6 Metal

  • Child of: artificial-material

  • Anthropogenic metal (alloy) and metal items.

  • Concept URI token: metal

1.2.1.6.1 Weathered metal

  • Child of: metal

  • This includes anthropogenic metal that has been altered by seawater and all corrosion products formed on the metal.

  • Concept URI token: weathered-metal

1.2.1.7 Plastic

  • Child of: artificial-material

  • Synthetic or semi-synthetic organic compounds, usually organic polymers of high molecular mass.

  • Concept URI token: plastic

1.2.1.8 Slag

  • Child of: artificial-material

  • Partially or completely melted lithic material usually as a by- product of smelting or glass creation.

  • Concept URI token: slag

1.2.1.8.1 Bodeachat

  • Child of: slag

  • A variety of Slag. German name for bluish to greenish slag from the iron smelters and glas smelters in the area of the upper Bode river, especially near Treseburg. NOT an agate (German: achat).

  • Concept URI token: bodeachat

1.2.1.8.2 ferrolite

  • Child of: slag

  • Black iron slag, said to be satisfactory for fashioning into gemstones.

  • Concept URI token: ferrolite

1.2.1.8.3 Glass slag

  • Child of: slag

  • Slag from glass making.

  • Concept URI token: glass-slag

1.2.1.8.4 Iron slag

  • Child of: slag

  • Slag from iron ore smelting.

  • Concept URI token: iron-slag

1.2.1.8.5 Non-ferrous metallic slag

  • Child of: slag

  • Slag from non-ferrous metal smelting.

  • Concept URI token: non-ferrous-metallic-slag

1.2.1.8.5.1 Weathered non-ferrous metallic slag

  • Child of: non-ferrous-metallic-slag

  • This includes non-ferrous metallic slags that have been altered by seawater.

  • Concept URI token: weathered-non-ferrous-metallic-slag

1.2.1.8.6 Sieberachat

  • Child of: slag

  • A German name for bluish slag from the Steinrenner Hutte (smelter) that smelted the iron ores from the Eisensteinberg. Named for the Sieber river (Sieber valley), Harz, Germany.Bodeachat is a similar bluish slag. NOT an agate (German: achat).

  • Concept URI token: sieberachat

1.2.2 Igneous rock

  • Child of: rock

  • Rocks that generally have solidified from magmas, but may include some formed from related cumulate, deuteric, metasomatic or metamorphic processes. Rock formed by the solidification of molten material that originated within the earth.

  • Alternate labels: Igneous Rock, undifferentiated, Unclassified igneous rock, unclassified igneous unit,

  • Concept URI token: igneous-rock

1.2.2.1 Anthraphyre

  • Child of: igneous-rock

  • An obsolete term proposed for igneous rocks intruding anthracite- rich formations.

  • Concept URI token: anthraphyre

1.2.2.2 Aphanide

  • Child of: igneous-rock

  • An obsolete field term for non-porphyritic rocks which contain a megascopically indeterminable component.

  • Concept URI token: aphanide

1.2.2.3 Cantalite

  • Child of: igneous-rock

  • An obsolete term used in several ways. It was originally defined as an ex- tremely silica-rich rock but later redefined for two compositions of pitchstone and a tephritic trachyte.

  • Concept URI token: cantalite

1.2.2.4 Diatectite

  • Child of: igneous-rock

  • A term for a rock formed by diatexis, i.e. from a pre-existing rock that has undergone complete or almost complete melting.

  • Concept URI token: diatectite

1.2.2.5 Dissogenite

  • Child of: igneous-rock

  • A term for igneous rocks containing two distinct sets of minerals, as can be created by assimilation.

  • Concept URI token: dissogenite

1.2.2.6 Eutectite

  • Child of: igneous-rock

  • An igneous rock formed by the crystallisation of residual lquids, according to Tomkeiff (1983).

  • Concept URI token: eutectite

1.2.2.7 Exotic crystalline igneous rock

  • Child of: igneous-rock

  • Igneous rocks that mostly do not fit into the standard QAPF, TAS and ultramafic diagrams. Commonly highly alkaline.

  • Concept URI token: exotic-crystalline-igneous-rock

1.2.2.7.1 Carbonatite

  • Child of: exotic-crystalline-igneous-rock

  • An igneous rock containing more than 50% modal primary carbonate.A carbonate rock of apparent magmatic origin, generally associated with kimberlites and alkalic rocks. Carbonatites have been variously explained as derived from magmatic melt, solid flow, hydrothermal solution, and gaseous transfer.

  • Concept URI token: carbonatite

1.2.2.7.1.1 Calcite-carbonatite

  • Child of: carbonatite

  • A carbonatite where more than 90% of the carbonate is calcite.

  • Alternate labels: Calciocarbonatite, Calcitite,

  • Concept URI token: calcite-carbonatite

1.2.2.7.1.1.1 Alvikite

  • Child of: calcite-carbonatite

  • A medium- to fine-grained calcium-carbonatite.

  • Concept URI token: alvikite

1.2.2.7.1.1.2 Calciocarbonatite lapillistone

  • Child of: calcite-carbonatite lapillistone

  • A lapillistone where the lapilli are calcium-carbonatite, cemented by calcite.

  • Concept URI token: calciocarbonatite-lapillistone

1.2.2.7.1.1.3 Sovite

  • Child of: calcite-carbonatite

  • A coarse-grained calcite-carbonatite.

  • Concept URI token: sovite

1.2.2.7.1.2 Ferrocarbonatite

  • Child of: carbonatite

  • A carbonatite where the main carbonate mineral is ferroan dolomite, ankerite or siderite, or when defined chemically as per the diagram below.

  • Concept URI token: ferrocarbonatite

1.2.2.7.1.2.1 Siderite carbonatite

  • Child of: ferrocarbonatite

  • A ferrocarbonatite where siderite is the primary carbonate.

  • Concept URI token: siderite-carbonatite

1.2.2.7.1.3 Magnesiocarbonatite

  • Child of: carbonatite

  • A carbonatite defined on basis of chemical composition where the MgO/CaO/(FeO+Fe2O3+MnO) ratio falls into the area as defined.

  • Concept URI token: magnesiocarbonatite

1.2.2.7.1.3.1 Dolomite-carbonatite

  • Child of: magnesiocarbonatite

  • A carbonatite where more than 90% of the carbonate is dolomite.

  • Concept URI token: dolomite-carbonatite

1.2.2.7.1.4 Natrocarbonatite

  • Child of: carbonatite

  • A carbonatite composed essentailly of sodium +/-potassium +/-calcium carbonate minerals. A lava known from only one locality currently.

  • Concept URI token: natrocarbonatite

1.2.2.7.1.5 Rodberg

  • Child of: carbonatite

  • An altered carbonatite composed of hematite-stained granular calcite, dolomite and sometimes ankerite.

  • Concept URI token: rodberg

1.2.2.7.1.6 Silicocarbonatite

  • Child of: carbonatite

  • A carbonatite with more than 20% silica.

  • Concept URI token: silicocarbonatite

1.2.2.7.2 Exotic alkaline rock

  • Child of: exotic-crystalline-igneous-rock

  • Kimberlite, lamproite, or lamprophyre. Generally are potassic, mafic or ultramafic rocks. Olivine (commonly serpentinized in kimberlite), and phlogopite are significant constituents.

  • Concept URI token: exotic-alkaline-rock

1.2.2.7.2.1 Kimberlite

  • Child of: exotic-alkaline-rock

  • A megacryst-rich ultramafic rock, rich in olivine, plus phlogopite, carbonate, pyrope, pyroxenes, and oxides. It occurs in vertical pipes, dikes, and sills. It is the principal primary host for diamonds, but only a small percentage of the known kimberlite occurrences are diamondiferous. A polymict ultramafic-rich volcanic breccia, dominated by olivine, phlogopite, and diopside +/- garnet, commonly highly serpentinized, porphyritic, and brecciated, which occurs in vertical pipes, dikes, and sills.

  • Alternate labels: Kimberlitic-rock, Ultramafic hypabyssal,

  • Concept URI token: kimberlite

1.2.2.7.2.1.1 Group-1-kimberlite

  • Child of: kimberlite

  • True kimberlite, previously termed basaltic kimberite.

  • Concept URI token: group-1-kimberlite

1.2.2.7.2.2 Lamproite

  • Child of: exotic-alkaline-rock ultrapotassic-rock

  • A poorly defined group of potassic to ultramafic, dark-colored hypabyssal or extrusive, volcanic to pyroclastic rocks, usually in dykes and pipes. A group name for such rocks rich in potassium and magnesium; also, any rock in that group, such as madupite, orendite, fitzroyite, verite, cedricite, or wyomingite.

  • Concept URI token: lamproite

1.2.2.7.2.2.1 Diopside-leucite lamproite

  • Child of: lamproite

  • Diopside-leucite bearing lamproite

  • Concept URI token: diopside-leucite-lamproite

1.2.2.7.2.2.2 Diopside-leucite-phlogopite lamproite

  • Child of: lamproite

  • Diopside-leucite-phlogopite bearing lamproite

  • Concept URI token: diopside-leucite-phlogopite-lamproite

1.2.2.7.2.2.3 Diopside-leucite-richterite-madupitic lamproite

  • Child of: lamproite

  • DIopside-leucite-richterite-phlogopite bearing lamproite

  • Concept URI token: diopside-leucite-richterite-madupitic-lamproite

1.2.2.7.2.2.4 Diopside-madupitic lamproite

  • Child of: lamproite

  • Diopside-phlogopite bearing lamproite

  • Concept URI token: diopside-madupitic-lamproite

1.2.2.7.2.2.5 Diopside-sanidine-phlogopite lamproite

  • Child of: lamproite

  • Diopside-sanidine-phlogopite bearing lamproite

  • Concept URI token: diopside-sanidine-phlogopite-lamproite

1.2.2.7.2.2.6 Enstatite-sanidine-phlogopite lamproite

  • Child of: lamproite

  • Enstatite-sanidine-phlogopite bearing lamproite

  • Concept URI token: enstatite-sanidine-phlogopite-lamproite

1.2.2.7.2.2.7 Hyalo-enstatite-phlogopite lamproite

  • Child of: lamproite

  • A glassy enstatite-phlogopite lamproite

  • Concept URI token: hyalo-enstatite-phlogopite-lamproite

1.2.2.7.2.2.8 Hyalo-olivine-diopside-phlogopite lamproite

  • Child of: lamproite

  • Hyalo-olivine-diopside-phlogopite bearing lamproite

  • Concept URI token: hyalo-olivine-diopside-phlogopite-lamproite

  • Leucite-richterite bearing lamproite

1.2.2.7.2.2.11 Olivine-diopside-richterite-madupitic lamproite

  • Child of: lamproite

  • Concept URI token: olivine-diopside-richterite-madupitic-lamproite

1.2.2.7.2.2.12 Olivine lamproite

  • Child of: lamproite

  • A rock type corresponding to micaceous or lamprophyric kimberites, or an olivine-rich lamproite.

  • Concept URI token: olivine-lamproite

1.2.2.7.2.3 Lamprophyre

  • Child of: exotic-alkaline-rock ultrapotassic-rock

  • A group of hypabyssal igneous rocks characterised by abundant primary hydrous silicates in phenocrysts and/ or groundmass, lacking felsic phenocrysts, usually occurring in dykes.A group of dark- colored, porphyritic, hypabyssal igneous rocks characterized by panidiomorphic texture, a high percentage of mafic minerals (esp. biotite, hornblende, and pyroxene), which form the phenocrysts, and a fine-grained groundmass with the same mafic minerals in addition to feldspars and/or feldspathoids; also, any rock in that group.

  • Concept URI token: lamprophyre

1.2.2.7.2.3.1 Aillikite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • An ultramafic carbonate-rich lamprophyre consisting of various phenocrysts including olivine, diopsidic pyroxene, amphiboles and phlogopite in a matrix of similar minerals with at least partly primary carbonate and minor perovskite but no melilite.

  • Concept URI token: aillikite

1.2.2.7.2.3.2 Antsohite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A local name for a lamprophyric dyke rock consisting of phenocrysts of biotite in a groundmass of biotite, hornblende and interstitial quartz.

  • Concept URI token: antsohite

1.2.2.7.2.3.3 Bermudite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A local name for a lamprophyre consisting of biotite and minor titanian augite in a groundmass of analcime (probably after nepheline). Possibly equivalent in composition to ouachitite.

  • Concept URI token: bermudite

1.2.2.7.2.3.4 Camptonite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A lamprophyre with plagioclase>K-feldspar and feldspars > feldspathoids; similar in composition to nepheline diorite, being composed essentially of plagioclase (usually labradorite) and brown hornblende.

  • Concept URI token: camptonite

1.2.2.7.2.3.5 Analcime camptonite

  • Child of: camptonite

  • A camptonite containing analcime.

  • Concept URI token: analcime-camptonite

1.2.2.7.2.3.6 Cascadite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A local name for a sodic melanocratic lamprophyre having phenocrysts of biotite, olivine and augite in a matrix essentially of alkali feldspar with patches of what could have been leucite.

  • Concept URI token: cascadite

1.2.2.7.2.3.7 Cocite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A melanocratic leucite-rich lamprophyre largely composed of clinopyroxene and subordinate olivine in a matrix of alkali feldspar, leucite and clinopyroxene with minor biotite. Similar to tjosite but with leucite instead of nepheline.

  • Concept URI token: cocite

1.2.2.7.2.3.8 Cuselite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A local name for an altered lamprophyric rock containing phenocrysts of plagioclase and uralitized diopside in a granular groundmass of plagioclase, orthoclase, chloritized biotite, hornblende, diopside and interstitial quartz.

  • Concept URI token: cuselite

1.2.2.7.2.3.9 Damkjernite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A melanocratic variety of nepheline lamprophyre. A hypabyssal rock containing phenocrysts of biotite and titanian augite in a groundmass of the same minerals with some nepheline, calcite and k-felspar, perovskite, and magnetite. Also spelled: damtjernite.

  • Concept URI token: damkjernite

1.2.2.7.2.3.10 Ehrwaldite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A lamprophyre of basanitic composition. Composed of titanian augite, biotite, serpentinised olivine and glass.

  • Concept URI token: ehrwaldite

1.2.2.7.2.3.11 Epibasite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • An obsolete term for non-porphyritic lamprophyres, which is somewhat of a contradiction of terms.

  • Concept URI token: epibasite

1.2.2.7.2.3.12 Eustratite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A name for a lamprophyric dyke rock from Haghios Eustratios, (now Ayios Evstratios Island), Greece with rare phenocrysts of olivine, corroded hornblende and occasional augite in a groundmass of augite, titanomagnetite, feldspar and glass.

  • Concept URI token: eustratite

1.2.2.7.2.3.13 Farrisite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A melonocratic melilite lamprophyre containing augite, barkevikite, biotite and olivine, but no feldspar.

  • Concept URI token: farrisite

1.2.2.7.2.3.14 Kersantite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A lamprophyre with plagioclase > K-feldspar and biotite as the dominant mafic mineral; no feldspathoid. A lamprophyre containing biotite and plagioclase (usually oligoclase or andesine), with or without clinopyroxene and olivine.

  • Concept URI token: kersantite

1.2.2.7.2.3.15 Aschaffite

  • Child of: kersantite

  • A type of kersantite (a lamprophyre) with abundant biotite in a matrix of plagioclase and quartz.

  • Concept URI token: aschaffite

1.2.2.7.2.3.16 Minette

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A lampropyre containing biotite and K-feldspar being the dominant felsic mineral.

  • Concept URI token: minette

1.2.2.7.2.3.17 Baltorite

  • Child of: minette vogesite

  • A local comprehensive term for potassic vogesites and potassic minettes.

  • Concept URI token: baltorite

1.2.2.7.2.3.18 Raabsite

  • Child of: minette

  • A type of minette consisting of microcline, sodic amphibole, biotite and olivine.

  • Concept URI token: raabsite

1.2.2.7.2.3.19 Sizunite

  • Child of: minette

  • A local term for a variety of minette characterized by high K2O (> 10%) and P2O5 (2.5%) and consisting of microcline, biotite, apatite and opaques.

  • Concept URI token: sizunite

1.2.2.7.2.3.20 Monchiquite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A lampropyre with feldspathoid and no feldspars.A lamprophyre containing phenocrysts of olivine, clinopyroxene, and typically biotite or amphibole (barkevikite), in a groundmass of glass or analcime, often highly altered. Nepheline or leucite may be present.

  • Concept URI token: monchiquite

1.2.2.7.2.3.21 Sannaite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A lampropyre with plagioclase>K-feldspar and feldspars > feldspathoid

  • Concept URI token: sannaite

1.2.2.7.2.3.22 Spessartite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A lampropyre with plagioclase>K-feldspar and hornblende the dominant mafic mineral; no feldspathoid.

  • Alternate labels: Spessartite rock, Spessartite-rock,

  • Concept URI token: spessartite

1.2.2.7.2.3.23 Camptospessartite

  • Child of: spessartite

  • A local term used for a basic spessartite containing titanian augite.

  • Concept URI token: camptospessartite

1.2.2.7.2.3.24 Vogesite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A lampropyre with plagioclase>K-feldspar and feldspars > feldspathoid

  • Concept URI token: vogesite

1.2.2.7.2.3.25 Augite vogesite

  • Child of: vogesite

  • A vogesite containing augite.

  • Concept URI token: augite-vogesite

1.2.2.7.2.3.26 Baltorite

  • Child of: minette vogesite

  • A local comprehensive term for potassic vogesites and potassic minettes.

  • Concept URI token: baltorite

1.2.2.7.2.3.27 Camptovogesite

  • Child of: vogesite

  • A basic variety of vogesite containing basaltic hornblende.

  • Concept URI token: camptovogesite

1.2.2.7.3 Kalsilitic and melilitic rock

  • Child of: exotic-crystalline-igneous-rock

  • Igneous rock containing greater than 10 percent melilite or kalsilite. Typically undersaturated, ultrapotassic (kalsilitic rocks) or calcium-rich (melilitic rocks) mafic or ultramafic rocks.

  • Concept URI token: kalsilitic-and-melilitic-rock

1.2.2.7.3.1 Kalsilitic-rock

  • Child of: kalsilitic-and-melilitic-rock

  • A rock containing at least 10% kalsilite.

  • Concept URI token: kalsilitic-rock

1.2.2.7.3.1.1 Kalmafite

  • Child of: kalsilitic-rock

  • A rock consisting of a mixture of kalsilite and mafic minerals.

  • Concept URI token: kalmafite

1.2.2.7.3.1.2 Kalsilite-biotite pyroxenite

  • Child of: kalsilitic-rock pyroxenite

  • A plutonic kalsilite-bearing pyroxenite from the Aldan and North Baikal petrological provinces of Russia.

  • Concept URI token: kalsilite-biotite-pyroxenite

1.2.2.7.3.1.3 Kalsilite-leucite-olivine melilitite

  • Child of: kalsilitic-rock olivine-melilitite

  • Concept URI token: kalsilite-leucite-olivine-melilitite

1.2.2.7.3.1.4 Kalsilite-phlogopite melilitite

  • A melilitite containing kalsilite and phlogopite.

  • Concept URI token: kalsilite-phlogopite-melilitite

1.2.2.7.3.1.5 Kalsilite-phlogopite-olivine-leucite melilitite

  • Child of: kalsilitic-rock olivine-melilitite

  • A melilitite containing kalsilite, phlogopite, leucite and olivine.

  • Concept URI token: kalsilite-phlogopite-olivine-leucite-melilitite

1.2.2.7.3.1.6 Kalsilite syenite

  • Child of: kalsilitic-rock syenite

  • A kalsilite-bearing plutonic rock first recorded from the Aldan and North Baikal petrological provinces of Russia.

  • Alternate labels: Synnyrite

  • Concept URI token: kalsilite-syenite

1.2.2.7.3.1.7 Kalsilitite

  • Child of: kalsilitic-rock

  • A fine-grained rock containing at least 10% kalsilite but no leucite or melilite.

  • Concept URI token: kalsilitite

1.2.2.7.3.1.8 Olivine-pyroxene kalsilitite

1.2.2.7.3.2 Melilite-bearing rock

  • Child of: kalsilitic-and-melilitic-rock

  • A rock containing more than 10% modal melilite and melilite > foids.

  • Concept URI token: melilite-bearing-rock

1.2.2.7.3.2.4 Melilitite

  • Child of: fine-grained-melititic-rock

  • A fine-grained melilitic rock containing < 10% olivine.A generally olivine-free extrusive rock composed of melilite with clinopyroxene (or other mafic minerals) usually comprising more than 90% of the rock, with minor amounts of feldspathoids and sometimes plagioclase.

  • Concept URI token: melilitite

1.2.2.7.3.2.7 Olivine-melilitite

  • Alternate labels: Melilite-bearing ultramafic volcanic, Olivine melilitite,

  • Concept URI token: olivine-melilitite

1.2.2.7.3.2.8 Kalsilite-leucite-olivine melilitite

1.2.2.7.3.2.9 Kalsilite-phlogopite-olivine-leucite melilitite

  • Child of: kalsilitic-rock olivine-melilitite

  • A melilitite containing kalsilite, phlogopite, leucite and olivine.

  • Concept URI token: kalsilite-phlogopite-olivine-leucite-melilitite

1.2.2.7.3.2.10 Lamprophyric-pyroxene-calcite-biotite olivine-melilitite

  • Child of: olivine-melilitite

  • A anusual and difficult rock to categorise; usually considered an intrusive, ultrapotassic rock, or an alkaline ultramafic igneous rock containing phlogopite-biotite, melilite, pyroxene, calcite and olivine.Also considered to be a lamprophyre chiefly composed of biotite or phlogopite and melilite as essential minerals, commonly with olivine, calcite, and clinopyroxene. Perovskite, apatite, nepheline, and garnet may be present.

  • Alternate labels: Alnoite

  • Concept URI token: lamprophyric-pyroxene-calcite-biotite-olivine-melilitite

1.2.2.7.3.2.11 Melilitolite

  • Child of: melilite-bearing-rock

  • A coarse-grained/plutonic rock containing more than 10% modal melilite and melilite > foids.

  • Alternate labels: Coarse grained melilitic rock

  • Concept URI token: melilitolite

1.2.2.7.3.2.12 Afrikandite

  • Child of: melilitolite

  • A melilitolite with more than 10% perovskite.

  • Concept URI token: afrikandite

1.2.2.7.3.2.13 Kugdite

  • Child of: melilitolite

  • A melilitolite with more than 10% olivine.

  • Alternate labels: Olivine melilitolite, Olivine-melilitolite,

  • Concept URI token: kugdite

1.2.2.7.3.2.14 Magnetite-pyroxene melilitolite

  • Child of: melilitolite

  • A melilitolite with at least 10% magnetite and 10% pyroxene.

  • Concept URI token: magnetite-pyroxene-melilitolite

1.2.2.7.3.2.15 Okaite

  • Child of: melilitolite

  • A melilitolite with more than 10% hauyne but more melilite than hauyne.

  • Concept URI token: okaite

1.2.2.7.3.2.16 Olivine-pyroxene melilitolite

  • Child of: melilitolite

  • A melilitolite with >10% pyroxene and >10% olivine; olivine

  • Alternate labels: Olivine uncompahgrite, Pyroxene Olivine melilitolite,

  • Concept URI token: olivine-pyroxene-melilitolite

1.2.2.7.3.2.17 Pyroxene-olivine melilitolite

  • Child of: melilitolite

  • A melilitolite with >10% pyroxene and >10% olivine; olivine>pyroxene.

  • Concept URI token: pyroxene-olivine-melilitolite

1.2.2.7.3.2.18 Turjaite

  • Child of: melilitolite

  • A melilitolite with more than 10% nepheline but more melilite than nepheline.

  • Concept URI token: turjaite

1.2.2.7.3.2.19 Kovdorite

  • Child of: turjaite

  • A local term for a variety of turjaite (a melilitolite) containing olivine. Not to be confused with kovdorskite, a phosphate mineral.

  • Concept URI token: kovdorite

1.2.2.7.3.2.20 Ultramelilitolite

  • Child of: melilitolite

  • A melilitolite with more than 65% melilite.

  • Concept URI token: ultramelilitolite

1.2.2.7.3.2.21 Uncompahgrite

  • Child of: melilitolite

  • A coarse grained melilitic rock with more than 10% pyroxene.

  • Alternate labels: Pyroxene melilitolite, Pyroxene-melilitolite,

  • Concept URI token: uncompahgrite

1.2.2.7.4 Kamafugite

  • Child of: exotic-crystalline-igneous-rock

  • Not a root name but a series of ultrapotassic igneous rocks, between kalsilitite and leucitite.

  • Concept URI token: kamafugite

1.2.2.7.5 Rock of restricted mineralogy

  • Child of: exotic-crystalline-igneous-rock

  • Rocks of restricted mineralogy, including cumulates. These are igneous rocks that do not fit into other classifications.

  • Concept URI token: rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

1.2.2.7.5.1 Aegirine-nepheline-rock

  • Child of: rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • A rock consisting essentially of aegirine and nepheline.

  • Concept URI token: aegirine-nepheline-rock

1.2.2.7.5.2 Apatite-forsteritite

  • Child of: rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • A proposed name by Egorov (1992) for a rock composed primarily of forsterite (olivine) and apatite, with forsterite > apatite, but forsterite < 90% This is not strictly a forsteritite.

  • Concept URI token: apatite-forsteritite

1.2.2.7.5.3 Apatite-magnetite-rock

  • Child of: rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • A rock consisting of at least 90% combined apatite and magnetite which may be metasomatic rather than igneous

  • Concept URI token: apatite-magnetite-rock

1.2.2.7.5.4 Apatitolite

  • Child of: rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • A rock of magmatic origin composed essentially of apatite.

  • Concept URI token: apatitolite

1.2.2.7.5.4.1 Nepheline-bearing apatitolite

  • Child of: apatitolite

  • An alkaline intrusive rock consisting mainly of apatite with variable amounts of nepheline and minor aegirine and biotite

  • Concept URI token: nepheline-bearing-apatitolite

1.2.2.7.5.5 Chromitite

  • Child of: rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • A rock consisting of at least 90% chromite or magnesiochromite, usually with olivine and/or serpentine. The chromite may be partly altered to ferritchromite.

  • Concept URI token: chromitite

1.2.2.7.5.6 Cumulate

  • Child of: rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • A general term for igneous rocks composed of crystals that accumulated due to gravitational settling in a magma. An igneous rock formed by the accumulation of crystals that settle out from a magma by the action of gravity; examples include layered igneous deposits such as the Bushveld complex in South Africa and the Stillwater complex in Montana. Synonym: accumulative rock

  • Concept URI token: cumulate

1.2.2.7.5.7 Eudialytite

  • Child of: rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • A melanocratic plutonic rock consisting essentially of eudialyte with minor variable amounts of microcline, arfvedsonite and aegirine.

  • Concept URI token: eudialytite

1.2.2.7.5.8 Ilmenitite

  • Child of: rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • A hypabyssal igneous rock composed almost entirely of ilmenite, with accessory pyrite, chalcopyrite, pyrrhotite, hypersthene, and labradorite. Compare with: nelsonite

  • Concept URI token: ilmenitite

1.2.2.7.5.9 Magnetitite

  • Child of: rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • A rock consisting of at least 90% magnetite.

  • Concept URI token: magnetitite

1.2.2.7.5.10 Micaite

  • Child of: rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • A rock consisting almost entirely of mica

  • Concept URI token: micaite

1.2.2.7.5.10.1 Biotitite

  • Child of: micaite

  • A black igneous rock consisting almost entirely of biotite.

  • Concept URI token: biotitite

1.2.2.7.5.11 Nelsonite

  • Child of: rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • A rock composed essentially of ilmenite and apatite, with or without rutile. The ratio of ilmenite to apatite varies widely.

  • Concept URI token: nelsonite

1.2.2.7.5.12 Nelsonite (of Egorov)

  • Child of: rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • This was propsed by Egorov (1992) to be defined as a rock consisting of at least 90% magnetite + apatite, with at least 10% each.

  • Concept URI token: nelsonite-ofegorov

1.2.2.7.5.13 Nephelinite

  • Child of: foidite rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • A foidite consisting mostly of nepheline with <10% mafic minerals.A fine-grained or porphyritic extrusive or hypabyssal rock, of basaltic character, but primarily composed of nepheline and clinopyroxene, esp. titanaugite, and lacking olivine and feldspar.

  • Concept URI token: nephelinite

1.2.2.7.5.13.1 Ampasimenite

  • Child of: ijolite nephelinite

  • A local name for a porphyritic variety of ijolite or nephelinite with a glassy matrix.

  • Concept URI token: ampasimenite

1.2.2.7.5.13.2 Leucite nephelinite

  • Child of: nephelinite

  • A nephelinite containing leucite

  • Concept URI token: leucite-nephelinite

1.2.2.7.5.13.3 Clinopyroxene-leucite nephelinite

  • Child of: leucite-nephelinite

  • A nephelinite containing leucite and clinopyroxene,

  • Concept URI token: clinopyroxene-leucite-nephelinite

1.2.2.7.5.13.4 Melilite nephelinite

  • Child of: nephelinite

  • nephelinite containing significant melilite

  • Concept URI token: melilite-nephelinite

1.2.2.7.5.13.5 Olivine nephelinite

  • Child of: nephelinite

  • A nephelinite containing olivine

  • Concept URI token: olivine-nephelinite

1.2.2.7.5.13.6 Ankaratrite

  • Child of: olivine-nephelinite

  • A melanocratic variety of olivine nephelinite containing biotite.

  • Concept URI token: ankaratrite

1.2.2.7.5.14 Nephelinolite

  • Child of: foidolite rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • A foidolite where nepheline is the most abundant foid.

  • Concept URI token: nephelinolite

1.2.2.7.5.14.1 Apatite nephelinolite

  • Child of: nephelinolite

  • A nephelinolite consisting mainly of apatite and nepheline with minor aegirine and biotite.

  • Concept URI token: apatite-nephelinolite

1.2.2.7.5.14.2 Ijolite

  • Child of: nephelinolite

  • A nephelinolite consisting of 30-70% nepheline with pyroxene.A series of plutonic rocks containing nepheline and 30% to 60% mafic minerals, generally clinopyroxene, and including minor titanite, apatite, and melanite; also, any rock of that series. Melteigite and jacupirangite are more mafic members of the series; urtite is a type rich in nepheline.

  • Alternate labels: Ngurumanite, Pyroxene nephelinolite,

  • Concept URI token: ijolite

1.2.2.7.5.14.3 Ampasimenite

  • Child of: ijolite nephelinite

  • A local name for a porphyritic variety of ijolite or nephelinite with a glassy matrix.

  • Concept URI token: ampasimenite

1.2.2.7.5.14.4 Calcite ijolite

  • Child of: ijolite

  • An ijolite with calcite, but not enough calcite to be classed as a carbonatite.

  • Concept URI token: calcite-ijolite

1.2.2.7.5.14.5 Calcitfels

  • Child of: ijolite

  • n obsolete term for a calcite-rich member of the ijolite-melteigite series.

  • Concept URI token: calcitfels

1.2.2.7.5.14.6 Ijolite-urtite

  • Child of: ijolite

  • A rock of intermediate composition between ijolite and urtite.

  • Concept URI token: ijolite-urtite

1.2.2.7.5.14.7 Lujavritite

  • Child of: ijolite

  • A variety of ijolite composed mainly of aegirine-augite and nepheline with much titanite and some apatite and characterized by the presence of small amounts of K- feldspar.

  • Concept URI token: lujavritite

1.2.2.7.5.14.8 Pegmatitic Ijolite

  • Child of: ijolite

  • A very coarsely crystalline ijolite.

  • Concept URI token: pegmatitic-ijolite

1.2.2.7.5.14.9 Leucocratic nephelinolite

  • Child of: nephelinolite

  • A nephelinolite consisting of over 70% nepheline, with some aegirine-augite but no feldspar.

  • Alternate labels: urtite

  • Concept URI token: leucocratic-nephelinolite

1.2.2.7.5.14.10 Congressite

  • Child of: leucocratic-nephelinolite

  • A local name for a coarse-grained nephelinolite consisting of about 70% nepheline with minor alkali feldspar, biotite, occasional sodalite and accessory minerals.

  • Concept URI token: congressite

1.2.2.7.5.14.11 Melanocratic nephelinolite

  • Child of: nephelinolite

  • A nephelinolite consisting of 10% to 30% nepheline with pyroxene.

  • Alternate labels: melteigite

  • Concept URI token: melanocratic-nephelinolite

1.2.2.7.5.14.12 Biotite melteigite

  • Child of: melanocratic-nephelinolite

  • A melanocratic nephelinolite containing biotite.

  • Concept URI token: biotite-melteigite

1.2.2.7.5.14.13 Fasinite

  • Child of: melanocratic-nephelinolite

  • A melanocratic nephelinolite consisting of 60-70% titanian augite with some nepheline.

  • Concept URI token: fasinite

1.2.2.7.5.15 Noseanite

  • Child of: foidite rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • A foidite consisting essentially of nosean with <10% mafic minerals.

  • Concept URI token: noseanite

1.2.2.7.5.16 Olivine-chromite-rock

  • Child of: rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • A rock consisting of at least 90% combined chromite and olivine which would not otherwise fit into the standard QAPF system.

  • Concept URI token: olivine-chromite-rock

1.2.2.7.5.17 Olivine-magnetitite

  • Child of: rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • A rock name proposed by Egorov (1992) for a rock consisting primarily of olivine (forsterite) and magnetite, with magnetite>50%. It is not strictly a magnetitite so the name is somewhat confusing.

  • Concept URI token: olivine-magnetitite

1.2.2.7.5.18 Ore olivinite

  • Child of: rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • A name proposed by Egorov (1992) for a rock related to forsteritite containing between 10% and 50% magnetite but with < 10% apatite.

  • Concept URI token: ore-olivinite

1.2.2.7.5.19 Phoscorite

  • Child of: rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • A rock composed primarily of magnetite, apatite and olivine, usually associated with carbonatites.

  • Concept URI token: phoscorite

1.2.2.7.5.20 Quartz-tourmaline-rock

  • Child of: rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • A rock composed almost entirely of quartz and tourmaline.

  • Concept URI token: quartz-tourmaline-rock

1.2.2.7.5.21 Sanidinite (igneous)

  • Child of: rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • An term used earlier in igneous nomenclature for an igneous rock, consisting mostly of sanidine. To avoid conflict with the metamorphic usage it should not be used for igneous rocks. Locally, for example in Italy, the term sanidinite is still used for a subvolcanic rock consisting mostly of sanidine.

  • Concept URI token: sanidinite-igneous

1.2.2.7.5.22 Sodalitite

  • Child of: foidite rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • A foidite consisting essentially of sodalite with <10% of olivine and other mafic minerals. An urtite composed chiefly of sodalite, with smaller amounts of acmite, eudialyte, and alkali feldspar.

  • Alternate labels: Sodalite basalt

  • Concept URI token: sodalitite

1.2.2.7.5.22.1 Olivine sodalitite

  • Child of: sodalitite

  • A sodalitite containing olivine.

  • Concept URI token: olivine-sodalitite

1.2.2.7.5.23 Sodalitolite

  • Child of: foidolite rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • A foidolite where sodalite is the most abundant foid.

  • Concept URI token: sodalitolite

1.2.2.7.5.23.1 Naujaite

  • Child of: sodalitolite

  • Where sodalite exceeds 50% it is classed as a sodalitolite, otherwise it is a nepheline sodalite-syenite. It is an agpaitic rock characterised by a poikilitic texture.

  • Concept URI token: naujaite

1.2.2.7.5.23.2 Tawite

  • Child of: sodalitolite

  • A variety of foidolite composed largely of crystals of sodalite together with aegirine. Some nepheline, alkali feldspar and eudialyte are usually present.

  • Concept URI token: tawite

1.2.2.7.5.23.3 Beloeilite

  • Child of: tawite

  • A type of tawite consisting of about 70% sodalite with nepheline, alkali feldspar, oligoclase and a little aegirine, originally described as a feldspathic variety of tawite.

  • Concept URI token: beloeilite

1.2.2.7.5.24 Spinellite

  • Child of: rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • A rock in which spinel is the predominant mineral. Also a medium- to coarse-grained hypidiomorphic-granular titaniferous magnetite-rich igneous rock with spinel from a few percent to 20%.

  • Concept URI token: spinellite

1.2.2.7.5.24.1 Magnetite spinellite

  • Child of: spinellite

  • A spinellite containing magnetite An eruptive iron ore occurring at Routivara, Sweden, and consisting of magnetite (in part titaniferous), spinel, and smaller amounts of olivine, pyroxene, apatite, and pyrrhotite. The ore contains about 14% titanic oxide.

  • Concept URI token: magnetite-spinellite

1.2.2.7.6 Ultrapotassic rock

  • Child of: exotic-crystalline-igneous-rock

  • A class of rare, generally ultramafic or mafic silica-depleted igneous rocks with K2O:Na2O at least 2:1.

  • Concept URI token: ultrapotassic-rock

1.2.2.7.6.1 Borengite

  • Child of: ultrapotassic-rock

  • An aphanitic ultrapotassic dyke-rock with the highest recorded K2O concentrations (more than 14 wt.%) among alkalic rocks.

  • Concept URI token: borengite

1.2.2.7.6.2 Burgasite

  • Child of: ultrapotassic-rock

  • A local name for a potassic volcanic rock with marked spheroidal structure composed of almost equal amounts of alkali feldspar and various zeolites with minor augite, biotite and aegirine-augite. It may be a metasomatized andesitic rock.

  • Concept URI token: burgasite

1.2.2.7.6.3 K-feldspar enriched leucogranite

  • Child of: leucogranite ultrapotassic-rock

  • A leucogranite enriched in K-feldspar.

  • Concept URI token: k-feldspar-enriched-leucogranite

1.2.2.7.6.4 Lamproite

  • Child of: exotic-alkaline-rock ultrapotassic-rock

  • A poorly defined group of potassic to ultramafic, dark-colored hypabyssal or extrusive, volcanic to pyroclastic rocks, usually in dykes and pipes. A group name for such rocks rich in potassium and magnesium; also, any rock in that group, such as madupite, orendite, fitzroyite, verite, cedricite, or wyomingite.

  • Concept URI token: lamproite

1.2.2.7.6.4.1 Diopside-leucite lamproite

  • Concept URI token: olivine-diopside-richterite-madupitic-lamproite

1.2.2.7.6.4.12 Olivine lamproite

  • Child of: lamproite

  • A rock type corresponding to micaceous or lamprophyric kimberites, or an olivine-rich lamproite.

  • Concept URI token: olivine-lamproite

1.2.2.7.6.5 Lamprophyre

  • Child of: exotic-alkaline-rock ultrapotassic-rock

  • A group of hypabyssal igneous rocks characterised by abundant primary hydrous silicates in phenocrysts and/ or groundmass, lacking felsic phenocrysts, usually occurring in dykes.A group of dark- colored, porphyritic, hypabyssal igneous rocks characterized by panidiomorphic texture, a high percentage of mafic minerals (esp. biotite, hornblende, and pyroxene), which form the phenocrysts, and a fine-grained groundmass with the same mafic minerals in addition to feldspars and/or feldspathoids; also, any rock in that group.

  • Concept URI token: lamprophyre

1.2.2.7.6.5.1 Aillikite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • An ultramafic carbonate-rich lamprophyre consisting of various phenocrysts including olivine, diopsidic pyroxene, amphiboles and phlogopite in a matrix of similar minerals with at least partly primary carbonate and minor perovskite but no melilite.

  • Concept URI token: aillikite

1.2.2.7.6.5.2 Antsohite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A local name for a lamprophyric dyke rock consisting of phenocrysts of biotite in a groundmass of biotite, hornblende and interstitial quartz.

  • Concept URI token: antsohite

1.2.2.7.6.5.3 Bermudite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A local name for a lamprophyre consisting of biotite and minor titanian augite in a groundmass of analcime (probably after nepheline). Possibly equivalent in composition to ouachitite.

  • Concept URI token: bermudite

1.2.2.7.6.5.4 Camptonite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A lamprophyre with plagioclase>K-feldspar and feldspars > feldspathoids; similar in composition to nepheline diorite, being composed essentially of plagioclase (usually labradorite) and brown hornblende.

  • Concept URI token: camptonite

1.2.2.7.6.5.5 Analcime camptonite

  • Child of: camptonite

  • A camptonite containing analcime.

  • Concept URI token: analcime-camptonite

1.2.2.7.6.5.6 Cascadite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A local name for a sodic melanocratic lamprophyre having phenocrysts of biotite, olivine and augite in a matrix essentially of alkali feldspar with patches of what could have been leucite.

  • Concept URI token: cascadite

1.2.2.7.6.5.7 Cocite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A melanocratic leucite-rich lamprophyre largely composed of clinopyroxene and subordinate olivine in a matrix of alkali feldspar, leucite and clinopyroxene with minor biotite. Similar to tjosite but with leucite instead of nepheline.

  • Concept URI token: cocite

1.2.2.7.6.5.8 Cuselite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A local name for an altered lamprophyric rock containing phenocrysts of plagioclase and uralitized diopside in a granular groundmass of plagioclase, orthoclase, chloritized biotite, hornblende, diopside and interstitial quartz.

  • Concept URI token: cuselite

1.2.2.7.6.5.9 Damkjernite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A melanocratic variety of nepheline lamprophyre. A hypabyssal rock containing phenocrysts of biotite and titanian augite in a groundmass of the same minerals with some nepheline, calcite and k-felspar, perovskite, and magnetite. Also spelled: damtjernite.

  • Concept URI token: damkjernite

1.2.2.7.6.5.10 Ehrwaldite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A lamprophyre of basanitic composition. Composed of titanian augite, biotite, serpentinised olivine and glass.

  • Concept URI token: ehrwaldite

1.2.2.7.6.5.11 Epibasite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • An obsolete term for non-porphyritic lamprophyres, which is somewhat of a contradiction of terms.

  • Concept URI token: epibasite

1.2.2.7.6.5.12 Eustratite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A name for a lamprophyric dyke rock from Haghios Eustratios, (now Ayios Evstratios Island), Greece with rare phenocrysts of olivine, corroded hornblende and occasional augite in a groundmass of augite, titanomagnetite, feldspar and glass.

  • Concept URI token: eustratite

1.2.2.7.6.5.13 Farrisite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A melonocratic melilite lamprophyre containing augite, barkevikite, biotite and olivine, but no feldspar.

  • Concept URI token: farrisite

1.2.2.7.6.5.14 Kersantite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A lamprophyre with plagioclase > K-feldspar and biotite as the dominant mafic mineral; no feldspathoid. A lamprophyre containing biotite and plagioclase (usually oligoclase or andesine), with or without clinopyroxene and olivine.

  • Concept URI token: kersantite

1.2.2.7.6.5.15 Aschaffite

  • Child of: kersantite

  • A type of kersantite (a lamprophyre) with abundant biotite in a matrix of plagioclase and quartz.

  • Concept URI token: aschaffite

1.2.2.7.6.5.16 Minette

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A lampropyre containing biotite and K-feldspar being the dominant felsic mineral.

  • Concept URI token: minette

1.2.2.7.6.5.17 Baltorite

  • Child of: minette vogesite

  • A local comprehensive term for potassic vogesites and potassic minettes.

  • Concept URI token: baltorite

1.2.2.7.6.5.18 Raabsite

  • Child of: minette

  • A type of minette consisting of microcline, sodic amphibole, biotite and olivine.

  • Concept URI token: raabsite

1.2.2.7.6.5.19 Sizunite

  • Child of: minette

  • A local term for a variety of minette characterized by high K2O (> 10%) and P2O5 (2.5%) and consisting of microcline, biotite, apatite and opaques.

  • Concept URI token: sizunite

1.2.2.7.6.5.20 Monchiquite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A lampropyre with feldspathoid and no feldspars.A lamprophyre containing phenocrysts of olivine, clinopyroxene, and typically biotite or amphibole (barkevikite), in a groundmass of glass or analcime, often highly altered. Nepheline or leucite may be present.

  • Concept URI token: monchiquite

1.2.2.7.6.5.21 Sannaite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A lampropyre with plagioclase>K-feldspar and feldspars > feldspathoid

  • Concept URI token: sannaite

1.2.2.7.6.5.22 Spessartite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A lampropyre with plagioclase>K-feldspar and hornblende the dominant mafic mineral; no feldspathoid.

  • Alternate labels: Spessartite rock, Spessartite-rock,

  • Concept URI token: spessartite

1.2.2.7.6.5.23 Camptospessartite

  • Child of: spessartite

  • A local term used for a basic spessartite containing titanian augite.

  • Concept URI token: camptospessartite

1.2.2.7.6.5.24 Vogesite

  • Child of: lamprophyre

  • A lampropyre with plagioclase>K-feldspar and feldspars > feldspathoid

  • Concept URI token: vogesite

1.2.2.7.6.5.25 Augite vogesite

  • Child of: vogesite

  • A vogesite containing augite.

  • Concept URI token: augite-vogesite

1.2.2.7.6.5.26 Baltorite

  • Child of: minette vogesite

  • A local comprehensive term for potassic vogesites and potassic minettes.

  • Concept URI token: baltorite

1.2.2.7.6.5.27 Camptovogesite

  • Child of: vogesite

  • A basic variety of vogesite containing basaltic hornblende.

  • Concept URI token: camptovogesite

1.2.2.7.6.6 Leucitite

  • Child of: foidite ultrapotassic-rock

  • Foidites with foids (mostly leucite) constituing 60 to 90% of light- coloured constituents

  • Alternate labels: Missourite

  • Concept URI token: leucitite

1.2.2.7.6.6.1 Batukite

  • Child of: leucitite

  • A melanocratic variety of leucitite essentially composed of clinopyroxene with small amounts of olivine and leucite.

  • Concept URI token: batukite

1.2.2.7.6.6.2 Clinopyroxene leucitite

  • Child of: leucitite

  • Leucitic rock with foids (mostly leucite) constituing 60 to 90% of light-coloured constituents and with pyroxene.

  • Concept URI token: clinopyroxene-leucitite

1.2.2.7.6.6.3 Leucitite (s.s.)

  • Child of: leucitite

  • Leucitic rock with foids (mostly leucite) constituing 90 to 100% of light-coloured constituents. Leucite is the only, or virtually the only, felspathoid mineral.

  • Concept URI token: leucitite-ss

1.2.2.7.6.6.4 Amphigenite

  • Child of: leucitite-ss tephritic-leucitite

  • An obsolete term originally used for leucite-tephrites but later used for intrusive rocks composed of more than 90% modal leucite.

  • Concept URI token: amphigenite

1.2.2.7.6.6.5 Melilite leucitite

  • Child of: leucitite-ss

  • A leucitite containing melilite.

  • Concept URI token: melilite-leucitite

1.2.2.7.6.6.6 Cecilite

  • Child of: melilite-leucitite

  • An aphyric variety of melilite leucitite consisting of essential leucite and clinopyroxene with small amounts of plagioclase, melilite and nepheline.

  • Concept URI token: cecilite

1.2.2.7.6.6.7 Lutalite

  • Child of: leucitite

  • An obsolete name for a variety of leucitite composed essentially of clinopyroxene and leucite and with subordinate olivine, nepheline and plagioclase. The value of Na2O/K2O is higher than in ordinary leucitites.

  • Concept URI token: lutalite

1.2.2.7.6.6.8 Pyroxene-olivine leucitite

  • Child of: leucitite

  • Leucitic rock with foids (mostly leucite) constituing 60 to 90% of light-coloured constituents and with pyroxene and olivine.

  • Concept URI token: pyroxene-olivine-leucitite

1.2.2.7.6.6.9 Sperone

  • Child of: leucitite

  • A local name for a yellowish, porous leucitite from the Alban Hills, Italy.

  • Concept URI token: sperone

1.2.2.7.6.7 Leucitolite

  • Child of: foidolite ultrapotassic-rock

  • A foidolite where leucite is the most abundant foid.

  • Concept URI token: leucitolite

1.2.2.7.6.7.1 Italite

  • Child of: leucitolite

  • A leucitolite consisting almost entirely of leucite held together by small amounts of glass.

  • Concept URI token: italite

1.2.2.8 Ferroplete

  • Child of: igneous-rock

  • An obsolete term for igneous rocks rich in iron oxide.

  • Concept URI token: ferroplete

1.2.2.9 Volcaniclastic rock and sediment

  • Child of: igneous-rock

  • Clastic rocks and sediments with mostly volcanic-derived clasts, containing at least 25% by volume of pyroclastic fragments. Volcaniclastic rocks and sediments include any natural materials composed in part or entirely of volcanic fragments, formed by any particle-forming mechanism. Volcanic debris is defined as fragments originating by volcanic processes, either primary or after redeposition.

  • Alternate labels: Epiclastic, Epiclastics, Fragmental/volcaniclastic igneous rock and sediment, Mixed volcanic and sedimentary rocks, Pyroclastic rock and sediment, Pyroclastic rock and tephra,

  • Concept URI token: fragmentalovervolcaniclastic-igneous-rock-and-sediment

1.2.2.9.1 Pyroclastic-rock

  • Child of: fragmentalovervolcaniclastic-igneous-rock-and-sediment

  • Rocks composed of volcanic fragments derived from explosive volcanic activity. Pyroclastic rocks contain more than 75% by volume of pyroclastic fragments, the remaining materials being generally of epiclastic, organic, chemical sedimentary or authigenic origin. Tephra is the unconsolidated equivalent.

  • Alternate labels: Pyroclastic rock, Pyroclastic, Pyroclastics,

  • Concept URI token: pyroclastic-rock

1.2.2.9.1.1 Agglomerate

  • Child of: pyroclastic-rock volcanic-breccia

  • A pyroclastic rock in which more than 75% of the pyroclastic fragments exceed 64mm and at least 50% of these are rounded.

  • Concept URI token: agglomerate

1.2.2.9.1.1.1 Agglutinate

  • Child of: agglomerate

  • A welded pyroclastic deposit or agglomerate where the ejecta (sintered vitric pyroclasts) were plastic when emplaced and are cemented together by thin skins of glass. Also spelled agglutinite.

  • Concept URI token: agglutinate

1.2.2.9.1.1.2 Pyroclastic-breccia

  • Child of: agglomerate

  • An agglomerate in which more than 75% of the pyroclastic fragments exceed 64mm and at least 50% of these are angular.

  • Alternate labels: Pyroclastic breccia

  • Concept URI token: pyroclastic-breccia

1.2.2.9.1.2 Ash tuff lapillistone and lapilli tuff

  • Child of: pyroclastic-rock

  • Pyroclastic rock in which less than 25 percent of rock by volume are more than 64 mm in longest diameter. Includes tuff, lapilli tuff, and lapillistone.

  • Concept URI token: ash-tuff-lapillistone-and-lapilli-tuff

1.2.2.9.1.2.1 Lapilli-tuff

  • Child of: ash-tuff-lapillistone-and-lapilli-tuff

  • A pyroclastic rock where beween 25% and 75% of the pyroclastic fragments are lapilli.

  • Alternate labels: Lapilli tuff

  • Concept URI token: lapilli-tuff

1.2.2.9.1.2.2 Andesitic lapilli-tuff

  • Child of: lapilli-tuff

  • A lapilli-tuff consisting of andesitic composition pyroclastic fragments.

  • Concept URI token: andesitic-lapilli-tuff

1.2.2.9.1.2.3 Dacitic lapilli-tuff

  • Child of: lapilli-tuff

  • A lapilli-tuff consisting of dacitic composition pyroclastic fragments.

  • Concept URI token: dacitic-lapilli-tuff

1.2.2.9.1.2.4 Rhyolitic lapilli-tuff

  • Child of: lapilli-tuff

  • A lapilli-tuff consisting of rhyolitic composition pyroclastic fragments.

  • Alternate labels: Rhyolite Lapilli Tuff

  • Concept URI token: rhyolitic-lapilli-tuff

1.2.2.9.1.2.5 Lapillistone

  • Child of: ash-tuff-lapillistone-and-lapilli-tuff

  • A pyroclastic rock where over 75% of the pyroclastic fragments are lapilli.

  • Concept URI token: lapillistone

1.2.2.9.1.2.6 Calciocarbonatite lapillistone

  • Child of: calcite-carbonatite lapillistone

  • A lapillistone where the lapilli are calcium-carbonatite, cemented by calcite.

  • Concept URI token: calciocarbonatite-lapillistone

1.2.2.9.1.2.7 Tuff

  • Child of: ash-tuff-lapillistone-and-lapilli-tuff

  • A pyroclastic rock where the average size of more than 75% of the pyroclastic fragments is less than 64mm and less than 25% of the fragments are lapilli. A general term for all consolidated pyroclastic rocks. Not to be confused with tufa. Adj: tuffaceous.

  • Alternate labels: Ash tuff, Ash-flow tuff, Ash-stone, Aso lava,

  • Concept URI token: tuff

1.2.2.9.1.2.8 Andesitic tuff

  • Child of: tuff

  • Tuff with mostly Andesitic clasts

  • Alternate labels: Andesite pyroclast, Andesite tuff, Andesitic pyroclast,

  • Concept URI token: andesitic-tuff

  • Child of: tuff

  • Tuff with mostly Basaltic clasts

  • Alternate labels: Brecciole, mafic tuff,

  • Concept URI token: basaltic-tuff

1.2.2.9.1.2.10 Coarse tuff

  • Child of: tuff

  • Tuff with clasts 0.03-2mm in size

  • Concept URI token: coarse-tuff

1.2.2.9.1.2.11 Crystal tuff

  • Child of: tuff

  • Tuff with mostly Crystal clasts. An indurated deposit of volcanic ash dominantly composed of intratelluric crystals and crystal fragments.

  • Concept URI token: crystal-tuff

1.2.2.9.1.2.12 Dacitic tuff

  • Child of: tuff

  • Tuff with mostly Dacitic clasts

  • Alternate labels: Dacite Tuff, Intermediate Tuff,

  • Concept URI token: dacitic-tuff

1.2.2.9.1.2.13 Duckstein

  • Child of: tuff

  • A local German name for a non-stratified tuff.

  • Concept URI token: duckstein

1.2.2.9.1.2.14 Epiclastic tuff

  • Child of: tuff

  • A tuff that has been reworked by sedimentary activity.

  • Concept URI token: epiclastic-tuff

1.2.2.9.1.2.15 Felsic tuff

  • Child of: tuff

  • Tuff with mostly Felsic clasts

  • Concept URI token: felsic-tuff

1.2.2.9.1.2.16 Fine tuff

  • Child of: tuff

  • Tuff with clasts <0.03mm in size

  • Concept URI token: fine-tuff

1.2.2.9.1.2.17 Lithic tuff

  • Child of: tuff

  • Tuff composed mostly of rock fragments. An indurated deposit of volcanic ash in which the fragments are composed of previously formed rocks; e.g., accidental particles of sedimentary rock, accessory pieces of earlier lavas in the same cone, or small bits of new lava (essential ejecta) that first solidify in the vent and are then blown out.

  • Concept URI token: lithic-tuff

1.2.2.9.1.2.18 Palagonite tuff

  • Child of: tuff

  • A tuff composed of sideromelane fragments and coarser pieces of basaltic rock, embedded in a palagonite matrix.

  • Concept URI token: palagonite-tuff

1.2.2.9.1.2.19 Rhyodactic tuff

  • Child of: tuff

  • Tuff with mostly Rhyodactic clasts

  • Alternate labels: Rhyodacite Ash Tuff, Rhyodacite Tuff,

  • Concept URI token: rhyodactic-tuff

1.2.2.9.1.2.20 Rhyolitic tuff

  • Child of: tuff

  • Tuff with mostly Rhyolitic clasts

  • Alternate labels: Rhyolite Ash Tuff, Rhyolite Tuff,

  • Concept URI token: rhyolitic-tuff

1.2.2.9.1.2.21 Trachytic tuff

  • Child of: tuff

  • Tuff with mostly Trachytic clasts

  • Concept URI token: trachytic-tuff

1.2.2.9.1.2.22 Ultramafic tuff

  • Child of: tuff

  • A rare tuff of ultramafic compsotion characterised by the abundance of olivine or serpentine and the scarcity or absence of feldspar and quartz.

  • Concept URI token: ultramafic-tuff

1.2.2.9.1.2.23 Vitric tuff

  • Child of: tuff

  • A tuff composed mostly of volcanic glass fragments.

  • Concept URI token: vitric-tuff

1.2.2.9.1.2.24 Ignimbrite

  • Child of: vitric-tuff

  • A vitric tuff where the glass fragments have welded together

  • Alternate labels: Ignimbritic tuff

  • Concept URI token: ignimbritic-tuff

1.2.2.9.1.3 Scoria

  • Child of: basaltic-glass pyroclastic-rock

  • Highly vesicular, basaltic glass. Bomb-size pyroclast that is irregular in form and generally very vesicular. In less restricted usage, a vesicular cindery crust on the surface of andesitic or basaltic lava, the vesicular nature of which is due to the escape of volcanic gases before solidification; it is usually heavier, darker, and more crystalline than pumice. The adj. form, scoriaceous, is usually applied to pyroclastic ejecta. Cinder is sometimes used synonymously.

  • Concept URI token: scoria

1.2.2.9.1.4 Tuff-breccia

  • Child of: pyroclastic-rock volcanic-breccia

  • A pyroclastic-rock where there is at least 25% of each of the main fragment size divisions (i.e. block/bomb, lapilli and ash.)

  • Alternate labels: Brecciated Tuff, Tuff breccia,

  • Concept URI token: tuff-breccia

1.2.2.9.1.5 Welded tuff

  • Child of: pyroclastic-rock

  • A pyroclastic-rock, of any origin, that was sufficiently hot at the time of deposition to weld together. A glass-rich pyroclastic rock that has been indurated by the welding together of its glass shards under the combined action of the heat retained by particles, the weight of overlying material, and hot gases. It is generally composed of silicic pyroclasts and appears banded or streaky.

  • Alternate labels: tuff lava

  • Concept URI token: welded-tuff

1.2.2.9.2 Pyroclastic sediment

  • Child of: fragmentalovervolcaniclastic-igneous-rock-and-sediment

  • Unimodal well-sorted pyroclastic sediments comprised of more than 75% pyroclastic fragments.

  • Alternate labels: Tephra

  • Concept URI token: pyroclastic-sediment

1.2.2.9.2.1 Ash

  • Child of: pyroclastic-sediment

  • A tephra where at least 75% of the fragments are ash grade (less than 2mm.)Fine pyroclastic material (under 2.0-mm diameter; under 0.063-mm diameter for fine ash). The term usually refers to the unconsolidated material but sometimes is also used for its consolidated counterpart, tuff.

  • Alternate labels: cinerite, pumicite, spodite, volcanic ash, volcanic dust,

  • Concept URI token: ash

1.2.2.9.2.1.1 Coarse ash

  • Child of: ash

  • Ash 0.03-2mm in size

  • Concept URI token: coarse-ash

  • Concept URI token: crystal-ash

  • Concept URI token: dacitic-ash

  • Child of: ash

  • Concept URI token: fine-ash

  • Child of: ash

  • Concept URI token: vitric-ash

1.2.2.9.2.1.8 Orange vitric ash

  • Child of: mare-basalt vitric-ash

  • A lunar soil consisting of orange glass spheres, some partially devitrified fron quenched fire fountain droplents of erupting mare Ti- rich basalt, dated at 3.48Ga. The outer surfaces of the spheres are commonaly coated with ZnS and other volatile minerals.

  • Concept URI token: orange-vitric-ash

1.2.2.9.2.2 Ash breccia bomb or block tephra

  • Child of: pyroclastic-sediment

  • Tephra in which more than 25 percent of particles are greater than 64 mm in largest dimension. Includes ash breccia, bomb tephra and block tephra of Gillespie and Styles (1999)

  • Concept URI token: ash-breccia-bomb-or-block-tephra

1.2.2.9.2.2.1 Ash-breccia

  • Child of: ash-breccia-bomb-or-block-tephra volcanic-breccia

  • A tephra where there is at least 25% of each of the main fragment size divisions (i.e. block/bomb, lapilli and ash.)

  • Concept URI token: ash-breccia

1.2.2.9.2.2.2 Block-bomb-tephra

  • Child of: ash-breccia-bomb-or-block-tephra

  • A tephra where the average size of more than 75% of the pyroclastic fragments exceeds 64mm and between 25% and 50% of these fragments are angular.

  • Concept URI token: block-bomb-tephra

1.2.2.9.2.2.3 Block-tephra

  • Child of: ash-breccia-bomb-or-block-tephra

  • A tephra where the average size of more than 75% of the pyroclastic fragments exceeds 64mm and more than 75% of these fragments are angular.

  • Concept URI token: block-tephra

1.2.2.9.2.2.4 Bomb-block-tephra

  • Child of: ash-breccia-bomb-or-block-tephra

  • A tephra where the average size of more than 75% of the pyroclastic fragments exceeds 64mm and between 50% and 75% of these fragments are angular.

  • Concept URI token: bomb-block-tephra

1.2.2.9.2.2.5 Bomb-tephra

  • Child of: ash-breccia-bomb-or-block-tephra

  • Concept URI token: bomb-tephra

1.2.2.9.4 Volcanic breccia

  • Child of: breccia fragmentalovervolcaniclastic-igneous-rock-and-sediment

  • A general or field term applying to all coarse-grained rocks containing abundant (>10%) angular volcanic fragments.

  • Alternate labels: alloclastic breccia, lava breccia, trachyte breccia,

  • Concept URI token: volcanic-breccia

1.2.2.9.4.1 Agglomerate

  • Child of: pyroclastic-rock volcanic-breccia

  • A pyroclastic rock in which more than 75% of the pyroclastic fragments exceed 64mm and at least 50% of these are rounded.

  • Concept URI token: agglomerate

1.2.2.9.4.1.1 Agglutinate

  • Child of: agglomerate

  • A welded pyroclastic deposit or agglomerate where the ejecta (sintered vitric pyroclasts) were plastic when emplaced and are cemented together by thin skins of glass. Also spelled agglutinite.

  • Concept URI token: agglutinate

1.2.2.9.4.1.2 Pyroclastic-breccia

  • Child of: agglomerate

  • An agglomerate in which more than 75% of the pyroclastic fragments exceed 64mm and at least 50% of these are angular.

  • Alternate labels: Pyroclastic breccia

  • Concept URI token: pyroclastic-breccia

  • A tephra where there is at least 25% of each of the main fragment size divisions (i.e. block/bomb, lapilli and ash.)

  • Concept URI token: ash-breccia

1.2.2.9.4.3 Tuff-breccia

  • Child of: pyroclastic-rock volcanic-breccia

  • A pyroclastic-rock where there is at least 25% of each of the main fragment size divisions (i.e. block/bomb, lapilli and ash.)

  • Alternate labels: Brecciated Tuff, Tuff breccia,

  • Concept URI token: tuff-breccia

1.2.2.10 Glassy igneous rock

  • Child of: glassy-rock igneous-rock

  • I. Glassy igneous rocks not otherwise classifiedii. Igneous rock that consists of greater than 80 percent massive glass.

  • Alternate labels: Volcanic Glass

  • Concept URI token: glassy-igneous-rock

1.2.2.10.1 Basaltic glass

  • Child of: glassy-igneous-rock

  • Glassy, fresh varieties of basalt, often contain microscopic crystals, or the interstital glass found in partly crystallised basalts.

  • Concept URI token: basaltic-glass

1.2.2.10.1.1 Hyaloclastite

  • Child of: basaltic-glass

  • A volcanic breccia composed almost entirely of basaltic glass.

  • Alternate labels: Hyaloclastite Breccia

  • Concept URI token: hyaloclastite

1.2.2.10.1.2 Pele’s hair

  • Child of: basaltic-glass

  • Threads or fibers of volcanic glass, usually basaltic. A natural spun glass formed by blowing-out during quiet fountaining of fluid lava, cascading lava falls, or turbulent flows, sometimes in association with Pele’s tear pyroclast. A single strand, with a diameter of less than 1/2 mm, may be as long as 2 m. Etymol: Pele, Hawaiian goddess of fire. Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: peles-hair

1.2.2.10.1.3 Pele’s tears

  • Child of: basaltic-glass

  • Tear-like drops of volcanic glass, usually basaltic

  • Concept URI token: peles-tears

1.2.2.10.1.4 Scoria

  • Child of: basaltic-glass pyroclastic-rock

  • Highly vesicular, basaltic glass. Bomb-size pyroclast that is irregular in form and generally very vesicular. In less restricted usage, a vesicular cindery crust on the surface of andesitic or basaltic lava, the vesicular nature of which is due to the escape of volcanic gases before solidification; it is usually heavier, darker, and more crystalline than pumice. The adj. form, scoriaceous, is usually applied to pyroclastic ejecta. Cinder is sometimes used synonymously.

  • Concept URI token: scoria

1.2.2.10.1.5 Sideromelane

  • Child of: basaltic-glass

  • The extremely common yellow or brown translucent glass in many basalts formed during submarine eruption or any magma/water interaction. Commonly occurring in palagonite tuff, for which it is characteristic. The term may refer to an interstitial glass or a rock composed mostly of such glass.

  • Concept URI token: sideromelane

1.2.2.10.1.6 Tachylite

  • Child of: basaltic-glass

  • Black or dark brown, opaque basaltic glass. The term may refer to an interstitial glass or a rock composed mostly of such glass.

  • Concept URI token: tachylite

1.2.2.10.2 Perlite

  • Child of: glassy-igneous-rock

  • An amorphous volcanic glass with a relatively high water content, frequently formed by the hydration of obsidian.

  • Concept URI token: perlite

1.2.2.10.3 Silicic volcanic glass

  • Child of: glassy-igneous-rock

  • Silica-rich volcanic glass

  • Concept URI token: silicic-volcanic-glass

1.2.2.10.3.1 Obsidian

  • Child of: silicic-volcanic-glass

  • Fresh igneous rocks with a high silica content and conchoidal fracture. Volcanic glass - a rock rather than a mineral, it is a mixture of cryptocrystalline grains of silica minerals in a glass-like suspension, a super-cooled liquid.

  • Alternate labels: Bergmahogany, Black Lava Glass, Hyalopsite, Isophyre,

  • Concept URI token: obsidian

1.2.2.10.3.1.1 Apache Tears

  • Child of: obsidian

  • ‘Apache tears’ originate from siliceous lava flows, lava domes or ash-flow tuffs, often in close association with or embedded in, gray perlite. The spherules occur as cores within perlite masses that typically exhibit concentrically curved, onion-skin fractures. Their formation is apparently related to differential cooling and differing alkali and water contents.

  • Concept URI token: apache-tears

1.2.2.10.3.1.2 Fire Obsidian

  • Child of: obsidian

  • An iridescent variety of obsidian. Its ‘fire’ is caused by thin layers of microcrystals of magnetite (which are approximately the thickness of a wavelength of light). The colour of Rainbow Obsidian occurs from a much thicker volume of the specimen (Nadin, 2007).

  • Concept URI token: fire-obsidian

1.2.2.10.3.1.3 Macusanite

  • Child of: obsidian

  • A natural glass of composition similar to some granite pegmatites. Most typically found as pale yellow-green transparent alluvial pebbles. The glass usually has abundant well developed micro crystals floating in it, including the rare quartz-like mineral Virgilite for which this is the type locality.

  • Alternate labels: Macusani glass

  • Concept URI token: macusanite

1.2.2.10.3.1.4 Mahogany Obsidian

  • Child of: obsidian

  • A mahogany coloured variety of Obsidian

  • Concept URI token: mahogany-obsidian

1.2.2.10.3.1.5 Marekanite

  • Child of: obsidian

  • Obsidian that occurs as rounded to subangular bodies, usually less than 2 inches (5.1 cm) in diameter and having indented surfaces. These bodies occur in masses of perlite and are of special interest because of their low water content as compared with the surrounding perlite. The name is from the Marekanka River, Okhotsk, Siberia, Russia. Marekanite (obsidian balls) have also been found at Cerro Tijerina, central Nicaragua and appear identical to apache tears. Compare with apache tears.

  • Concept URI token: marekanite

1.2.2.10.3.1.6 Rainbow Obsidian

  • Child of: obsidian

  • Obsidian with multicolored iridescence caused by inclusions of magnetite nanoparticles (Nadin, 2007).

  • Concept URI token: rainbow-obsidian

1.2.2.10.3.1.7 Sheen Obsidian

  • Child of: obsidian

  • A variety of obsidian exhibiting a golden sheen effect.

  • Concept URI token: sheen-obsidian

1.2.2.10.3.1.8 Snowflake Obsidian

  • Child of: obsidian

  • A natural volcanic glass containing white ‘snowflake’ crystal patterns of the mineral cristobalite, originated due to partial crystallisation of the glass.

  • Concept URI token: snowflake-obsidian

1.2.2.10.3.1.9 Stigmite

  • Child of: obsidian

  • An obsolete name for a porphyritic variety of pitchstone or obsidian.

  • Concept URI token: stigmite

1.2.2.10.3.2 Pitchstone

  • Child of: silicic-volcanic-glass

  • Glassy silicic igneous rocks lacking a conchoidal fracture. A dark, resinous volcanic glass.

  • Concept URI token: pitchstone

1.2.2.10.3.3 Pumice

  • Child of: silicic-volcanic-glass

  • Glassy, highly vesicular, mostly silicic igneous rocks.

  • Alternate labels: Bimsstein, Bymsftein, Bynftein, Spumulite,

  • Concept URI token: pumice

1.2.2.10.3.3.1 Reticulite

  • Child of: pumice

  • An extremely vesiculated variety of pumice consisting of a broken network of glass threads which join a series of points forming a polyhedral space lattice. It is formed from pumice by the collapse of the walls of adjacent vesicles and the retraction of the liquid into threads which form the perimeters of the former polygonal faces. The threads are usually of triangular cross section, indicating chilling, before rounding could take place. Such rock has generally been known by Dana’s name, thread-lace scoria.

  • Concept URI token: reticulite

1.2.2.11 Normal crystalline igneous rock

  • Child of: igneous-rock

  • Chemically/mineralogically ‘normal’ igneous rocks that can be defined mineralogically on a QAPF diagram, or ultramafic diagrams, or chemically on a TAS diagram.

  • Concept URI token: normal-crystalline-igneous-rock

1.2.2.11.21 Dolerine

  • Concept URI token: dolerine

1.2.2.11.22 Dolerite

  • Child of: normal-crystalline-igneous-rock

  • Dolerite is usually defined as a medium grained mafic intrusive rocks. It can include microgabbro, basalt, andesite, microdiorite and other rock types. A medium grained mafic intrusive rock whose main components are calcic plagioclase and clinopyroxene and which is characterized by ophitic to subophitic texture; usually found in sills and dykes. Of similar mineralogy to basalt and gabbro, and intermediate in grainsize between them.

  • Alternate labels: Basalton, Bizeul, Diabase, Ferrilite,

  • Concept URI token: dolerite

1.2.2.11.22.1 Albite dolerite

  • Child of: dolerite

  • A dolerite containing albite.

  • Concept URI token: albite-dolerite

  • Child of: dolerite

  • According to Tomkeieff et al. (1983) this rock is a diabase containing calcic plagioclase. However, the term does not ap- pear in the reference cited.

  • Concept URI token: anorthobase

  • Child of: dolerite

  • An aplitic dolerite.

1.2.2.11.22.4 Cabytauite

  • Child of: dolerite

  • A mnenonic name from CAlcite, BYtownite and AUgite, given to an altered dolerite composed mainly of highly calcic plagioclase, minor augite, calcite and biotite with secondary iron oxides.

  • Concept URI token: cabytauite

  • Concept URI token: olivine-dolerite

1.2.2.11.22.7 Quartz dolerite

  • Child of: dolerite

  • A variety of dolerite composed mainly of plagioclase and pyroxenes with interstitial quartz or micropegmatite. The rock has tholeiitic affinities and its pyroxenes are usually subcalcic augite accompanied by pigeonite or orthopyroxene.

  • Concept URI token: quartz-dolerite

1.2.2.11.23 Eorhyolite

  • Child of: normal-crystalline-igneous-rock

  • Concept URI token: eorhyolite

1.2.2.11.24 Essexite-basalt

  • Child of: normal-crystalline-igneous-rock

  • An obsolete name for a volcanic rock consisting of serpentinized olivine phenocrysts in a groundmass of olivine, augite, labradorite, sanidine, biotite, ore and interstitial nepheline.

  • Concept URI token: essexite-basalt

1.2.2.11.25 Eurite

  • Child of: normal-crystalline-igneous-rock

  • A name originally suggested by d Aubuisson for a compact felsitic rock and later extended to cover all aphanitic rocks of granitic composition.

  • Concept URI token: eurite

1.2.2.11.26 Extrusive igneous rock

  • Child of: normal-crystalline-igneous-rock

  • Fine-grained (‘volcanic’) crystalline igneous rock that have grains <2mm, not readily identifiable to the naked eye. The subtypes usually must be petrographically and/or chemically analysed and plotted on QAPF or TAS diagrams to characterise them.

  • Alternate labels: Aphanitic volcanic rock, Extrusive rock, Extrusive, Unclassified volcanic rock, Undifferentiated volcanic, Volcanic Rock, Volcanic Rock, undifferentiated, Volcanic rock (aphanitic), Volcanic, unclassified volcanic unit,

  • Concept URI token: extrusive-igneous-rock

1.2.2.11.26.1 Acid volcanic rock

  • Child of: extrusive-igneous-rock

  • A chemical classification based on the TAS diagram for normal volcanic rocks with at least 63 wt % SiO2.This includes, dacite, rhyolite, trachyte (in part) and trachdacite (in part).

  • Alternate labels: Acid / Felsic Volcanic, Acid Volcanic, Acid/Felsic Volcanic, Felsic Volcanic,

  • Concept URI token: acid-volcanic-rock

1.2.2.11.26.1.1 Dacite

  • Child of: acid-volcanic-rock dacitoid

  • Dacitic rocks with felsics comprising >20% quartz and alkali feldspar/plagioclase <0.5. QAPF#4A fine-grained extrusive rock with a similar general composition to andesite, but having a more sodic plagioclase and more K-feldspar and quartz; it is the extrusive equivalent of granodiorite.

  • Alternate labels: Aphyric Dacite, quartz andesite,

  • Concept URI token: dacite

1.2.2.11.26.1.2 Ambonite

  • Child of: andesitoid dacite

  • A local collective name for a series of andesites and dacites containing cordierite possibly formed by assimilation of sillimanite- cordierite gneiss.

  • Concept URI token: ambonite

1.2.2.11.26.1.3 Cryptodacite

  • Child of: andesitoid dacite

  • A dacite with a glassy groundmass.

  • Concept URI token: cryptodacite

1.2.2.11.26.1.4 Porphyritic Andesite

  • Child of: dacite

  • A porphyritic variety of rhyolite.

  • Alternate labels: Andesite Porphyry, Andesitic Porphyry,

  • Concept URI token: porphyritic-andesite

1.2.2.11.26.1.5 Porphyritic Dacite

  • Child of: dacite

  • A porphyritic variety of rhyolite.

  • Concept URI token: porphyritic-dacite

1.2.2.11.26.1.6 Rhyolite

  • Child of: acid-volcanic-rock rhyolitoid

  • Rhyolite, with felsic minerals comprising >20% quartz and alkali feldspar/plagioclase 40-90%. QAPF#3A group of extrusive igneous rocks, typically porphyritic and commonly exhibiting flow texture, with phenocrysts of quartz and alkali feldspar in a glassy to cryptocrystalline groundmass; also, any rock in that group; the extrusive equivalent of granite. Rhyolite grades into rhyodacite with decreasing alkali feldspar content and into trachyte with a decrease in quartz.

  • Alternate labels: Aphyric Rhyolite, Liparite,

  • Concept URI token: rhyolite

1.2.2.11.26.1.7 Aporhyolite

  • Child of: rhyolite

  • A rhyolite, the groundmass of which was once glassy but has become devitrified.

  • Concept URI token: aporhyolite

1.2.2.11.26.1.8 Baulite

  • Child of: rhyolite

  • A variety of rhyolite.

  • Concept URI token: baulite

1.2.2.11.26.1.9 Crocodile Jasper

  • Child of: rhyolite

  • A tradename for a greenish colored volcanic rhyolite rock quarried by Norcross in Madagascar. The rock consist of the minerals quartz, pyroxene (aegirine), albite, and K feldspar. The characteristic, blackish, rounded aggregates consist of needles of amphiboles (riebeckite to paragasite in composition).

  • Concept URI token: crocodile-jasper

1.2.2.11.26.1.10 Nevadite

  • Child of: rhyolite

  • A variety of RhyoliteA highly porphyritic variety of rhyolite, rich in quartz phenocrysts. Not to be confused with the mineral nevadaite.

  • Concept URI token: nevadite

1.2.2.11.26.1.11 Pantelleritic rhyolite

  • Child of: rhyolite

  • A variety of peralkaline rhyolite of TAS field R in which Al2O3 <1.33 x total iron as FeO + 4.4. A peralkaline rhyolite or quartz trachyte with normative quartz exceeding 10%. It is more mafic than comendite.

  • Alternate labels: Pantellerite

  • Concept URI token: pantelleritic-rhyolite

1.2.2.11.26.1.12 Peralkaline rhyolite

  • Child of: rhyolite

  • A rhyolite containing alkali pyroxenes or amphiboles, or with (Na2O+K2O)>Al2O3.

  • Alternate labels: Alkali rhyolite

  • Concept URI token: peralkaline-rhyolite

1.2.2.11.26.1.13 Comenditic rhyolite

  • Child of: peralkaline-rhyolite

  • A variety of peralkaline rhyolite of TAS field R in which Al2O3 > 1.33 x total iron as FeO + 4.4. A sodic rhyolite containing alkalic amphibole and/or pyroxene.

  • Alternate labels: Comendite, Commendite,

  • Concept URI token: comenditic-rhyolite

1.2.2.11.26.1.14 Porphyritic rhyolite

  • Child of: rhyolite
