  • Child of: rhyolite

  • A local Italian name for a glassy rhyolite from Lipari Island.

  • Concept URI token: smalto

1.2.2.11.26.2 Adakite

  • Child of: extrusive-igneous-rock

  • A series of andesites, dacites and sodic rhyolites of unusual composition, characterized by high values of Sr, high Sr/Y and La/Yb ratios and negative Nb, Ti and Zr anomalies; the more mafic rocks of the series may contain high contents of transition metals such as Cr and Ni. They usually contain phenocrysts of plagioclase, amphibole, mica, very rare orthopyroxene, but no clinopyroxene; titanomagnetite, apatite, zircon and titanite are common.

  • Concept URI token: adakite

1.2.2.11.26.3 Amygdaloid

  • Child of: extrusive-igneous-rock

  • A field term proposed for a rock containing amygdales. A rock texture in a vesicular or cellular igneous rock, most commonly basaltic, in which the vesicles have been partly or completely filled with a secondary deposit of calcite, quartz, epidote, native copper or zeolites.

  • Concept URI token: amygdaloid

1.2.2.11.26.4 Andesite-basalt

  • Child of: extrusive-igneous-rock

  • An obsolete term originally used as a synonym for basanite and later for rocks intermediate in composition between andesite and basalt. A synonym of Basaltic andesite.

  • Alternate labels: Andesite Basalt, Andesitic Basalt,

  • Concept URI token: andesite-basalt

1.2.2.11.26.5 Andesitoid

  • Child of: extrusive-igneous-rock

  • Rocks tentatively identified as andesite (also includes basaltic- andesite.)

  • Alternate labels: Andesitic rock, Andesitic-rock,

  • Concept URI token: andesitoid

1.2.2.11.26.5.1 Ambonite

  • Child of: andesitoid dacite

  • A local collective name for a series of andesites and dacites containing cordierite possibly formed by assimilation of sillimanite- cordierite gneiss.

  • Concept URI token: ambonite

1.2.2.11.26.5.2 Andesite

  • Child of: andesitoid intermediate-volcanic-rock

  • A dark-colored, fine-grained, mostly extrusive rock that is approximately the fine-grained equivalent of diorite. When porphyritic, andesite rocks contain phenocrysts composed primarily of zoned sodic plagioclase and one or more mafic minerals (usually <20%), with a groundmass of similar composition, although the plagioclase may be more sodic, and generally small amounts of quartz. Andesitic rocks plot on the QAPF diagram with 0-20% quartz, and >65% of feldspars being plagioclase; on the TAS diagram: <57-63% SiO2, (Na2O+K2O)<~6%

  • Concept URI token: andesite

  • Concept URI token: amphibole-enstatite-andesite

1.2.2.11.26.6 Aphanite

1.2.2.11.26.7 Augitite

  • Child of: extrusive-igneous-rock

1.2.2.11.26.8 Basaltoid

  • Child of: extrusive-igneous-rock

  • Fine grained igneous (usually volcanic) rocks tentatively identified as basalt. It may include some quartz or foid bearing basalts and andesites.

  • Concept URI token: basaltoid

1.2.2.11.26.8.1 Allgovite

  • Child of: basaltoid basic-volcanic-rock

  • An obsolete name temporarily proposed for a group of basaltic rocks which could not be classified as melaphyres or trapps as their age was unknown.

  • Concept URI token: allgovite

1.2.2.11.26.8.2 Anamesite

  • Child of: basaltoid basic-volcanic-rock

  • An obsolete term for basaltic rocks which are between basalt and dolerite in texture.

1.2.2.11.26.8.3 Angarite

  • Child of: basaltoid basic-volcanic-rock

  • A local name for Siberian basalts and dolerites.

  • Concept URI token: angarite

1.2.2.11.26.8.4 Basalt

  • Child of: basaltoid basic-volcanic-rock

  • A mafite or basaltoid containing mostly calcic plagioclase, clinopyroxene +/- olivine, foids, oxides and rarely quartz.A general term for fine-grained, mafic (dark-colored) igneous rocks, commonly extrusive (volcanic) but locally intrusive (e.g., as dikes or pipes), composed chiefly of plagioclase and clinopyroxene; the fine-grained equivalent of gabbro. Olivine and iron-titanium oxides are very common and nepheline, orthopyroxene, or quartz may be present. Adj. basaltic.

  • Concept URI token: basalt

1.2.2.11.26.8.5 Albasalt

  • Child of: basalt

  • An obsolete name proposed for a basalt with excess alumina and alkalis.

  • Concept URI token: albasalt

1.2.2.11.26.8.6 Alboranite

  • Child of: basalt

  • A variety of basalt containing phenocrysts of hypersthene (= enstatite), augite and calcic plagioclase in a groundmass of plagioclase, augite and glass.

  • Concept URI token: alboranite

1.2.2.11.26.8.7 Alkali basalt

  • Child of: basalt

  • A term used for basalts containing accessory foids. Such rocks generally contain plagioclase and augite and olivine as their main ferromagnesian phases. Defined as a variety of basalt within TAS field B which contains normative nepheline, or as field 10 in the QAPF diagram.

  • Alternate labels: Alkaline basalt

  • Concept URI token: alkali-basalt

1.2.2.11.26.8.8 Alkali olivine basalt

  • Child of: alkali-basalt

  • A subtype of alkali basalt characterised by abundant olivine, often as small phenocrysts.

  • Concept URI token: alkali-olivine-basalt

1.2.2.11.26.8.9 Amygdaloidal basalt

  • Child of: basalt

  • A field term for basalt containing amygdaloidal ‘nodules’ of calcite, agate, chalcedony or zeolite minerals.

  • Concept URI token: amygdaloidal-basalt

1.2.2.11.26.8.10 Arapahite

  • Child of: basalt

  • A type of basalt containing over 50% magnetite.

  • Concept URI token: arapahite

1.2.2.11.26.8.11 Basaltine

  • Child of: basalt

  • An obsolete term for a porphyritic or fine-grained variety of basalt.

  • Concept URI token: basaltine

1.2.2.11.26.8.12 Baslatite

  • Child of: basalt latite

  • An extrusive rock intermediate between basalt and latite.

  • Concept URI token: baslatite

1.2.2.11.26.8.13 Carmeloite

  • Child of: basalt

  • A local name for an iddingsite-bearing basalt.

  • Concept URI token: carmeloite

1.2.2.11.26.8.14 Flood basalt

  • Child of: basalt

  • A general term for basaltic lavas occurring in continental regions as vast accumulations of subhorizontal flows that have been erupted, probably from fissures, in rapid succession on a regional scale. Many of the lavas are transitional basalts, but tholeiitic basalts are also common.

  • Concept URI token: flood-basalt

1.2.2.11.26.8.15 Glassy basalt

  • Child of: basalt

  • A glassy volcanic rock of basaltic composition.

  • Concept URI token: glassy-basalt

1.2.2.11.26.8.16 High-Al ophitic basalt

  • Child of: basalt mare-basalt

  • A type of lunar basalt.

  • Concept URI token: high-al-ophitic-basalt

1.2.2.11.26.8.17 High-Ti basalt

  • Child of: basalt mare-basalt

  • Typical basalts of older mare lavas on the moon. They have 9-13% TiO2.

  • Concept URI token: high-ti-basalt

1.2.2.11.26.8.18 Low-Ti basalt

  • Child of: basalt mare-basalt

  • Typical basalts of younger mare lavas on the moon. They have 1-5% TiO2.

  • Concept URI token: low-ti-basalt

1.2.2.11.26.8.19 Ocean island basalts

  • Child of: basalt

  • Ocean island basalts (OIB) are basaltic rocks found on many volcanic islands away from tectonic plate boundaries, typically associated with hot spots. The chemical composition of these basalts can vary from tholeiite to alkali basalt within the same island group, but it is never calc-alkaline.

  • Concept URI token: ocean-island-basalts

1.2.2.11.26.8.20 Olivine basalt

  • Child of: basalt

  • A basalt containing olivine.

  • Concept URI token: olivine-basalt

1.2.2.11.26.8.21 Picritic-rock

  • Child of: basalt fine-grained-ultramafic-rock

  • Fine grained ultramafic or basaltic rocks with <53% SiO2, (Na2O+K2O)<2%, MgO>18%.

  • Alternate labels: High Magnesium Basalt, High Mg Basalt, High-Magnesium Basalt, High-Mg Basalt,

  • Concept URI token: picritic-rock

1.2.2.11.26.8.22 Komatiite

  • Child of: picritic-rock

  • Picritic rocks defined chemically as having <1% (Na2O+K2O) and <1% TiO2, or a field term for similar rocks exhibiting spinifex textures from skeletal olivine.The term was originally applied by Viljoen and Viljoen (1969) to basaltic and ultramafic lavas near the Komati river, Barberton Mountain Land, Transvaal, South Africa. Nickel-copper sulfide mineral deposits may be associated with komatiites.

  • Concept URI token: komatiite

1.2.2.11.26.8.23 Basaltic komatiite

  • Child of: komatiite

  • A member of the komatiite series with MgO in the range 5% to 15% typically displaying spinifex texture and evidence of rapid quenching of high-temperature magma. Chemically they are intermediate between tholeiitic basalt and boninite and are thought to have been komatiite magmas contaminated by crustal material.

  • Alternate labels: Komatiitic Basalt

  • Concept URI token: basaltic-komatiite

1.2.2.11.26.8.24 Meimechite

  • Child of: picritic-rock

  • Picritic rocks defined chemically as having <1% (Na2O+K2O) and >1% TiO2.

  • Concept URI token: meimechite

1.2.2.11.26.8.25 Picrite

  • Child of: picritic-rock

  • Picritic rocks defined chemically as having 1-2% (Na2O+K2O).

  • Concept URI token: picrite

1.2.2.11.26.8.26 Ferropicrite

  • Child of: picrite

  • A picrite wiht the total FeO exceeding 13% (originally proposed at 14%.)

  • Concept URI token: ferropicrite

1.2.2.11.26.8.27 Rhazite

  • Child of: basalt

  • An obsolete term for a fine-grained basalt containing a ferromagnesian mineral.

  • Concept URI token: rhazite

1.2.2.11.26.8.28 Subalkali basalt

  • Child of: basalt

  • A basalt lacking normative nepheline.

  • Concept URI token: subalkali-basalt

1.2.2.11.26.8.29 Calc-alkali basalt

  • Child of: subalkali-basalt

  • A variety of basalt associated with andesites and dacites in orogenic belts and island arcs.

  • Alternate labels: calc-alkaline basalt

  • Concept URI token: calc-alkali-basalt

1.2.2.11.26.8.30 Tholeiitic basalt

  • Child of: subalkali-basalt

  • A variety of basalt which is saturated or slightly oversaturated in silica with respect to alkalis. A silica-oversaturated (quartz- normative) basalt, characterized by the presence of low-calcium pyroxenes (orthopyroxene and/or pigeonite) in addition to clinopyroxene and calcic plagioclase. Olivine may be present in the mode, but neither olivine nor nepheline appear in the norm

  • Alternate labels: Tholeiite

  • Concept URI token: tholeiitic-basalt

1.2.2.11.26.8.31 Island arc basalt

  • Child of: tholeiitic-basalt

  • Basalts typical of intra-oceanic island arcs, abbreviated as IABs. IAB are characteristically enriched in large-ion-lithophile (LIL) elements (e.g., Sr, Rb, Ba and Pb) relative to the rare-earth elements and depleted in high-field-strength ions (e.g., Zr, Nb and Hf) relative to normal MORB (N-type) and Intra-plate basalts (IPB).

  • Concept URI token: island-arc-basalt

1.2.2.11.26.8.32 Mid-ocean-ridge basalt

  • Child of: tholeiitic-basalt

  • A variety of low Ti, low-K tholeiitic basalt. MORB (mid-ocean ridge basalt) is the most abundant volcanic rock type, it makes up much of the upper oceanic crust. The dominant basalts in Island arc and continental tholeiites are less mafic and more siliceous than MORB.

  • Concept URI token: mid-ocean-ridge-basalt

1.2.2.11.26.8.33 Transitional basalt

  • Child of: subalkali-basalt

  • A transitional basalt between tholeiitic basalt and alkali basalt.

  • Concept URI token: transitional-basalt

1.2.2.11.26.8.34 Foid-Bearing Andesite

  • Child of: basaltoid

  • Basaltoid Rock with a plagioclase to total feldspar ratio between 0.65 and 0.9 and a foid proportion between 0.0 and 0.1. QAPF field 9’

  • Concept URI token: foid-bearing-andesite

1.2.2.11.26.8.35 Foid-Bearing Basalt

  • Child of: basaltoid

  • Basaltoid Rock with a plagioclase to total feldspar ratio greater than 0.9 and a foid proportion between 0.0 and 0.1. QAPF field 10’

  • Concept URI token: foid-bearing-basalt

1.2.2.11.26.8.36 Quartz-Bearing Andesite

  • Child of: basaltoid

  • Basaltoid Rock with a plagioclase to total feldspar ratio between 0.65 and 0.9 and a quartz proportion between 0.05 and 0.2. QAPF field 9*

  • Concept URI token: quartz-bearing-andesite

1.2.2.11.26.8.37 Quartz-Bearing Basalt

  • Child of: basaltoid

  • Basaltoid Rock with a plagioclase to total feldspar ratiogreater than 0.9 and a quartz proportion between 0.05 and 0.2. QAPF field 10*

  • Concept URI token: quartz-bearing-basalt

1.2.2.11.26.8.38 Sakalavite

  • Child of: basaltoid

  • A local name for a quartz normative basaltic rock containing intermediate plagioclase, augite, opaques and plentiful glass.

  • Concept URI token: sakalavite

1.2.2.11.26.8.39 Variolite

  • Child of: basaltoid basic-volcanic-rock

  • An old term for basaltic rocks with a pock-marked appearance, composed of variolites (radial aggregates of feldspar and pyroxene microlites) in a microcrystalline or devitrified glassy base. The variolitic texture denotes rapid cooling and the quench growth of the crystals, such as is often found in submarine basalts, and should not be confused with spherulitic texture which indicates devitrification.

  • Concept URI token: variolite

1.2.2.11.26.9 Basanitoid

  • Child of: extrusive-igneous-rock

  • A term originally used for volcanic rocks intermediate between olivine basalt and basanite. Has also been used for rocks with the composition of basanite but without modal nepheline.

  • Concept URI token: basanitoid

1.2.2.11.26.10 Basic volcanic rock

  • Child of: extrusive-igneous-rock

  • A chemical classification based on the TAS diagram for normal volcanic rocks with between 45 and 52 wt % SiO2. This includes, foidite (only some very high Na^2O + K^2O wt %), basalt, phonotephrite (in part), tracybasalt, basaltic trachyandesite (in part) and tephriphonolite (in part).

  • Concept URI token: basic-volcanic-rock

1.2.2.11.26.10.1 Allgovite

  • Child of: basaltoid basic-volcanic-rock

  • An obsolete name temporarily proposed for a group of basaltic rocks which could not be classified as melaphyres or trapps as their age was unknown.

  • Concept URI token: allgovite

1.2.2.11.26.10.2 Anamesite

  • Child of: basaltoid basic-volcanic-rock

  • An obsolete term for basaltic rocks which are between basalt and dolerite in texture.

  • Concept URI token: anamesite

1.2.2.11.26.10.3 Angarite

  • Child of: basaltoid basic-volcanic-rock

  • A local name for Siberian basalts and dolerites.

  • Concept URI token: angarite

1.2.2.11.26.10.4 Basalt

  • Child of: basaltoid basic-volcanic-rock

  • A mafite or basaltoid containing mostly calcic plagioclase, clinopyroxene +/- olivine, foids, oxides and rarely quartz.A general term for fine-grained, mafic (dark-colored) igneous rocks, commonly extrusive (volcanic) but locally intrusive (e.g., as dikes or pipes), composed chiefly of plagioclase and clinopyroxene; the fine-grained equivalent of gabbro. Olivine and iron-titanium oxides are very common and nepheline, orthopyroxene, or quartz may be present. Adj. basaltic.

  • Concept URI token: basalt

1.2.2.11.26.10.5 Albasalt

  • Child of: basalt

  • An obsolete name proposed for a basalt with excess alumina and alkalis.

  • Concept URI token: albasalt

1.2.2.11.26.10.31 Island arc basalt

  • Child of: tholeiitic-basalt

  • Basalts typical of intra-oceanic island arcs, abbreviated as IABs. IAB are characteristically enriched in large-ion-lithophile (LIL) elements (e.g., Sr, Rb, Ba and Pb) relative to the rare-earth elements and depleted in high-field-strength ions (e.g., Zr, Nb and Hf) relative to normal MORB (N-type) and Intra-plate basalts (IPB).

  • Concept URI token: island-arc-basalt

1.2.2.11.26.10.32 Mid-ocean-ridge basalt

  • Child of: tholeiitic-basalt

  • A variety of low Ti, low-K tholeiitic basalt. MORB (mid-ocean ridge basalt) is the most abundant volcanic rock type, it makes up much of the upper oceanic crust. The dominant basalts in Island arc and continental tholeiites are less mafic and more siliceous than MORB.

  • Concept URI token: mid-ocean-ridge-basalt

1.2.2.11.26.10.33 Transitional basalt

  • Child of: subalkali-basalt

  • A transitional basalt between tholeiitic basalt and alkali basalt.

  • Concept URI token: transitional-basalt

1.2.2.11.26.10.34 Trachybasalt

  • Child of: basic-volcanic-rock trachytoid

  • A alkaline/basic extrusive rock intermediate in composition between trachyte and basalt, difficult to define without the TAS diagram. Characterized by the presence of both calcic plagioclase and alkali feldspar, along with clinopyroxene, olivine, and possibly minor analcime or leucite. Approx. synonymous with hawaiite.

  • Concept URI token: trachybasalt

1.2.2.11.26.10.35 Anorthoclase basalt

  • Child of: trachybasalt

  • A variety of trachybasalt containing phenocrysts of anorthoclase, augite and enstatite in a groundmass of these minerals, labradorite and opaques.

  • Concept URI token: anorthoclase-basalt

1.2.2.11.26.10.36 Hawaiite

  • Child of: trachybasalt

  • A sodium-rich trachybasalt where Na2O-2>K2O

  • Concept URI token: hawaiite

1.2.2.11.26.10.37 Potassic-trachybasalt

  • Child of: trachybasalt

  • A potassium-rich trachybasalt where Na2O-2<K2O

  • Alternate labels: Potassic trachybasalt

  • Concept URI token: potassic-trachybasalt

1.2.2.11.26.10.38 Variolite

  • Child of: basaltoid basic-volcanic-rock

  • An old term for basaltic rocks with a pock-marked appearance, composed of variolites (radial aggregates of feldspar and pyroxene microlites) in a microcrystalline or devitrified glassy base. The variolitic texture denotes rapid cooling and the quench growth of the crystals, such as is often found in submarine basalts, and should not be confused with spherulitic texture which indicates devitrification.

  • Concept URI token: variolite

1.2.2.11.26.11 Craignurite

  • Child of: extrusive-igneous-rock

  • A local Hebridian name for a series of volcanic rocks occurring as cone sheets and ranging in composition from intermediate to acid, characterized by acicular and skeletal crystals of plagioclase, augite and hornblende in a felsic groundmass.

  • Concept URI token: craignurite

1.2.2.11.26.12 Dacitoid

  • Child of: extrusive-igneous-rock

  • Rocks tentatively identified as dacite, with felsics comprising >20% quartz and alkali feldspar/plagioclase <0.5

  • Alternate labels: Dacitic-rock, Intermediate Intrusive,

  • Concept URI token: dacitoid

1.2.2.11.26.12.1 Dacite

  • Child of: acid-volcanic-rock dacitoid

  • Dacitic rocks with felsics comprising >20% quartz and alkali feldspar/plagioclase <0.5. QAPF#4A fine-grained extrusive rock with a similar general composition to andesite, but having a more sodic plagioclase and more K-feldspar and quartz; it is the extrusive equivalent of granodiorite.

  • Alternate labels: Aphyric Dacite, quartz andesite,

  • Concept URI token: dacite

1.2.2.11.26.12.2 Ambonite

  • Child of: andesitoid dacite

  • A local collective name for a series of andesites and dacites containing cordierite possibly formed by assimilation of sillimanite- cordierite gneiss.

  • Concept URI token: ambonite

1.2.2.11.26.12.3 Cryptodacite

  • Child of: andesitoid dacite

  • A dacite with a glassy groundmass.

  • Concept URI token: cryptodacite

1.2.2.11.26.12.4 Porphyritic Andesite

  • Child of: dacite

  • A porphyritic variety of rhyolite.

  • Alternate labels: Andesite Porphyry, Andesitic Porphyry,

  • Concept URI token: porphyritic-andesite

1.2.2.11.26.12.5 Porphyritic Dacite

  • Child of: dacite

  • A porphyritic variety of rhyolite.

  • Alternate labels: Dacite Porphyry, Dacitic Porphyry, Intermediate Porphyry,

  • Concept URI token: porphyritic-dacite

1.2.2.11.26.12.6 Plagidacite

  • Child of: dacitoid

  • A Dacitic Rock with a plagioclase to total feldspare ratio greater than 0.9.

  • Concept URI token: plagidacite

1.2.2.11.26.12.7 Rhyodacite

  • Child of: dacitoid rhyolitoid

  • Rocks intermediate between rhyolite and dacite, containing >10% quartz and subequal amounts of plagioclase and alkali feldspar. The extrusive equivalent of granodiorite. The principal minerals, sodic plagioclase, K-feldspar, quartz, and biotite or hornblende, commonly occur as phenocrysts in a finely crystalline groundmass of feldspar and quartz. Accessory minerals are apatite and magnetite, and occasionally augite.

  • Alternate labels: Dellenite

  • Concept URI token: rhyodacite

1.2.2.11.26.12.8 Dellenitoid

  • Child of: rhyodacite

  • A rhyodacite with no visible orthoclase.

  • Concept URI token: dellenitoid

1.2.2.11.26.13 Felsite

  • Child of: extrusive-igneous-rock

  • As a rock term initially used for the microcrystalline groundmass of porphyries but now more commonly used for microcrystalline rocks of granitic composition. The name had previously been used by Kirwan

  1. for a microcrystalline variety of feldspar. Synonym of: felstone, aphanite

  • Alternate labels: Felsic rock, Felsites, Felstone,

  • Concept URI token: felsite

1.2.2.11.26.13.1 Albite felsite

  • Child of: felsite

  • A felsite rich in albite.

  • Concept URI token: albite-felsite

1.2.2.11.26.14 Foiditoid

  • Child of: extrusive-igneous-rock

  • Fine grained igneous rocks with >60% foids.

  • Alternate labels: Foiditic-rock

  • Concept URI token: foiditoid

1.2.2.11.26.14.1 Basanitic-foidite

  • Child of: foiditoid

  • Foiditoids with felsics comprising 60-90% foids and alkali feldspar/total feldspar <0.5, olivine >10%

  • Concept URI token: basanitic-foidite

1.2.2.11.26.14.2 Basanitic-analcimite

  • Child of: basanitic-foidite

  • Analcimitic rock with foids (mostly analcime) constituing 60 to 90% of light-coloured constituents and plagioclase > alkali feldspar.

  • Concept URI token: basanitic-analcimite

1.2.2.11.26.14.3 Basanitic-hauynite

  • Child of: basanitic-foidite

  • Hauynitic rock with foids (mostly hauyne) constituing 60 to 90% of light-coloured constituents and plagioclase > alkali feldspar.

  • Concept URI token: basanitic-hauynite

  • Child of: basanitic-foidite

  • Leucitic rock with foids (mostly leucite) constituing 60 to 90% of light-coloured constituents and plagioclase > alkali feldspar.

  • Child of: basanitic-foidite

  • Concept URI token: basanitic-nephelinite

1.2.2.11.26.14.6 Foidite

  • Child of: foiditoid

  • Fine grained igneous rocks that contain <90% mafics and foids >90% of felsics.

  • Alternate labels: Feldspathoidite

  • Concept URI token: foidite

1.2.2.11.26.14.7 Analcimite

  • Child of: foidite

  • A fine to medium grained, extrusive or hypabyssal igneous rock consisting mainly of analcime and pyroxene (usually titanaugite). Other feldspathoids, plagioclase, and/or olivine may be present. Apatite, sphene, and opaque oxides may be present as accessories. On the QAPF diagram, it is a foidite consisting of >90% feldspathoids, mostly analcime, with <10% mafic minerals.

  • Concept URI token: analcimite

1.2.2.11.26.14.8 Augite analcimite

  • Child of: analcimite

  • A analcimite containing augite.

  • Concept URI token: augite-analcimite

1.2.2.11.26.14.9 Baldite

  • Child of: augite-analcimite

  • A variety of analcimite composed essentially of analcime and titanian augite with minor olivine and opaques. The rock was originally called analcime basalt.

  • Concept URI token: baldite

1.2.2.11.26.14.10 Leucocratic analcimite

  • Child of: analcimite

  • A monomineralic volcanic rock consisting of analcime.

  • Concept URI token: leucocratic-analcimite

1.2.2.11.26.14.11 Blairmorite

  • Child of: leucocratic-analcimite

  • A leucocratic variety of analcimite with phenocrysts of analcime in a groundmass of analcime and aegirine-augite with minor nepheline, sanidine and melanite garnet.

  • Concept URI token: blairmorite

1.2.2.11.26.14.12 Olivine analcimite

  • Child of: analcimite

  • A analcimite containing olivine.

  • Concept URI token: olivine-analcimite

1.2.2.11.26.14.13 Haueynophyre

  • Child of: foidite

  • An extrusive fine grained igneous rock similar in composition to a leucitophyre but containing hauyne in place of the leucite. Other subordinate phases may include nepheline, augite, magnetite, apatite, melilite, and mica. A partial syn. of haueynitite; some rocks are called haueynophyre when hauyne is a conspicuous mineral but not necessarily a major constituent.

  • Concept URI token: haueynophyre

1.2.2.11.26.14.14 Hauynite

  • Child of: foidite

  • A foidite consisting essentially of hauyne with <10% mafic minerals.

  • Concept URI token: hauyite

  • Child of: foidite ultrapotassic-rock

1.2.2.11.26.14.18 Leucitite (s.s.)

  • Child of: leucitite

  • Leucitic rock with foids (mostly leucite) constituing 90 to 100% of light-coloured constituents. Leucite is the only, or virtually the only, felspathoid mineral.

  • Concept URI token: leucitite-ss

  • Concept URI token: cecilite

1.2.2.11.26.14.22 Lutalite

  • Child of: leucitite

  • An obsolete name for a variety of leucitite composed essentially of clinopyroxene and leucite and with subordinate olivine, nepheline and plagioclase. The value of Na2O/K2O is higher than in ordinary leucitites.

  • Concept URI token: lutalite

1.2.2.11.26.14.25 leucitophyre

  • Child of: foidite

  • Concept URI token: leucitophyre

1.2.2.11.26.14.26 Nephelinite

  • Child of: foidite rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • A foidite consisting mostly of nepheline with <10% mafic minerals.A fine-grained or porphyritic extrusive or hypabyssal rock, of basaltic character, but primarily composed of nepheline and clinopyroxene, esp. titanaugite, and lacking olivine and feldspar.

  • Concept URI token: nephelinite

1.2.2.11.26.14.42 Braccianite

  • Child of: tephritic-leucitite

  • An aphyric variety of tephritic leucitite essentially composed of leucite and clinopyroxene in about equal proportions with small amounts of plagioclase. Minor olivine and nepheline may be present.

  • Concept URI token: braccianite

1.2.2.11.26.15 Intermediate volcanic rock

  • Child of: extrusive-igneous-rock

  • A chemical classification based on the TAS diagram for normal volcanic rocks with between 52 and 63 wt % SiO2.This includes, basaltic-andesite, andesite, phonotephrite (in part), trachyandesite, basaltic trachyandesite (in part), phonolite (in part), trachyte (in part), trachydacite (in part) and tephriphonolite (in part).

  • Alternate labels: Intermediate Rock, Intermediate Volcanic, Intermediate Volcanics,

  • Concept URI token: intermediate-volcanic-rock

1.2.2.11.26.15.1 Andesite

  • Child of: andesitoid intermediate-volcanic-rock

  • A dark-colored, fine-grained, mostly extrusive rock that is approximately the fine-grained equivalent of diorite. When porphyritic, andesite rocks contain phenocrysts composed primarily of zoned sodic plagioclase and one or more mafic minerals (usually <20%), with a groundmass of similar composition, although the plagioclase may be more sodic, and generally small amounts of quartz. Andesitic rocks plot on the QAPF diagram with 0-20% quartz, and >65% of feldspars being plagioclase; on the TAS diagram: <57-63% SiO2, (Na2O+K2O)<~6%

  • Concept URI token: andesite

1.2.2.11.26.15.2 Amphibole-enstatite andesite

  • Child of: andesite

  • A variety of andesite.

  • Concept URI token: amphibole-enstatite-andesite

  • Concept URI token: andelatite

1.2.2.11.26.15.4 Asperite

  • Child of: andesite

  • An obsolete field term for a variety of andesite with trachytic character.

  • Concept URI token: asperite

1.2.2.11.26.15.8 Bajaite

  • Child of: boninite

  • Originally used as bajaite series rocks the term is now used as a rock name for a variety of boninite with MgO ‰ˆ 8%, SiO2 ‰ˆ 56% and characterized by high contents of Sr (> 1000 ppm) and high K/Rb ratios (> 1000). It was originally described as a magnesian andesite.

  • Concept URI token: bajaite

1.2.2.11.26.15.21 Bajaite

  • Child of: boninite

  • Originally used as bajaite series rocks the term is now used as a rock name for a variety of boninite with MgO ‰ˆ 8%, SiO2 ‰ˆ 56% and characterized by high contents of Sr (> 1000 ppm) and high K/Rb ratios (> 1000). It was originally described as a magnesian andesite.

  • Concept URI token: bajaite

1.2.2.11.26.15.22 Icelandite

  • Child of: intermediate-volcanic-rock

  • A variety of intermediate volcanic rock containing phenocrysts of andesine, clinopyroxene and/or orthopyroxene and/or pigeonite and less commonly olivine in a groundmass of the same minerals. It differs chemically from a typical orogenic andesite in being poorer in alumina and richer in iron.

  • Concept URI token: icelandite

1.2.2.11.26.15.23 Duncanite

  • Child of: icelandite

  • A icelandite where the groundmass plagioclase is andesine

  • Concept URI token: duncanite

1.2.2.11.26.16 Mafic volcanic rock

  • Child of: extrusive-igneous-rock

  • A field name for darker volcanic rocks dominated by mafic minerals.

  • Alternate labels: Basic / Mafic Volcanic, Basic/Mafic Vocanic, Mafite, mafic rock, mafic volcanic, mafic, mafites,

  • Concept URI token: mafic-volcanic-rock

1.2.2.11.26.17 Melaphyre

  • Child of: extrusive-igneous-rock

  • A very old name replacing trapporphyr and originally used for amygdaloidal rocks composed of plagioclase and augite but later used for Upper Palaeozoic rocks, usually basaltic.

  • Concept URI token: melaphyre

1.2.2.11.26.18 Phonolitoid

  • Child of: extrusive-igneous-rock

  • Mafites tentatively identified as phonolite, with felsics comprising 10-60% foids and alkali feldspar/total feldspar >0.5, <10% olivine.

  • Alternate labels: Phonolitic-rock

  • Concept URI token: phonolitoid

1.2.2.11.26.18.1 Phonolite

  • Child of: phonolitoid

  • Phonolitic rocks, with felsics comprising 10-60% foids and alkali feldspar/total feldspar >0.9.The extrusive or fine grained equivalent of nepheline syenite. The principal mineral is anorthoclase or sanidine. Other major minerals may be nepheline, aegirine and diopside, usually with other feldspathoidal minerals such as sodalite or hauyne. Accessories include apatite and sphene.

  • Concept URI token: phonolite

1.2.2.11.26.18.2 Analcime-phonolite

  • Child of: phonolite

  • Phonolite containing primary analcime

  • Concept URI token: analcime-phonolite

1.2.2.11.26.18.3 Hauyne-phonolite

  • Child of: phonolite

  • Phonolite, with hauyne the dominant foid.

  • Concept URI token: hauyne-phonolite

1.2.2.11.26.18.4 Leucite-phonolite

  • Child of: phonolite

  • A phonolite containing leucite.

  • Concept URI token: leucite-phonolite

1.2.2.11.26.18.5 Muniongite

  • Child of: phonolite

  • A variety of phonolite with phenocrysts of nepheline in a groundmass of sanidine, aegirine-augite and glass.

  • Concept URI token: muniongite

1.2.2.11.26.18.6 Nepheline-phonolite

  • Child of: phonolite

  • Concept URI token: nepheline-phonolite

1.2.2.11.26.18.9 Boderite

  • Child of: nosean-phonolite

  • A term proposed for a melanocratic variety of nosean phonolite, originally called a nosean sanidine biotite augitite, with more alkali feldspar than nosean, biotite and augite.

  • Concept URI token: boderite

1.2.2.11.26.18.10 Rodderite

  • Child of: nosean-phonolite noseanolite

  • A melanocratic variety of nosean phonolite or noseanolite, with more nosean than alkali feldspar, biotite and augite.

  • Concept URI token: rodderite

1.2.2.11.26.18.11 Peralkaline phonolite

  • Child of: phonolite

  • A variety of phonolite of QAPF field 11 that contains alkali pyroxene and/or alkali amphibole and/or a variety of phonolite of TAS field Ph that has a peralkaline index > 1.

  • Concept URI token: peralkaline-phonolite

1.2.2.11.26.18.12 Apachite

  • Child of: peralkaline-phonolite

  • A variety of peralkaline phonolite rich in sodic amphiboles and containing sodic pyroxene and aenigmatite.

  • Alternate labels: Apachite (of Osann)

  • Concept URI token: apachite

1.2.2.11.26.18.13 Tinguaite

  • Child of: phonolite

  • A variety of phonolite consisting of alkali feldspar, nepheline with or without other foids, aegirine and sometimes biotite and characterized by ‘tinguaitic texture’ in which needles of aegirine occur interstitially in a mosaic of alkali feldspar and foids.

  • Concept URI token: tinguaite

1.2.2.11.26.18.14 Tephritic-phonolite

  • Child of: phonolitoid

  • Phonolitic rocks, with felsics comprising 60-90% foids and alkali feldspar/total feldspar 0.9-0.5

  • Alternate labels: Tephri-phonolite, Tephriphonolite, Tephritic phonolite,

  • Concept URI token: tephritic-phonolite

1.2.2.11.26.18.15 Guardiaite

  • Child of: tephritic-phonolite

  • A variety of tephritic phonolite or nepheline-bearing latite containing plagioclase phenocrysts mantled with alkali feldspar in a groundmass of essential nepheline, augite, biotite and glass.

  • Concept URI token: guardiaite

1.2.2.11.26.18.16 Tautirite

  • Child of: tephritic-phonolite

  • A type of tephritic phonolite consisting of small phenocrysts of hornblende, titanite, augite and biotite in a groundmass of alkali feldspar and andesine with some nepheline and sodalite.

  • Concept URI token: tautirite

1.2.2.11.26.18.17 Tephritic-leucite-phonolite

  • Child of: tephritic-phonolite

  • A tephritic-phonolite where leucite is the predominant foid.

  • Concept URI token: tephritic-leucite-phonolite

1.2.2.11.26.18.18 Columbretite

  • Child of: tephritic-leucite-phonolite

  • A tephritic-leucite-phonolite composed of alkali feldspar and plagioclase with minor leucite/analcime, clinopyroxene and amphibole.

  • Concept URI token: columbretite

1.2.2.11.26.19 Pillow lava

  • Child of: extrusive-igneous-rock

  • Pillow lava forms where lava erupts into water - most notably mid- ocean ridges and marine hotspot volcanoes, but they can also be formed by eruptions into fresh water. Mostly basaltic in composition, but andesite, komatiite, picrite, boninite, basaltic andesite, andesite, dacite and even rhyolite pillow lavas are known. They form as the lava cools on contact with water to form a lobe with a thin glassy skin, which then expands until the pressure of lava forces the skin to break allowing the lava to escape and start a new lobe, or pillow.

  • Concept URI token: pillow-lava

1.2.2.11.26.20 Rhombporphyry

  • Child of: extrusive-igneous-rock

  • A term applied to rocks which vary in composition from porphyritic trachytes to trachyandesites and carry rhomb-shaped phenocrysts of feldspar.

  • Concept URI token: rhombporphyry

1.2.2.11.26.21 Rhyolitoid

  • Child of: extrusive-igneous-rock

  • Felsites (acid volcanic rocks) tentatively identified as rhyolite, with felsic minerals comprising >20% quartz and alkali feldspar/plagioclase 40-100%

  • Alternate labels: Rhyolitic-rock

  • Concept URI token: rhyolitoid

1.2.2.11.26.21.1 Alkali-feldspar-rhyolite

  • Child of: rhyolitoid

  • A rhyolitoid where plagioclase is less than 10% of the total feldspar. QAPF#2

  • Alternate labels: Alkali feldspar rhyolite, Rhyolite - Alkali-Feldspar,

  • Concept URI token: alkali-feldspar-rhyolite

1.2.2.11.26.21.2 Rhyodacite

  • Child of: dacitoid rhyolitoid

  • Rocks intermediate between rhyolite and dacite, containing >10% quartz and subequal amounts of plagioclase and alkali feldspar. The extrusive equivalent of granodiorite. The principal minerals, sodic plagioclase, K-feldspar, quartz, and biotite or hornblende, commonly occur as phenocrysts in a finely crystalline groundmass of feldspar and quartz. Accessory minerals are apatite and magnetite, and occasionally augite.

  • Alternate labels: Dellenite

  • Concept URI token: rhyodacite

1.2.2.11.26.21.3 Dellenitoid

  • Child of: rhyodacite

  • A rhyodacite with no visible orthoclase.

  • Concept URI token: dellenitoid

1.2.2.11.26.21.4 Rhyolite

  • Child of: acid-volcanic-rock rhyolitoid

  • Rhyolite, with felsic minerals comprising >20% quartz and alkali feldspar/plagioclase 40-90%. QAPF#3A group of extrusive igneous rocks, typically porphyritic and commonly exhibiting flow texture, with phenocrysts of quartz and alkali feldspar in a glassy to cryptocrystalline groundmass; also, any rock in that group; the extrusive equivalent of granite. Rhyolite grades into rhyodacite with decreasing alkali feldspar content and into trachyte with a decrease in quartz.

  • Alternate labels: Aphyric Rhyolite, Liparite,

  • Concept URI token: rhyolite

1.2.2.11.26.21.5 Aporhyolite

  • Child of: rhyolite

  • A rhyolite, the groundmass of which was once glassy but has become devitrified.

  • Concept URI token: aporhyolite

1.2.2.11.26.21.6 Baulite

  • Child of: rhyolite

  • A variety of rhyolite.

  • Concept URI token: baulite

1.2.2.11.26.21.7 Crocodile Jasper

  • Child of: rhyolite

  • A tradename for a greenish colored volcanic rhyolite rock quarried by Norcross in Madagascar. The rock consist of the minerals quartz, pyroxene (aegirine), albite, and K feldspar. The characteristic, blackish, rounded aggregates consist of needles of amphiboles (riebeckite to paragasite in composition).

  • Concept URI token: crocodile-jasper

1.2.2.11.26.21.8 Nevadite

  • Child of: rhyolite

  • A variety of RhyoliteA highly porphyritic variety of rhyolite, rich in quartz phenocrysts. Not to be confused with the mineral nevadaite.

  • Concept URI token: nevadite

1.2.2.11.26.21.9 Pantelleritic rhyolite

  • Child of: rhyolite

  • A variety of peralkaline rhyolite of TAS field R in which Al2O3 <1.33 x total iron as FeO + 4.4. A peralkaline rhyolite or quartz trachyte with normative quartz exceeding 10%. It is more mafic than comendite.

  • Alternate labels: Pantellerite

  • Concept URI token: pantelleritic-rhyolite

1.2.2.11.26.21.10 Peralkaline rhyolite

  • Child of: rhyolite

  • A rhyolite containing alkali pyroxenes or amphiboles, or with (Na2O+K2O)>Al2O3.

  • Alternate labels: Alkali rhyolite

  • Concept URI token: peralkaline-rhyolite

1.2.2.11.26.21.11 Comenditic rhyolite

  • Child of: peralkaline-rhyolite

  • A variety of peralkaline rhyolite of TAS field R in which Al2O3 > 1.33 x total iron as FeO + 4.4. A sodic rhyolite containing alkalic amphibole and/or pyroxene.

  • Alternate labels: Comendite, Commendite,

  • Concept URI token: comenditic-rhyolite

1.2.2.11.26.21.12 Porphyritic rhyolite

  • Child of: rhyolite

  • A porphyritic variety of rhyolite.

  • Alternate labels: Rhyolite Porphyry

  • Concept URI token: porphyritic-rhyolite

1.2.2.11.26.21.13 Beschtauite

  • Child of: porphyritic-rhyolite

  • A porphyritic rhyolite containing phenocrysts of sanidine and oligoclase.

  • Concept URI token: beschtauite

1.2.2.11.26.21.14 Rhyolitic crystal tuff

  • Child of: rhyolite

  • A crystal tuff of rhyolite composition.

  • Concept URI token: rhyolitic-crystal-tuff

1.2.2.11.26.21.15 Smalto

  • Child of: rhyolite

  • A local Italian name for a glassy rhyolite from Lipari Island.

  • Concept URI token: smalto

1.2.2.11.26.22 Tephritoid

  • Child of: extrusive-igneous-rock

  • Mafites tentatively identified as tephrite, with felsics comprising 10-60% foids and alkali feldspar/total feldspar <0.5, <10% olivine

  • Alternate labels: Tephritic-rock

  • Concept URI token: tephritoid

  • Colour:BlackTephritic rocks, with felsics comprising 10-60% foids and alkali feldspar/total feldspar <0.1, >10% olivineA black flinty jasper or chert once used for estimating the purity of gold alloys.Not to be confused with bassanite, the mineral, or basanite, the basaltic rock.

1.2.2.11.26.22.14 Tephrite

  • Child of: tephritoid

  • Tephritic rocks, with felsics comprising 10-60% foids and alkali feldspar/total feldspar <0.1, <10% olivine.A group of extrusive rocks, of basaltic character, primarily composed of calcic plagioclase, augite, and nepheline or leucite as the main feldspathoids, with accessory alkali feldspar; also, any member of that group; the extrusive equivalent of theralite. With the addition of olivine, the rock would be called a basanite.

  • Concept URI token: tephrite

1.2.2.11.26.22.15 Leucite-tephrite

  • Child of: tephrite

  • A leucite-rich tephrite comprising mostly leucite, clinopyroxene and plagioclase

  • Concept URI token: leucite-tephrite

  • Concept URI token: analcime-tephrite

1.2.2.11.26.22.17 Dancalite

  • Child of: analcime-tephrite

  • Concept URI token: dancalite

1.2.2.11.26.22.18 Campanite

  • Child of: leucite-tephrite

  • A variety of leucite tephrite with large leucite crystals associated with essential plagioclase and clinopyroxene with minor sanidine, nepheline and hauyne.

  • Concept URI token: campanite

1.2.2.11.26.22.19 Kivite

1.2.2.11.26.22.23 Buchonite

1.2.2.11.26.23 Trachytoid

  • Child of: extrusive-igneous-rock

  • Rocks tentatively identified as trachyte, with felsics comprising <20% quartz, <10%foids and plagioclase/alkali feldspar <2.

  • Alternate labels: Trachytic-rock

  • Concept URI token: trachytoid

1.2.2.11.26.23.1 Alkali feldspar trachytic rock

  • Child of: trachytoid

  • Trachytoid that has a plagioclase to total feldspar ratio less than 0.1. QAPF fields 6, 6’, and 6*.

  • Concept URI token: alkali-feldspar-trachytic-rock

1.2.2.11.26.23.2 Alkali-feldspar-trachyte

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-trachytic-rock

  • A trachytoid where plagioclase is less than 10% of the total feldspar.

  • Alternate labels: Alkali feldspar trachyte, Trachyte - Alkalifeldspar,

  • Concept URI token: alkali-feldspar-trachyte

1.2.2.11.26.23.3 Foid-bearing-alkali-feldspar-trachyte

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-trachytic-rock

  • Trachytic rocks, with felsics comprising 0-10% foids and alkali feldspar/total feldspar >0.9

  • Alternate labels: Foid-bearing alkali feldspar trachyte

  • Concept URI token: foid-bearing-alkali-feldspar-trachyte

1.2.2.11.26.23.4 Quartz-alkali-feldspar-trachyte

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-trachytic-rock

  • Trachytic rocks, with felsics comprising 5-20% quartz and alkali feldspar/total feldspar >0.9

  • Alternate labels: Quartz alkali feldspar trachyte

  • Concept URI token: quartz-alkali-feldspar-trachyte

1.2.2.11.26.23.5 Basaltic-trachyandesite

  • Child of: trachytoid

  • A alkaline/basic rocktype intermediate between andesite and phonolite.

  • Alternate labels: Basaltic trachyandesite

  • Concept URI token: basaltic-trachyandesite

1.2.2.11.26.23.6 Mugearite

  • Child of: basaltic-trachyandesite

  • A sodic basaltic-trachybasalt where Na2O-2>K2O.

  • Concept URI token: mugearite

1.2.2.11.26.23.7 Shoshonite

  • Child of: basaltic-trachyandesite

  • Named after the Shoshone River, WY.A potassic basaltic- trachyandesite where Na2O-22O.A trachyandesite composed of olivine and augite phenocrysts in a groundmass of labradorite with alkali feldspar rims, olivine, augite, a small amount of leucite, and some dark- colored glass.

  • Concept URI token: shoshonite

1.2.2.11.26.23.8 Absarokite

  • Child of: shoshonite

  • A basaltic-trachyandesite rock containing phenocrysts of olivine and augite in a groundmass of augite, calcic plagioclase, alkali feldspar and sometimes leucite.

  • Concept URI token: absarokite

1.2.2.11.26.23.9 Latitic rock

  • Child of: trachytoid

  • Trachytoid that has a plagioclase to total feldspar ratio between 0.35 and 0.65. QAPF fields 8, 8’ and 8*.

  • Concept URI token: latitic-rock

1.2.2.11.26.23.10 Foid-bearing-latite

  • Child of: latitic-rock trachyandesite

  • Trachytic rocks, with felsics comprising 0-10% foids and alkali feldspar/total feldspar 0.35-0.65

  • Alternate labels: Foid-bearing latite

  • Concept URI token: foid-bearing-latite

1.2.2.11.26.23.11 Latite

  • Child of: latitic-rock trachyandesite

  • Trachytic rocks, with felsics comprising 0-5% quartz and alkali feldspar/total feldspar 0.35-0.65. Also a potassic trachyandesite where Na2O-22O.A porphyritic extrusive rock having phenocrysts of plagioclase and potassium feldspar in nearly equal amounts, little or no quartz, and a finely crystalline to glassy groundmass, which may contain obscure potassium feldspar; the extrusive equivalent of monzonite.

  • Concept URI token: latite

1.2.2.11.26.23.12 Andelatite

  • Child of: andesite latite

  • An extrusive rock intermediate between andesite and latite.

  • Concept URI token: andelatite

1.2.2.11.26.23.13 Baslatite

  • Child of: basalt latite

  • An extrusive rock intermediate between basalt and latite.

  • Concept URI token: baslatite

1.2.2.11.26.23.14 Quartz-latite

  • Child of: latitic-rock

  • Trachytic rocks, with felsics comprising 5-20% quartz and alkali feldspar/total feldspar 0.35-0.65.This is compositionally equivalent to the coarse-grained rock quartz-monzonite.

  • Alternate labels: Quartz latite

  • Concept URI token: quartz-latite

1.2.2.11.26.23.15 Coloradoite

  • Child of: quartz-latite

  • A variety of quartz latite that corresponds to the opdalitic magma- type of Niggli (1923).

  • Alternate labels: Coloradoite (of Niggli)

  • Concept URI token: coloradoite

1.2.2.11.26.23.16 Trachyandesite

  • Child of: trachytoid

  • A alkaline/basic rocktype intermediate between basaltic andesite and phonolite, difficult to define without the TAS diagram.An extrusive rock, intermediate in composition between trachyte and andesite, with sodic plagioclase, alkali feldspar, and one or more mafic minerals (biotite, amphibole, or pyroxene).

  • Alternate labels: Alkali andesite, Alkaliandesite, Etnaite, Trachy andesite,

  • Concept URI token: trachyandesite

1.2.2.11.26.23.17 Banakite

  • Child of: trachyandesite

  • A trachyandesitic or basaltic rock containing phenocrysts of augite and sometimes olivine in a groundmass of calcic plagioclase (labradorite-andesine) with alkali feldspar (sanidine) rims, plus augite, biotite, analcime, leucite, opaques and possibly quartz. Banakite grades into shoshonite with an increase in olivine and clinopyroxene and decreasing alkali feldspar, and into absarokite with more olivine and clinopyroxene.

  • Concept URI token: banakite

1.2.2.11.26.23.18 Benmoreite

  • Child of: trachyandesite

  • A sodic trachyandesite where Na2O-2>K2O.

  • Concept URI token: benmoreite

1.2.2.11.26.23.19 Doreite

  • Child of: trachyandesite

  • A type of trachyandesite characterized by micro-phenocrysts of andesine and augite.

  • Concept URI token: doreite

1.2.2.11.26.23.20 Dumalite

  • Child of: trachyandesite

  • A variety of trachyandesite with an intersertal texture and a glassy groundmass of nepheline composition.

  • Concept URI token: dumalite

1.2.2.11.26.23.21 Foid-bearing-latite

  • Child of: latitic-rock trachyandesite

Also a potassic trachyandesite where Na2O-22O.A porphyritic extrusive rock having phenocrysts of plagioclase and potassium feldspar in nearly equal amounts, little or no quartz, and a finely crystalline to glassy groundmass, which may contain obscure potassium feldspar; the extrusive equivalent of monzonite.

1.2.2.11.26.23.27 Trachybasalt

  • Child of: basic-volcanic-rock trachytoid

  • A alkaline/basic extrusive rock intermediate in composition between trachyte and basalt, difficult to define without the TAS diagram. Characterized by the presence of both calcic plagioclase and alkali feldspar, along with clinopyroxene, olivine, and possibly minor analcime or leucite. Approx. synonymous with hawaiite.

  • Concept URI token: trachybasalt

1.2.2.11.26.23.28 Anorthoclase basalt

  • Child of: trachybasalt

  • A variety of trachybasalt containing phenocrysts of anorthoclase, augite and enstatite in a groundmass of these minerals, labradorite and opaques.

  • Concept URI token: anorthoclase-basalt

1.2.2.11.26.23.29 Hawaiite

  • Child of: trachybasalt

  • A sodium-rich trachybasalt where Na2O-2>K2O

  • Concept URI token: hawaiite

1.2.2.11.26.23.30 Potassic-trachybasalt

  • Child of: trachybasalt

  • A potassium-rich trachybasalt where Na2O-2<K2O

  • Alternate labels: Potassic trachybasalt

  • Concept URI token: potassic-trachybasalt

1.2.2.11.26.23.31 Trachydacite

  • Child of: trachytoid

  • A rocktype intermediate between phonolite and dacite, similar to trachyte, but notably has >20% quartz.

  • Concept URI token: trachydacite

1.2.2.11.26.23.32 Trachytic rock

  • Child of: trachytoid

  • Trachytoid that has a plagioclase to total feldspar ratio between 0.1 and 0.35. QAPF fields 7, 7’, and 7*.

  • Concept URI token: trachytic-rock

1.2.2.11.26.23.33 Foid-bearing-trachyte

  • Child of: trachytic-rock

  • Trachytic rocks, with felsics comprising 0-10% foids and alkali feldspar/total feldspar 0.65-0.9

  • Alternate labels: Foid-bearing trachyte

  • Concept URI token: foid-bearing-trachyte

1.2.2.11.26.23.34 Nepheline trachyte

  • Child of: foid-bearing-trachyte

  • A trachyte containing nepheline

  • Concept URI token: nepheline-trachyte

1.2.2.11.26.23.35 Quartz-trachyte

  • Child of: trachytic-rock

  • Trachytic rocks, with felsics comprising 5-20% quartz and alkali feldspar/total feldspar 0.65-0.9

  • Alternate labels: Quartz trachyte

  • Concept URI token: quartz-trachyte

1.2.2.11.26.23.36 Trachyte

  • Child of: trachytic-rock

  • Trachytic rocks, with felsics comprising 0-5% quartz and alkali feldspar/total feldspar: 0.65-0.9 A group of fine-grained, generally porphyritic, extrusive rocks having alkali feldspar and minor mafic minerals (biotite, hornblende, or pyroxene) as the main components, and possibly a small amount of sodic plagioclase; also, any member of that group; the extrusive equivalent of syenite. Trachyte grades into latite as the alkali feldspar content decreases, and into rhyolite with an increase in quartz.

  • Concept URI token: trachyte

1.2.2.11.26.23.37 Arsoite

  • Child of: trachyte

  • A type of trachyte consisting of phenocrysts of sanidine, diopside, andesine and a little olivine in a groundmass of sanidine, oligoclase and diopside with minor amounts of leucite. The same rock had previously been called ciminite by Washington.

  • Concept URI token: arsoite

1.2.2.11.26.23.38 Balgarite

  • Child of: trachyte

  • A type of trachyte with marked spheroidal structure composed essentially of perthite with minor amounts of biotite and aegirine- augite.

  • Concept URI token: balgarite

1.2.2.11.26.23.39 Basalt-trachyte

  • Child of: trachyte

  • An obsolete name for a trachyte containing augite and hornblende.

  • Concept URI token: basalt-trachyte

1.2.2.11.26.23.40 Beringite

  • Child of: trachyte

  • An local name for a melanocratic variety of trachyte containing nearly 50% barkevikite.

  • Concept URI token: beringite

1.2.2.11.26.23.41 Bjornsjoite

  • Child of: trachyte

  • A local name for a trachyte composed of albite with small amounts of aegirine-augite.

  • Concept URI token: bjornsjoite

1.2.2.11.26.23.42 Domite

  • Child of: trachyte

  • A type of trachyte that contains a few phenocrysts of oligoclase and biotite in a potentially quartz-bearing glassy groundmass.

  • Concept URI token: domite

1.2.2.11.26.23.43 Keratophyre

  • Child of: trachyte

  • A term originally used for a quartz-bearing orthoclase-plagioclase rock with a dense groundmass, but later used for albitized felsic extrusive rocks consisting essentially of albite with minor mafic minerals, often altered to chlorite. Potassic keratophyres are also recognized in which the feldspar is orthoclase.

  • Concept URI token: keratophyre

1.2.2.11.26.23.44 Maenaite

  • Child of: trachyte

  • A type of trachyte which occurs as dykes and consists essentially of albite and orthoclase.

  • Concept URI token: maenaite

1.2.2.11.26.23.45 Peralkaline trachyte

  • Child of: trachyte

  • A trachyte containing alkali pyroxenes or amphiboles, or with (Na2O+K2O)>Al2O3.

  • Concept URI token: peralkaline-trachyte

1.2.2.11.26.23.46 Comenditic trachyte

  • Child of: peralkaline-trachyte

  • A variety of peralkaline trachyte of TAS field R in which Al2O3 > 1.33 x total iron as FeO + 4.4.

  • Concept URI token: comenditic-trachyte

1.2.2.11.26.23.47 Drakontite

  • Child of: peralkaline-trachyte

  • A variety of peralkaline trachyte containing biotite and alkali amphibole.

  • Concept URI token: drakontite

1.2.2.11.26.23.48 Pantelleritic trachyte

  • Child of: peralkaline-trachyte

  • A variety of peralkaline trachyte of TAS field R in which Al2O3 <1.33 x total iron as FeO + 4.4.

  • Concept URI token: pantelleritic-trachyte

1.2.2.11.26.24 Ultrabasic volcanic rock

  • Child of: extrusive-igneous-rock

  • A chemical classification based on the TAS diagram for normal volcanic rocks with less than 45% wt % SiO2.This includes, foidite (in part), picrobasalt, basanite (in part) and tephrite (in part).

  • Alternate labels: Ultrabasic rock

  • Concept URI token: ultrabasic-volcanic-rock

1.2.2.11.26.24.1 Picrobasalt

  • Child of: fine-grained-ultramafic-rock ultrabasic-volcanic-rock

  • Fine grained ultramafic rocks with 41-45% SiO2, 2-3% (Na2O+K2O)

  • Concept URI token: picrobasalt

1.2.2.11.27 Feldspar-basalt

  • Child of: normal-crystalline-igneous-rock

  • An obsolete name for a fine-graned igneous rock essentially composed of plagioclase and augite.

  • Concept URI token: feldspar-basalt

1.2.2.11.28 Feldspathine

  • Child of: normal-crystalline-igneous-rock

  • An obsolete term for a feldspar rock.

  • Concept URI token: feldspathine

1.2.2.11.29 Felsophyrite

  • Child of: normal-crystalline-igneous-rock

  • An obsolete term for a non-porphyritic rock with microcrysalline texture and some glass, but later used for effusive rock corresponding to a diorite composition.

  • Concept URI token: felsophyrite

1.2.2.11.30 Fine-grained ultramafic-rock

  • Child of: normal-crystalline-igneous-rock

  • A fine-grained crystalline rock composed mostly (>90%) of mafic minerals

  • Alternate labels: Ultramafic volcanic, Ultramafitite,

  • Concept URI token: fine-grained-ultramafic-rock

1.2.2.11.30.1 Picritic-rock

  • Child of: basalt fine-grained-ultramafic-rock

  • Fine grained ultramafic or basaltic rocks with <53% SiO2, (Na2O+K2O)<2%, MgO>18%.

  • Alternate labels: High Magnesium Basalt, High Mg Basalt, High-Magnesium Basalt, High-Mg Basalt,

  • Concept URI token: picritic-rock

1.2.2.11.30.1.1 Komatiite

  • Child of: picritic-rock

  • Picritic rocks defined chemically as having <1% (Na2O+K2O) and <1% TiO2, or a field term for similar rocks exhibiting spinifex textures from skeletal olivine.The term was originally applied by Viljoen and Viljoen (1969) to basaltic and ultramafic lavas near the Komati river, Barberton Mountain Land, Transvaal, South Africa. Nickel-copper sulfide mineral deposits may be associated with komatiites.

  • Concept URI token: komatiite

1.2.2.11.30.1.2 Basaltic komatiite

  • Child of: komatiite

  • A member of the komatiite series with MgO in the range 5% to 15% typically displaying spinifex texture and evidence of rapid quenching of high-temperature magma. Chemically they are intermediate between tholeiitic basalt and boninite and are thought to have been komatiite magmas contaminated by crustal material.

  • Alternate labels: Komatiitic Basalt

  • Concept URI token: basaltic-komatiite

1.2.2.11.30.1.3 Meimechite

  • Child of: picritic-rock

  • Picritic rocks defined chemically as having <1% (Na2O+K2O) and >1% TiO2.

  • Concept URI token: meimechite

1.2.2.11.30.1.4 Picrite

  • Child of: picritic-rock

  • Picritic rocks defined chemically as having 1-2% (Na2O+K2O).

  • Concept URI token: picrite

1.2.2.11.30.1.5 Ferropicrite

  • Child of: picrite

  • A picrite wiht the total FeO exceeding 13% (originally proposed at 14%.)

  • Concept URI token: ferropicrite

1.2.2.11.30.2 Picrobasalt

  • Child of: fine-grained-ultramafic-rock ultrabasic-volcanic-rock

  • Fine grained ultramafic rocks with 41-45% SiO2, 2-3% (Na2O+K2O)

  • Concept URI token: picrobasalt

1.2.2.11.31 Firmicite

  • Child of: normal-crystalline-igneous-rock

  • An obsolete term for rocks consist- ing of hornblende and feldspar.

  • Concept URI token: firmicite

1.2.2.11.32 Hybrid igneous rock and intrusive breccia

  • Child of: breccia normal-crystalline-igneous-rock

  • Mixed rocks including xenoliths and and breccias formed where igneous rocks intrude, vein, metamorphose and assimilate preexisting igneous rocks and other rocks.

  • Concept URI token: hybrid-igneous-rock-and-intrusive-breccia

1.2.2.11.32.1 Intrusive breccia

  • Child of: hybrid-igneous-rock-and-intrusive-breccia

  • A breccia of intrusive rock. Intrusive rocks can become brecciated in appearance by multiple stages of intrusion, especially if fresh magma is intruded into partly consolidated or solidified magma.

  • Alternate labels: Gabbroic breccia, Granite breccia,

  • Concept URI token: intrusive-breccia

1.2.2.11.32.2 Peperite

  • Child of: hybrid-igneous-rock-and-intrusive-breccia

  • Most commonly used to refer to breccias, clastic rocks comprising both igneous and sedimentary components, which were generated by intrusive processes, or along the basal contacts of lava flows or hot volcaniclastic deposits with unconsolidated, typically wet, sediments (Skilling et al, 2002). It usually consists of highly irregular fragments of glassy igneous rock within sediments and/or the opposite. Formed essentially in situ by disintegration of magma intruding and mingling with typically wet sediments.

  • Alternate labels: Pepperite

  • Concept URI token: peperite

1.2.2.11.33 Intrusive igneous rock

  • Child of: normal-crystalline-igneous-rock

  • Coarse-grained crystalline normal igneous rock. Coarse grained usually means >2mm, easily visible to the naked eye. In many classification systems these are termed ‘plutonic’ and are usually intrusive.

  • Alternate labels: Intrusive Rock (unspecified), Intrusive Rock, Intrusive Rock, undifferentiated, Intrustive, Plutonic rock, Unclassified intrusive rock, coarse grained crystalline igneous rock, unclassified intrusive unit,

  • Concept URI token: intrusive-igneous-rock

1.2.2.11.33.1 Anorthositoid

  • Child of: intrusive-igneous-rock

  • An anorthoclase-rich coarse-grained crystalline igneous rock. Composed mostly of calcian plagioclase feldspar (90-100%), with a small mafic component (0-10%). Pyroxene, ilmenite, magnetite and olivine are commonly present.

  • Alternate labels: Anorthositic-rock

  • Concept URI token: anorthositoid

1.2.2.11.33.1.1 Anorthosite

  • Child of: anorthositoid

  • A coarse-grained crystalline rock consisting mostly of calcic plagioclase (>90%, usually labradorite) with <10% mafics. The mafic mineral may be clinopyroxene, orthopyroxene, olivine, or, more rarely, amphibole. Oxides, mostly magnetite or ilmenite, are also common.

  • Alternate labels: Anortholite, Plagioclasite,

  • Concept URI token: anorthosite

1.2.2.11.33.1.2 Andesinite

  • Child of: anorthosite

  • A coarse-grained igneous rock almost entirely composed of andesine. Compare with: anorthosite

  • Concept URI token: andesinite

1.2.2.11.33.1.3 Anorthosite norite

  • Child of: anorthosite norite

  • A rock intermediate between anorthosite and norite in composition.

  • Concept URI token: anorthosite-norite

1.2.2.11.33.1.4 Calciclasite

  • Child of: anorthosite

  • A term for varieties of anorthosite containing calcic plagioclase.

  • Concept URI token: calciclasite

1.2.2.11.33.1.5 Anorthitite

  • Child of: calciclasite

  • A term proposed for a variety of anorthosite consisting essentially of anorthite. In the original description the composition of the plagioclase was probably incorrectly de- termined.

  • Concept URI token: anorthitite

1.2.2.11.33.1.6 Labradoritite

  • Child of: calciclasite

  • A coarse-grained igneous rock almost entirely composed of labradorite.

  • Concept URI token: labradoritite

1.2.2.11.33.1.7 Charnockitic anorthosite

  • Child of: anorthositoid

  • A orthopyroxene-bearing anorthosite

  • Concept URI token: charnockitic-anorthosite

1.2.2.11.33.1.8 Foid-bearing-anorthosite

  • Child of: anorthositoid

  • A foid-bearing anorthosite

  • Alternate labels: Foid-bearing anorthosite

  • Concept URI token: foid-bearing-anorthosite

1.2.2.11.33.1.9 Cancrinite-bearing-anorthosite

  • Child of: foid-bearing-anorthosite

  • A foid-bearing-anorthosite where cancrinite is the most abundant foid.

  • Concept URI token: cancrinite-bearing-anorthosite

1.2.2.11.33.1.10 Nepheline-bearing-anorthosite

  • Child of: foid-bearing-anorthosite

  • A foid-bearing-anorthosite where nepheline is the most abundant foid.

  • Concept URI token: nepheline-bearing-anorthosite

1.2.2.11.33.1.11 Sodalite-bearing-anorthosite

  • Child of: foid-bearing-anorthosite

  • A foid-bearing-anorthosite where sodalite is the most abundant foid.

  • Concept URI token: sodalite-bearing-anorthosite

1.2.2.11.33.1.12 Quartz-anorthosite

  • Child of: anorthositoid

  • A quartz-bearing anorthosite

  • Alternate labels: Quartz anorthosite

  • Concept URI token: quartz-anorthosite

1.2.2.11.33.1.13 Troctolitic anorthosite

  • Child of: anorthositoid

  • An olivine-bearing anorthosite.

  • Concept URI token: troctolitic-anorthosite

1.2.2.11.33.2 Aplite

  • Child of: intrusive-igneous-rock

  • A light-coloured, igneous rock characterized by a medium-grained (usually 0.1-2mm) saccharoidal (i.e., aplitic) texture. Aplites may range in composition from granitic to gabbroic, but the term aplite with no modifier is generally understood to mean granitic aplite or aplitic granite, consisting essentially of quartz, potassium feldspar, and sodic plagioclase.

  • Alternate labels: Haplite

  • Concept URI token: aplite

1.2.2.11.33.3 Apotroctolite

  • Child of: intrusive-igneous-rock

  • A term used for a coarse-grained rock consisting essentially of alkali feldspar and olivine, with minor pyroxene, biotite and chlorite.

  • Concept URI token: apotroctolite

1.2.2.11.33.4 Appinite

  • Child of: intrusive-igneous-rock

  • A local, general term for medium- to coarse-grained, meso- to melanocratic rocks with conspicuous hornblende in a base of oligoclase-andesine and/or orthoclase with or without quartz. The plutonic equivalent of vogesite and spessartite.

  • Concept URI token: appinite

1.2.2.11.33.5 Banatite

  • Child of: intrusive-igneous-rock

  • A term used for a series of rocks ranging from granite to diorite (but mainly granodiorite) that were intruded in Upper Cretaceous time in the Banat and adjacent areas of Hungary and Serbia.

  • Concept URI token: banatite

1.2.2.11.33.6 Bauchite

  • Child of: intrusive-igneous-rock

  • A local name for varieties of fayalite-bearing orthopyroxene granite and quartz monzonite of QAPF fields 3, 7* and 8*

  • Concept URI token: bauchite

1.2.2.11.33.7 Belugite

  • Child of: intrusive-igneous-rock

  • An obsolete term for a plutonic rock with feldspar which is intermediate in composition between those typical of diorite and gabbro.

  • Concept URI token: belugite

1.2.2.11.33.8 Calavorite

  • Child of: intrusive-igneous-rock

  • An obsolete local name proposed in place of the term oligoclasite for a leucocratic plutonic rock consisting of orthoclase and lesser oligoclase with hornblende.

  • Concept URI token: calavorite

1.2.2.11.33.9 Coarse-grained-ultramafic-rock

  • Child of: intrusive-igneous-rock

  • A coarse-grained crystalline igneous rock composed mostly (>90%) of mafic minerals

  • Alternate labels: Ultramafic intrusive rock, Ultramafitolite, ultrabasic intrusive,

  • Concept URI token: coarse-grained-ultramafic-rock

1.2.2.11.33.9.1 Amphibololite

  • Child of: coarse-grained-ultramafic-rock

  • A general term used in France for medium- to coarse-grained igneous rocks composed almost entirely of amphibole. Not to be confused with amphibolite which is now used solely as a term for metamorphic rocks consisting of hornblende and plagioclase.

  • Concept URI token: amphibololite

1.2.2.11.33.9.2 Hornblendite

  • Child of: coarse-grained-ultramafic-rock

  • An ultramafic rock comprising mostly hornblende.

  • Concept URI token: hornblendite

1.2.2.11.33.9.3 Hornblendite (s.s.)

  • Child of: hornblendite

  • A hornblendite containing at least 90% hornblende

  • Concept URI token: hornblendite-ss

1.2.2.11.33.9.4 Olivine-hornblendite

  • Child of: hornblendite

  • A hornblendite containing 5-50% olivine

  • Alternate labels: Argeinite, Olivine hornblendite,

  • Concept URI token: olivine-hornblendite

1.2.2.11.33.9.5 Olivine-pyroxene-hornblendite

  • Child of: hornblendite

  • A hornblendite containing 5-50% olivine+ pyroxene

  • Alternate labels: Olivine pyroxene hornblendite, Pyroxene-olivine-hornblendite,

  • Concept URI token: olivine-pyroxene-hornblendite

1.2.2.11.33.9.6 Cortlandite

  • Child of: olivine-pyroxene-hornblendite

  • A variety of olivine-pyroxene-hornblendite composed of large crystals of hornblende poikilitically enclosing olivine, hypersthene and augite.

  • Concept URI token: cortlandite

1.2.2.11.33.9.7 Pyroxene-hornblendite

  • Child of: hornblendite

  • A hornblendite containing 5-50% pyroxene

  • Alternate labels: Pyroxene hornblendite

  • Concept URI token: pyroxene-hornblendite

1.2.2.11.33.9.8 Avezacite

  • Child of: pyroxene-hornblendite

  • A type of pyroxene-hornblendite which occurs as dykes and consists of phenocrysts of hornblende in a groundmass of hornblende, augite and abundant ilmenite.

  • Concept URI token: avezacite

1.2.2.11.33.9.9 Kovdite

  • Child of: pyroxene-amphibolite pyroxene-hornblendite

  • A type of pyroxene hornblendite composed of green amphibole and orthopyroxene, with small amounts of biotite and plagioclase and occasional garnet. It may be a metamorphic rock.

  • Concept URI token: kovdite

1.2.2.11.33.9.10 Olivinite

  • Child of: coarse-grained-ultramafic-rock

  • A term originally used for ore-bearing olivine rocks and later for plutonic rocks composed of olivine with pyroxene and/or amphibole. In the Russian Republic the term is used for olivine rocks with accessory magnetite to distinguish them from dunite, which contains accessory chromite.

  • Concept URI token: olivinite

1.2.2.11.33.9.11 Forsteritite

  • Child of: olivinite

  • An olivinite where the olivine composition is forsterite.

  • Concept URI token: forsteritite

1.2.2.11.33.9.12 Peridotite

  • Child of: coarse-grained-ultramafic-rock

  • A peridotite is an ultramafic rock containing more than 40% olivine (Mg2SiO4).A general term for a coarse-grained plutonic rock composed chiefly of olivine with or without other mafic minerals such as pyroxenes, amphiboles, or micas, and containing little or no feldspar. Accessory minerals of the spinel group are commonly present. Peridotite is commonly altered to serpentinite.

  • Alternate labels: Ultramafic plutonic

  • Concept URI token: peridotite

1.2.2.11.33.9.13 Biotite peridotite

  • Child of: peridotite

  • A peridotite containing biotite.

  • Concept URI token: biotite-peridotite

1.2.2.11.33.9.14 Dunite

  • Child of: peridotite

  • A peridotite comprising >90% olivine. Accessory chromite almost always present.

  • Concept URI token: dunite

1.2.2.11.33.9.15 Alexoite

  • Child of: dunite

  • A variety of dunite composed of olivine, pyrrhotite and smaller amounts of magnetite and pentlandite.

  • Concept URI token: alexoite

1.2.2.11.33.9.16 Chassignite meteorite

  • Child of: dunite martian-achrondite-meteorite

  • A dunite composition Martian meteorite. Meteoritical Society Code: Martian (chassignite)

  • Concept URI token: chassignite-meteorite

1.2.2.11.33.9.17 Cumberlandite

  • Child of: dunite

  • A variety of dunite from Cumberland, Rhode Island, USA

  • Concept URI token: cumberlandite

1.2.2.11.33.9.18 magnetite olivinite

  • Child of: dunite

  • A dunite high in content of titaniferous magnetite and containing shreds of biotite.

  • Concept URI token: magnetite-olivinite

1.2.2.11.33.9.19 Eulysite

  • Child of: peridotite

  • A variety of peridotite composed essentially of olivine, diopside, opaques and anthophyllite.

  • Concept URI token: eulysite

1.2.2.11.33.9.20 Feldspathic peridotite

  • Child of: peridotite

  • A peridotite containing feldspar.

  • Concept URI token: feldspathic-peridotite

1.2.2.11.33.9.21 Garnet-peridotite

  • Child of: peridotite

  • A peridotite containing garnets.

  • Concept URI token: garnet-peridotite

1.2.2.11.33.9.22 Harzburgite

  • Child of: peridotite ultramafic-metamorphic-rock

  • A peridotite containing <5% hornblende, >5% orthopyroxene and <5% clinopyroxene.A variety of peridotite that consists essentially of olivine and enstatite or bronzite.

  • Concept URI token: harzburgite

1.2.2.11.33.9.23 Hornblende harzburgite

  • Child of: harzburgite

  • A harzburgite containing up to 5% hornblende.

  • Concept URI token: hornblende-harzburgite

1.2.2.11.33.9.24 Bragancaite

  • Child of: hornblende-harzburgite

  • A local name for a hornblende harzburgite composed of olivine, enstatite and hornblende.

  • Concept URI token: bragancaite

1.2.2.11.33.9.25 Hornblende-peridotite

  • Child of: peridotite

  • A peridotite containing >5% hornblende

  • Alternate labels: Hornblende peridotite

  • Concept URI token: hornblende-peridotite

1.2.2.11.33.9.26 Phlogopite-hornblende-olivine peridotite

  • Child of: hornblende-peridotite

  • A variety of peridotite composed of olivine, hornblende and phlogopite

  • Concept URI token: phlogopite-hornblende-olivine-peridotite

1.2.2.11.33.9.27 Lherzolite

  • Child of: peridotite ultramafic-metamorphic-rock

  • A peridotite containing >40% olivine, <5% hornblende, >5% orthopyroxene and >5% clinopyroxene.

  • Alternate labels: Buchnerite

  • Concept URI token: lherzolite

1.2.2.11.33.9.28 Spinel lherzolite

  • Child of: lherzolite

  • A lherzolite rich in spinel.

  • Concept URI token: spinel-lherzolite

1.2.2.11.33.9.29 Pyroxene-hornblende-peridotite

  • Child of: peridotite

  • A peridotite containing >5% hornblende and >5% pyroxene

  • Alternate labels: Pyroxene hornblend peridotite, Pyroxene hornblende peridotite,

  • Concept URI token: pyroxene-hornblende-peridotite

1.2.2.11.33.9.30 Valbellite

  • Child of: pyroxene-hornblende-peridotite

  • An obsolete name for a variety of peridotite consisting of olivine, bronzite, hornblende, magnetite and some pyrrhotite. Cf. weigelite.

  • Concept URI token: valbellite

1.2.2.11.33.9.31 Pyroxene-peridotite

  • Child of: peridotite

1.2.2.11.33.9.32 Wehrlite

  • Child of: peridotite

  • Concept URI token: wehrlite

1.2.2.11.33.9.33 Pyroxenite

  • Child of: coarse-grained-ultramafic-rock

  • Ultramafic rocks comprising >60% pyroxene. The term pyroxenite (s.s.) refers to a ‘true’ pyroxenite containing >90% pyroxene. A coarse-grained, holocrystalline igneous rock which may contain biotite, hornblende, or olivine as accessories.

  • Concept URI token: pyroxenite

1.2.2.11.33.9.50 Aegirinolith

  • Child of: clinopyroxenite

1.2.2.11.33.9.51 Astridite

1.2.2.11.33.9.59 Sagvandite

  • A type of orthopyroxenite composed of bronzite (= Fe-bearing variety of enstatite) and small amounts of magnesite.

  • Concept URI token: sagvandite

1.2.2.11.33.9.60 Olivine-bearing sagvandite

  • Child of: sagvandite

  • A sagvandite containing olivine.

  • Concept URI token: olivine-bearing-sagvandite

1.2.2.11.33.9.61 Websterite

  • Child of: pyroxenite-ss ultramafic-metamorphic-rock

  • A pyroxenite with >5% clinopyroxene and >5% orthopyroxene. (Not the namesake mineral ‘websterite’)

  • Concept URI token: websterite

1.2.2.11.33.9.62 Anabohitsite

  • Child of: websterite

  • A type of websterite consisting of hypersthene (= enstatite), augite, ilmenite and magnetite with minor olivine and hornblende. Named after it s first recorded locality, Anabohitsy, Atsimo- Andrefana, Madagascar

  • Concept URI token: anabohitsite

1.2.2.11.33.9.63 Ariegite

  • Child of: websterite

  • A local group name for a variety of websterite composed of clinopyroxene, orthopyroxene, abundant spinel and often pyrope-rich garnet and hornblende.

  • Concept URI token: ariegite

1.2.2.11.33.10 Dioride

  • Child of: intrusive-igneous-rock

  • An obsolete field term for a coarse-grained ingeous rock containing more than 50% amphibole.

  • Concept URI token: dioride

1.2.2.11.33.11 Dioritoid

  • Child of: intrusive-igneous-rock

  • A field term for coarse-grained crystalline normal igneous rocks with <90% mafic minerals and the felsic minerals containing <20% quartz, <10% felspathoids and plagioclase being >65% of total feldspars. The plagioclase is sodium rich, in contrast to gabbroids, which have calcium rich plagioclase. The group includes diorite, quartz diorite, quartz monzodiorite, foid- bearing diorite, foid- bearing monzodiorite and monzodiorite.

  • Alternate labels: Intermediate plutonic

  • Concept URI token: dioritoid

1.2.2.11.33.11.1 Dioritic rock

  • Child of: dioritoid

  • Phaneritic crystalline rock with M less than 90, consisting of intermediate plagioclase, commonly with hornblende and often with biotite or augite. A dioritoid with a plagioclase to total feldspar ratio (in the QAPF fraction) greater than 0.9. Includes rocks defined modally in QAPF fields 10, 10’ and 10*.

  • Concept URI token: dioritic-rock

1.2.2.11.33.11.2 Diorite

  • Child of: dioritic-rock

  • A dioritic rock with <5% quartz and <10% alkali feldspar on the QAPF diagram. Plutonic rocks intermediate in composition between acidic and basic, characteristically composed of dark-colored amphibole (esp. hornblende), acid plagioclase (oligoclase - andesine), calcic pyroxene, and sometimes a small amount of quartz. The approximate intrusive equivalent of andesite. Diorite grades into monzonite with an increase in the alkali feldspar content.

  • Concept URI token: diorite

1.2.2.11.33.11.3 Alkali diorite

  • Child of: diorite

  • A variety of diorite with alkaline character due to the presence of such dark constituents as barkevikite or kaersutite.

  • Concept URI token: alkali-diorite

1.2.2.11.33.11.4 Anchorite

  • Child of: diorite

  • An obsolete local name for a diorite containing occasional syenite veins and scattered mafic segregation patches.

  • Concept URI token: anchorite

1.2.2.11.33.11.5 Andendiorite

  • Child of: diorite

  • A diorite that is younger than typically found in a local area.

  • Concept URI token: andendiorite

1.2.2.11.33.11.6 Aplitic diorite

  • Child of: diorite

  • An aplitic variety of diorite.

  • Concept URI token: aplitic-diorite

1.2.2.11.33.11.7 Porpyhritic-aplitic diorite

  • Child of: aplitic-diorite

  • A porphyritic aplitic diorite.

  • Concept URI token: porpyhritic-aplitic-diorite

1.2.2.11.33.11.8 Augite diorite

  • Child of: diorite

  • A diorite in which augite is a prominent mafic mineral.

  • Concept URI token: augite-diorite

1.2.2.11.33.11.9 Esboite

  • Child of: diorite

  • A variety of diorite, from Esbo (Espoo), Finland, often orbicular, consisting of abundant sodic plagioclase with small amounts of orthoclase and biotite.

  • Concept URI token: esboite

1.2.2.11.33.11.10 Essexite-diorite

  • Child of: diorite

  • An obsolete term for a variety of diorite containing titanian augite.

  • Concept URI token: essexite-diorite

1.2.2.11.33.11.11 Gabbrodiorite

  • Child of: diorite gabbro

  • A group of basic intrusive igneous rocks composed principally of basic plagioclase (commonly labradorite or bytownite) and clinopyroxene (augite), with or without olivine and orthopyroxene; also, any member of that group. It is the approximate coarse- grained/intrusive equivalent of basalt. Apatite, magnetite, and ilmenite are common accessory minerals. Commonly dark-colored.

  • Concept URI token: gabbrodiorite

1.2.2.11.33.11.12 Hornblende diorite

  • Child of: diorite

  • A coarse grained diorite with prominent porphyritic hornblende in a sodic plagioclase-rich matrix, the plutonic equivalent of spessartite (lamprophyre).

  • Concept URI token: hornblende-diorite

1.2.2.11.33.11.13 Hornblende oligoclase diorite

  • Child of: hornblende-diorite

  • A diorite containing hornblende and oligoclase

  • Concept URI token: hornblende-oligoclase-diorite

1.2.2.11.33.11.14 Ornoite

  • Child of: hornblende-diorite

  • A type of diorite consisting of sodic plagioclase with minor hornblende, microcline, biotite and quartz.

  • Concept URI token: ornoite

1.2.2.11.33.11.15 Porphyritic hornblende diorite

  • Child of: hornblende-diorite

  • Concept URI token: porphyritic-hornblende-diorite

  • Concept URI token: leucodiorite

  • Concept URI token: olivine-diorite

1.2.2.11.33.11.22 Rikotite

1.2.2.11.33.11.33 Alentegite

  • Child of: quartz-diorite tonalite

1.2.2.11.33.11.34 Esterellite

  • Child of: quartz-diorite

1.2.2.11.33.11.38 Monzodioritic rock

  • Child of: dioritoid

  • Phaneritic crystalline igneous rock consisting of sodic plagioclase (An0 to An50), alkali feldspar, hornblende and biotite, with or without pyroxene, and 0 to 10 percent feldspathoid or 0 to 20 percent quartz in the QAPF fraction. Plagioclase to total feldspar ratio in the QAPF fraction is between 0.65 and 0.9. Includes rocks defined modally in QAPF field 9, 9’ and 9* as monzodiorite, foid-beaing monzodiorite, and quartz monzodiorite.

  • Concept URI token: monzodioritic-rock

1.2.2.11.33.11.39 Foid-bearing-monzodiorite

  • Child of: monzodioritic-rock

  • A diorite with <10% foids and 10-35% alkali feldspar on the QAPF diagram.

1.2.2.11.33.11.46 Sorkedalite

  • Child of: olivine-monzodiorite

  • A type of olivine monzodiorite consisting of abundant antiperthitic andesine, which may be mantled by anorthoclase, and by olivine, opaques and apatite with minor clinopyroxene and biotite.

  • Concept URI token: sorkedalite

1.2.2.11.33.11.47 Quartz-monzodiorite

1.2.2.11.33.11.48 Cizlakite

  • Child of: quartz-monzodiorite quartz-monzogabbro

  • A melanocratic variety of quartz monzodiorite or monzogabbro consisting of abundant augite with smaller amounts of hornblende and plagioclase with minor alkali feldspar, quartz and biotite.

  • Concept URI token: cizlakite

1.2.2.11.33.11.49 Amherstite

  • Child of: cizlakite

  • A leucocratic variety of quartz monzodiorite of QAPF field 9* belonging to the charnockitic rock series. The rock consists essentially of andesine- microcline antiperthite with minor quartz and hypersthene (= enstatite). It is suggested (Streckeisen, 1974, p.357) that this term should be abandoned.

  • Concept URI token: amherstite

1.2.2.11.33.11.50 Leucoquartz-monzodiorite

  • Child of: quartz-monzodiorite

  • A quartz-monzodiorite with an M’ colour index of less than 15.

  • Concept URI token: leucoquartz-monzodiorite

1.2.2.11.33.11.51 Melaquartz-monzodiorite

  • Child of: quartz-monzodiorite

  • A quartz-monzodiorite with an M’ colour index of greater than 40.

  • Concept URI token: melaquartz-monzodiorite

1.2.2.11.33.12 Ditro-essexite

  • Child of: intrusive-igneous-rock

  • A comprehensive term for various plutonic rocks of essexitic and theralitic chemistry from the alkaline complex of Ditro, Romania. The term includes such types as diorite, monzonite and essexite. They contain large amounts of barkevikite and kaersutite.

  • Concept URI token: ditro-essexite

1.2.2.11.33.13 Ferrodiorite

  • Child of: intrusive-igneous-rock

  • Field term for rocks of gabbroic appearance containing Fe-rich pyroxenes and olivines but with plagioclase more sodic than An50. See also ferrogabbro.

  • Concept URI token: ferrodiorite

1.2.2.11.33.14 Foid-dioritoid

  • Alternate labels: Foid dioritoid

  • Concept URI token: foid-dioritoid

  • Child of: leucite-monzosyenite

  • A medium- to coarse-grained variety of leucite-monzosyenite consisting of phenocrysts of titanian augite and lesser olivine in a groundmass of sanidine, labradorite and leucite. It occurrs abundantly among the ejected blocks of Mt Somma.
