1.2.2.11.33.16.29 Nepheline-syenite

  • Child of: foid-syenite

  • As a Commodity:Nepheline SyeniteA foid-syenite where nepheline is the most abundant foid.A plutonic rock composed essentially of alkali feldspar and nepheline. It may contain an alkali ferromagnesian mineral, such as an amphibole (riebeckite, arfvedsonite, barkevikite) or a pyroxene (aegirine or aegirine-augite); the intrusive equivalent of phonolite. Sodalite, cancrinite, hauyne, and nosean, in addition to apatite, sphene, and opaque oxides, are common accessories. Rare minerals are also frequent accessories.

  • Alternate labels: eleolite syenite, midalkalite, nepheline syenite,

  • Concept URI token: nepheline-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.16.30 Alkali-feldspar nepheline-syenite

  • Child of: nepheline-syenite

  • A nepheline-syenite containing alkali feldspar.

  • Concept URI token: alkali-feldspar-nepheline-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.16.31 Peralkaline-alkali-feldspar nepheline-syenite

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-nepheline-syenite

  • A alkali-feldspar nepheline-syenite characterised by complex Zr and Ti minerals such as eudialyte rather than simple minerals sch as zircon or ilmenite.

  • Concept URI token: peralkaline-alkali-feldspar-nepheline-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.16.32 Apgaitic nepheline-syenite

  • Child of: nepheline-syenite

  • An apgaitic variety of nepheline-syenite

  • Concept URI token: apgaitic-nepheline-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.16.33 Assyntite

  • Child of: nepheline-syenite

  • A type of nepheline-syenite composed of abundant orthoclase, smaller amounts of sodalite, and nepheline with aegirine-augite, biotite and large crystals of titanite.

  • Concept URI token: assyntite

1.2.2.11.33.16.34 Borolanite

  • Child of: nepheline-syenite

  • A local name for a coarse-grained variety of nepheline-syenite consisting of alkali feldspar, nepheline (or its alteration products), melanite and biotite, and sometimes characterized by the presence of pseudoleucite.

  • Concept URI token: borolanite

1.2.2.11.33.16.35 Canadite

  • Child of: nepheline-syenite

  • A coarse-grained variety of nepheline-syenite in which the feldspar is essentially albite or sodic plagioclase, with abundant mafic minerals, notably biotite and amphibole.

  • Concept URI token: canadite

1.2.2.11.33.16.36 Ditroite

  • Child of: nepheline-syenite

  • A biotite-bearing nepheline-syenite containing cancrinite and primary calcite.

  • Concept URI token: ditroite

1.2.2.11.33.16.37 Eudialyte-bearing nepheline-syenite

  • Child of: nepheline-syenite

  • A nepheline-syenite containing eudialyte.

  • Concept URI token: eudialyte-bearing-nepheline-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.16.38 Khibinite

  • Child of: eudialyte-bearing-nepheline-syenite

  • A variety of eudialyte-bearing nepheline-syenite with aegirine, alkali amphibole and many accessory minerals, particularly those containing Ti and Zr.

  • Concept URI token: khibinite

1.2.2.11.33.16.39 Foyaite

  • Child of: nepheline-syenite

  • A hypersolvus nepheline syenite sometimes used as a group name for nepheline syenites. Now used as a term for nepheline syenites having a trachytic texture caused by the platy alkali feldspar crystals. A nepheline syenite with predominant orthoclase and a trachytic texture. Synonym of: midalkalite

  • Concept URI token: foyaite

1.2.2.11.33.16.40 Grennaite

  • Child of: nepheline-syenite

  • A variety of agpaitic nepheline-syenite with phenocrysts of catapleiite and/or eudialyte in a fine-grained groundmass rich in aegirine and showing gneissose textures. The rock is most probably a deformed and partly recrystallised lujavrite.

  • Concept URI token: grennaite

1.2.2.11.33.16.41 Kaxtorpite

  • Child of: nepheline-syenite

  • A local name for a coarse-grained, sometimes schistose, variety of nepheline syenite consisting of alkali feldspar, nepheline, alkali amphibole with or without pectolite and aegirine. First described from Norra Karr, Sweden.

  • Concept URI token: kaxtorpite

1.2.2.11.33.16.42 Lakarpite

  • Child of: nepheline-syenite

  • A local name for a coarse-grained variety of nepheline syenite consisting of alkali feldspar, altered nepheline, abundant arfvedsonite, aegirine and a little pectolite.

  • Concept URI token: lakarpite

1.2.2.11.33.16.43 Lardalite

  • Child of: nepheline-syenite

  • A local name for a coarse-grained variety of nepheline syenite characterized by rhomb-shaped alkali or ternary feldspar crystals and large crystals of nepheline.

  • Concept URI token: lardalite

1.2.2.11.33.16.44 Litchfieldite

  • Child of: nepheline-syenite

  • A coarse-grained, somewhat foliated variety of nepheline-syenite consisting of K-feldspar, albite, nepheline, cancrinite, sodalite and lepidomelane.

  • Concept URI token: litchfieldite

1.2.2.11.33.16.45 Lujavrite

  • Child of: nepheline-syenite

  • A term, originally spelt luijaurite, for a melanocratic agpaitic variety of nepheline-syenite rich in eudialyte, arfvedsonite and aegirine with perthitic alkali feldspar or separate microcline and albite. A pronounced igneous lamination is characteristic, as is the abundance in minerals rich in incompatible elements such as the REE, U, Th, Li etc.

  • Concept URI token: lujavrite

1.2.2.11.33.16.46 Malignite

  • Child of: nepheline-syenite

  • A mesocratic nepheline-syenite containing abundant aegirine-augite and some orthoclase and nepheline in equal amounts. Many other mafic minerals, such as amphibole, garnet, biotite, may be present.

  • Concept URI token: malignite

1.2.2.11.33.16.47 Melanocratic nepheline-syenite

  • Child of: nepheline-syenite

  • A melanocratic variety of nepheline-syenite.

  • Concept URI token: melanocratic-nepheline-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.16.48 Covite

  • Child of: melanocratic-nepheline-syenite

  • A local name for a melanocratic nepheline-syenite with sodic pyroxene and amphibole.

  • Concept URI token: covite

1.2.2.11.33.16.49 Pseudoleucite syenite

  • Child of: nepheline-syenite

  • A nepheline-syenite containing pseudoleucite (a pseudomorph of nepheline and orthoclase after leucite)

  • Concept URI token: pseudoleucite-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.16.50 Porphyritic pseudoleucite syenite

  • Child of: pseudoleucite-syenite

  • A pseudoleucite syenite with a porphyritic texture.

  • Concept URI token: porphyritic-pseudoleucite-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.16.51 Rischorrite

  • Child of: nepheline-syenite

  • A variety of biotite-bearing nepheline syenite in which the nepheline crystals are poikilitically enclosed in microcline perthite. Aegirine-augite, apatite and opaques are often abundant.

  • Concept URI token: rischorrite

1.2.2.11.33.16.52 Saibarite

  • Child of: nepheline-syenite

  • A type of nepheline-syenite with trachytoidal texture and banded structure consisting of nepheline, aegirine, alkali feldspar and albite, with minor alkali amphibole.

  • Concept URI token: saibarite

1.2.2.11.33.16.53 Shonkinite

  • Child of: foid-syenite

  • A coarse-grained rock with abundant augite, some olivine, biotite or hornblende, and essential alkali feldspar and foids, usually nepheline. Now defined modally as a melanocratic variety of foid syenite in QAPF field 11. A dark-colored syenite composed chiefly of augite and alkali feldspar, and possibly containing olivine, hornblende, biotite, and nepheline.

  • Alternate labels: Melanocratic foid-syenite

  • Concept URI token: shonkinite

1.2.2.11.33.16.54 Sodalite-syenite

  • Child of: foid-syenite

  • A foid-syenite where sodalite is the most abundant foid.

  • Alternate labels: Sodalite syenite

  • Concept URI token: sodalite-syenite

  • Child of: sodalite-syenite

  • A sodalite-syenite containing nepheline

  • Concept URI token: nepheline-sodalite-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.16.56 Nepheline-syenitic-rock

1.2.2.11.33.17 Foidolite

  • Child of: intrusive-igneous-rock

  • Foid-rich rocks in which >60% of the light coloured minerals are foids.A coarse-grained crystalline rock with <90% mafics, >60% of felsics being foids.

  • Alternate labels: Feldspathidolite

  • Concept URI token: foidolite

1.2.2.11.33.17.1 Fergusite

  • Child of: foidolite

  • A plutonic rock consisting of roughly 70% pseudoleucite (alkali feldspar, nepheline, kalsilite and minor analcime) and 30% pyroxene. Now defined modally as a variety of foidolite in QAPF field 15.

  • Concept URI token: fergusite

1.2.2.11.33.17.2 Nepheline fergusite

  • Child of: fergusite

  • A fergusite containing nepheline

  • Concept URI token: nepheline-fergusite

1.2.2.11.33.17.3 Arkite

  • Child of: nepheline-fergusite

  • A local name for a leucocratic variety of nepheline fergusite consisting of leucite or pseudoleucite in a matrix of nepheline, melanite garnet, biotite, sodic pyroxene, amphibole and minor alkali feldspar.

  • Concept URI token: arkite

1.2.2.11.33.17.4 Leucitolite

  • Child of: foidolite ultrapotassic-rock

  • A foidolite where leucite is the most abundant foid.

  • Concept URI token: leucitolite

1.2.2.11.33.17.5 Italite

  • Child of: leucitolite

  • A leucitolite consisting almost entirely of leucite held together by small amounts of glass.

  • Concept URI token: italite

1.2.2.11.33.17.6 Melilite foidolite

  • Child of: foidolite

  • A foidolite with melilite < feldspathoid and with feldspathoid > 10%.

  • Concept URI token: melilite-foidolite

1.2.2.11.33.17.7 Nephelinolite

  • Child of: foidolite rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

1.2.2.11.33.17.8 Apatite nephelinolite

  • Child of: nephelinolite

  • A nephelinolite consisting mainly of apatite and nepheline with minor aegirine and biotite.

  • Concept URI token: apatite-nephelinolite

1.2.2.11.33.17.9 Ijolite

  • Child of: nephelinolite

  • A nephelinolite consisting of 30-70% nepheline with pyroxene.A series of plutonic rocks containing nepheline and 30% to 60% mafic minerals, generally clinopyroxene, and including minor titanite, apatite, and melanite; also, any rock of that series. Melteigite and jacupirangite are more mafic members of the series; urtite is a type rich in nepheline.

  • Alternate labels: Ngurumanite, Pyroxene nephelinolite,

  • Concept URI token: ijolite

1.2.2.11.33.17.10 Ampasimenite

  • Child of: ijolite nephelinite

  • A local name for a porphyritic variety of ijolite or nephelinite with a glassy matrix.

  • Concept URI token: ampasimenite

1.2.2.11.33.17.11 Calcite ijolite

  • Child of: ijolite

  • An ijolite with calcite, but not enough calcite to be classed as a carbonatite.

  • Concept URI token: calcite-ijolite

1.2.2.11.33.17.12 Calcitfels

  • Child of: ijolite

  • n obsolete term for a calcite-rich member of the ijolite-melteigite series.

  • Concept URI token: calcitfels

1.2.2.11.33.17.13 Ijolite-urtite

  • Child of: ijolite

  • A rock of intermediate composition between ijolite and urtite.

  • Concept URI token: ijolite-urtite

1.2.2.11.33.17.14 Lujavritite

  • Child of: ijolite

  • A variety of ijolite composed mainly of aegirine-augite and nepheline with much titanite and some apatite and characterized by the presence of small amounts of K- feldspar.

  • Concept URI token: lujavritite

1.2.2.11.33.17.15 Pegmatitic Ijolite

  • Child of: ijolite

  • A very coarsely crystalline ijolite.

  • Concept URI token: pegmatitic-ijolite

1.2.2.11.33.17.16 Leucocratic nephelinolite

  • Child of: nephelinolite

  • A nephelinolite consisting of over 70% nepheline, with some aegirine-augite but no feldspar.

  • Alternate labels: urtite

  • Concept URI token: leucocratic-nephelinolite

1.2.2.11.33.17.17 Congressite

  • Child of: leucocratic-nephelinolite

  • A local name for a coarse-grained nephelinolite consisting of about 70% nepheline with minor alkali feldspar, biotite, occasional sodalite and accessory minerals.

  • Concept URI token: congressite

1.2.2.11.33.17.18 Melanocratic nephelinolite

  • Child of: nephelinolite

  • A nephelinolite consisting of 10% to 30% nepheline with pyroxene.

  • Alternate labels: melteigite

  • Concept URI token: melanocratic-nephelinolite

1.2.2.11.33.17.19 Biotite melteigite

  • Child of: melanocratic-nephelinolite

  • A melanocratic nephelinolite containing biotite.

  • Concept URI token: biotite-melteigite

1.2.2.11.33.17.20 Fasinite

  • Child of: melanocratic-nephelinolite

  • A melanocratic nephelinolite consisting of 60-70% titanian augite with some nepheline.

  • Concept URI token: fasinite

1.2.2.11.33.17.21 Noseanolite

  • Child of: foidolite

  • A foidolite where nosean is the most abundant foid.

  • Concept URI token: noseanolite

1.2.2.11.33.17.22 Rodderite

  • Child of: nosean-phonolite noseanolite

  • A melanocratic variety of nosean phonolite or noseanolite, with more nosean than alkali feldspar, biotite and augite.

  • Concept URI token: rodderite

1.2.2.11.33.17.23 Sodalitolite

  • Child of: foidolite rock-of-restricted-mineralogy

  • A foidolite where sodalite is the most abundant foid.

  • Concept URI token: sodalitolite

1.2.2.11.33.17.24 Naujaite

  • Child of: sodalitolite

  • Where sodalite exceeds 50% it is classed as a sodalitolite, otherwise it is a nepheline sodalite-syenite. It is an agpaitic rock characterised by a poikilitic texture.

  • Concept URI token: naujaite

1.2.2.11.33.17.25 Tawite

  • Child of: sodalitolite

  • A variety of foidolite composed largely of crystals of sodalite together with aegirine. Some nepheline, alkali feldspar and eudialyte are usually present.

  • Concept URI token: tawite

1.2.2.11.33.17.26 Beloeilite

  • Child of: tawite

  • A type of tawite consisting of about 70% sodalite with nepheline, alkali feldspar, oligoclase and a little aegirine, originally described as a feldspathic variety of tawite.

  • Concept URI token: beloeilite

1.2.2.11.33.18 Gabbroid

  • Child of: intrusive-igneous-rock

  • A field term for coarse-grained crystalline rocks with <90% mafics, and calcic plagioclase dominant.

  • Alternate labels: Basic / Mafic Intrusive, Basic/Mafic Intrusive, Gabbroic-rock, Mafic intrusive,

  • Concept URI token: gabbroid

1.2.2.11.33.18.1 Calcogranitone

  • Child of: gabbroid

  • An obsolete term for a gabbroic rock impregnated with calcite.

  • Concept URI token: calcogranitone

1.2.2.11.33.18.2 Drusite

  • Child of: gabbroid

  • An obsolete name for a gabbroic rock containing concentric coronas of minerals (drusy structure).

  • Concept URI token: drusite

1.2.2.11.33.18.3 Foid-bearing gabbroic-rock

  • Child of: gabbroid

  • A gabbroic-rock containing foid minerals.

  • Concept URI token: foid-bearing-gabbroic-rock

1.2.2.11.33.18.4 Cancrinite-bearing-gabbroic-rock

  • Child of: foid-bearing-gabbroic-rock

  • A foid-bearing-gabbroic-rock where cancrinite is the most abundant foid.

  • Concept URI token: cancrinite-bearing-gabbroic-rock

1.2.2.11.33.18.5 Nepheline-bearing-gabbroic-rock

  • Child of: foid-bearing-gabbroic-rock

  • A foid-bearing-gabbroic-rock where nepheline is the most abundant foid.

  • Concept URI token: nepheline-bearing-gabbroic-rock

1.2.2.11.33.18.6 Sodalite-bearing-gabbroic-rock

  • Child of: foid-bearing-gabbroic-rock

  • Concept URI token: sodalite-bearing-gabbroic-rock

1.2.2.11.33.18.7 Gabbroic rock

  • Child of: gabbroid

  • Gabbroid that has a plagioclase to total feldspar ratio greater than 0.9 in the QAPF fraction. Includes QAPF fields 10*, 10, and 10’. This category includes the various categories defined in LeMaitre et al.

  1. based on the mafic mineralogy, but apparently not subdivided based on the quartz/feldspathoid content.
  • Concept URI token: gabbroic-rock

1.2.2.11.33.18.8 Foid-bearing-gabbro

  • Child of: gabbroic-rock

  • A gabbro containing up to 10% foid minerals.

  • Alternate labels: Foid-bearing gabbro

  • Concept URI token: foid-bearing-gabbro

1.2.2.11.33.18.9 Alkali gabbro

  • Child of: foid-bearing-gabbro

  • A variety of gabbro in QAPF field 10’, with alkaline character due to the presence of analcime or nepheline and such dark constituents as barkevikite (see p.44), kaersutite, titanian augite etc.

  • Concept URI token: alkali-gabbro

1.2.2.11.33.18.13 Gabbro

  • Child of: gabbroic-rock

  • A gabbroid composed of 10-90% Ca-dominant plagioclase and >5% clinopyroxene.A group of basic intrusive igneous rocks composed principally of basic plagioclase (commonly labradorite or bytownite) and clinopyroxene (augite), with or without olivine and orthopyroxene; also, any member of that group. It is the approximate coarse- grained/intrusive equivalent of basalt. Apatite, magnetite, and ilmenite are common accessory minerals. Commonly dark-colored.

  • Alternate labels: Finlandite

  • Concept URI token: gabbro

1.2.2.11.33.18.14 Anorthitissite

1.2.2.11.33.18.24 Gabbrodiorite

  • Child of: diorite gabbro

  • A group of basic intrusive igneous rocks composed principally of basic plagioclase (commonly labradorite or bytownite) and clinopyroxene (augite), with or without olivine and orthopyroxene; also, any member of that group. It is the approximate coarse- grained/intrusive equivalent of basalt. Apatite, magnetite, and ilmenite are common accessory minerals. Commonly dark-colored.

  • Concept URI token: gabbrodiorite

  • Child of: gabbro

1.2.2.11.33.18.56 Troctolite

  • Child of: gabbro

  • A gabbroid with <5% pyroxene and is composed chiefly of calcic plagioclase (e.g., labradorite) and olivine. Such rocks commonly are speckled like trout.Synonym of: forellenstein, troutstone

  • Concept URI token: troctolite

1.2.2.11.33.18.57 Allivalite

  • Child of: troctolite

  • A variety of troctolite composed of olivine and highly calcic plagioclase.

  • Concept URI token: allivalite

1.2.2.11.33.18.58 Bytownite-troctolite

  • Child of: troctolite

  • A variety of troctolite containing bytownite

  • Concept URI token: bytownite-troctolite

1.2.2.11.33.18.59 Harrisite

  • Child of: troctolite

  • A variety of troctolite in which the large black lustrous olivines have a branching habit of growth and are orientated perpendicular to the layering. These crystals, unlike most large crystals in igneous rocks, grew quickly after a slowly-cooling magma became supersaturated (over-enriched) in olivine components or was trapped beneath another rock layer. The matrix to the olivines is composed of highly calcic plagioclase and minor pyroxene.

  • Concept URI token: harrisite

  • Gabbroid with a plagioclase to total feldspar ratio between 0.65 and 0.9. QAPF field 9, 9 prime and 9 asterisk

  • Concept URI token: monzogabbroic-rock

1.2.2.11.33.18.70 Amherstite

  • Child of: cizlakite

  • A leucocratic variety of quartz monzodiorite of QAPF field 9* belonging to the charnockitic rock series. The rock consists essentially of andesine- microcline antiperthite with minor quartz and hypersthene (= enstatite). It is suggested (Streckeisen, 1974, p.357) that this term should be abandoned.

  • Concept URI token: amherstite

1.2.2.11.33.18.74 Ophigranitone

  • Child of: quartz-monzogabbro

  • Concept URI token: ophigranitone

1.2.2.11.33.19 Granitoid

  • Child of: intrusive-igneous-rock

  • A granitoid is a coarse grained igneous rock composed mostly of quartz, K-feldspar (alkali-feldspar) and plagioclase), with 20-60% quartz on the QAPF diagram. It usually contains minor micas and/or amphiboles. Most commonly granite and granodiorite.

  • Alternate labels: Acid / Felsic Intrusive, Acid Intrusive, Acid Plutonic, Acid/Felsic Intrusive, Felsic Intrusive, Felsic plutonic, Granitic-rock,

  • Concept URI token: granitoid

1.2.2.11.33.19.1 A-type granite

  • Child of: granitoid

  • A general term for granitoids typically occurring in rift zones and the interiors of stable continental plates. The prefix A stands for anorogenic. Usually mildly alkaline and K-rich.

  • Concept URI token: a-type-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.2 Adamellite

  • Child of: granitoid

  • A term originally used for orthoclase-bearing tonalite of the Adamello Massif, but later used for granites with about equal amounts of alkali feldspar and plagioclase, which do not occur in the Adamello. The term should be avoided because of ambiguity and it is recommended that such rocks should be called monzogranite of QAPF field 3b.

  • Concept URI token: adamellite

1.2.2.11.33.19.3 Alkali-feldspar-granite

  • Child of: granitoid

  • A light-coloured granitoid (a coarse grained igneous rock composed mostly of quartz, Kspar (alkali-feldspar) and sodic plagioclase), where plagioclase is less than 10% of the total feldspar on the QAPF diagram

  • Alternate labels: Alkali feldspar granite, Aplogranite, Granite - Alkali Feldspar,

  • Concept URI token: alkali-feldspar-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.4 Alaskite

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-granite

  • A light coloured alkali-feldspar-granite with M’ colour index less than 10.In the United States, a commonly used term for a granitic rock containing few, if any, dark minerals. The term is used to designate granitoid rocks in which quartz constitutes 20% to 60% of the felsic minerals and in which the ratio of alkali feldspar to total feldspar is greater than 90%; i.e., the equivalent of alkali-feldspar granite. Alaskite is a commercial source of feldspar near Spruce Pine, NC.

  • Alternate labels: leuco-alkali-feldspar granite

  • Concept URI token: alaskite

1.2.2.11.33.19.5 Albite-granite

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-granite

  • An alkali-felspar-granite where the dominant feldspar is albite.

  • Concept URI token: albite-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.6 Charnockitic alkali-feldspar-granite

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-granite

  • An orthopyroxene-bearing alkali-feldspar-granite, part of the charnockite suite.

  • Alternate labels: Alkali-feldspar-charnockite, Hypersthene alkali-feldspar-granite, Opx alkali feldspar granite, Orthopyroxene alkali-feldspar-granite,

  • Concept URI token: charnockitic-alkali-feldspar-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.7 Evergreenite

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-granite

  • An alkali-feldspar-granite from the Evergreen Mine, Apex, Oregon, USA containing wollastonite.

  • Concept URI token: evergreenite

1.2.2.11.33.19.8 Lundyite

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-granite alkali-feldspar-syenite

  • A local name for a rock which is close to the boundary of alkali feldspar syenite and alkali feldspar granite and contains small amounts of katophorite.

  • Concept URI token: lundyite

1.2.2.11.33.19.9 Mela-alkali-feldspar-granite

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-granite

  • An alkali-feldspar-granite with an M’ colour index of greater than

  • Concept URI token: mela-alkali-feldspar-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.10 Peralkaline alkali-feldspar-granite

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-granite

  • A term that may be used for a variety of alkali feldspar granite that contains alkali pyroxene and/or amphibole. This term should be used in preference to alkali granite.

  • Alternate labels: Alkali granite, Peralkaline granite,

  • Concept URI token: peralkaline-alkali-feldspar-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.11 Brandbergite

  • Child of: peralkaline-alkali-feldspar-granite

  • A local name for a peralkaline alkali-feldspar-granite containing biotite and small amounts of arfvedsonite.

  • Concept URI token: brandbergite

1.2.2.11.33.19.12 Dahamite

  • Child of: peralkaline-alkali-feldspar-granite

  • An obsolete name for a fine-grained peralkaline alkali-feldspar- granite.

  • Concept URI token: dahamite

1.2.2.11.33.19.13 Dalmatian Stone

  • Child of: peralkaline-alkali-feldspar-granite

  • A trade name for a peraklakine rock (microgranite, aplite or rhyolite) consisting of dark spots (arfvedsonite) on a light (mostly feldspar) background.The material is often incorrectly termed as a ‘jasper’ and the black spots are frequently misidentified as tourmaline.

  • Alternate labels: Dalmatian Jasper

  • Concept URI token: dalmatian-stone

1.2.2.11.33.19.14 Ekerite

  • Child of: peralkaline-alkali-feldspar-granite

  • A local name for a peralkaline alkali-feldspar-granite from Eiker (Eker), Oslo district, Norway, comtaining anorthoclase, microperthite with small amounts of arfvedsonite and aegirine.

  • Concept URI token: ekerite

1.2.2.11.33.19.15 Evisite

  • Child of: peralkaline-alkali-feldspar-granite

  • A comprehensive term for peralkaline syenite and peralkaline alkali- feldspar-granite

  • Concept URI token: evisite

1.2.2.11.33.19.16 Fasibitikite

  • Child of: peralkaline-alkali-feldspar-granite

  • A fine-grained peralkaline alkali-feldspar-granite, similar to rockallite, containing large amounts of aegirine and riebeckite and characterized by the presence of eucolite

  • Concept URI token: fasibitikite

1.2.2.11.33.19.17 Porphyritic peralkaline alkali-feldspar-granite

  • Child of: peralkaline-alkali-feldspar-granite

  • A porphyritic and peralkaline variety of alkali-feldspar-granite.

  • Concept URI token: porphyritic-peralkaline-alkali-feldspar-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.18 Rockallite

  • Child of: peralkaline-alkali-feldspar-granite

  • A local name for a peralkaline granite containing abundant aegirine- augite and albite. From Rockall Island.

  • Concept URI token: rockallite

1.2.2.11.33.19.19 Peralkaline microgranite

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-granite

  • A microgranite of peralkaline composition.

  • Concept URI token: peralkaline-microgranite

1.2.2.11.33.19.20 C-type granite

  • Child of: granitoid

  • A general term for granitoid rocks with charnockitic features.

  • Concept URI token: c-type-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.21 Christianite

  • Child of: granitoid

  • An obsolete term based on an obsolete classification for granitic rocks where CaO:Na2O:K2O ‰ˆ 1:2.3:2.4 and SiO2 ‰ˆ 70%.

  • Concept URI token: christianite

1.2.2.11.33.19.22 Granite

  • Child of: granitoid

  • A granitoid (a coarse-grained igneous rock composed mostly of quartz, K-feldspar (alkali-feldspar) and plagioclase). More specifically a rock having an alkali-feldspar/total feldspar ratio from 0.35-0.90 on the QAPF diagram and 20-60% quartz.A coarse-grained, holocrystalline, felsic, acidic, plutonic rock.

  • Concept URI token: granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.23 Andengranite

  • Child of: granite

  • A granite that is younger than typically found in a local area.

  • Concept URI token: andengranite

1.2.2.11.33.19.24 Aplitic granite

  • Child of: granite

  • A fine-grained granite consisting of only feldspar and quartz.

  • Alternate labels: Granite aplite

  • Concept URI token: aplitic-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.25 Nepheline-bearing aplitic granite

  • Child of: aplitic-granite

  • An aplite containing some nepheline

  • Alternate labels: Aploid

  • Concept URI token: nepheline-bearing-aplitic-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.26 Biotite granite

  • Child of: granite

  • A granite containing biotite.

  • Alternate labels: Dartmoor granite

  • Concept URI token: biotite-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.27 Orbicular biotite granite

  • Child of: biotite-granite

  • A biotite granite containing orbicular features.

  • Concept URI token: orbicular-biotite-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.28 Shap granite

  • Child of: biotite-granite

  • One of the most distinctive British granites. Large pink phenocrysts of orthoclase in a groundmass of plagioclase, quartz and biotite.

  • Concept URI token: shap-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.29 Biquahororthandite

  • Child of: granite

  • A mnemoic name created by Johannsen (1931) to demonstrate the classification systsem of Belyankin (1929). This name indicates a granitic rock consisting of biotite, quartz, hornblende, orthoclase and andesine.

  • Concept URI token: biquahororthandite

1.2.2.11.33.19.30 Brecciated granite

  • Child of: breccia granite

  • A granite that has been brecciated, usually as part of a fault or shear zone.

  • Concept URI token: brecciated-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.31 Caucasite

  • Child of: granite

  • A type of granite containing anorthoclase or sanidine

  • Alternate labels: Kaukasite

  • Concept URI token: caucasite

1.2.2.11.33.19.32 Charnockitic granite

  • Child of: granite

  • An orthopyroxene-bearing granite, part of the charnockite suite.

  • Alternate labels: Charnockite

  • Concept URI token: charnockitic-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.33 Mesoperthite charnockitic granite

  • Concept URI token: mesoperthite-charnockitic-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.34 Corcovadite

  • Child of: granite

  • An obsolete local name for the hypabyssal equivalent of andengranite.

  • Concept URI token: corcovadite

1.2.2.11.33.19.35 Elvan

  • Child of: granite

  • A Cornish mining term for dyke rocks of granitic composition containing phenocrysts of quartz and orthoclase with tourmaline occurring as isolated crystals and radiating groups.

  • Alternate labels: Elvanite

  • Concept URI token: elvan

1.2.2.11.33.19.36 Engadinite

  • Child of: granite

  • A granite low in quartz.Named for the Engadin region, Switzerland.

  • Concept URI token: engadinite

1.2.2.11.33.19.37 Felsparite

  • Child of: granite

  • An obsolete term for a granite rich in feldspar.

  • Concept URI token: felsparite

1.2.2.11.33.19.38 Fluorine-rich granite

  • Child of: granite

  • A granite rich in fluorine, leading to the inclusion of minerals such as fluorite and topaz.

  • Concept URI token: fluorine-rich-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.39 Granophyric granite

  • Child of: granite

  • A granite exhibiting granophyric texture.

  • Alternate labels: Granophyre, micropegmatite,

  • Concept URI token: granophyric-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.40 Lunar granophyric granite

  • Child of: granophyric-granite highland-rock

  • A granite exhibiting granophyric texture. Fragments of this material have been found in lunar breccias and soils.

  • Alternate labels: Lunar granophyre

  • Concept URI token: lunar-granophyric-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.41 Graphic granite

  • Child of: granite

  • From the latin ‘Graphus’ (and greek ‘Graphos’) meaning to write - in allusion to the appearance of script-like characters in the polished rock.A granite exhibiting a graphic texture due to exsolution of quartz from feldspar.

  • Alternate labels: Hebraic Granite, Hebrew Stone, Runite, Schriftgranit@de,

  • Concept URI token: graphic-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.42 Hornblende-biotite granite

  • Child of: granite

  • A granite containing biotite and hornblende.

  • Concept URI token: hornblende-biotite-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.43 Hornblende granite

  • Child of: granite

  • A granite containing hornblende. Informally, a felsic plutonic rock, generally adamellite or granodiorite, containing an amphibole (often hornblende) as an essential dark-colored constituent; with decreasing quartz it grades through tonalite into normal diorite.

  • Concept URI token: hornblende-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.44 Leucogranite

  • Child of: granite

  • A granite with an M’ colour index of less than 5.

  • Alternate labels: Leucogranitoid

  • Concept URI token: leucogranite

1.2.2.11.33.19.45 K-feldspar enriched leucogranite

  • Child of: leucogranite ultrapotassic-rock

  • A leucogranite enriched in K-feldspar.

  • Concept URI token: k-feldspar-enriched-leucogranite

1.2.2.11.33.19.46 Melagranite

  • Child of: granite

  • A granite with an M’ colour index of greater than 20, i.e. a relatively dark granite (Greek mela = black).

  • Concept URI token: melagranite

1.2.2.11.33.19.47 Microgranite

  • Child of: granite

  • A granite with grainsize about 1-5mm.

  • Alternate labels: Felsic hypabyssal

  • Concept URI token: microgranite

1.2.2.11.33.19.48 Ailsyte

  • Child of: microgranite

  • A type of microgranite or quartz microsyenite consisting of orthoclase, quartz and riebeckite.

  • Alternate labels: Ailsite

  • Concept URI token: ailsyte

1.2.2.11.33.19.49 Monzogranite

  • Child of: granite

  • A granitoid (a coarse grained igneous rock composed mostly of quartz, Kspar (alkali-feldspar) and plagioclase), with subequal amounts of plagioclase and Kspar. More specifically a granite having an alkali-feldspar/total feldspar ratio from 0.35-0.65 on the QAPF diagram. Often called an adamellite, though this name has been used for other rocktypes also.

  • Alternate labels: Beta granite, Monzogranit@de,

  • Concept URI token: monzogranite

1.2.2.11.33.19.50 Leucomonzogranite

  • Child of: monzogranite

  • A monzogranite with an M’ colour index of less than 5.

  • Concept URI token: leucomonzogranite

  • Concept URI token: orthopyroxene-monzogranite

1.2.2.11.33.19.53 Muscovite-biotite granite

  • Child of: granite

  • A granite containing both muscovite and biotite.

1.2.2.11.33.19.55 Porphyritic granite

  • Child of: granite

  • A granite exhibiting porphyritic texture.

  • Concept URI token: porphyritic-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.56 Luxulianite

  • Child of: porphyritic-granite

  • A type of porphyritic granite containing abundant tourmaline replacing various minerals.A granite characterized by phenocrysts of potassium feldspar and quartz that enclose clusters of radially arranged acicular tourmaline crystals in a groundmass of quartz, tourmaline, alkali feldspar, brown mica, and cassiterite. Its name is derived from Luxulyan, Cornwall. Also spelled: luxulianite; luxulyanite. Var: luxuliane.

  • Alternate labels: Luxullianite, Luxulyanite,

  • Concept URI token: luxulianite

1.2.2.11.33.19.57 Trowlesworthite

  • Child of: porphyritic-granite

  • An obsolete name for a coarse-grained pneumatolytic vein found in granite consisting of red orthoclase, tourmaline and fluorite with minor quartz.

  • Concept URI token: trowlesworthite

1.2.2.11.33.19.58 Rapakivi granite

  • Child of: granite

  • A term, used as both an adjective and noun, for a variety of granite usually containing amphibole and biotite and characterized by the presence of large oval grains (ovoids) of orthoclase which are usually mantled by plagioclase. Two generations of quartz are often present. From the Finnish word for ’rotten stone.’Many of the classical buildings in St Petersburg, Russia, are clad with Rapakivi granite imported from Finland.

  • Alternate labels: Rapakivi

  • Concept URI token: rapakivi-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.59 Riebeckite granite

  • Child of: granite

  • A granite containing riebeckite.

  • Concept URI token: riebeckite-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.60 Syenogranite

  • Child of: granite

  • A granitoid (a coarse grained igneous rock composed of mostly quartz, plus Kspar (alkali-feldspar) and plagioclase), with plagioclase < Kspar. More specifically a granite having an alkali- feldspar/total feldspar ratio from 0.65-0.90, and 20-60% quartz on the QAPF diagram.

  • Alternate labels: Alpha granite

  • Concept URI token: syenogranite

1.2.2.11.33.19.61 Leucosyenogranite

  • Child of: syenogranite

  • A syenogranite with an M’ colour index of less than 5.

  • Concept URI token: leucosyenogranite

1.2.2.11.33.19.62 Melasyenogranite

  • Child of: syenogranite

  • A syenogranite with an M’ colour index of greater than 25.

  • Concept URI token: melasyenogranite

1.2.2.11.33.19.63 Granodiorite

  • Child of: granitoid

  • A granitoid (a coarse grained igneous rock with <90% mafics, composed mostly of quartz, K-feldspar (alkali-feldspar) and plagioclase). It has 20-60% quartz and plagioclase is 65-90% of the total feldspar on the QAPF diagram. Coarse-grained plutonic rocks intermediate in composition between tonalite and granite containing quartz, plagioclase (oligoclase or andesine), and subordinate potassium feldspar, with biotite and/or hornblende, or, more rarely, pyroxene, as the mafic components; the approximate intrusive equivalent of rhyodacite.

  • Concept URI token: granodiorite

1.2.2.11.33.19.64 Charnockitic granodiorite

  • Child of: granodiorite

  • An orthopyroxene-bearing granodiorite

  • Alternate labels: Charno-enderbite, Opdalite, Orthopyroxene granodiorite,

  • Concept URI token: charnockitic-granodiorite

1.2.2.11.33.19.65 Engelburgite

  • Child of: granodiorite

  • A variety of hybrid biotite granodiorite containing leucocratic spots consisting of alkali feldspar and abundant titanite.

  • Concept URI token: engelburgite

1.2.2.11.33.19.66 Hornblende-biotite granodiorite

  • Child of: granodiorite

  • A granodiorite containing hornblende and biotite.

  • Concept URI token: hornblende-biotite-granodiorite

  • Child of: microgranodiorite

  • A porphyritic microgranodiorite.

  • Concept URI token: porphyritic-microgranodiorite

1.2.2.11.33.19.71 Volhynite

  • Child of: microgranodiorite

  • A local name for a microgranodiorite which occurs as dykes and contains phenocrysts of labradorite, hornblende and biotite in a groundmass of andesine, orthoclase and quartz.

  • Alternate labels: Wolhynite

  • Concept URI token: volhynite

1.2.2.11.33.19.72 I-type granite

  • Child of: granitoid

  • Granitoid rocks derived from igneous source rocks, usually plagioclase-rich and muscovite poor.

  • Concept URI token: i-type-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.73 M-type granite

  • Child of: granitoid

  • A general term for a granitoids occurring in some continental margins and having the chemical and isotopic compo- sitions of island arc volcanic rocks. The prefix M implies a mantle origin as they are assumed to have formed by partial melting of the subducted oceanic crust.

  • Concept URI token: m-type-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.74 miarolite

  • Child of: granitoid

  • A granite having miarolitic cavities; a textural modification of normal granite.

  • Concept URI token: miarolite

1.2.2.11.33.19.75 Microgranitoid

  • Child of: granitoid

  • A granitoid with a grainsize of 1-5mm.

  • Concept URI token: microgranitoid

1.2.2.11.33.19.76 S-type granite

  • Child of: granitoid

  • Granitoid rocks derived from sedimentary source rocks, usually peraluminous, with muscovite and Al-rich minerals like garnet, cordierite and andalusite.

  • Concept URI token: s-type-granite

1.2.2.11.33.19.77 Tonalite

  • Child of: granitoid

  • A granitoid (a coarse grained igneous rock with <90% mafics; felsic minerals are composed mostly of quartz (20-60%), Kspar (alkali- feldspar) and plagioclase), where plagioclase is >90% of the total feldspar on the QAPF diagram.

  • Concept URI token: tonalite

1.2.2.11.33.19.78 Alentegite

  • Child of: quartz-diorite tonalite

  • An group of mica quartz diorites containing 16% to 33% of quartz. Erroneously spelt alentecite by Tomkeieff.

  • Alternate labels: Alentecite

  • Concept URI token: alentegite

1.2.2.11.33.19.79 Amphibole tonalite

  • Child of: tonalite

  • A tonalite containing amphibole.

  • Alternate labels: Andersonite (of Riba)

  • Concept URI token: amphibole-tonalite

1.2.2.11.33.19.80 Calc-tonalite

  • Child of: tonalite

  • An obsolete term for a tonalite in which the alkali feldspar to plagioclase ratio is less than 1 to 6.5.

  • Concept URI token: calc-tonalite

1.2.2.11.33.19.81 Charnockitic tonalite

  • Child of: tonalite

  • A pyroxene-bearing tonalite.

  • Alternate labels: Enderbite

  • Concept URI token: charnockitic-tonalite

1.2.2.11.33.19.82 Leucocratic charnockitic tonalite

  • Child of: charnockitic-tonalite

  • Concept URI token: leucocratic-charnockitic-tonalite

1.2.2.11.33.19.83 M-enderbite

  • Child of: charnockitic-tonalite

  • A charnockitic tonalite containing mesoperthite.

  • Concept URI token: m-enderbite

1.2.2.11.33.19.84 Leucotonalite

  • Child of: tonalite

  • A tonalite with an M’ colour index of less than 10.

  • Concept URI token: leucotonalite

1.2.2.11.33.19.85 Trondhjemite

  • Child of: leucotonalite

  • A leucotonalite whose plagioclase is oligoclase or andesine, quartz at least 20% of the leucocratic minerals, and and alkali feldspar be no more than 10% of the total feldspar. Color index must be 10 or less.

  • Concept URI token: trondhjemite

1.2.2.11.33.19.86 Melatonalite

  • Child of: tonalite

  • A tonalite with an M’ colour index of greater than 40.

  • Concept URI token: melatonalite

1.2.2.11.33.19.87 Microtonalite

  • Child of: tonalite

  • A tonalite with a grainsize of 1-5mm.

  • Concept URI token: microtonalite

1.2.2.11.33.20 Haueynitite

  • Child of: intrusive-igneous-rock

  • A coarse graied plutonic or hypabyssal igneous rock composed chiefly of hauyne and pyroxene, usually titanaugite. Small amounts of other feldspathoids and sometimes plagioclase and/or olivine are present. Apatite, sphene, and opaque oxides occur as accessories.

  • Concept URI token: haueynitite

1.2.2.11.33.21 Orbiculite

  • Child of: intrusive-igneous-rock

  • A coarse grained igneous rock with an orbicular structure. It may be a granite, granodiorite, diorite or gabbro.The orbicules are concentrically layered, spheroidal structures composed mostly of feldspars and mafic minerals, formed by rapid nucleation in a magma.

  • Concept URI token: orbiculite

1.2.2.11.33.22 Quartz-rich-coarse-grained-crystalline-rock

  • Child of: intrusive-igneous-rock

  • Quartz-rich (>60%) coarse-grained crystalline igneous rock. They usually include some feldspars and micas and/or amphiboles. It is subdivided into quartzolite (>90% quartz) and Quartz-rich granitic rock (60-90% quartz).In many cases these rocks may be hydrothermally altered granitoids (i.e greisens) rather than true igneous rocks.

  • Alternate labels: Quartz rich coarse grained crystalline rock

  • Concept URI token: quartz-rich-coarse-grained-crystalline-rock

1.2.2.11.33.22.1 Quartz-rich-granitic-rock

  • Child of: quartz-rich-coarse-grained-crystalline-rock

  • A coarse-grained crystalline igneous rock in which quartz comprises between 60-90% of the felsic minerals, and has <90% mafic minerals. It usually includes some feldspars and micas and/or amphiboles, and grades into quartzolite with increasing quartz, or granitoids with increasing feldspar.

  • Alternate labels: Quartz-rich granitoid

  • Concept URI token: quartz-rich-granitic-rock

1.2.2.11.33.22.2 Arizonite

  • Child of: quartz-rich-granitic-rock

  • A local name for a dyke rock consisting of 80% quartz with 18% orthoclase and 2% muscovite.

  • Alternate labels: Arizonite of (Spurr & Washington)

  • Concept URI token: arizonite

1.2.2.11.33.22.3 Quartzolite

  • Child of: quartz-rich-coarse-grained-crystalline-rock

  • A rare coarse-grained crystalline igneous rock in which quartz comprises more than 90% of the felsic minerals, and has <90% mafic minerals. It usually includes some feldspars and micas and/or amphiboles, and grades into quartz-rich granitic rocks with increasing feldspars. In many cases these rocks may be hydrothermally altered granitoids (i.e greisens) rather than true igneous rocks.

  • Concept URI token: quartzolite

1.2.2.11.33.22.4 Esmeraldite

  • Child of: quartzolite

  • A granular quartzolite, possibly an extremene differentiate, consisting predominantly of quartz with some muscovite.

  • Concept URI token: esmeraldite

1.2.2.11.33.22.5 Silexite

  • Child of: chert quartzolite

    1. An igneous rock composed essentially of primary quartz (60% to 100%), e.g., a quartz dike, segregation mass, or inclusion inside or outside its parent rock.Ref: AGIii. The French term for chert; specif. chert occurring in calcareous beds.See Also: Chert

  • Concept URI token: silexite

1.2.2.11.33.23 Syenitoid

  • Child of: intrusive-igneous-rock

  • A coarse grained felsic igneous rock having an alkali- feldspar/plagioclase ratio from 0.9-0.35, 0-10% foids and 0-20% quartz.

  • Alternate labels: Syenitic-rock

  • Concept URI token: syenitoid

1.2.2.11.33.23.1 Alkali feldspar syenitic rock

  • Child of: syenitoid

  • Syenitoid with a plagioclase to total feldspar ratio of less than 0.1. QAPF fields 6, 6*, and 6’.

  • Alternate labels: Alkali-feldspar syentitic rock, Alkali-feldspar-syenitic-rock,

  • Concept URI token: alkali-feldspar-syenitic-rock

1.2.2.11.33.23.2 Alkali-feldspar-syenite

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-syenitic-rock

  • A syenitic-rock where plagioclase is less than 10% of the total feldspar.

  • Alternate labels: Alkali feldspar syenite, Syenite - Alkali-Feldspar,

  • Concept URI token: alkali-feldspar-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.3 Anorthoclasite

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-syenite

  • A variety of alkali feldspar syenite composed almost entirely of anorthoclase.

  • Concept URI token: anorthoclasite

1.2.2.11.33.23.4 Bigwoodite

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-syenite

  • A variety of alkali feldspar syenite consisting essentially of orthoclase, microcline and albite with traces of foids and sodic pyroxene and/or amphibole.

  • Concept URI token: bigwoodite

1.2.2.11.33.23.5 Bostonite

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-syenite

  • A variety of fine-grained leucocratic alkali feldspar syenite consisting almost entirely of alkali feldspar and characterized by a bostonitic texture, i.e. irregular, subparallel laths of feldspar arranged in a divergent manner.

  • Concept URI token: bostonite

1.2.2.11.33.23.6 Maenite

  • Child of: bostonite

  • An intrusive trachytic rock, regarded as a differentiation product of a gabbroic magma. Maenite is a bostonite relatively high in calcium and low in potassium.

  • Concept URI token: maenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.7 Charnockitic alkali-feldspar-syenite

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-syenite

  • A pyroxene-bearing alkali-feldspar-syenite

  • Alternate labels: Opx alkali feldspar syenite

  • Concept URI token: charnockitic-alkali-feldspar-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.8 Ankaranandite

  • Child of: charnockitic-alkali-feldspar-syenite charnockitic-syenite

  • A group name for varieties of orthopyroxene alkali-feldspar-syenite to orthopyroxene syenite of QAPF fields 6-6* to 7-7* belonging to the charnockitic rock series. It is suggested (Streckeisen, 1974, p.357) that this term should be abandoned.

  • Concept URI token: ankaranandite

1.2.2.11.33.23.9 Elkhornite

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-syenite

  • A alkali-feldspar-syenite containing some labradorite.

  • Concept URI token: elkhornite

1.2.2.11.33.23.10 Finandranite

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-syenite

  • A K-rich variety of alkali-feldspar-syenite consisting essentially of microcline and torendrikite (= magnesio- riebeckite), with some biotite and ilmenite.

  • Concept URI token: finandranite

1.2.2.11.33.23.11 Lundyite

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-granite alkali-feldspar-syenite

  • A local name for a rock which is close to the boundary of alkali feldspar syenite and alkali feldspar granite and contains small amounts of katophorite.

  • Concept URI token: lundyite

1.2.2.11.33.23.12 Mela-alkali-feldspar-syenite

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-syenite

  • An alkali-feldspar-syenite with an M’ colour index of greater than

  • Concept URI token: mela-alkali-feldspar-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.13 Microclinite

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-syenite

  • A variety of alkali-feldspar-syenite composed almost entirely of microcline.

  • Concept URI token: microclinite

1.2.2.11.33.23.14 Nordmarkite

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-syenite

  • A variety of quartz-bearing alkali-feldspar-syenite composed mainly of microperthite with minor biotite, alkali amphibole or pyroxene.

  • Concept URI token: nordmarkite

1.2.2.11.33.23.15 Peralkaline alkali-feldspar-syenite

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.16 Lusitanite

  • Child of: peralkaline-alkali-feldspar-syenite

  • A variety of peralkaline alkali-feldspar-syenite containing riebeckite and aegirine. Also used as family name for rocks consisting essentially of alkali feldspar.

  • Concept URI token: lusitanite

1.2.2.11.33.23.17 Umptekite

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-syenite

  • A variety of alkali-feldspar-syenite consisting of microperthite, arfvedsonite, aegirine and, sometimes, nepheline.

  • Concept URI token: umptekite

1.2.2.11.33.23.18 Foid-bearing-alkali-feldspar-syenite

  • Child of: alkali-feldspar-syenitic-rock

  • An alkali-feldspar-syenite with no quartz and containing up to 10% foids.

  • Alternate labels: Foid-bearing alkali feldspar syenite

  • Concept URI token: foid-bearing-alkali-feldspar-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.21 Pulaskite

  • Child of: nepheline-bearing-alkali-feldspar-syenite

  • A variety of nepheline-bearing-alkali-feldspar-syenite containing alkali feldspar and varying amounts of sodic pyroxenes and amphiboles, fayalite, biotite and minor amounts of nepheline.

  • Concept URI token: pulaskite

1.2.2.11.33.23.26 Aplosyenite

  • Child of: syenitoid

  • An obsolete term used as a family name for syenites with less than 5% mafics.

1.2.2.11.33.23.27 Monzonitic rock

  • Child of: syenitoid

  • Syenitoid with a plagioclase to total feldspar ratio between 0.35 and 0.65. Includes rocks in QAPF fields 8, 8*, and 8’.

  • Concept URI token: monzonitic-rock

1.2.2.11.33.23.28 Foid-bearing-monzonite

  • Child of: monzonitic-rock

  • A monzonite with no quartz and <10% foids

  • Alternate labels: Foid-bearing monzonite, Foid-bearing monzosyenite, Foid-bearing-monzosyenite,

1.2.2.11.33.23.31 Sodalite-bearing-monzonite

  • Child of: foid-bearing-monzonite

  • A foid-bearing-monzonite where sodalite is the most abundant foid.

  • Concept URI token: sodalite-bearing-monzonite

1.2.2.11.33.23.32 Monzonite

  • Child of: monzonitic-rock

  • A coarse-grained igneous rock containing almost equal amounts of alkali feldspar and plagioclase, and thus intermediate between syenite and diorite. Quartz is minor or absent. Either hornblende or diopside, or both, are present and biotite is a common constituent. Accessories are apatite, zircon, sphene, and opaque oxides. The intrusive equivalent of latite.

  • Alternate labels: Monzosyenite, syenodiorite,

  • Concept URI token: monzonite

1.2.2.11.33.23.33 Aplitic monzonite

  • Child of: monzonite

  • An aplitic monzonite.

  • Concept URI token: aplitic-monzonite

1.2.2.11.33.23.34 Augite monzonite

  • Child of: monzonite

  • A monzonite containing augite.

  • Concept URI token: augite-monzonite

1.2.2.11.33.23.35 Charnockitic monzonite

  • Child of: monzonite

  • A monzonite containing orthopyroxenes.

  • Alternate labels: Mangerite

  • Concept URI token: charnockitic-monzonite

1.2.2.11.33.23.36 Highwoodite

  • Child of: monzonite

  • An obsolete name for a dark-colored intrusive rock composed of alkali feldspar, labradorite, pyroxene, biotite, iron oxides, apatite, and possibly a small amount of nepheline. It is essentially a monzonite. Its name, given by Johannsen in 1938, is derived from the Highwood Mountains, Montana, USA.

  • Concept URI token: highwoodite

1.2.2.11.33.23.37 Kentallenite

  • Child of: monzonite

  • A local term for a melanocratic variety of monzonite composed of olivine, augite, zoned plagioclase, biotite and green micas and interstitial alkali feldspar.

  • Concept URI token: kentallenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.38 Leucomonzonite

  • Child of: monzonite

  • A monzonite with an M’ colour index of less than 15.

  • Concept URI token: leucomonzonite

1.2.2.11.33.23.39 Melamonzonite

  • Child of: monzonite

  • A monzonite with an M’ colour index of greater than 45.

  • Concept URI token: melamonzonite

1.2.2.11.33.23.40 Micromonzonite

  • Child of: monzonite

  • A monzonite with a grainsize of 1-5mm.

  • Alternate labels: Micro-Quartz Monzonite

  • Concept URI token: micromonzonite

1.2.2.11.33.23.41 Bereshite

  • Child of: microgabbro micromonzonite

  • A term for a porphyritic micromonzonite or monzogabbro rich in nepheline phenocrysts and containing analcime, titanian augite rimmed by aegirine. Later transliterated as bereshite.

  • Concept URI token: bereshite

1.2.2.11.33.23.42 Olivine monzonite

  • Child of: monzonite

  • An olivine-bearing monzonite.

  • Concept URI token: olivine-monzonite

1.2.2.11.33.23.43 Quartz-monzonite

  • Child of: monzonitic-rock

  • A syenitoid with 5-20% quartz and subequal K-feldspar and plagioclase (35-65% of the feldspars being plagioclase) on the QAPF diagram, and no foids.This is a coarse-grained equivalent of quartz- latite.

  • Alternate labels: Quartz monzonite

  • Concept URI token: quartz-monzonite

  • Child of: quartz-monzonite

  • Concept URI token: melaquartz-monzonite

1.2.2.11.33.23.47 Syenitic rock

  • Child of: syenitoid

  • Syenitoid with a plagioclase to total feldspar ratio between 0.1 and 0.35. Includes rocks in QAPF fields 7, 7*, and 7’.

  • Alternate labels: Alkali Intrusive, K-Feldspar quartz rock,

  • Concept URI token: syenitic-rock

1.2.2.11.33.23.54 Cancarixite

  • Child of: peralkaline-quartz-syenite

  • Concept URI token: quartz-microsyenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.57 Syenite

  • Child of: syenitic-rock

  • A granitoid having an alkali-feldspar/plagioclase ratio from 65-90% and <5% quartz. A group of plutonic rocks containing alkali feldspar (usually orthoclase, microcline, or perthite), a small amount of plagioclase (less than in ‘monzonite’), one or more mafic minerals (esp. hornblende), and quartz, if present, only as an accessory.

  • Concept URI token: syenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.58 Albite syenite

  • Child of: syenite

  • A syenite where the primary feldspar component is albite.

  • Concept URI token: albite-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.59 Alkorthosite

  • Child of: syenite

  • An obsolete name for a variety of consisting predominantly of Na- orthoclase.

  • Concept URI token: alkorthosite

1.2.2.11.33.23.60 Anorthoclase syenite

  • Child of: syenite

  • A syenite cotanining anorthoclase

  • Concept URI token: anorthoclase-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.61 Porphyritic anorthoclase syenite

  • Child of: anorthoclase-syenite

  • A porphyritic anorthoclase syenite.

  • Alternate labels: Anorthophyre

  • Concept URI token: porphyritic-anorthoclase-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.62 Anorthosyenite

  • Child of: syenite

  • An obsolete term for a variety of syenite with phenocrysts of anorthoclase.

  • Concept URI token: anorthosyenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.63 Augite syenite

  • Child of: syenite

  • A syenite containing prominent augite.

  • Concept URI token: augite-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.64 Larvikite

  • Child of: augite-syenite

  • After the town of Larvik in Norway, where it was described from.A variety of augite syenite or monzonite consisting of rhomb-shaped ternary feldspars (with a distinctive schiller), barkevikite, titanian augite and lepidomelane.

  • Alternate labels: Laurvikite, blue granite,

  • Concept URI token: larvikite

1.2.2.11.33.23.65 Kjelsasite

  • Child of: larvikite

  • A local name given to a plagioclase-rich larvikite which is a variety of augite syenite or monzonite.

  • Concept URI token: kjelsasite

1.2.2.11.33.23.66 Tonsbergite

  • Child of: larvikite

  • A local name introduced by Bragger (1898) for a reddish variety of larvikite. Named for the locality, the town of Tansberg, Vestfod, Norway. A hydrothermally altered larvikite.

  • Concept URI token: tonsbergite

1.2.2.11.33.23.67 Biotite hornblende syenite

  • Child of: syenite

  • A syenite containing hornblende and biotite.

  • Concept URI token: biotite-hornblende-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.68 Charnockitic syenite

  • Child of: syenite

  • A syenite containing pyroxene which is part of the charnokitic suite of rocks.

  • Alternate labels: Opx syenite, Orthopyroxene syenite,

  • Concept URI token: charnockitic-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.69 Ankaranandite

  • Child of: charnockitic-alkali-feldspar-syenite charnockitic-syenite

  • A group name for varieties of orthopyroxene alkali-feldspar-syenite to orthopyroxene syenite of QAPF fields 6-6* to 7-7* belonging to the charnockitic rock series. It is suggested (Streckeisen, 1974, p.357) that this term should be abandoned.

  • Concept URI token: ankaranandite

1.2.2.11.33.23.70 Episyenite

  • Child of: syenite

  • An igneous-looking rock of syenite composition produced by hydrothermal dissolutioon of quartz crystals in an altered granite. May host uranium deposits.

  • Concept URI token: episyenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.71 Granosyenite

  • Child of: syenite

  • An obsolete term for a syenitic rock closer to granitic composition.

  • Concept URI token: granosyenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.72 jadeolite

  • Child of: syenite

  • A deep-green chromiferous syenite cut as a gemstone and resembling jade in appearance. Obsolete.

  • Concept URI token: jadeolite

1.2.2.11.33.23.73 Kalsilite syenite

  • Child of: kalsilitic-rock syenite

  • A kalsilite-bearing plutonic rock first recorded from the Aldan and North Baikal petrological provinces of Russia.

  • Alternate labels: Synnyrite

  • Concept URI token: kalsilite-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.74 Leucosyenite

  • Child of: syenite

  • A syenite with an M’ colour index of less than 10.

  • Concept URI token: leucosyenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.75 Melasyenite

  • Child of: syenite

  • A syenite with an M’ colour index of greater than 35.

  • Concept URI token: melasyenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.76 Microsyenite

  • Child of: syenite

  • A syenite with a grainsize of 1-5mm.

  • Concept URI token: microsyenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.77 Akerite

  • Child of: microsyenite

  • A collective term for varieties of microsyenite and micromonzonite consisting of alkali feldspar with more or less oligoclase, biotite, pyroxene and often quartz. Characterised by rectangular oligoclase.

  • Concept URI token: akerite

1.2.2.11.33.23.78 Essexite-akerite

  • Child of: akerite

  • A dark plagioclase-rich akerite. From Lortlauptal, W. Vikersund, Oslo district, Norway.

  • Concept URI token: essexite-akerite

1.2.2.11.33.23.79 Durbachite

  • Child of: microsyenite

  • A melanocratic microsyenite consisting of large biotite flakes with hornblende and orthoclase megacrysts in a groundmass of oligoclase and a little quartz.

  • Concept URI token: durbachite

1.2.2.11.33.23.80 Rafaelite

  • Child of: microsyenite

  • A variety of analcime-bearing microsyenite containing amphibole and labradorite, but no nepheline.

  • Alternate labels: Rafaelite (of Johannsen)

  • Concept URI token: rafaelite

1.2.2.11.33.23.81 Peralkaline syenite

  • Child of: syenite

  • A syenite containing alkali amphibole or pyroxene.

  • Alternate labels: Alkali syenite

  • Concept URI token: peralkaline-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.82 Angolaite

  • Child of: peralkaline-syenite

  • A peralkaline syenite consisting of alkali feldspar (87% in type material), titanaugite with aegirine-augite rims (5%), aegirine (0.7%), fayalite (3.6%) and accessory magnetite, apatite, aenigmatite, hastingsite and cancrinite.

  • Concept URI token: angolaite

1.2.2.11.33.23.83 Pegmatitic peralkaline syenite

  • Child of: pegmatite peralkaline-syenite

  • A pegmatite of peralkaline syenite composition.

  • Alternate labels: Peralkaline syenite pegmatite

  • Concept URI token: pegmatitic-peralkaline-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.84 Bowralite

  • Child of: pegmatitic-peralkaline-syenite

  • A pegmatitic peralkaline syenite composed of idiomorphic feldspar with interstitial arfvedsonite and aegirine-augite.

  • Concept URI token: bowralite

1.2.2.11.33.23.85 Nepheline syenite pegmatite

  • Child of: pegmatitic-peralkaline-syenite

  • A pegmatite of nepheline-syenite composition.

  • Concept URI token: nepheline-syenite-pegmatite

1.2.2.11.33.23.86 Agpaitic nepheline syenite pegmatite

  • Child of: nepheline-syenite-pegmatite

  • A pegmatite of a peralkaline nepheline-syenite with complex Na-Ca- Ti-Zr-silicate minerals, such as eudialyte group, wohlerite group and rinkite group minerals.

  • Concept URI token: agpaitic-nepheline-syenite-pegmatite

1.2.2.11.33.23.87 Syenite pegmatite

  • Child of: pegmatitic-peralkaline-syenite

  • A pegmatite of syenite composition.

  • Concept URI token: syenite-pegmatite

1.2.2.11.33.23.88 Porphyritic peralkaline syenite

  • Child of: peralkaline-syenite

  • A porphyritic and peralkaline variety of syenite.

  • Concept URI token: porphyritic-peralkaline-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.89 Sodic syenite

  • Child of: syenite

  • A syenite enriched in Na2O relative to K2O.

  • Concept URI token: sodic-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.90 Pegmatitic sodic syenite

  • Child of: pegmatite sodic-syenite

  • A pegmatite of sodic syenite composition.

  • Concept URI token: pegmatitic-sodic-syenite

1.2.2.11.33.23.91 Antifenitepegmatite

  • Child of: pegmatitic-sodic-syenite

  • A pegmatitic sodic syenite composed mainly of antiperthite with minor biotite and opaques.

  • Concept URI token: antifenitepegmatite

1.2.2.11.33.23.92 Sviatonossite

  • Child of: syenite

  • A local term for syenites characterised by the presence of andradite garnet, possibly hybrid rocks.

  • Concept URI token: sviatonossite

1.2.2.11.34 Labradorite (rock)

  • Child of: normal-crystalline-igneous-rock

  • An old name once used as a group name for gabbros, basalts etc. Also used by the Russians and French for labradorite-phyric basalts.

  • Alternate labels: Labradorite (of Senft)

  • Concept URI token: labradorite-rock

1.2.2.11.35 Ophiolite

  • Child of: normal-crystalline-igneous-rock

  • Rocks consisting mainly of serpentine, and the rock suite of Alpine- type peridotites, gabbros, dolerites, spilites and keratophyres. Now used to define the association of basic to ultrabasic rocks thought to represent oceanic crust. A group of mafic and ultramafic igneous rocks ranging from spilite and basalt to gabbro and peridotite, including rocks rich in serpentine, chlorite, epidote, and albite derived from them by later metamorphism, whose origin is associated with an early phase of the development of a geosyncline.

  • Concept URI token: ophiolite

1.2.2.11.36 Porphyry

  • Child of: normal-crystalline-igneous-rock

  • Any rock with coarse phenocrysts in a finer groundmass. Most commonly used for felsic rocks such as rhyolites, granites, etc. The rock name descriptive of the groundmass composition usually precedes the term; e.g., diorite porphyry.

  • Alternate labels: Porphyritic rock, Porphyry Undifferentiated,

  • Concept URI token: porphyry

1.2.2.11.36.1 Alsbachite

  • Child of: porphyry

  • A local name for a porphyritic dyke rock containing phenocrysts of quartz, feldspar and garnet in a fine-grained groundmass of quartz, feldspar and colourless mica.

  • Concept URI token: alsbachite

1.2.2.11.36.2 Augite porphyry

  • Child of: porphyry

  • Augite-phyric porphyry

  • Concept URI token: augite-porphyry

1.2.2.11.36.3 Biotite-feldspar porphyry

  • Biotite-feldspar porphyry

  • Concept URI token: biotite-feldspar-porphyry

  • Concept URI token: feldspar-porphyry

1.2.2.11.36.5 Hornblende porphyry

  • Concept URI token: hornblende-porphyry

1.2.2.11.36.6 Nepheline-feldspar porphyry

  • A nepheline-feldspar porphyry.

  • Concept URI token: nepheline-feldspar-porphyry

1.2.2.11.36.7 Nepheline porphyry

  • Child of: porphyry

  • A porphyry containing nepheline as the primary mineral.

  • Concept URI token: nepheline-porphyry

1.2.2.11.36.8 Porphyrite

  • Child of: porphyry

  • An obsolete term originally used for porphyries that contain mostly plagioclase phenocrysts and mafics in contrast to those that contain mostly alkali feldspar phenocrysts.

  • Concept URI token: porphyrite

1.2.2.11.36.9 Quartz-feldspar-biotite porphyry

  • Child of: porphyry

  • A porphyry predominantly composed of quartz, feldspar and biotite.

  • Concept URI token: quartz-feldspar-biotite-porphyry

1.2.2.11.36.10 Quartz-feldspar porphyry

  • Child of: porphyry

  • Quartz-feldspar-phyric porphyry

  • Alternate labels: Quartz feldspar porphyry

  • Concept URI token: quartz-feldspar-porphyry

1.2.2.11.36.11 Quartz porphyry

  • Child of: porphyry

  • Quartz-phyric porphyry. A field term for a medium-grained porphyritic igneous rock of felsic but unspecified composition occurring normally as minor stock or dyke intrusions, and carrying prominent phenocrysts of quartz. It is a common altered host rock to porphyry copper deposits.

  • Alternate labels: quartz felsite

  • Concept URI token: quartz-porphyry

1.2.2.11.36.12 Vitrophyric porphyry

  • Child of: porphyry

  • A porphyry with phenocrysts in a glassy groundmass

  • Concept URI token: vitrophyric-porphyry

1.2.2.11.37 Ultramafic-rock

  • Child of: normal-crystalline-igneous-rock

  • Originally a term for a rock consisting essentially of mafic minerals, e.g. peridotite, dunite. Now defined as a rock with M > 90%, fine or coarse grained.

  • Alternate labels: Ultramafic rock, Ultramafic,

  • Concept URI token: ultramafic-rock

1.2.2.12 Pegmatite

  • Child of: igneous-rock

  • An exceptionally coarse-grained igneous rock, with interlocking crystals, usually found as irregular dikes, lenses, or veins, esp. at the margins of batholiths. Most grains are 1 cm or more in diameter. Although pegmatites having gross compositions similar to other rock types are known, their composition is generally that of granite; the composition may be simple or complex and may include rare minerals rich in such elements as lithium, boron, fluorine, niobium, tantalum, uranium, and rare earths.

  • Alternate labels: Pegmatite (vein), Pegmatyte, giant granite,

  • Concept URI token: pegmatite

1.2.2.12.1 Biotite-quartz-feldspar pegmatite

  • Child of: pegmatite

  • Biotite-quartz-feldspar pegmatite

  • Concept URI token: biotite-quartz-feldspar-pegmatite

1.2.2.12.2 Margarite-corundum pegmatite

  • Child of: pegmatite

  • A pegmatite composed primarily of margarite and corundum.

  • Concept URI token: margarite-corundum-pegmatite

  • Child of: pegmatite

  • A pegmatitic dolerite containing albite.

  • Concept URI token: pegmatitic-albite-dolerite

1.2.2.12.4 Pegmatitic gabbro
