  • Concept URI token: pegmatitic-gabbro

1.2.2.12.5 Pegmatitic granite

  • Child of: granite pegmatite

  • A pegmatite of granite composition.

  • Alternate labels: Granite pegmatite, Granitic pegmatite,

  • Concept URI token: pegmatitic-granite

1.2.2.12.6 Pegmatitic peralkaline syenite

  • Child of: pegmatite peralkaline-syenite

  • A pegmatite of peralkaline syenite composition.

  • Alternate labels: Peralkaline syenite pegmatite

  • Concept URI token: pegmatitic-peralkaline-syenite

1.2.2.12.6.1 Bowralite

  • Child of: pegmatitic-peralkaline-syenite

  • A pegmatitic peralkaline syenite composed of idiomorphic feldspar with interstitial arfvedsonite and aegirine-augite.

  • Concept URI token: bowralite

1.2.2.12.6.2 Nepheline syenite pegmatite

  • Child of: pegmatitic-peralkaline-syenite

  • A pegmatite of nepheline-syenite composition.

  • Concept URI token: nepheline-syenite-pegmatite

1.2.2.12.6.2.1 Agpaitic nepheline syenite pegmatite

  • Child of: nepheline-syenite-pegmatite

  • A pegmatite of a peralkaline nepheline-syenite with complex Na-Ca- Ti-Zr-silicate minerals, such as eudialyte group, wohlerite group and rinkite group minerals.

  • Concept URI token: agpaitic-nepheline-syenite-pegmatite

1.2.2.12.6.3 Syenite pegmatite

  • Child of: pegmatitic-peralkaline-syenite

  • A pegmatite of syenite composition.

  • Concept URI token: syenite-pegmatite

1.2.2.12.7 Pegmatitic sodic syenite

  • Child of: pegmatite sodic-syenite

  • A pegmatite of sodic syenite composition.

  • Concept URI token: pegmatitic-sodic-syenite

1.2.2.12.7.1 Antifenitepegmatite

  • Child of: pegmatitic-sodic-syenite

  • A pegmatitic sodic syenite composed mainly of antiperthite with minor biotite and opaques.

  • Concept URI token: antifenitepegmatite

1.2.2.12.8 Pegmatoid

  • Child of: pegmatite

  • An term proposed for both feldspathoidal pegmatites and for pegmatites without graphic texture.

  • Concept URI token: pegmatoid

1.2.2.12.9 Yatalite

  • Child of: pegmatite

  • A local name for a coarse-grained uralitized mafic pegmatite composed of actinolite (after augite), albite, microcline and quartz.

  • Concept URI token: yatalite

1.2.3 Metamorphic rock

  • Child of: rock

  • Any rock derived from preexisting rocks by mineralogical, chemical, and/or structural changes, essentially in the solid state, in response to marked changes in temperature, pressure, shearing stress, and chemical environment, generally at depth in the Earth’s crust.

  • Alternate labels: Metamorphic Rock (undiff.), Metamorphic Rock, undifferentiated, Metamorphic rocks, Unclassified metamorphic rock, unclassified metamorphic unit,

  • Concept URI token: metamorphic-rock

1.2.3.1 Catawbarite

  • Child of: metamorphic-rock

  • A weakly schistose metamorphic rock from York/Union districts of South Carolina, USA, composed of talc and magnetite.

  • Concept URI token: catawbarite

1.2.3.2 Contact metamorphic rock

  • Child of: metamorphic-rock

  • Metamorphic rock formed at a local extent with country rocks around emplaced magma bodies at any depth and both continental and oceanic settings.

  • Concept URI token: contact-metamorphic-rock

1.2.3.2.1 Adinole

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-rock metasomatic-rock

  • A compact, fine-to-very-fine grained albite-rich metasomatic rock with subordinate quartz with minor amounts of other consitutents. It has a splintery fracture, and is commonly finely banded alternating grey, green or reddish layers of variable colour intensity. It is . Chemically it contains up to 10% by weight of soda. Adinolisation may result from a Na-metasomatic process related to the intrusion of mafic igneous rocks into pelitic rocks.

  • Concept URI token: adinole

1.2.3.2.1.1 Contact adinole

  • Child of: adinole

  • An adinole found in the contact aureoles of diabase dykes.

  • Concept URI token: contact-adinole

1.2.3.2.1.2 Tuffaceous adinole

  • Child of: adinole

  • An adinole (an albite-rich metasomatic rock) found as layers within metasedimentary sequences unrelated to the proximity of mafic intrusions. Possibly albitisehd tuffs.

  • Concept URI token: tuffaceous-adinole

1.2.3.2.2 Atatschite

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-rock

  • An obsolete term originally used for a glassy orthophyre containing sillimanite and cordierite, but later shown to be contact metamorphosed tuffs and agglomerates with porphyry boulders. The correct transliteration should be atachite.

  • Concept URI token: atatschite

1.2.3.2.3 Burned-rock

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-rock

  • A general term for a compact, vescicular or clinkery, glassy to holocrystalline metamorphic rock of various colours, produced by the combustion metamorphism of pre-existing sedimentary rocks.

  • Concept URI token: burned-rock

1.2.3.2.4 Contact-marble

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-rock marble

  • A contact rock containing more than 50% vol. of carbonate minerals.

  • Concept URI token: contact-marble

1.2.3.2.4.1 Brucite-marble

  • Child of: contact-marble impure-marble

  • A contact-metamorphosed dolostone in the innermost part of many low- pressure aureoles.

  • Concept URI token: brucite-marble

1.2.3.2.4.1.1 Pencatite

  • Child of: brucite-marble

  • A brucite-marble having CaO and MgO amounts similar to those in pure dolomitic rocks (31% and 21% by weight respectively.)

  • Concept URI token: pencatite

1.2.3.2.4.1.2 Predazzite

  • Child of: brucite-marble

  • A brucite-marble reduced in MgO and enriched in CaO compared to dolomitic rocks. Compare with pencatite.

  • Concept URI token: predazzite

1.2.3.2.4.2 Coarse-grained contact-marble

  • Child of: contact-marble

  • A coarse-grained contact-marble.

  • Concept URI token: coarse-grained-contact-marble

1.2.3.2.4.3 Diopside-wollastonite-calcite contact-marble

  • Child of: contact-marble

  • A contact-marble containing diopside, wollastonite and calcite.

  • Concept URI token: diopside-wollastonite-calcite-contact-marble

1.2.3.2.4.4 Fine-grained contact-marble

  • Child of: contact-marble

  • A fine-grained contact-marble.

  • Concept URI token: fine-grained-contact-marble

1.2.3.2.4.5 Saccharoidal contact-marble

  • Child of: contact-marble

  • A saccharoidal contact-marble.

  • Concept URI token: saccharoidal-contact-marble

1.2.3.2.4.6 Scapolite contact-marble

  • Child of: contact-marble

  • A contact-marble containing scapolite.

  • Concept URI token: scapolite-contact-marble

1.2.3.2.4.7 Spinel-forsterite-calcite contact-marble

  • Child of: contact-marble

  • A contact-marble containing spinel, forsterite and calcite.

  • Concept URI token: spinel-forsterite-calcite-contact-marble

1.2.3.2.5 Contact metamorphic glassy rock

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-rock glassy-rock

  • Rocks heated to very high temperatures in a very short time followed by rapid cooling, forming vitreous or semivitreous materials.

  • Concept URI token: contact-metamorphic-glassy-rock

1.2.3.2.5.1 Buchite

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-glassy-rock

  • A compact, vesicular or slaggy metamorphic rock of any composition containing more than 20% vol. of glass, either produced by contact metamorphism in volcanic to subvolcanic settings or generated by combustion metamorphism.

  • Concept URI token: buchite

1.2.3.2.5.1.1 Clinker

  • Child of: buchite

  • Fused or partly fused coal ash, a byproduct of combustion. Characteristic features of clinkers is its resemblance to pavement brick (klinkaerd) and a ‘metallic’ sound when hit by a hammer. Clinkers are the most common rocks found in burning coal mining dumps and are usually red or pink, hard, having well preserved shaly texture. They are usually composed of quartz, partially/fully dehydrated clay minerals, and minor mullite. ref: ACSG, 2

  • Concept URI token: clinker

1.2.3.2.5.1.2 Combustion buchite

  • Child of: buchite

  • A buchite formed through combustion metamorphism.

  • Concept URI token: combustion-buchite

1.2.3.2.5.1.3 Contact buchite

  • Child of: buchite

  • A buchite formed through contact metamorphism.

  • Concept URI token: contact-buchite

1.2.3.2.5.1.4 Systil

  • Child of: contact-buchite

  • A dull, hard rock with a conchoidal to splintery fracture derived from contact metamorphism of claystone or marly sandstone by basalt. Also used as a synonym of basalt jasper.

  • Concept URI token: systil

1.2.3.2.5.2 Fritted-rock

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-glassy-rock

  • A compact, vesicular or slaggy metamorphic rock of any composition with a glass content ranging from a few percent up to a maximum of 20% vol., and either produced by contact metamorphism in volcanic to subvolcanic settings or generated by combustion metamorphism.

  • Concept URI token: fritted-rock

1.2.3.2.5.2.1 Combustion fritted-rock

  • Child of: fritted-rock

  • A fritted-rock formed through combustion metamorphism.

  • Concept URI token: combustion-fritted-rock

1.2.3.2.5.2.2 Contact fritted-rock

  • Child of: fritted-rock

  • A fritted-rock formed through contact metamorphism.

  • Concept URI token: contact-fritted-rock

1.2.3.2.5.3 Fulgurite

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-glassy-rock

  • Natural silica-rich glass formed by lightning striking and melting sands or bare rock (colour is therefore variable, depending on the chemical composition of these sands and rocks.) They form hollow tubes that are often irregular and branched. Originally described from Senne plateau, Gutersloh, Eastern Westphalia, North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany.

  • Concept URI token: fulgurite

1.2.3.2.5.4 Glassy hornfels

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-glassy-rock hornfels

  • A hornfels with a vitreous or subvitreous texture.

  • Concept URI token: glassy-hornfels

1.2.3.2.5.5 Parabasalt

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-glassy-rock

  • A type of pyrometamorphic rock derived from complete-to-near- complete melting and recrystallisation of sedimentary rocks.

  • Alternate labels: Paralava

  • Concept URI token: parabasalt

1.2.3.2.5.6 Pseudotachylite

  • Child of: cohesive-cataclasite contact-metamorphic-glassy-rock

  • A cohesive cataclasite in which fragments occur in a glassy groundmass produced by frictional melting.

  • Concept URI token: pseudotachylite

1.2.3.2.5.6.1 Brecciated pseudotachylite

  • Child of: pseudotachylite

  • A Pseudotachylite that has been brecciated.

  • Concept URI token: brecciated-pseudotachylite

1.2.3.2.5.7 Tektite

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-glassy-rock impact-melt-rock

  • A natural glass formed from a meteorite impact melting the local rock. Depending on the nature of the latter, the composition of tektites is variable.

  • Concept URI token: tektite

1.2.3.2.5.7.1 Australite

  • Child of: tektite

  • A tektite variety from the Australasian strewnfield. Dark, mostly black. The crater of this strewnfield has not be located, but is assumed to lie in Southeast Asia.

  • Concept URI token: australite

1.2.3.2.5.7.2 Bediasite

  • Child of: tektite

  • A black tektite variety from North American strewnfield (Chesapeake Bay impact crater), found in Texas, USA.

  • Concept URI token: bediasite

1.2.3.2.5.7.3 Bikolite

  • Child of: tektite

  • A name given to tektites from the Bikol area of the Philippines.

  • Concept URI token: bikolite

1.2.3.2.5.7.4 Billitonite

  • Child of: tektite

  • A tektite material found on Billiton Island, between Sumatra and Borneo. Compare indochinite.

  • Concept URI token: billitonite

1.2.3.2.5.7.5 Chinite

  • Child of: tektite

  • A black tektite variety found in Chinafrom the Australasian strewnfield.

  • Concept URI token: chinite

1.2.3.2.5.7.6 Darwin Glass

  • Child of: tektite

  • A variety of Tektite From Tasmania, Australia.

  • Concept URI token: darwin-glass

1.2.3.2.5.7.7 Georgiaite

  • Child of: tektite

  • A green tektite variety from North American strewnfield (Chesapeake Bay impact crater), found in Georgia, USA.

  • Concept URI token: georgiaite

1.2.3.2.5.7.8 Indochinite

  • Child of: tektite

  • A tektite variety from the Australasian strewnfield. Dark, mostly black. The crater of this strewnfield has not be located, but is assumed to lie in Southeast Asia.

  • Concept URI token: indochinite

1.2.3.2.5.7.9 Irghizite

  • Child of: tektite

  • Tektite from the Zhamanshin meteor crater in Kazakhstan (latitude: 48° 24’ North, longitude: 60° 58’ East).

  • Concept URI token: irghizite

1.2.3.2.5.7.10 Ivorite

  • Child of: tektite

  • A black tektite variety from the Ivory Coast strewnfield (Lake Bosumtwi Crater, Ghana). Found in the Cote d’Ivoire (Ivory Coast).NOTE: Some tectites from the large Australasian field are fraudulently sold in Ivory Coast as being Ivory Coast tektites (the latter are extremely rare).

  • Concept URI token: ivorite

1.2.3.2.5.7.11 Microtektite

  • Child of: tektite

  • Milimeter-size tektites.

  • Concept URI token: microtektite

1.2.3.2.5.7.12 Uruguaite

  • Child of: tektite

  • Black tektites from a new strewn field discovered in 2016 (Ferriare et al., 2017).

  • Concept URI token: uruguaite

1.2.3.2.5.7.13 Zhamanshinite

  • Child of: tektite

  • Tektites from the Zhamanshin meteor crater.

  • Concept URI token: zhamanshinite

1.2.3.2.6 Hornfels

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-rock granofels

  • A fine-grained metamorphic rock composed of a mosaic of equidimensional grains without preferred orientation and usually formed by contact metamorphism. Porphyroblasts or relict phenocrysts may be present in the granoblastic matrix.

  • Alternate labels: Corneenne

  • Concept URI token: hornfels

1.2.3.2.6.1 Albite-epidote hornfels

  • Child of: hornfels

  • A hornfels where epidote and albite are the primary constituents.

  • Concept URI token: albite-epidote-hornfels

1.2.3.2.6.2 Andalusite hornfels

  • Child of: hornfels

  • A hornfels composed predominantly of andalusite.

  • Concept URI token: andalusite-hornfels

1.2.3.2.6.2.1 Schistose andalusite hornfels

  • Child of: andalusite-hornfels

  • A schistose andalusite hornfels.

  • Concept URI token: schistose-andalusite-hornfels

1.2.3.2.6.3 Biotite hornfels

  • Child of: hornfels

  • A hornfels composed predominantly of biotite.

  • Alternate labels: Corneite

  • Concept URI token: biotite-hornfels

1.2.3.2.6.4 Calc-silicate hornfels

  • Child of: hornfels

  • A hornfels containing a large proportion of calcium silicate minerals. See also: calc-flinta, limurite, skarn, tactite

  • Concept URI token: calc-silicate-hornfels

1.2.3.2.6.4.1 Limurite

  • Child of: calc-silicate-hornfels

  • A metasomatic rock usually found at the contact of calcareous rocks with intruded granite and consisting of more than 50% axinite. Other minerals may include diopside, actinolite, zoisite, albite, and quartz.

  • Concept URI token: limurite

1.2.3.2.6.5 Cordierite-sillimanite hornfels

  • Child of: hornfels

  • A hornfels containing cordierite and sillimanite. It can be formed from increased metamorphism in the series: mudstone > metamudstone > muscovite-biotite hornfels > cordierite-sillimanite hornfels.

  • Concept URI token: cordierite-sillimanite-hornfels

1.2.3.2.6.6 Cornean

  • Child of: hornfels

  • Obsolete term for a feldspar-quartz-hornblende rock from the Trap Formation of Pembrokeshire, Wales.

  • Concept URI token: cornean

1.2.3.2.6.7 Glassy hornfels

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-glassy-rock hornfels

  • A hornfels with a vitreous or subvitreous texture.

  • Concept URI token: glassy-hornfels

1.2.3.2.6.8 Hornfelsed schist

  • Child of: hornfels schist

  • Hornfelsic rocks with trace of pre-existing schistosity.

  • Concept URI token: hornfelsed-schist

1.2.3.2.6.9 Mafic-hornfels

  • Child of: hornfels

  • Fine-grained hard hornfels with a mafic source rock.

  • Concept URI token: mafic-hornfels

1.2.3.2.6.9.1 Beerbachite

  • Child of: mafic-hornfels

  • A high-grade, fine granined, granoblastic contact-metamorphic rock - a basaltic dyke rock metamorphosed by contact with gabbroic rock.

  • Concept URI token: beerbachite

1.2.3.2.6.9.2 High-grade mafic-hornfels

  • Child of: mafic-hornfels

  • A high-grade mafic hornfels.

  • Concept URI token: high-grade-mafic-hornfels

1.2.3.2.6.9.3 Magnetite-olivine-augite-plagioclase mafic-hornfels

  • Child of: mafic-hornfels

  • A mafic-hornfels containing magnetite, olivine, augite and plagioclase.

  • Concept URI token: magnetite-olivine-augite-plagioclase-mafic-hornfels

1.2.3.2.6.9.4 Medium-grade mafic-hornfels

  • Child of: mafic-hornfels

  • A medium-grade mafic hornfels.

  • Concept URI token: medium-grade-mafic-hornfels

1.2.3.2.6.9.5 Plagioclase-hornblende mafic-hornfels

  • Child of: mafic-hornfels

  • A mafic-hornfels containing plagioclase and hornblende.

  • Concept URI token: plagioclase-hornblende-mafic-hornfels

1.2.3.2.6.10 Muscovite-biotite hornfels

  • Child of: hornfels

  • A hornfels containing biotite and muscovite. It can be formed from increased metamorphism in the series: mudstone > metamudstone > muscovite-biotite hornfels > cordierite-sillimanite hornfels.

  • Concept URI token: muscovite-biotite-hornfels

1.2.3.2.6.11 Pelitic hornfels

  • Child of: hornfels

  • A fine-grained, nonfissile metamorphic rock derived from an argillaceous sediment.

  • Concept URI token: pelitic-hornfels

1.2.3.2.6.12 Schistose hornfels

  • Child of: hornfels

  • A totally recrystallised hornfels of the innermost aureole characterised by the same mineralogical composition as the associated hornfelses and a schistose texture. Not to be confused with hornfelsed schist.

  • Concept URI token: schistose-hornfels

1.2.3.2.6.13 Tourmaline-quartz-mica hornfels

  • Child of: hornfels

  • A hornfels containing mica, quartz and tourmaline.

  • Concept URI token: tourmaline-quartz-mica-hornfels

1.2.3.2.6.14 Ultramafic-hornfels

  • Child of: hornfels

  • Fine-grained, hard hornfels formed from an ultramafic rock.

  • Concept URI token: ultramafic-hornfels

1.2.3.2.6.14.1 High-grade ultramafic-hornfels

  • Child of: ultramafic-hornfels

  • A high-grade ultramafic hornfels.

  • Concept URI token: high-grade-ultramafic-hornfels

1.2.3.2.6.14.2 Medium-grade ultramafic-hornfels

  • Child of: ultramafic-hornfels

  • A medium-grade ultramafic hornfels.

  • Concept URI token: medium-grade-ultramafic-hornfels

1.2.3.2.7 Metacarbonate slag

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-rock

  • Type of pyrometamorphic rock formed in expense of carbonate protolith via its calcination (decarbonatisation). As such it differs from the artificial, smelting slags.

  • Concept URI token: metacarbonate-slag

1.2.3.2.8 Paraquartzite

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-rock quartzite

  • A quartzite formed by contact metamorphism.

  • Concept URI token: paraquartzite

1.2.3.3 Cornubianite

  • Child of: metamorphic-rock

  • The term was first used for a banded fine-grained compact to schistose rock essentially composed of quartz, feldspar and micas generated by contact metamorphism of a gneisose to schistose protolith, Also used later for a schistose andalusite hornfels or a tourmaline-quartz-mica hornfels. Also used in italy as a synonym of hornfels.

  • Concept URI token: cornubianite

1.2.3.4 Coronite

  • Child of: metamorphic-rock

  • A field term for any rock containing coronas.

  • Concept URI token: coronite

1.2.3.5 Diaphthorite

  • Child of: metamorphic-rock

  • A crystalline rock in which minerals characteristic of a lower metamorphic grade have developed by retrograde metamorphism at the expense of minerals peculiar to a higher metamorphic grade. Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: diaphthorite

1.2.3.6 Fault-rock

  • Child of: metamorphic-rock

  • Rock formed as a result of deformation in a fault zone.

  • Alternate labels: Fault rock, Fault,

  • Concept URI token: fault-rock

1.2.3.6.1 Cataclasite

  • Child of: fault-rock

  • A fault-rock which is cohesive with a poorly developed or absent schistosity, or which is incohesive, characterised by generally angular porphyroclasts and lithic fragments in a finer-grained matrix of similar composition.

  • Alternate labels: Cataclastic-rock

  • Concept URI token: cataclasite

1.2.3.6.1.1 Cohesive cataclasite

  • Child of: cataclasite mylonite

  • A cataclasite showing cohesion.

  • Concept URI token: cohesive-cataclasite

1.2.3.6.1.1.1 Cohesive fault-breccia

  • Child of: cohesive-cataclasite fault-breccia

  • A fault-breccia showing cohesion.

  • Alternate labels: Mosaic breccia

  • Concept URI token: cohesive-fault-breccia

1.2.3.6.1.1.2 Cohesive protocataclasite

  • Child of: cohesive-cataclasite

  • A protocataclasite showing cohesion.

  • Concept URI token: cohesive-protocataclasite

1.2.3.6.1.1.3 Cohesive ultracataclasite

  • Child of: cohesive-cataclasite

  • A mesocataclasite showing cohesion.

  • Concept URI token: cohesive-ultracataclasite

1.2.3.6.1.1.4 Pseudotachylite

  • Child of: cohesive-cataclasite contact-metamorphic-glassy-rock

  • A cohesive cataclasite in which fragments occur in a glassy groundmass produced by frictional melting.

  • Concept URI token: pseudotachylite

1.2.3.6.1.1.5 Brecciated pseudotachylite

  • Child of: pseudotachylite

  • A Pseudotachylite that has been brecciated.

  • Concept URI token: brecciated-pseudotachylite

1.2.3.6.1.2 Fault-breccia

  • Child of: breccia cataclasite

  • A medium-to-carse grained cataclasite containing >30% visible fragments.

  • Alternate labels: Cataclastic breccia, Coarse-grained cataclasite, Crush breccia, Fault Breccia, Milled breccia, Shear zone, breccia, fault,

  • Concept URI token: fault-breccia

1.2.3.6.1.2.1 Cohesive fault-breccia

  • Child of: cohesive-cataclasite fault-breccia

  • A fault-breccia showing cohesion.

  • Alternate labels: Mosaic breccia

  • Concept URI token: cohesive-fault-breccia

1.2.3.6.1.3 Incohesive cataclasite

  • Child of: cataclasite incohesive-fault-rock

  • A cataclasite without cohesion.

  • Concept URI token: incohesive-cataclasite

1.2.3.6.1.3.1 Incohesive fault-breccia

  • Child of: incohesive-cataclasite

  • A fault-breccia without cohesion.

  • Concept URI token: incohesive-fault-breccia

1.2.3.6.1.3.2 Incohesive protocataclasite

  • Child of: incohesive-cataclasite

  • A protocataclasite without cohesion.

  • Concept URI token: incohesive-protocataclasite

1.2.3.6.1.3.3 Incohesive ultracataclasite

  • Child of: incohesive-cataclasite

  • A mesocataclasite without cohesion.

  • Concept URI token: incohesive-ultracataclasite

1.2.3.6.1.4 Mesocataclasite

  • Child of: cataclasite

  • A cataclasite in which the matrix forms between 50% and 90% of the rock volume.

  • Concept URI token: mesocataclasite

1.2.3.6.1.5 Protocataclasite

  • Child of: cataclasite

  • A cataclasite in which the matrix forms less than 50% of the rock volume.

  • Concept URI token: protocataclasite

1.2.3.6.1.6 Ultracataclasite

  • Child of: cataclasite

  • A cataclasite in which the matrix forms more than 90% of the rock volume.

  • Concept URI token: ultracataclasite

1.2.3.6.2 Cohesive fault-rock

  • Child of: fault-rock

  • A category of fault-rock showing cohesion.

  • Concept URI token: cohesive-fault-rock

1.2.3.6.2.1 mylonite

  • Child of: cohesive-fault-rock foliated-metamorphic-rock

  • A cohesive fault-rock which is characterised by tectonic reduction of grain size and recrystallisation, and commonly contains lensoidal to rounded porphyroclasts and lithic fragments of similar composition to minerals in the matrix.A compact, chert-like rock without cleavage, but with a streaky or banded structure, produced by the extreme granulation and shearing of rocks that have been pulverized and rolled during overthrusting or intense dynamic metamorphism. Mylonite may also be described as a microbreccia with flow texture.

  • Alternate labels: Mylonitic-rock

  • Concept URI token: mylonite

1.2.3.6.2.1.1 Augen-mylonite

  • Child of: mylonite

  • A mylonite containing distinctive large crystals or lithic fragments around which foliated fine-grained matrix is wrapped, often forming symmetric or asymmetric tails.

  • Concept URI token: augen-mylonite

1.2.3.6.2.1.2 Blastomylonite

  • Child of: mylonite

  • A mylonite with extensive recrystallisation and mineral growth accompanying deformation.

  • Concept URI token: blastomylonite

1.2.3.6.2.1.3 Cohesive cataclasite

  • Child of: cataclasite mylonite

  • A cataclasite showing cohesion.

  • Concept URI token: cohesive-cataclasite

1.2.3.6.2.1.4 Cohesive fault-breccia

  • Child of: cohesive-cataclasite fault-breccia

  • A fault-breccia showing cohesion.

  • Alternate labels: Mosaic breccia

  • Concept URI token: cohesive-fault-breccia

1.2.3.6.2.1.5 Cohesive protocataclasite

  • Child of: cohesive-cataclasite

  • A protocataclasite showing cohesion.

  • Concept URI token: cohesive-protocataclasite

1.2.3.6.2.1.6 Cohesive ultracataclasite

  • Child of: cohesive-cataclasite

  • A mesocataclasite showing cohesion.

  • Concept URI token: cohesive-ultracataclasite

1.2.3.6.2.1.7 Pseudotachylite

  • Child of: cohesive-cataclasite contact-metamorphic-glassy-rock

  • A cohesive cataclasite in which fragments occur in a glassy groundmass produced by frictional melting.

  • Concept URI token: pseudotachylite

1.2.3.6.2.1.8 Brecciated pseudotachylite

  • Child of: pseudotachylite

  • A Pseudotachylite that has been brecciated.

  • Concept URI token: brecciated-pseudotachylite

1.2.3.6.2.1.9 Mesomylonite

  • Child of: mylonite

  • A mylonite in which more than 50% and less than 90% of the rock volumne has undergone grain size reduction.

  • Concept URI token: mesomylonite

1.2.3.6.2.1.10 Phyllonite

  • Child of: mylonite

  • A mylonite of phyllitic appearance dominated by platy minerals.A rock that macroscopically resembles phyllite but that is formed by mechanical degradation (mylonitisation) of initially coarser rocks (e.g., graywacke, granite, or gneiss). Silky films of recrystallised mica or chlorite, smeared out along schistosity surfaces, and formation by dislocation metamorphism are characteristic.

  • Alternate labels: phyllite-mylonite

  • Concept URI token: phyllonite

1.2.3.6.2.1.11 Protomylonite

  • Child of: mylonite

  • A mylonite where less than 50% of the rock volume has undergone grain size reduction. i. A mylonitic rock produced from contact- metamorphosed rock, with granulation and flowage being due to overthrusts following the contact surfaces between intrusion and country rock. Ref: AGI ii. A coherent crush breccia whose characteristically lenticular, megascopic particles faintly retain primary structures. It is a lower grade in the development of mylonite and ultramylonite. Compare with: ultramylonite

  • Concept URI token: protomylonite

1.2.3.6.2.1.12 Ultramylonite

  • Child of: mylonite

  • A mylonite where more than 90% of the rock volume has undergone grain size reduction. Primary structures and porphyroclasts have been obliterated so that the rock becomes homogeneous and dense, with little if any parallel structure. Synonym of: flinty crush rock Compare with: protomylonite, pseudotachylyte

  • Concept URI token: ultramylonite

1.2.3.6.3 Incohesive fault-rock

  • Child of: fault-rock

  • A category of fault-rock without cohesion.

  • Alternate labels: Fault rock without primary cohesion

  • Concept URI token: incohesive-fault-rock

1.2.3.6.3.1 Fault-gouge

  • Child of: incohesive-fault-rock

  • A fault rock without primary cohesion where less than 30% of the fragments are visible to the naked eye and the rest is fine-grained and clayey.

  • Alternate labels: Fault Clay, Fault Gouge, Gouge,

  • Concept URI token: fault-gouge

1.2.3.6.3.2 Incohesive cataclasite

  • Child of: cataclasite incohesive-fault-rock

  • A cataclasite without cohesion.

  • Concept URI token: incohesive-cataclasite

1.2.3.6.3.2.1 Incohesive fault-breccia

  • Child of: incohesive-cataclasite

  • A fault-breccia without cohesion.

  • Concept URI token: incohesive-fault-breccia

  • Child of: incohesive-cataclasite

  • A protocataclasite without cohesion.

  • Concept URI token: incohesive-protocataclasite

1.2.3.6.3.2.3 Incohesive ultracataclasite

  • Child of: incohesive-cataclasite

  • A mesocataclasite without cohesion.

  • Concept URI token: incohesive-ultracataclasite

1.2.3.7 Foliated metamorphic rock

  • Child of: metamorphic-rock

  • Metamorphic rock in which 10 percent or more of the contained mineral grains are elements in a planar or linear fabric. Cataclastic or glassy character precludes classification with this concept.

  • Concept URI token: foliated-metamorphic-rock

1.2.3.7.1 Gneiss

  • Child of: foliated-metamorphic-rock

  • A medium- to high-grade metamorphic rock that commonly has a banded structure and is generally medium-to-coarse grained with poorly developed schistosity. A foliated rock formed by regional metamorphism, in which bands or lenticles of granular minerals alternate with bands or lenticles in which minerals having flaky or elongate prismatic habits predominate. Generally, less than 50% of the minerals show preferred parallel orientation.

  • Concept URI token: gneiss

1.2.3.7.1.1 Agmatitic gneiss

  • Child of: gneiss

  • This is a breccia-like gneiss, typically with angular blocks of amphibolite in a quartzo-feldspathic matrix (an agmatitic texture).

  • Concept URI token: agmatitic-gneiss

1.2.3.7.1.2 Augen gneiss

  • Child of: gneiss

  • A gneiss exhibiting large lenticular mineral grains or mineral aggregates having the shape of an eye in cross section, in contrast to the shapes of other minerals in the rock.

  • Concept URI token: augen-gneiss

1.2.3.7.1.2.1 Dynamogranite

  • Child of: augen-gneiss

  • Augen gneiss containing much microline and orthoclase.

  • Concept URI token: dynamogranite

1.2.3.7.1.2.2 Garnet-biotite augen gneiss

  • Child of: augen-gneiss

  • An augen gneiss containing biotite and garnet.

  • Concept URI token: garnet-biotite-augen-gneiss

1.2.3.7.1.2.3 Quartz-plagioclase-hornblende augen gneiss

  • Child of: augen-gneiss

  • An augen gneiss containing a fine-grained hornblende groundmass with numerous large crystals of quartz and plagioclase.

  • Concept URI token: quartz-plagioclase-hornblende-augen-gneiss

1.2.3.7.1.3 Banded gneiss

  • Child of: gneiss

  • A gneiss exhibiting a banded texture.

  • Concept URI token: banded-gneiss

1.2.3.7.1.4 Biotite gneiss

  • Child of: gneiss

  • A gneiss containing biotite mica as the major mafic component.

  • Alternate labels: Melano biotite gneiss

  • Concept URI token: biotite-gneiss

1.2.3.7.1.4.1 Garnet-biotite gneiss

  • Child of: biotite-gneiss

  • A gneiss containing both biotite and garnet as primary components. See also Garnet-biotite augen gneiss.

  • Concept URI token: garnet-biotite-gneiss

1.2.3.7.1.4.2 Hornblende-biotite gneiss

  • Child of: biotite-gneiss

  • A gneiss containing hornblende and biotite.

  • Concept URI token: hornblende-biotite-gneiss

1.2.3.7.1.4.3 Muscovite-biotite gneiss

  • Child of: biotite-gneiss

  • A gneiss containing both muscovite and biotite.

  • Concept URI token: muscovite-biotite-gneiss

1.2.3.7.1.5 Composite gneiss

  • Child of: gneiss

  • A gneiss produced by interlayering or mixture of two distinct rock types, one of which generally has an igneous aspect. A banded rock usually resulting from intimate penetration of magma (usually granite) into adjacent rocks. See Also: injection gneiss, migmatite

  • Concept URI token: composite-gneiss

1.2.3.7.1.5.1 Lit-par-lit gneiss

  • Child of: composite-gneiss

  • A gneiss having the characteristic of a layered rock, the laminae of which have been penetrated by numerous thin, roughly parallel sheets of igneous material, usually granitic. The name comes from the French, ‘bed-by-bed’.

  • Concept URI token: lit-par-lit-gneiss

1.2.3.7.1.6 Cordierite-garnet gneiss

  • Child of: gneiss

  • A gneiss predominantly composed of cordierite and garnet.

  • Concept URI token: cordierite-garnet-gneiss

1.2.3.7.1.7 Garnet-biotite-quartz-feldspar gneiss

  • Child of: gneiss

  • A gneiss composed of feldspar, quartz, biotite and garnet.

  • Concept URI token: garnet-biotite-quartz-feldspar-gneiss

1.2.3.7.1.8 Garnet Gneiss

  • Child of: gneiss

  • A gneiss containing garnets.

  • Alternate labels: Garnet Bearing Gneiss

  • Concept URI token: garnet-gneiss

1.2.3.7.1.9 Garnet-quartz-plagioclase gneiss

  • Child of: gneiss

  • A gneiss containing plagioclase, quartz and garnet.

  • Concept URI token: garnet-quartz-plagioclase-gneiss

1.2.3.7.1.10 Glaucophane gabbro gneiss

  • Child of: gneiss

  • A gneiss of gabbroic composition containing glaucophane.

  • Concept URI token: glaucophane-gabbro-gneiss

1.2.3.7.1.11 Glaucophane gneiss

  • Child of: gneiss

  • A gneiss containing glaucophane as a major component.

  • Concept URI token: glaucophane-gneiss

1.2.3.7.1.12 Granitic gneiss

  • Child of: gneiss

  • A gneiss of granitic composition.

  • Alternate labels: Gneissic granite, Granite Gneiss,

  • Concept URI token: granitic-gneiss

1.2.3.7.1.12.1 Protogine

  • Child of: granitic-gneiss metagranite

  • A term used in the Alps for a metagranitic rock with a gneissose structure containing greenschist facies minerals such as sericite, chlorite, epidote, and garnet, and shows evidence of a composite origin or of crystallisation (or partial recrystallisation) under stress after consolidation. Also spelled protogene. The term, dating from 1806, is obsolete. Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: protogine

1.2.3.7.1.16 Lineated gneiss

  • Concept URI token: lineated-gneiss

1.2.3.7.3 phyllite

  • Child of: foliated-metamorphic-rock very-low-to-low-grade-metamorphic-rock

  • A fine to medium-grained metamorphic rock characterised by a lustrous sheen and a well-developed schistosity resulting from the parallel arrangement of phyllosilicates.A metamorphic rock, intermediate in grade between slate and mica schist. Minute crystals of sericite/muscovite and chlorite impart a silky sheen to the surfaces of cleavage (or schistosity). Phyllites commonly exhibit corrugated/crenulated cleavage surfaces.

  • Concept URI token: phyllite

1.2.3.7.3.1 Muscovite-chlorite phyllite

  • Child of: phyllite

  • A phyllite comprising a muscovite-chlorite groundmass.

  • Concept URI token: muscovite-chlorite-phyllite

  • Concept URI token: calcite-bearing-muscovite-chlorite-phyllite

1.2.3.7.3.2 Quartz phyllite

  • Child of: phyllite

  • A quartz-rich phyllite. May grade into quartzite.

  • Concept URI token: quartz-phyllite

1.2.3.7.4 Schist

  • Child of: foliated-metamorphic-rock

  • A medium-grained strongly-foliated crystalline metamorphic rock, formed by dynamic metamorphism, that can be readily split into thin flakes or slabs due to the well developed parallelism of more than 50% of the minerals present, particularly those of lamellar or elongate prismatic habit, e.g., mica and hornblende.

  • Alternate labels: Crystalline schist, Schistes,

  • Concept URI token: schist

1.2.3.7.4.1 Actinolite-mica schist

  • Child of: schist

  • A schistose metamorphic rock containing actinolite and mica.

  • Concept URI token: actinolite-mica-schist

1.2.3.7.4.2 Actinolite schist

  • Child of: schist

  • A schistose rock composed predominantly of actinolite.

  • Concept URI token: actinolite-schist

1.2.3.7.4.3 Bibliolite

  • Child of: schist

  • A laminated schist.

  • Concept URI token: bibliolite

1.2.3.7.4.4 Blueschist

  • Child of: high-pt-metamorphic-rock schist

  • A schist whose bluish colour is due to the presence of alkali amphibole.

  • Concept URI token: blueschist

1.2.3.7.4.4.1 Crossite-pumpellyite granofels

  • Child of: blueschist granofels

  • A granofels containing crossite and pumpellyite.

  • Concept URI token: crossite-pumpellyite-granofels

1.2.3.7.4.4.2 Epidote-glaucophane schist

  • Child of: blueschist

  • A schistose metamorphic rock with glaucophane and epidote as the only major components.

  • Concept URI token: epidote-glaucophane-schist

1.2.3.7.4.4.3 Glaucophane schist

  • Child of: blueschist

  • A schistose metamorphic rock with glaucophane as the major (>5%) constituent. The use of prefixes (jadeite bearing glaucophane- phengite-schist) is recommended if additional minerals are present as minor or major constituents. A type of amphibole schist in which glaucophane rather than hornblende is an abundant mineral. Epidote frequently occurs, and there are quartz, albite and mica-rich varieties.

  • Concept URI token: glaucophane-schist

1.2.3.7.4.4.4 Jadeite-bearing glaucophane-phengite schist

  • Child of: blueschist

  • A schistose metamorphic rock with glaucophane and phengite as the only major components but containing up to 5% jadeite.

  • Concept URI token: jadeite-bearing-glaucophane-phengite-schist

1.2.3.7.4.5 Carbonate-chlorite schist

  • Child of: schist

  • Child of: schist

  • A schist containing silicate and carbonate minerals.

  • Concept URI token: carbonate-silicate-schist

1.2.3.7.4.7 Chlorite schist

  • Child of: schist

  • A schistose metamorphic rock with chlorite minerals as the major (>50%) constituent. Chlorite imparts a schistosity by parallel arrangement of its flakes. Quartz, epidote, magnetite, and garnet may be accessories, the last two often as conspicuous porphyroblasts.

  • Concept URI token: chlorite-schist

1.2.3.7.4.7.1 Muscovite-chlorite schist

  • Child of: chlorite-schist

  • A schist comprising a muscovite-chlorite groundmass.

  • Concept URI token: muscovite-chlorite-schist

1.2.3.7.4.8 Feldspathic schist

  • Child of: schist

  • A schistose metamorphic rock with feldspar minerals as the only major (>5%) constituent.

  • Concept URI token: feldspathic-schist

1.2.3.7.4.16 Greenschist

  • Child of: schist very-low-to-low-grade-metamorphic-rock

  • Concept URI token: greenschist

1.2.3.7.4.16.2 Chlorogrisonite schist

  • Child of: greenschist

1.2.3.7.4.17 Hornblende schist

  • Child of: schist

  • A schistose metamorphic rock with hornblende as the only major (>5%) constituent. A schistose metamorphic rock consisting principally of hornblende, with little or no quartz. Unlike amphibolite, it does not need to contain plagioclase.

  • Concept URI token: hornblende-schist

1.2.3.7.4.18 Hornfelsed schist

  • Child of: hornfels schist

  • Hornfelsic rocks with trace of pre-existing schistosity.

  • Concept URI token: hornfelsed-schist

  • Child of: schist

  • Concept URI token: jadeite-garnet-phengite-schist

  • A schist containing talc and kyanite.

  • Concept URI token: kyanite-talc-schist

1.2.3.7.4.21 Lineated schist

  • Child of: schist

  • A metamorphic rock displaying a linear fabric rather than a schistosity and which will split on a scale of one centimeter or less. See also lineated gneiss.

  • Concept URI token: lineated-schist

1.2.3.7.4.22 Magnetite-chlorite schist

  • Child of: schist

  • A schist containing magnetite and chlorite.

  • Concept URI token: magnetite-chlorite-schist

1.2.3.7.4.23 Mica schist

  • Child of: schist

  • A schistose metamorphic rock with mica minerals as a major (>5%) constituent; usually also quartz-rich. The schistosity is mainly due to the parallel arrangement of mica flakes.

  • Alternate labels: Biotite-muscovite schist

  • Concept URI token: mica-schist

1.2.3.7.4.23.1 Biotite schist

  • Child of: mica-schist

  • A schistose metamorphic rock with biotite as the only major (>5%) constituent.

  • Concept URI token: biotite-schist

  • A schistose metamorphic rock with phlogopite as the only major (>5%) constituent.

  • Concept URI token: phlogopite-schist

1.2.3.7.4.24 murasakite

  • Child of: schist

  • A schistose rock composed of piedmontite and quartz. See Also: ollenite Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: murasakite

1.2.3.7.4.25 ollenite

  • Child of: schist

  • A type of hornblende schist characterized by abundant epidote, sphene, and rutile. Garnet is one of the accessories. Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: ollenite

1.2.3.7.4.26 Orthoschist

  • Child of: schist

  • A schist with an igneous protolith. Compare with: paraschist.

  • Concept URI token: orthoschist

  • Concept URI token: paraphyllite

1.2.3.7.4.38 Whiteschist

  • Child of: high-pt-metamorphic-rock schist

  • A light-coloured schist containing kyanite and talc. These rocks represent Al-rich rocks metamorphosed under the conditions of the eclogite facies.

  • Concept URI token: whiteschist

1.2.3.7.4.38.1 Kyanite-talc-phengite schist

  • Child of: whiteschist

  • A whiteschist with phengite as the primary constituent.

  • Concept URI token: kyanite-talc-phengite-schist

1.2.3.7.5 slate

  • Child of: foliated-metamorphic-rock very-low-to-low-grade-metamorphic-rock

  • An ultrafine- or very fine-grained rock displaying strong slaty cleavage and hence can be split into slabs and thin plates. Most slate was formed from shale. Slate is usually of very low to low metamorphic grade conditions. A fine-grained metamorphic rock that breaks into thin slabs or sheets.

  • Concept URI token: slate

1.2.3.7.5.1 Pyritic slate

  • Child of: slate

  • A slate containing pyrite.

  • Concept URI token: pyritic-slate

1.2.3.8 Granofels

  • Child of: metamorphic-rock

  • A granular medium- to coarse-grained granoblastic metamorphic rock with little or no foliation or lineation.

  • Concept URI token: granofels

1.2.3.8.1 Charnockitic suite

  • Child of: granofels

  • A group of metamorphic or igneous rocks, all being coarse grained, orthopyroxene-rich quartzofeldspathic rocks, formed at high temperature and pressure. They have a contentious origin, some probably by melting of dry rocks, thus be strictly igneous granitoids, but others appear to be highly metamorphosed metasediments (regionally metamorphosed granofels). They are usually banded and intermixed with other metasedimentary rocks.

  • Concept URI token: charnockitic-suite

1.2.3.8.2 Chlorite-epidote granofels

  • Child of: granofels

  • A granofels containing chlorite and epidote.

  • Concept URI token: chlorite-epidote-granofels

1.2.3.8.3 Crossite-pumpellyite granofels

  • Child of: blueschist granofels

  • A granofels containing crossite and pumpellyite.

  • Concept URI token: crossite-pumpellyite-granofels

1.2.3.8.4 Garnet-quartz-plagioclase granofels

  • Child of: granofels

  • A granofels containing plagioclase, quartz and garnet.

  • Concept URI token: garnet-quartz-plagioclase-granofels

1.2.3.8.5 Glaucophane granofels

  • Child of: granofels

  • A granofels containing glaucophane.

  • Concept URI token: glaucophane-granofels

1.2.3.8.6 Greenstone

  • Child of: granofels very-low-to-low-grade-metamorphic-rock

  • A granofels whose greenish colour is due to the presence of minerals such as actinolite, chlorite and epidote. Also a field term applied to any compact dark-green altered or metamorphosed basic igneous rock that owes its color to the presence of chlorite, actinolite, or epidote.

  • Concept URI token: greenstone

1.2.3.8.7 Hornblende granofels

  • Child of: granofels

  • A granofels containing hornblende as the major constituent.

  • Concept URI token: hornblende-granofels

1.2.3.8.8 Hornfels

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-rock granofels

  • A fine-grained metamorphic rock composed of a mosaic of equidimensional grains without preferred orientation and usually formed by contact metamorphism. Porphyroblasts or relict phenocrysts may be present in the granoblastic matrix.

  • Alternate labels: Corneenne

  • Concept URI token: hornfels

1.2.3.8.8.1 Albite-epidote hornfels

  • Child of: hornfels

  • A hornfels where epidote and albite are the primary constituents.

  • Concept URI token: albite-epidote-hornfels

1.2.3.8.8.2 Andalusite hornfels

  • Child of: hornfels

  • A hornfels composed predominantly of andalusite.

  • Concept URI token: andalusite-hornfels

1.2.3.8.8.2.1 Schistose andalusite hornfels

  • Child of: andalusite-hornfels

  • A schistose andalusite hornfels.

  • Concept URI token: schistose-andalusite-hornfels

1.2.3.8.8.3 Biotite hornfels

  • Child of: hornfels

  • A hornfels composed predominantly of biotite.

  • Alternate labels: Corneite

  • Concept URI token: biotite-hornfels

1.2.3.8.8.4 Calc-silicate hornfels

  • Child of: hornfels

  • A hornfels containing a large proportion of calcium silicate minerals. See also: calc-flinta, limurite, skarn, tactite

  • Concept URI token: calc-silicate-hornfels

1.2.3.8.8.4.1 Limurite

  • Child of: calc-silicate-hornfels

  • A metasomatic rock usually found at the contact of calcareous rocks with intruded granite and consisting of more than 50% axinite. Other minerals may include diopside, actinolite, zoisite, albite, and quartz.

  • Concept URI token: limurite

1.2.3.8.8.5 Cordierite-sillimanite hornfels

  • Child of: hornfels

  • A hornfels containing cordierite and sillimanite. It can be formed from increased metamorphism in the series: mudstone > metamudstone > muscovite-biotite hornfels > cordierite-sillimanite hornfels.

  • Concept URI token: cordierite-sillimanite-hornfels

1.2.3.8.8.6 Cornean

  • Child of: hornfels

  • Obsolete term for a feldspar-quartz-hornblende rock from the Trap Formation of Pembrokeshire, Wales.

  • Concept URI token: cornean

1.2.3.8.8.7 Glassy hornfels

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-glassy-rock hornfels

  • A hornfels with a vitreous or subvitreous texture.

  • Concept URI token: glassy-hornfels

1.2.3.8.8.8 Hornfelsed schist

  • Child of: hornfels schist

  • Hornfelsic rocks with trace of pre-existing schistosity.

  • Concept URI token: hornfelsed-schist

1.2.3.8.8.9 Mafic-hornfels

  • Child of: hornfels

  • Fine-grained hard hornfels with a mafic source rock.

  • Concept URI token: mafic-hornfels

1.2.3.8.8.9.1 Beerbachite

  • Child of: mafic-hornfels

  • A high-grade, fine granined, granoblastic contact-metamorphic rock - a basaltic dyke rock metamorphosed by contact with gabbroic rock.

  • Concept URI token: beerbachite

  • Concept URI token: high-grade-mafic-hornfels

  • A mafic-hornfels containing magnetite, olivine, augite and plagioclase.

  • Concept URI token: magnetite-olivine-augite-plagioclase-mafic-hornfels

1.2.3.8.8.9.4 Medium-grade mafic-hornfels

  • Child of: mafic-hornfels

  • Concept URI token: medium-grade-mafic-hornfels

1.2.3.8.8.9.5 Plagioclase-hornblende mafic-hornfels

  • Child of: mafic-hornfels

  • A mafic-hornfels containing plagioclase and hornblende.

  • Concept URI token: plagioclase-hornblende-mafic-hornfels

1.2.3.8.8.10 Muscovite-biotite hornfels

  • Child of: hornfels

  • A hornfels containing biotite and muscovite. It can be formed from increased metamorphism in the series: mudstone > metamudstone > muscovite-biotite hornfels > cordierite-sillimanite hornfels.

  • Concept URI token: muscovite-biotite-hornfels

1.2.3.8.8.11 Pelitic hornfels

  • Child of: hornfels

  • A fine-grained, nonfissile metamorphic rock derived from an argillaceous sediment.

  • Concept URI token: pelitic-hornfels

1.2.3.8.8.12 Schistose hornfels

  • Child of: hornfels

  • A totally recrystallised hornfels of the innermost aureole characterised by the same mineralogical composition as the associated hornfelses and a schistose texture. Not to be confused with hornfelsed schist.

  • Concept URI token: schistose-hornfels

1.2.3.8.8.13 Tourmaline-quartz-mica hornfels

  • Child of: hornfels

  • A hornfels containing mica, quartz and tourmaline.

  • Concept URI token: tourmaline-quartz-mica-hornfels
