  • Concept URI token: medium-grade-ultramafic-hornfels

1.2.3.8.9 Layered granofels

  • Child of: granofels

  • A granofels containing layers of different composition.

  • Concept URI token: layered-granofels

1.2.3.8.10 Orthogranofels

  • Child of: granofels

  • A granofels with an igneous protolith.

  • Concept URI token: orthogranofels

1.2.3.8.11 Paragranofels

  • Child of: granofels

  • A metasedimentary rock with a granofelsic texture.

  • Concept URI token: paragranofels

1.2.3.8.11.1 Nebulitic-biotite-plagioclase-quartz paragranofels

  • Child of: paragranofels

  • A nebulitic biotite, plagioclase-quartz paragranofels. See also migmatite

  • Concept URI token: nebulitic-biotite-plagioclase-quartz-paragranofels

1.2.3.8.12 Propylite

  • Child of: granofels metasomatic-rock

  • A low to medium-temperature metasomatic rock, sometimes a granofels or schist, generally formed by the propylitic alteration of basic to intermediate volcanic rocks around hydrothermal ore deposits or by plate magmatic alteration. Low-temperature varieties are principally composed of albite, calcite and chlorite; high-temperature varieties contain more epidote. Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: propylite

1.2.3.8.13 Spinel-pyrope granofels

  • Child of: alkremite granofels

  • A granofels containing spinel and pyrope.

  • Concept URI token: spinel-pyrope-granofels

1.2.3.9 High-grade metamorphic rock

  • Child of: metamorphic-rock

  • Metamorphic rock formed from high-grade metamorphic processes.

  • Concept URI token: high-grade-metamorphic-rock

1.2.3.9.1 Amausite

  • Child of: high-grade-metamorphic-rock

  • An obsolete term for a granulite, leptynite or namiesterstein.

  • Concept URI token: amausite

1.2.3.9.2 Amphibolite

  • Child of: high-grade-metamorphic-rock

  • Amphibolite is a gneissose or granofelsic metamorphic rock mainly consisting of green, brown or black amphibole and plagioclase (including albite), which combined form ‰¥75% of the rock and both of which are present as major constituents; the amphibole constitutes ‰¥50% of the total mafic constituents and is present in an amount of ‰¥30%. A crystalloblastic rock consisting mainly of amphibole and plagioclase with little or no quartz.

  • Alternate labels: Analcitite

  • Concept URI token: amphibolite

1.2.3.9.2.1 Chlorite amphibolite

  • Child of: amphibolite

  • An amphibolite containing chlorite

  • Concept URI token: chlorite-amphibolite

1.2.3.9.2.2 Davianite

  • Child of: amphibolite

  • An obsolete term for a granular variety of hornblendite, probably metamorphic, consisting essentially of brown hornblende with cores of pyroxene.

  • Concept URI token: davianite

1.2.3.9.2.3 Epidote amphibolite

  • Child of: amphibolite

  • An amphibolite rich in epidote

  • Concept URI token: epidote-amphibolite

1.2.3.9.2.4 Feather amphibolite

  • Child of: amphibolite

  • An amphibolite in which porphyroblastic crystals of amphibole (usually hornblende) form stellate or sheaf-like groups on the planes of foliation or schistosity. Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: feather-amphibolite

1.2.3.9.2.5 Ortho-amphibolite

  • Child of: amphibolite

  • An amphibolite from an igneous protolith.

  • Alternate labels: Ortho Amphibolite

  • Concept URI token: ortho-amphibolite

1.2.3.9.2.6 Para-amphibolite

  • Child of: amphibolite

  • An amphibolite from an sedimentary protolith.

  • Alternate labels: Para amphibolite

  • Concept URI token: para-amphibolite

1.2.3.9.2.7 Post-eclogite amphibolite

  • Child of: amphibolite

  • An eclogite which has experienced later metamorphism and that now contains omphacite and garnet as abundant relics in an amphibolite groundmass.

  • Concept URI token: post-eclogite-amphibolite

1.2.3.9.2.8 Pyroxene amphibolite

  • Child of: amphibolite

  • An amphibolite containing pyroxene as the only other significant constituent.

  • Concept URI token: pyroxene-amphibolite

1.2.3.9.2.8.1 Kovdite

  • Child of: pyroxene-amphibolite pyroxene-hornblendite

  • A type of pyroxene hornblendite composed of green amphibole and orthopyroxene, with small amounts of biotite and plagioclase and occasional garnet. It may be a metamorphic rock.

  • Concept URI token: kovdite

1.2.3.9.3 disthenite

  • Child of: high-grade-metamorphic-rock

  • A metamorphic rock composed almost entirely of kyanite (disthene) and some quartz, often associated with magnetiferous quartzite and amphibolite. Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: disthenite

1.2.3.9.4 Granulite

  • Child of: high-grade-metamorphic-rock

  • A high-grade metamorphic rock in which the silicates are dominantly water-free, eg, feldspars, garnet, pyroxene; the presence of feldspar and the absence of primary muscovite are critical, and cordierite may also be present. A relatively coarse, granular rock formed at high pressures and temperatures, which may exhibit a crude gneissic structure due to the parallelism of flat lenses of quartz and/or feldspar. The texture is typically granoblastic.

  • Concept URI token: granulite

1.2.3.9.4.1 Biotite-garnet-plagioclase granulite

  • Child of: granulite

  • A granulite composed primarily of plagioclase, garnet and biotite.

  • Concept URI token: biotite-garnet-plagioclase-granulite

1.2.3.9.4.2 Diopside-garnet granulite

  • Child of: granulite

  • A granulite composed primarily of garnet and diopside.

  • Concept URI token: diopside-garnet-granulite

1.2.3.9.4.3 Felsic-granulite

  • Child of: granulite

  • A granulite with <30% mafic minerals.

  • Concept URI token: felsic-granulite

1.2.3.9.4.4 Garnet-clinopyroxene-plagioclase granulite

  • Child of: granulite

  • A granulite composed primarily of plagioclase, clinopyroxene and garnet.

  • Concept URI token: garnet-clinopyroxene-plagioclase-granulite

1.2.3.9.4.5 Garnet granulite

  • Child of: granulite

  • A granulite rich in garnet

  • Concept URI token: garnet-granulite

1.2.3.9.4.6 Garnet-pyroxene-feldspar granulite

  • Child of: granulite

  • A granulite composed primarily of feldspar, pyroxene and garnet.

  • Concept URI token: garnet-pyroxene-feldspar-granulite

1.2.3.9.4.7 Garnet-pyroxene granulite

  • Child of: granulite

  • A granulite composed primarily of garnet and pyroxene.

  • Concept URI token: garnet-pyroxene-granulite

1.2.3.9.4.8 kinzigite

  • Child of: granulite

  • A coarse-grained metamorphic rock of pelitic composition occurring in the granulite facies. Essential minerals are garnet and biotite, with which occur varying amounts of quartz, K-feldspar, oligoclase, muscovite, cordierite, and sillimanite. The name is from Kinzig, Schwarzwald, Germany. Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: kinzigite

1.2.3.9.4.9 Kyanite-garnet-anorthite-quartz granulite

  • Child of: granulite

  • A granulite containing kyanite, anorthite, quartz and garnet.

  • Concept URI token: kyanite-garnet-anorthite-quartz-granulite

1.2.3.9.4.10 Kyanite granulite

  • Child of: granulite

  • A granulite containing kyanite.

  • Concept URI token: kyanite-granulite

1.2.3.9.4.11 Mafic-granulite

  • Child of: granulite

  • A granulite with >30% mafic minerals.

  • Concept URI token: mafic-granulite

1.2.3.9.4.11.1 Hornblende mafic-granulite

  • Child of: mafic-granulite

  • A mafic-granulite where hornblende is the major constituent.

  • Concept URI token: hornblende-mafic-granulite

1.2.3.9.4.12 Namiesterstein

  • Child of: granulite

  • An obsolete name for granulite from the Namist (Namiest in German) in the Bohemian Massif.

  • Concept URI token: namiesterstein

1.2.3.9.4.13 Quartz-feldspar granulite

  • Child of: granulite

  • A granulite composed primarily of quartz and feldspar.

  • Concept URI token: quartz-feldspar-granulite

1.2.3.9.5 Halleflinta

  • Child of: high-grade-metamorphic-rock

  • An obsolete term used mostly in Sweden and Finland for a fine- grained compact quartzofeldspathic rock of horny aspect, which may be banded and/or blastoporphyritic. It is derived from acid igneous rocks or acid tuffs and is partly synonymous with leptynite. Ojakangas and Marmo (1995) considered the Proterozoic Leptite and Halleflinta (Tuff and Tuffite) Sequences of Southern Finland to be tectonised quartzofeldspathic volcanic rocks.

  • Concept URI token: halleflinta

1.2.3.9.6 High P/T metamorphic rock

  • Child of: high-grade-metamorphic-rock

  • Metamorphic rock formed at high pressure and temperature.

  • Concept URI token: high-pt-metamorphic-rock

1.2.3.9.6.1 Blueschist

  • Child of: high-pt-metamorphic-rock schist

  • A schist whose bluish colour is due to the presence of alkali amphibole.

  • Concept URI token: blueschist

1.2.3.9.6.1.1 Crossite-pumpellyite granofels

  • Child of: blueschist granofels

  • A granofels containing crossite and pumpellyite.

  • Concept URI token: crossite-pumpellyite-granofels

1.2.3.9.6.1.2 Epidote-glaucophane schist

  • Child of: blueschist

  • A schistose metamorphic rock with glaucophane and epidote as the only major components.

  • Concept URI token: epidote-glaucophane-schist

1.2.3.9.6.1.3 Glaucophane schist

  • Child of: blueschist

  • A schistose metamorphic rock with glaucophane as the major (>5%) constituent. The use of prefixes (jadeite bearing glaucophane- phengite-schist) is recommended if additional minerals are present as minor or major constituents. A type of amphibole schist in which glaucophane rather than hornblende is an abundant mineral. Epidote frequently occurs, and there are quartz, albite and mica-rich varieties.

  • Concept URI token: glaucophane-schist

1.2.3.9.6.1.4 Jadeite-bearing glaucophane-phengite schist

  • Child of: blueschist

  • A schistose metamorphic rock with glaucophane and phengite as the only major components but containing up to 5% jadeite.

  • Concept URI token: jadeite-bearing-glaucophane-phengite-schist

1.2.3.9.6.2 Eclogite

  • Child of: high-pt-metamorphic-rock

  • A high P/T metamorphic rock composed of more than 75% vol. garnet (often pyrope or Mg-rich almandine) and omphacite (Na-Ca-Al-Mg clinopyroxene). Both must be present and neither component more than 75% vol. Eclogite never contains plagioclase. Rutile, kyanite, and quartz are typically present.

  • Concept URI token: eclogite

1.2.3.9.6.2.1 Kyanite-paragonite eclogite

  • Child of: eclogite

  • An eclogite containing at least 5% vol. kyanite and paragonite with paragonite > kyanite.

  • Concept URI token: kyanite-paragonite-eclogite

1.2.3.9.6.3 Eclogitoid

  • Child of: high-pt-metamorphic-rock

  • A metamorphic rock that contains both garnet and omphacite but does not fulfill the criteria of being classificed as eclogite.

  • Concept URI token: eclogitoid

1.2.3.9.6.3.1 Garnet omphacitite

  • Child of: eclogitoid omphacitite

  • A omphacitite containing garnet.

  • Concept URI token: garnet-omphacitite

1.2.3.9.6.3.2 Omphacite garnetite

  • Child of: eclogitoid garnetite

  • A garnetite containing omphacite.

  • Concept URI token: omphacite-garnetite

1.2.3.9.6.4 Garnetite

  • Child of: high-pt-metamorphic-rock

  • A high P/T metamorphic rock composed of more than 75% vol. garnet. The name eclogite cannot be applied in this case.

  • Concept URI token: garnetite

1.2.3.9.6.4.1 Omphacite garnetite

  • Child of: eclogitoid garnetite

  • A garnetite containing omphacite.

  • Concept URI token: omphacite-garnetite

1.2.3.9.6.5 Glaucophanite

  • Child of: high-pt-metamorphic-rock

  • A rock containing more than 75% vol. of glaucophane or ferroglaucophane. The name has previously been used as a synonym for glaucophane gneiss or glaucophane granofels with at least 50% vol. glaucophane or as a straight synonym of glaucophane schist.

  • Concept URI token: glaucophanite

1.2.3.9.6.6 Griquaite

  • Child of: high-pt-metamorphic-rock

  • An obsolete name for a rock composed of pyrope, diopside and/or orthopyroxene.

  • Concept URI token: griquaite

1.2.3.9.6.7 Grospydrite

  • Child of: high-pt-metamorphic-rock

  • An obsolete name for a plagioclase-free rock mainly composed of Ca- Al clinopyroxene and calcic garnet together with some kyanite.

  • Concept URI token: grospydrite

1.2.3.9.6.8 Metamorphic pyroxenite

  • Child of: high-pt-metamorphic-rock

  • A high p/t metamorphic rock composed of at least 75% pyroxene. See also pyroxenite for igneous-derived pyroxene-rich rocks.

  • Concept URI token: metamorphic-pyroxenite

1.2.3.9.6.8.1 Fei Cui Jade

  • Child of: jade metamorphic-pyroxenite

  • The chinese name (in pinyin) for what was previously called jadeite- jade. The name Fei Cui however covers a range of compositions of jade that include the minerals jadeite, omphacite and kosmochlor. It is a polycrystalline aggregate of one or more of the above clinopyroxenes with a compact structure. The name pyroxene jade may be a more appropriate western synonym than jadeite-jade.

  • Concept URI token: fei-cui-jade

1.2.3.9.6.8.2 Jadeite Jade

  • Child of: fei-cui-jade jadeitite

  • A gem/ornamental stone name which is used for a variety of jadeitite with good colour, texture and, ideally, translucency. It is composed primarily of the mineral jadeite (although some specimens called ‘jadeite jade’ actually are compositionally omphacitite or kosmochlorite.

  • Concept URI token: jadeite-jade

1.2.3.9.6.8.3 Kosmochlor Fei Cui

  • Child of: fei-cui-jade

  • A variety of Fei Cui Jade

  • Concept URI token: kosmochlor-fei-cui

1.2.3.9.6.8.4 Omphacite Fei Cui

  • Child of: fei-cui-jade

  • A variety of Fei Cui Jade

  • Concept URI token: omphacite-fei-cui

1.2.3.9.6.8.5 Jadeitite

  • Child of: metamorphic-pyroxenite

  • Jadeitite is a metamorphic rock found in blueschist-grade metamorphic terrains, in isolated metasomatically altered bodies within serpentinite associated with subduction zone environments. Jadeitite consists almost entirely of jadeite pyroxene and is typically mined as a source of the ornamental rock or gemstone, jade - however not all jade contains the mineral jadeite - see the entry for jadeite jade.

  • Concept URI token: jadeitite

1.2.3.9.6.8.6 Jadeite Jade

  • Child of: fei-cui-jade jadeitite

  • A gem/ornamental stone name which is used for a variety of jadeitite with good colour, texture and, ideally, translucency. It is composed primarily of the mineral jadeite (although some specimens called ‘jadeite jade’ actually are compositionally omphacitite or kosmochlorite.

  • Concept URI token: jadeite-jade

1.2.3.9.6.8.7 Kosmochlorite

  • Child of: metamorphic-pyroxenite

  • A metamorphic pyroxenite composed predominantly of kosmochlor. See also jadeite jade.

  • Concept URI token: kosmochlorite

1.2.3.9.6.8.8 Omphacitite

  • Child of: metamorphic-pyroxenite

  • A high P/T metamorphic rock composed of more than 75% vol. omphacite. The name eclogite cannot be applied in this case.

  • Concept URI token: omphacitite

1.2.3.9.6.8.9 Garnet omphacitite

  • Child of: eclogitoid omphacitite

  • A omphacitite containing garnet.

  • Concept URI token: garnet-omphacitite

1.2.3.9.6.9 Mucronite

  • Child of: high-pt-metamorphic-rock

  • An obsolete name for a metamorphic rock mainly composed of jadeite, garnet, phengite, quartz with or without k-feldspar.

  • Concept URI token: mucronite

1.2.3.9.6.10 Ultramafic metamorphic rock

  • Child of: high-pt-metamorphic-rock

  • Ultramafic rocks containing olivine and/or pyroxene and/or hornblende may be formed by either metamorphic or igneous processes.

  • Concept URI token: ultramafic-metamorphic-rock

1.2.3.9.6.10.1 Alkremite

  • Child of: ultramafic-metamorphic-rock

  • An obsolete term for an ultramafic metamorphic rock composed of spinel and pyrope which together form about 75% of the rock and both of which are present in large proportion.

  • Concept URI token: alkremite

1.2.3.9.6.10.2 Spinel-pyrope granofels

  • Child of: alkremite granofels

  • A granofels containing spinel and pyrope.

  • Concept URI token: spinel-pyrope-granofels

1.2.3.9.6.10.3 Harzburgite

  • Child of: peridotite ultramafic-metamorphic-rock

  • A peridotite containing <5% hornblende, >5% orthopyroxene and <5% clinopyroxene.A variety of peridotite that consists essentially of olivine and enstatite or bronzite.

  • Concept URI token: harzburgite

1.2.3.9.6.10.4 Hornblende harzburgite

  • Child of: harzburgite

  • A harzburgite containing up to 5% hornblende.

  • Concept URI token: hornblende-harzburgite

1.2.3.9.6.10.5 Bragancaite

  • Child of: hornblende-harzburgite

  • A local name for a hornblende harzburgite composed of olivine, enstatite and hornblende.

  • Concept URI token: bragancaite

1.2.3.9.6.10.6 Lherzolite

  • Child of: peridotite ultramafic-metamorphic-rock

  • A peridotite containing >40% olivine, <5% hornblende, >5% orthopyroxene and >5% clinopyroxene.

  • Alternate labels: Buchnerite

  • Concept URI token: lherzolite

1.2.3.9.6.10.7 Spinel lherzolite

  • Child of: lherzolite

  • A lherzolite rich in spinel.

  • Concept URI token: spinel-lherzolite

1.2.3.9.6.10.8 Pyroxene-olivine gneiss

  • Child of: gneiss ultramafic-metamorphic-rock

  • A gneiss containing pyroxene and olivine as the major components.

  • Concept URI token: pyroxene-olivine-gneiss

1.2.3.9.6.10.9 Ultramafic Gneiss

  • Child of: ultramafic-metamorphic-rock

  • A gneiss with a ultramafic protolith.

  • Concept URI token: ultramafic-gneiss

1.2.3.9.6.10.10 Ultramafic schist

  • Child of: ultramafic-metamorphic-rock

  • A schist with a ultramafic protolith.

  • Concept URI token: ultramafic-schist

1.2.3.9.6.10.11 Websterite

  • Child of: pyroxenite-ss ultramafic-metamorphic-rock

  • A pyroxenite with >5% clinopyroxene and >5% orthopyroxene. (Not the namesake mineral ‘websterite’)

  • Concept URI token: websterite

1.2.3.9.6.10.12 Anabohitsite

  • Child of: websterite

  • A type of websterite consisting of hypersthene (= enstatite), augite, ilmenite and magnetite with minor olivine and hornblende. Named after it s first recorded locality, Anabohitsy, Atsimo- Andrefana, Madagascar

  • Concept URI token: anabohitsite

1.2.3.9.6.10.13 Ariegite

  • Child of: websterite

  • A local group name for a variety of websterite composed of clinopyroxene, orthopyroxene, abundant spinel and often pyrope-rich garnet and hornblende.

  • Concept URI token: ariegite

1.2.3.9.6.11 Whiteschist

  • Child of: high-pt-metamorphic-rock schist

  • A light-coloured schist containing kyanite and talc. These rocks represent Al-rich rocks metamorphosed under the conditions of the eclogite facies.

  • Concept URI token: whiteschist

1.2.3.9.6.11.1 Kyanite-talc-phengite schist

  • Child of: whiteschist

  • A whiteschist with phengite as the primary constituent.

  • Concept URI token: kyanite-talc-phengite-schist

1.2.3.9.7 Jade

  • Child of: high-grade-metamorphic-rock

  • A greenish black to creamy white ornamental stone or gemstone. Many different rocks and minerals have been marketed as jade, especially nephrite and serpentine, but also green quartz, vesuvianite (californite), etc. Gemmologists, however, usually restrict the name to just jadeite and nephrite.

  • Concept URI token: jade

1.2.3.9.7.1 Fei Cui Jade

  • Child of: jade metamorphic-pyroxenite

  • The chinese name (in pinyin) for what was previously called jadeite- jade. The name Fei Cui however covers a range of compositions of jade that include the minerals jadeite, omphacite and kosmochlor. It is a polycrystalline aggregate of one or more of the above clinopyroxenes with a compact structure. The name pyroxene jade may be a more appropriate western synonym than jadeite-jade.

  • Concept URI token: fei-cui-jade

1.2.3.9.7.1.1 Jadeite Jade

  • Child of: fei-cui-jade jadeitite

  • A gem/ornamental stone name which is used for a variety of jadeitite with good colour, texture and, ideally, translucency. It is composed primarily of the mineral jadeite (although some specimens called ‘jadeite jade’ actually are compositionally omphacitite or kosmochlorite.

  • Concept URI token: jadeite-jade

1.2.3.9.7.1.2 Kosmochlor Fei Cui

  • Child of: fei-cui-jade

  • A variety of Fei Cui Jade

  • Concept URI token: kosmochlor-fei-cui

1.2.3.9.7.1.3 Omphacite Fei Cui

  • Child of: fei-cui-jade

  • A variety of Fei Cui Jade

  • Concept URI token: omphacite-fei-cui

1.2.3.9.7.2 Nephrite

  • Child of: jade

  • Nephrite is a rock comprising mostly massive microcrystalline to cryptocrystalline felted amphiboles of the tremolite - actinolite series. Nephrite is one of the two rocks termed as jade. White nephrite, termed white jade or mutton-fat jade, is nearly pure tremolite, while most nephrite is green owing to the Fe content in actinolite.

  • Concept URI token: nephrite

1.2.3.9.8 Lapis lazuli

  • Child of: high-grade-metamorphic-rock meta-evaporite

  • An uncommon metamorphic rock having lazurite as an essential component. Believed to be meta-evaporites recrystallised during high- grade regional metamorphism.

  • Concept URI token: lapis-lazuli

1.2.3.9.9 Leptynite

  • Child of: high-grade-metamorphic-rock

  • An obsolete term, initially applied to a fine-granied granulite- facies rock, predominantly consisting of alkali-feldspar, containing minor quartz, white mica, garnet and tourmaline, and with a planar gneissose structure. Later used for any white-coloured quartzofeldspathic rock, typically forming bands alternating with metabasic rock, irrespective of the intensity of metamorphism.

  • Concept URI token: leptynite

1.2.3.9.10 Migmatite and related rock

  • Child of: high-grade-metamorphic-rock

  • A group of rocks that are in transition between metamorphic and plutonic state.

  • Concept URI token: migmatite-and-related-rock

1.2.3.9.10.1 Anatexite

  • Child of: migmatite-and-related-rock

  • A rock still showing the evidence of in situ formation by anatexis.

  • Concept URI token: anatexite

1.2.3.9.10.2 Chorismite

  • Child of: migmatite-and-related-rock

  • A general term for a group of mixed rocks, which are the result of the injection of the crystallisation products of intruding magmas into, and/or the mixture of such material with, the enclosing rocks, sedimentary or metamorphic. There are several varieties. The term is not widely used. Compare with: migmatite

  • Concept URI token: chorismite

1.2.3.9.10.3 Migmatite

  • Child of: migmatite-and-related-rock

  • A banded metamorphic rock, pervasively heterogeneous on a meso- to megascopic scale. It typically consists of darker bands rich in mafic minerals and lighter quartzofeldspathic parts. The darker parts usually exhibit features of metamorphic rocks (eg. gneiss or amphibolite) whereas the lighter parts are of granitic texture.

  • Concept URI token: migmatite

1.2.3.9.10.3.1 Agmatite

  • Child of: breccia migmatite

  • A migmatite with a breccia-like structure.

  • Concept URI token: agmatite

1.2.3.9.10.3.2 Arterite

  • Child of: migmatite

  • A type of migmatite where the darker parts are injected by veins of lighter material (leucosomes) introduced from outside.

  • Concept URI token: arterite

1.2.3.9.10.3.3 Crocydite

  • Child of: migmatite

  • A migmatite with centimeter-scale irregular or star-shaped metatects that are strongly interlaced with the palaeosome.

  • Concept URI token: crocydite

1.2.3.9.10.3.4 Diatexite

  • Child of: migmatite

  • A type of migmatite where the darker and the lighter parts form schlieren and nebulitic structures which merge into one another.

  • Concept URI token: diatexite

1.2.3.9.10.3.5 Dictyonite

  • Child of: migmatite

  • A migmatite with a reticulated structure formed by a network of small veins.

  • Concept URI token: dictyonite

1.2.3.9.10.3.6 Metatexite

  • Child of: migmatite

  • A variety of migmatite with discrete lecuosomes, meosomes and melanosomes.

  • Concept URI token: metatexite

1.2.3.9.10.3.7 Nebulite

  • Child of: migmatite

  • A migmatite with diffuse relics of pre-existing rocks or rock structures. A type of mixed rock whose fabric is characterized by indistinct, streaky inhomogeneities or schlieren and in which no sharp distinction can be made between the component parts of the fabric. Adj: nebulitic.

  • Concept URI token: nebulite

1.2.3.9.10.3.8 Phlebite

  • Child of: migmatite

  • In contrast with venite or arterite which have a genetic definition, this refers simply a veined rock; the veins may have been injected from outside or exuded in situ.

  • Concept URI token: phlebite

1.2.3.9.10.3.9 Stromatite

  • Child of: migmatite

  • A migmatite with regular layers, the layers having two or more different compositions or apperances, for example the alternation of mesosome and leucosome. A type of mixed rock or chorismite in which the units of the fabric (granitic material and metamorphic or sedimentary rock) form a system of layers, strata, or bands so intricately united that the whole rather than the individual layers constitutes the geological field unit.

  • Concept URI token: stromatite

1.2.3.9.10.3.10 Venite

  • Child of: migmatite

  • A type of migmatite in which the material of the lighter veins (leucosomes) is extracted from the parent rock. Migmatite of which the mobile portion(s) were formed by exudation (secretion) from the rock itself (Dietrich & Mehnert, 1961). Not widely used. Compare with: veined gneiss, composite gneiss Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: venite

1.2.3.9.11 Pyribolite

  • Child of: high-grade-metamorphic-rock

  • An obsolete name for a high-grade metamorphic rock composed of plagioclase, hornblend, clinopyroxene, orthopyroxene and garnet.

  • Concept URI token: pyribolite

1.2.3.9.12 Pyrigarnie

  • Child of: high-grade-metamorphic-rock

  • An obsolete name for a high-grade metamorphic rock composed of plagioclase, garnet and pyroxenes, with mafic content higher than 30% vol. Now replaced by garnet-rich mafic-granulite or pyroxene-garnet- plagioclase granofels.

  • Concept URI token: pyrigarnie

1.2.3.9.13 Stronalite

  • Child of: high-grade-metamorphic-rock

  • An obsolete regional term for a high-grade metamorphic rock mainly composed of garnet, feldspar and quartz. The name may be replaced by granulite, garnet-quartz-plagioclase gneiss or garnet-quartz- plagioclase granofels.

  • Concept URI token: stronalite

1.2.3.9.14 Zoisitite

  • Child of: high-grade-metamorphic-rock

  • A rock comprised primarily of zoisite.

  • Concept URI token: zoisitite

1.2.3.9.14.1 Anyolite

  • Child of: zoisitite

  • Anyolite is a metamorphic rock consisting of a granular mass of bright green chrome-zoisite with minor black (in fact very dark green) pargasite (commonly both as grains a few mm diameter), containing conspicuous coarse porphyroblasts of purplish red corundum (var. ruby) which may be up to several centimetres across.

  • Concept URI token: anyolite

1.2.3.10 Impactite

  • Child of: metamorphic-rock

  • Rocks affected by one or more hypervelocity impact(s) resulting from collision(s) of planetary bodies.i. A vesicular, glassy to finely crystalline material produced by fusion or partial fusion of target rock by the heat generated from the impact of a large meteorite, and occurring in and around the resulting crater, typically as individual bodies composed of mixtures of melt and rock fragments, often with traces of meteoritic material; a rock from a presumed impact site.ii. A term used incorrectly for any shock-metamorphosed rock.

  • Alternate labels: impact generated material, impact glass, impact slag,

  • Concept URI token: impactite

1.2.3.10.1 Multiple impact impactite

  • Child of: impactite

  • Impactites resulting from multiple collisions (eg on the moon or asteroids.)

  • Concept URI token: multiple-impact-impactite

1.2.3.10.1.1 Impact regolith

  • Child of: lunar-regolith multiple-impact-impactite

  • Unconsolidated clastic impact debris.

  • Concept URI token: impact-regolith

1.2.3.10.1.2 Shock lithified impact regolith

  • Child of: multiple-impact-impactite

  • Consolidated clastic impact debris.

  • Concept URI token: shock-lithified-impact-regolith

1.2.3.10.1.2.1 Shock lithified impact regolith breccia

  • Child of: breccia shock-lithified-impact-regolith

  • Consolidated clastic impact debris breccia.

  • Alternate labels: Shatter Breccia

  • Concept URI token: shock-lithified-impact-regolith-breccia

1.2.3.10.1.2.2 Lithic breccia

  • Child of: shock-lithified-impact-regolith-breccia

  • Consolidated clastic impact debris without matrix melt or melt particles.

  • Concept URI token: lithic-breccia

1.2.3.10.1.2.3 Regolith breccia

  • Child of: shock-lithified-impact-regolith-breccia

  • Consolidated clastic impact debris with matrix melt and melt particles.

  • Concept URI token: regolith-breccia

1.2.3.10.2 Single impact impactite

  • Child of: impactite

  • Impactites resulting from a single impact.

  • Concept URI token: single-impact-impactite

1.2.3.10.2.1 Impact-melt-rock

  • Child of: single-impact-impactite

  • Rocks which have undergone whole rock melting.

  • Concept URI token: impact-melt-rock

1.2.3.10.2.1.1 Clast-free impact-melt-rock

  • Child of: impact-melt-rock

  • An impact-melt-rock with no clasts.

  • Concept URI token: clast-free-impact-melt-rock

1.2.3.10.2.1.2 Clast-poor impact-melt-rock

  • Child of: impact-melt-rock

  • An impact-melt-rock with few clasts.

  • Concept URI token: clast-poor-impact-melt-rock

1.2.3.10.2.1.3 Clast-rich impact-melt-rock

  • Child of: impact-melt-rock

  • An impact-melt-rock rich in clasts.

  • Concept URI token: clast-rich-impact-melt-rock

1.2.3.10.2.1.4 Tagamite

  • Child of: impact-melt-rock

  • An impact-melt rock found on the crater floor of impact craters composed of more or less completely melted material.

  • Concept URI token: tagamite

1.2.3.10.2.1.5 Tektite

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-glassy-rock impact-melt-rock

  • A natural glass formed from a meteorite impact melting the local rock. Depending on the nature of the latter, the composition of tektites is variable.

  • Concept URI token: tektite

1.2.3.10.2.1.6 Australite

  • Child of: tektite

  • A tektite variety from the Australasian strewnfield. Dark, mostly black. The crater of this strewnfield has not be located, but is assumed to lie in Southeast Asia.

  • Concept URI token: australite

1.2.3.10.2.1.7 Bediasite

  • Child of: tektite

  • A black tektite variety from North American strewnfield (Chesapeake Bay impact crater), found in Texas, USA.

  • Concept URI token: bediasite

1.2.3.10.2.1.8 Bikolite

  • Child of: tektite

  • A name given to tektites from the Bikol area of the Philippines.

  • Concept URI token: bikolite

1.2.3.10.2.1.9 Billitonite

  • Child of: tektite

  • A tektite material found on Billiton Island, between Sumatra and Borneo. Compare indochinite.

  • Concept URI token: billitonite

1.2.3.10.2.1.10 Chinite

  • Child of: tektite

  • A black tektite variety found in Chinafrom the Australasian strewnfield.

  • Concept URI token: chinite

1.2.3.10.2.1.11 Darwin Glass

  • Child of: tektite

  • A variety of Tektite From Tasmania, Australia.

  • Concept URI token: darwin-glass

1.2.3.10.2.1.12 Georgiaite

  • Child of: tektite

  • A green tektite variety from North American strewnfield (Chesapeake Bay impact crater), found in Georgia, USA.

  • Concept URI token: georgiaite

1.2.3.10.2.1.13 Indochinite

  • Child of: tektite

  • A tektite variety from the Australasian strewnfield. Dark, mostly black. The crater of this strewnfield has not be located, but is assumed to lie in Southeast Asia.

  • Concept URI token: indochinite

1.2.3.10.2.1.14 Irghizite

  • Child of: tektite

  • Tektite from the Zhamanshin meteor crater in Kazakhstan (latitude: 48° 24’ North, longitude: 60° 58’ East).

  • Concept URI token: irghizite

1.2.3.10.2.1.15 Ivorite

  • Child of: tektite

  • A black tektite variety from the Ivory Coast strewnfield (Lake Bosumtwi Crater, Ghana). Found in the Cote d’Ivoire (Ivory Coast).NOTE: Some tectites from the large Australasian field are fraudulently sold in Ivory Coast as being Ivory Coast tektites (the latter are extremely rare).

  • Concept URI token: ivorite

1.2.3.10.2.1.16 Microtektite

  • Child of: tektite

  • Milimeter-size tektites.

  • Concept URI token: microtektite

1.2.3.10.2.1.17 Uruguaite

  • Child of: tektite

  • Black tektites from a new strewn field discovered in 2016 (Ferriare et al., 2017).

  • Concept URI token: uruguaite

1.2.3.10.2.1.18 Zhamanshinite

  • Child of: tektite

  • Tektites from the Zhamanshin meteor crater.

  • Concept URI token: zhamanshinite

1.2.3.10.2.2 Monomict impact breccia

  • Child of: breccia single-impact-impactite

  • Impact breccia from a single lithology target.

  • Concept URI token: monomict-impact-breccia

1.2.3.10.2.3 Polymict impact breccia

  • Child of: breccia single-impact-impactite

  • Impact breccia from a complex lithology target.

  • Concept URI token: polymict-impact-breccia

1.2.3.10.2.3.1 Lithic impact breccia

  • Child of: polymict-impact-breccia

  • An impact breccia that contains shocked and unshocked clasts in a clastic matrix but lacks cogenetic melt particles.

  • Concept URI token: lithic-impact-breccia

1.2.3.10.2.3.2 Suevite

  • Child of: polymict-impact-breccia

  • An impact breccia that contains shocked and unshocked clasts in a clastic matrix along with cogenetic melt particles. Suevite is one of the diagnostic rock-types for large impact structures. It has been described from many of the larger impact structures identified on earth.

  • Concept URI token: suevite

1.2.3.10.2.4 Shocked rock

  • Child of: single-impact-impactite

  • Non-brecciated rocks which show unequivocal effects of shock metamorphism, exclujding whole rock melting.

  • Concept URI token: shocked-rock

1.2.3.12.7 Metagabbro

  • Child of: meta-igneous-rock

  • A metamorphically-altered gabbro.

  • Alternate labels: meta gabbro, meta-gabbro,

  • Concept URI token: metagabbro

1.2.3.12.7.1 Allalinite

  • Child of: metagabbro

  • An ophiolitic metagabbro with Cr-bearing omphacite and whose original structure is still preserved despite the total pseudomorphic alteration of the igneous assemblage.

  • Concept URI token: allalinite

1.2.3.12.7.2 Epidiorite

  • Child of: metagabbro

  • A metamorphosed gabbro or dolerite in which generally fibrous amphibole (uralite) has replaced the original clinopyroxene (commonly augite). It is usually massive but may have some schistosity. Commonly found as dykes and usually composed of amphibole, plagioclase, chlorite, ilmenite and magnetite.

  • Alternate labels: Epidiorite (of Gumbel)

  • Concept URI token: epidiorite-of-gumbel

1.2.3.12.8.11.3 Protogine

  • Child of: granitic-gneiss metagranite

  • A term used in the Alps for a metagranitic rock with a gneissose structure containing greenschist facies minerals such as sericite, chlorite, epidote, and garnet, and shows evidence of a composite origin or of crystallisation (or partial recrystallisation) under stress after consolidation. Also spelled protogene. The term, dating from 1806, is obsolete. Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: protogine

1.2.3.12.13 Serpentinite

  • Child of: meta-igneous-rock metasomatic-rock

  • A rock composed of one or more serpentine group minerals, e.g., antigorite, chrysotile and lizardite, formed by serpentinisation (hydration and metamorphic transformation) of rock consisting almost wholly of ferromagnesian silicate minerals, such as olivine and pyroxene (usually ultramafic igneous rocks). Accessory chlorite, talc, and magnetite may be present.

  • Alternate labels: Bergmanite

  • Concept URI token: serpentinite

1.2.3.12.13.1 Atlantisite

  • Child of: serpentinite

  • A trade name for a variety of serpentinite consisting of serpentine group minerals and purple stichtite.

  • Concept URI token: atlantisite

1.2.3.12.13.2 Blacolite

  • Child of: serpentinite

  • A serpentinite containing grains of bastite.

  • Concept URI token: blacolite

1.2.3.12.13.3 Infinite

  • Child of: serpentinite

  • Superfluous trade name for a light-green serpentine with bands of white chrysotile.

  • Concept URI token: infinite

1.2.3.12.14 Talc-rock

  • Child of: meta-igneous-rock

  • A meta-ultramafic-rock rich intalc.

  • Alternate labels: Soapstone

  • Concept URI token: talc-rock

1.2.3.15.6 Metacarbonate-rock

  • Child of: metasedimentary-rock

  • A metamorphosed carbonate-rich sedimentary rock or sediment.

  • Alternate labels: Metacarbonate Rock

  • Concept URI token: metacarbonate-rock

1.2.3.15.6.1 Calc-silicate rock

  • Child of: metacarbonate-rock

  • Also written ’calcsilicate rock.’A metamorphic rock mainly composed of calc-silicate minerals, such as diopside, grossular-andradite, clinozoisite-epidote and wollastonite, and containing less than 5% vol. of carbonate minerals (usually dolomite or calcite). Formed by metamorphism of impure limestone or dolostone; related to skarns.

  • Alternate labels: Calcsilicate rock, calc-silicate, calcsilicate,

  • Concept URI token: calc-silicate-rock

1.2.3.15.6.1.1 Californite

  • Child of: calc-silicate-rock

  • A dark-green to grass-green compact massive rock consisting primarily of vesuvianite.

  • Alternate labels: American Jade, California jade,

  • Concept URI token: californite

1.2.3.15.6.1.2 Tactite

  • Child of: calc-skarn californite

  • A calc-silicate rock formed by contact metasomatism of a carbonate or marly rock. A rock of complex mineralogical composition, formed by contact metamorphism and metasomatism of carbonate rocks. It is typically coarse-grained and mostly rich in calcic garnet, calcium- iron-rich pyroxene, vesuvianite, epidote, wollastonite, and scapolite. Approximate syn: skarn. Often mined for scheelite (tungsten ore), and less commonly as decorative dimension stone. See Also: calc-silicate hornfels

  • Concept URI token: tactite

1.2.3.15.6.2 Carbonate-silicate rock

  • Child of: metacarbonate-rock

  • A metamorphic rock mainly composed of silicate minerals (including calc-silicate minerals) and containing between 5% and 50% vol. of carbonate minerals.

  • Concept URI token: carbonate-silicate-rock

1.2.3.15.6.3 Cipolin

  • Child of: metacarbonate-rock

  • An obsolete term for a metacarbonate rock rich in chlorite and other phyllosilicates and displaying a saccharoidal structure.

  • Concept URI token: cipolin

1.2.3.15.6.4 Marble

  • Child of: metacarbonate-rock

  • Metamorphic rock containing more than 50% vol. of carbonate minerals.

  • Alternate labels: Crystalline limestone

  • Concept URI token: marble

1.2.3.15.6.4.1 Contact-marble

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-rock marble

  • A contact rock containing more than 50% vol. of carbonate minerals.

  • Concept URI token: contact-marble

1.2.3.15.6.4.2 Brucite-marble

  • Child of: contact-marble impure-marble

  • A contact-metamorphosed dolostone in the innermost part of many low- pressure aureoles.

  • Concept URI token: brucite-marble

1.2.3.15.6.4.3 Pencatite

  • Child of: brucite-marble

  • A brucite-marble having CaO and MgO amounts similar to those in pure dolomitic rocks (31% and 21% by weight respectively.)

  • Concept URI token: pencatite

1.2.3.15.6.4.4 Predazzite

  • Child of: brucite-marble

  • A brucite-marble reduced in MgO and enriched in CaO compared to dolomitic rocks. Compare with pencatite.

  • Concept URI token: predazzite

1.2.3.15.6.8 Ophicarbonate

  • Child of: breccia metacarbonate-rock

  • A rock consisting of serpentine and carbonate; the serpentine is commonly fragmented or brecciated, and veined and impregnated by the carbonate material (calcite, dolomite or magnesite). It forms by the serpentinisation of ultramafic rocks and their reaction with CO2-bearing solutions.

  • Concept URI token: ophicarbonate

1.2.3.15.6.8.1 Ophicalcite

  • Child of: ophicarbonate

  • Strictly an ophicarbonate where calcite is the predominant carbonate, but it has been traditionally used as a synonym of ophicarbonate. A recrystallised metamorphic rock composed of calcite and serpentine, commonly formed by dedolomitisation of a siliceous dolostone. Some ophicalcites are highly veined and brecciated and are associated with serpentinite.

  • Concept URI token: ophicalcite

1.2.3.15.6.8.2 Ophidolomite

  • Child of: ophicarbonate

  • A ophicarbonate where dolomite is the predominant carbonate.

  • Concept URI token: ophidolomite

1.2.3.15.6.8.3 Ophimagnesite

  • Child of: ophicarbonate

  • A ophicarbonate where magnesite is the predominant carbonate.

  • Concept URI token: ophimagnesite

1.2.3.15.6.9 Quartz-mica-carbonate schist

  • Child of: metacarbonate-rock schist

  • A metacarbonate rock with a schistose structure and composed of carbonate, oriented mica and quartz.

  • Concept URI token: quartz-mica-carbonate-schist

1.2.3.16 Metasomatic-rock

  • Child of: metamorphic-rock

  • Metamomorphic rocks that have undergone a significant change in mineral and chemical bulk composition by metasomatism.

  • Alternate labels: Metasomatic rock, Metasomatite,

  • Concept URI token: metasomatic-rock

1.2.3.16.1 Aceite

  • Child of: metasomatic-rock

  • A low-temperature alkaline metasomatic rock, mainly composed of albite with subsidiary carbonate and hematite. U-bearing apatite is a common accessory.

  • Concept URI token: aceite

1.2.3.16.2 Adinole

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-rock metasomatic-rock

  • A compact, fine-to-very-fine grained albite-rich metasomatic rock with subordinate quartz with minor amounts of other consitutents. It has a splintery fracture, and is commonly finely banded alternating grey, green or reddish layers of variable colour intensity. It is . Chemically it contains up to 10% by weight of soda. Adinolisation may result from a Na-metasomatic process related to the intrusion of mafic igneous rocks into pelitic rocks.

  • Concept URI token: adinole

1.2.3.16.2.1 Contact adinole

  • Child of: adinole

  • An adinole found in the contact aureoles of diabase dykes.

  • Concept URI token: contact-adinole

1.2.3.16.2.2 Tuffaceous adinole

  • Child of: adinole

  • An adinole (an albite-rich metasomatic rock) found as layers within metasedimentary sequences unrelated to the proximity of mafic intrusions. Possibly albitisehd tuffs.

  • Concept URI token: tuffaceous-adinole

1.2.3.16.3 Albitite

  • Child of: metasomatic-rock

  • A rock consisting almost entirely of albite, usually a high to medium-temperature metasomatic rock formed by the intense sodic alteration of various rocks.Sometimes used for a rock comprising mostly albite and quartz, but this is better termed an albite granite, classed under alkali-feldspar-granite in the QAPF system.

  • Alternate labels: Albite porphyrite

  • Concept URI token: albitite

1.2.3.16.4 Argillisite

  • Child of: metasomatic-rock

  • A low-temperature metasomatic rock that is mainly composed of clay minerals, also present may be silica minerals, carbonates and iron sulphides. The rock forms from the hydrothermal alteration of both igneous and sedimentary rocks.

  • Concept URI token: argillisite

1.2.3.16.5 Basalt-wacke

  • Child of: metabasalt metasomatic-rock

  • An obsolete term for an altered basalt.

  • Concept URI token: basalt-wacke

1.2.3.16.6 Beresite

  • Child of: metasomatic-rock

  • A low-temperature metasomatic rock characterised by quartz, sericite, carbonate (ankerite) and pyrite resulting from the replacement of both igneous and sedimentary protoliths. It may be associated with a variety of Au, Au-Ag, Ag-Pb and U ore mineralisations.

  • Concept URI token: beresite

1.2.3.16.7 Beresite-listvenite

  • Child of: metasomatic-rock

  • Similar to a listvenite but with a mafic protolith.

  • Concept URI token: beresite-listvenite

1.2.3.16.8 Boetonite

  • Child of: metasomatic-rock

  • A vein rock composed primarily of opal and chalcedony with some chromite, marcasite and locally magnesite. Found in ultrabasic rocks.

  • Concept URI token: boetonite

1.2.3.16.9 Charoitite

  • Child of: metasomatic-rock

  • A charoite-dominated potassic metasomatic-rock rock uniquely found in the Sakha Republic, Yakutia, Russia. It is found where a syenite of the Murunskii Massif has intruded into and altered limestone deposits.

  • Concept URI token: charoitite

1.2.3.16.10 Chloritolite

  • Child of: metasomatic-rock

  • A monomineralic chliorite rock formed by hydrothermal metamorphism and occurring as veims.

  • Concept URI token: chloritolite

1.2.3.16.11 Epidotite

  • Child of: metasomatic-rock

  • A name most strictly used for an epidote-dominant metamorphic rock, but, confusingly used, depending on context, as a synonym of epidote, a synonym of epidosite or of epidote amphibolite.

  • Concept URI token: epidotite

1.2.3.16.11.1 Epidosite

  • Child of: epidotite

  • A low to medium-temperature metasomatic rock mostly formed by the alteration of basaltic rocks, but also other basic to acid igneous rocks; principally composed of epidote and quartz, with minor chlorite and amphibole.A quartz-rich, amphibole poor epidotite.

  • Concept URI token: epidosite

1.2.3.16.12 Fault-related alkaline metasomatite

  • Child of: metasomatic-rock

  • A family of related metasomatic rock commonm in Precambrian shields. They consist primarily of albite, aegirine and riebeckite.

  • Concept URI token: fault-related-alkaline-metasomatite

1.2.3.16.12.1 Albitized gneiss

  • Child of: fault-related-alkaline-metasomatite

  • An albitized gneiss. It is commonly accompanied by greisenisation and mineralisation of Ta-Nb and Be.

  • Concept URI token: albitized-gneiss

1.2.3.16.12.2 Albitized granite

  • Child of: fault-related-alkaline-metasomatite

  • An albitized granite. It is commonly accompanied by greisenisation and mineralisation of Ta-Nb and Be.

  • Concept URI token: albitized-granite

1.2.3.16.12.3 Apojasperoid

  • Child of: fault-related-alkaline-metasomatite

  • A fault-related alkaline metasomatite that differs from albitized granite through an absence of albite because the alumina content in the original rocks is too low.

  • Concept URI token: apojasperoid

1.2.3.16.12.4 Carbonatite-related albitite

  • Child of: fault-related-alkaline-metasomatite

  • An albitite related to ‘linear’ carbonatite bodies in shear zones forming rims around carbonatite lenses and veins and separate veins in the upper part of the alkaline-carbonatite rock bodies. Albitites of this type may form by the action of aqueous-CO2 fluids replacing previously fenitized host rocks (gneisses or amphibolites.) They are commonly associated with gold mineralisation.

  • Concept URI token: carbonatite-related-albitite

1.2.3.16.13 Fenite

  • Child of: metasomatic-rock

  • A high-temperature metasomatic rock characterised by the presence of alkali feldspar, sodic amphibole and sodic pyroxene. Nepheline, calcite and biotite/phlogopite may also be present and typical accessories are titanite and apatite. Fenites occur as zoned aureoles around alkaline igneous complexes, including carbonatites, forming in a wide range of host lithologies. They occur on the metre to kilometre scale.

  • Concept URI token: fenite

1.2.3.16.14 Greisen

  • Child of: metasomatic-rock

  • A medium-temperature metasomatic rock characterized by the presence of quartz and white mica, commonly with topaz, fluorite, tourmaline and locally with amazonite, orthoclase, andalusite and diaspore. Typically greisens may host Be, W, Mo, Sn and Ta mineralisation. They are associated with high-level late-orogenic leucogranites and form as replacements either in the granite body and/or in a wide range of country rocks. Zoning may be present.

  • Concept URI token: greisen

1.2.3.16.14.1 Endogreisen

  • Child of: greisen

  • A greisen that has replaced the granite.

  • Concept URI token: endogreisen

1.2.3.16.14.2 Exogreisen

  • Child of: greisen

  • A greisen that has replaced the country rock.

  • Concept URI token: exogreisen

1.2.3.16.15 Gumberite

  • Child of: metasomatic-rock

  • A medium to low-temperature metasomatic rock mainly composed of quartz, orthoclase and carbonate. It forms as an alteration of granodiorite or syenite and is closely associated with W-Cu or Au-U- bearing veins.

  • Concept URI token: gumberite

1.2.3.16.16 Hydrothermal breccia

  • Child of: breccia metasomatic-rock

  • Breccias comprising largely hydrothemal minerals, cementing clasts.

  • Alternate labels: breccia, hydrothermal, siliceous breccia,

  • Concept URI token: hydrothermal-breccia

1.2.3.16.17 Jasperoid

  • Child of: metasomatic-rock

  • A dense, usually gray, chertlike siliceous rock, in which chalcedony or cryptocrystalline quartz has replaced the carbonate minerals of limestone or dolomite; a silicified limestone. It typically develops as the gangue of metasomatic sulfide deposits of the lead-zinc type.

  • Concept URI token: jasperoid

1.2.3.16.18 Listvenite

  • Child of: metasomatic-rock

  • A low-temperature metasomatic rock similar to beresite but formed from ultrabasic rocks.

  • Alternate labels: Listwaenite:, listwanite,

  • Concept URI token: listvenite

1.2.3.16.19 Propylite

  • Child of: granofels metasomatic-rock

  • A low to medium-temperature metasomatic rock, sometimes a granofels or schist, generally formed by the propylitic alteration of basic to intermediate volcanic rocks around hydrothermal ore deposits or by plate magmatic alteration. Low-temperature varieties are principally composed of albite, calcite and chlorite; high-temperature varieties contain more epidote. Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: propylite

1.2.3.16.20 Rodingite

  • Child of: metasomatic-rock

  • A metasomatic rock primarily composed of grossular-andradite garnet and calcic pyroxene (diopside, etc); vesuvianite, epidote, scapolite, prehnite and iron ores are characteristic accessories. Rodingite mostly replaces dykes or inclusions of basic rocks within serpentinized ultramafic bodies. May also replace other basic rocks, such as volcanic rocks or amphibolites associated with ultramafic bodies.

  • Concept URI token: rodingite

1.2.3.16.21 Secondary-quartzite

  • Child of: metasomatic-rock quartzite

  • A medium to low-temperature metasomatic rock mainly composed of quartz with subsidiary high-alumina minerals, such as pyrophyllite, diaspore, alunite and kaolinite. Common accessories include fluorite, dumortierite and lazulite. Secondary-quartzites are associated with volcanic and subvolcanic rocks of rhyolitic to andesitic composition. Normally they form as replacements of acid igneous rocks and more rarely of sedimentary rocks. They may host mineral deposits of alunite, pyrophyllite, Au, Cu, Sb and Hg.

  • Concept URI token: secondary-quartzite

1.2.3.16.22 Serpentinite

  • Child of: meta-igneous-rock metasomatic-rock

  • A rock composed of one or more serpentine group minerals, e.g., antigorite, chrysotile and lizardite, formed by serpentinisation (hydration and metamorphic transformation) of rock consisting almost wholly of ferromagnesian silicate minerals, such as olivine and pyroxene (usually ultramafic igneous rocks). Accessory chlorite, talc, and magnetite may be present.

  • Alternate labels: Bergmanite

  • Concept URI token: serpentinite

1.2.3.16.22.1 Atlantisite

  • Child of: serpentinite

  • A trade name for a variety of serpentinite consisting of serpentine group minerals and purple stichtite.

  • Concept URI token: atlantisite

1.2.3.16.22.2 Blacolite

  • Child of: serpentinite

  • A serpentinite containing grains of bastite.

  • Concept URI token: blacolite

1.2.3.16.22.3 Infinite

  • Child of: serpentinite

  • Superfluous trade name for a light-green serpentine with bands of white chrysotile.

  • Concept URI token: infinite

1.2.3.16.23 Skarn

  • Child of: metasomatic-rock

  • A metasomatic rock formed at the contact between a silicate rock (or magmatic melt) and a carbonate rock. It consists mainly of Ca, Mg, Fe and/or Mn silicates which are free from or poor in water.

  • Alternate labels: Wrigglite

  • Concept URI token: skarn

1.2.3.16.23.1 Calc-skarn

  • Child of: skarn

  • A high to medium-temperature skarn consisting mainly of granditic garnet, salite (to ferrosalite or/and johannsenite-rich pyroxene), wollastonite or Mn-rich pyroxenoids and formed at the contacts of magmatic (or other silicate rocks) with calcium carbonate rocks. It can replace former magnesian-skarns (in hypabyssal or subvolcanic conditions.) Typically calc-skarns may host ores of Fe, base metals, Cu, W, Mo, Be, B, U, REE.

  • Concept URI token: calc-skarn

1.2.3.16.23.1.1 Iron-calc-skarn

  • Child of: calc-skarn

  • A calc-skarn enriched in Fe2+.

  • Concept URI token: iron-calc-skarn

1.2.3.16.23.1.2 Mangan-calc-skarn

  • Child of: calc-skarn

  • A calc-skarn enriched in Mn2+.

  • Concept URI token: mangan-calc-skarn

1.2.3.16.23.1.3 Tactite

  • Child of: calc-skarn californite

  • A calc-silicate rock formed by contact metasomatism of a carbonate or marly rock. A rock of complex mineralogical composition, formed by contact metamorphism and metasomatism of carbonate rocks. It is typically coarse-grained and mostly rich in calcic garnet, calcium- iron-rich pyroxene, vesuvianite, epidote, wollastonite, and scapolite. Approximate syn: skarn. Often mined for scheelite (tungsten ore), and less commonly as decorative dimension stone. See Also: calc-silicate hornfels

  • Concept URI token: tactite

1.2.3.16.23.2 Endoskarn

  • Child of: skarn

  • A skarn formed within the igneous mass itself, usually late in the intrusive emplacement and consisting of cross-cutting stockworks, cooling joints and around the margins and uppermost sections of the intrusion itself.

  • Concept URI token: endoskarn

1.2.3.16.23.3 Exoskarn

  • Child of: skarn

  • A skarn formed at and outside the intrusion which produced them, and are alterations of wall rocks.

  • Alternate labels: Alloskarn

  • Concept URI token: exoskarn

1.2.3.16.23.4 Magnesian-skarn

  • Child of: skarn

  • A high-temperature skarn rock containing forsterite, diopside, spinel, periclase, clinohumite, phlogopite, pargasite and formed at the contacts of magmatic and calci-magnesian or magnesian carbonate rocks. Typically these rocks may also host ores of iron, base metals, Cu, Au, Fe-Mg-borates and phlogopite.

  • Concept URI token: magnesian-skarn

1.2.3.16.23.4.1 Chondrodite skarn

  • Child of: magnesian-skarn

  • A skarn containing chondrodite.

  • Concept URI token: chondrodite-skarn

1.2.3.16.23.4.2 Serpentine skarn

  • Child of: magnesian-skarn

  • A skarn containing serpentine.

  • Concept URI token: serpentine-skarn

1.2.3.16.23.5 Magnetite skarn

  • Child of: skarn

  • A skarn rich in magentite.

  • Concept URI token: magnetite-skarn

1.2.3.16.23.6 Manganesian-skarn

  • Child of: skarn

  • A rare facies of skarn analogous to magnesian-skarn except that the magnesium is completely replaced by manganese. This facies is developed at the contacts of silicate rocks with manganese carbonates.

  • Concept URI token: manganesian-skarn

1.2.3.16.23.7 Near-skarn rock

  • Child of: skarn

  • In the outermost zone of the endoskarn or the nearest zone of the exoskarn may contain not only Ca-Mg-Fe silicates but also feldspar or scapolite and/or feldspathoid

  • Concept URI token: near-skarn-rock

1.2.3.16.24 Tourmalinite

  • Child of: metasomatic-rock

  • Metasomatic rocks containing in excess of 15 % tourmaline, and can be associated with Sn-W ore deposits.

  • Concept URI token: tourmalinite

1.2.3.16.25 Unakite

  • Child of: metasomatic-rock

  • A low to medium-temperature metasomatic rock mostly formed by the alteration of granitic rocks; principally composed of epidote, K-feldspar and quartz.

  • Concept URI token: unakite

1.2.3.17 Porphyroid

  • Child of: metamorphic-rock

  • Ambiguous term originally proposed for igneous rocks allied to porphyry. Later used for metamorphosed acid volcanic rocks or tuffs. Perhaps most commonly used for metamorphosed blastoporphyritic rocks of uncertain but probable igneous origin with phenocrysts or porphyroblasts, usually of feldspar and quartz, typically in a phyllic groundmass.

  • Concept URI token: porphyroid

1.2.3.18 Very low to low-grade metamorphic rock

  • Child of: metamorphic-rock

  • Metamorphic rock formed from very low to low-grade metamorphic processes.

  • Concept URI token: very-low-to-low-grade-metamorphic-rock

1.2.3.18.1 Coticule

  • Child of: very-low-to-low-grade-metamorphic-rock

  • A low-grade very-fine-grained metamorphic rock consisting of spessartine in a matrix of white mica and +/- submicroscopic quartz.

  • Concept URI token: coticule

1.2.3.18.2 Greenschist

  • Child of: schist very-low-to-low-grade-metamorphic-rock

  • A schist whose greenish colour is due to the presence of minerals such as actinolite, chlorite and epidote.

  • Alternate labels: Greenslate

  • Concept URI token: greenschist

1.2.3.18.2.1 Actinolite-chlorite schist

  • Child of: greenschist

  • A schistose metamorphic rock containing actinolite and chlorite.

  • Concept URI token: actinolite-chlorite-schist

1.2.3.18.2.2 Chlorogrisonite schist

  • Child of: greenschist

  • An obsolete term for a group of greenschists characterized by variable contents of plagioclase, actinolite, epidote, chlorite and magnetite.

  • Concept URI token: chlorogrisonite-schist

1.2.3.18.2.3 Greenschist facies andesite

  • Child of: greenschist meta-andesite

  • A metamorphosed andesite of the greenschist facies.

  • Concept URI token: greenschist-facies-andesite

1.2.3.18.2.4 Greenschist facies basaltic-andesite

  • Child of: greenschist metabasaltic-andesite

  • A metamorphosed basaltic-andesite of the greenschist facies.

  • Concept URI token: greenschist-facies-basaltic-andesite

1.2.3.18.3 Greenstone

  • Child of: granofels very-low-to-low-grade-metamorphic-rock

  • A granofels whose greenish colour is due to the presence of minerals such as actinolite, chlorite and epidote. Also a field term applied to any compact dark-green altered or metamorphosed basic igneous rock that owes its color to the presence of chlorite, actinolite, or epidote.

  • Concept URI token: greenstone

1.2.3.18.4 phyllite

  • Child of: foliated-metamorphic-rock very-low-to-low-grade-metamorphic-rock

  • A fine to medium-grained metamorphic rock characterised by a lustrous sheen and a well-developed schistosity resulting from the parallel arrangement of phyllosilicates.A metamorphic rock, intermediate in grade between slate and mica schist. Minute crystals of sericite/muscovite and chlorite impart a silky sheen to the surfaces of cleavage (or schistosity). Phyllites commonly exhibit corrugated/crenulated cleavage surfaces.

  • Concept URI token: phyllite

1.2.3.18.4.1 Muscovite-chlorite phyllite

  • Child of: phyllite

  • A phyllite comprising a muscovite-chlorite groundmass.

  • Concept URI token: muscovite-chlorite-phyllite

1.2.3.18.4.1.1 Calcite-bearing muscovite-chlorite phyllite

  • Child of: muscovite-chlorite-phyllite

  • A phyllite comprising a muscovite-chlorite groundmass containing calcite crystals.

  • Concept URI token: calcite-bearing-muscovite-chlorite-phyllite

1.2.3.18.4.2 Quartz phyllite

  • Child of: phyllite

  • A quartz-rich phyllite. May grade into quartzite.

  • Concept URI token: quartz-phyllite

1.2.3.18.5 slate

  • Child of: foliated-metamorphic-rock very-low-to-low-grade-metamorphic-rock

  • An ultrafine- or very fine-grained rock displaying strong slaty cleavage and hence can be split into slabs and thin plates. Most slate was formed from shale. Slate is usually of very low to low metamorphic grade conditions. A fine-grained metamorphic rock that breaks into thin slabs or sheets.

  • Concept URI token: slate

1.2.3.18.5.1 Pyritic slate

  • Child of: slate

  • A slate containing pyrite.

  • Concept URI token: pyritic-slate

1.2.3.18.6 Spilite

  • Child of: very-low-to-low-grade-metamorphic-rock

  • An altered basic to intermediate, volcanic or subvolcanic rock in which the feldspar is partially or completely composed of albite and is typically accompanied by chlorite, calcite, quartz, epidote, prehnite, or other low-temperature hydrous crystallisation products.

  • Concept URI token: spilite

1.2.4 Meteorite and other extra-terrestrial rock and sediment

  • Child of: rock

  • Includes meteorites, Lunar rock and sediment, and rock and sediment from other extraterrestrial bodies.

  • Alternate labels: Meteorite and lunar and other extra-terrestrial rock and sediment

  • Concept URI token: meteorite-and-other-extra-terrestrial-rock-and-sediment

1.2.4.1 Lunar fragmental rock and sediment

  • Child of: meteorite-and-other-extra-terrestrial-rock-and-sediment

  • Lunar rock and soils composed of fragments of older rocks.

  • Concept URI token: lunar-fragmental-rock-and-sediment

1.2.4.1.1 Lunar breccia

  • Child of: lunar-fragmental-rock-and-sediment

  • Lunar rocks composed of sharp angular fragments of older rocks, often including reworked fragments of previous lunar breccias.

  • Concept URI token: lunar-breccia

1.2.4.1.1.1 Feldspathic breccia

  • Child of: lunar-breccia

  • a breccia of primarily feldspathic lithologies

  • Concept URI token: feldspathic-breccia

1.2.4.1.2 Lunar regolith

  • Child of: lunar-fragmental-rock-and-sediment

  • Lunar soil.

  • Concept URI token: lunar-regolith

1.2.4.1.2.1 Impact regolith

  • Child of: lunar-regolith multiple-impact-impactite

  • Unconsolidated clastic impact debris.

  • Concept URI token: impact-regolith

1.2.4.1.2.2 Lunar highland regolith

  • Child of: lunar-regolith

  • A lunar soil from the lunar highlands. Commonly contains felspathic breccias, agglutinates, feldspar framents and occasional mare basalt fragments.

  • Concept URI token: lunar-highland-regolith

1.2.4.1.2.3 Lunar mare regolith

  • Child of: lunar-regolith

  • A lunar soil from the lunar maria (dark basaltic plains.) Mostly derived from High-Ti basalts.

  • Concept URI token: lunar-mare-regolith

1.2.4.2 Lunar igneous rock

  • Child of: meteorite-and-other-extra-terrestrial-rock-and-sediment

  • Primary lunar igneous rocks.

  • Concept URI token: lunar-igneous-rock

1.2.4.2.1 Highland rock

  • Child of: lunar-igneous-rock

  • Older, highland lunar rock.

  • Concept URI token: highland-rock

1.2.4.2.1.1 Lunar granophyric granite

  • Child of: granophyric-granite highland-rock

  • A granite exhibiting granophyric texture. Fragments of this material have been found in lunar breccias and soils.

  • Alternate labels: Lunar granophyre

  • Concept URI token: lunar-granophyric-granite

1.2.4.2.2 Mare basalt

  • Child of: lunar-igneous-rock

  • Basalt from the lunar maria.

  • Concept URI token: mare-basalt

1.2.4.2.2.1 High-Al ophitic basalt

  • Child of: basalt mare-basalt

  • A type of lunar basalt.

  • Concept URI token: high-al-ophitic-basalt

1.2.4.2.2.2 High-Ti basalt

  • Child of: basalt mare-basalt

  • Typical basalts of older mare lavas on the moon. They have 9-13% TiO2.

  • Concept URI token: high-ti-basalt

1.2.4.2.2.3 Low-Ti basalt

  • Child of: basalt mare-basalt

  • Typical basalts of younger mare lavas on the moon. They have 1-5% TiO2.

  • Concept URI token: low-ti-basalt

1.2.4.2.2.4 Orange vitric ash

  • Child of: mare-basalt vitric-ash

  • A lunar soil consisting of orange glass spheres, some partially devitrified fron quenched fire fountain droplents of erupting mare Ti- rich basalt, dated at 3.48Ga. The outer surfaces of the spheres are commonaly coated with ZnS and other volatile minerals.

  • Concept URI token: orange-vitric-ash

1.2.4.3 Meteorite

  • Child of: meteorite-and-other-extra-terrestrial-rock-and-sediment

  • Rock types associated with meteorites and asteroids.Meteorite Mineralogy: An Explicitly Planetological-Planetochemical Perspective

  • Concept URI token: meteorite

1.2.4.3.1 Chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: meteorite

  • A a stony (non-metallic) meteorite that has not been modified, by either melting or differentiation of the parent body. Meteoritical Society Code: Chondrite-uncl

  • Concept URI token: chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.1 Carbonaceous chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: chondrite-meteorite

  • Stony (non-metallic) meteorites that have not been modified due to melting or differentiation of the parent body. Meteoritical Society Code: C

  • Concept URI token: carbonaceous-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.1.1 C chondrite meteorite

  • Concept URI token: c-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.1.2 C1 chondrite meteorite

  • A C chondrite that is petrologic type 2. Meteoritical Society Code: C2

  • Concept URI token: c2-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.1.6 Ungrouped C1/2 chondrite meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.1.12 C4 chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: c-chondrite-meteorite petrologic-type-4-chondrite-meteorite

  • Concept URI token: c4-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.1.22 CB chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: carbonaceous-chondrite-meteorite

  • Bencubbn class carbonaceous chondrite. With metal and pyroxene. Ongoing research suggests this is the product of asteroidal collisions. Meteoritical Society Code: CB

  • Concept URI token: cb-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.1.23 CBa chondrite meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.1.26 CH chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: carbonaceous-chondrite-meteorite

  • Concept URI token: ch-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.1.29 CI chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: carbonaceous-chondrite-meteorite

  • The Ivuna (CI) chemical group of carbonaceous chondrites, distinguished by the complete absence of chondrules and refractory inclusions, and high degree of hydration.

  • Concept URI token: ci-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.1.30 CI1 chondrite meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.1.31 CK chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: carbonaceous-chondrite-meteorite

  • The Karoonda (CK) chemical group of carbonaceous chondrites, distinguished by abundant fine-grained matrix (~75 vol%), mm-sized chondrules that lack igneous rims, relatively few refractory inclusions, and a high degree of oxidation; most CK chondrites have been metamorphosed to type 4 or higher. Meteoritical Society Code: CK

  • Concept URI token: ck-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.1.48 CM chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: carbonaceous-chondrite-meteorite

  • The Mighei (CM) chemical group of carbonaceous chondrites, distinguished by small chondrules and refractory inclusions (0.3 mm), abundant fine-grained matrix (~70 vol%), and abundant hydrated minerals. Meteoritical Society Code: CM

  • Concept URI token: cm-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.1.70 CR chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: carbonaceous-chondrite-meteorite

  • The Renazzo (CR) chemical group of carbonaceous chondrites, distinguished by large, abundant porphyritic chondrules (0.7 mm, 50 vol%), many of which have igneous rims, few refractory inclusions, abundant metal (5-8 vol%), and fine-grained matrix that is commonly hydrated (up to 50 vol%). Meteoritical Society Code: CR

  • Concept URI token: cr-chondrite-meteorite

  • Concept URI token: cr1-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.1.76 CV chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: carbonaceous-chondrite-meteorite

  • The Vigarano (CV) chemical group of carbonaceous chondrites, distinguished by large (mm-sized) chondrules, many of which are surrounded by igneous rims, large refractory inclusions and abundant matrix (40 vol%); CV chondrites may be divided into oxidized and reduced subgroups.

  • Concept URI token: cv-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.3 Chondrite meteorite by petrological type

  • Child of: chondrite-meteorite

  • An alternative classification grouping together all chondrite types by their petrological type rather than origin.

  • Concept URI token: chondrite-meteorite-by-petrological-type

1.2.4.3.1.3.1 Petrologic Type 1 chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: chondrite-meteorite-by-petrological-type

  • Chondrites which have experienced a high degree of aqueous alteration. Most primary minerals have been replaced by secondary phases and chondrules are generally absent.

  • Concept URI token: petrologic-type-1-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.3.21 Petrologic Type 3 chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: chondrite-meteorite-by-petrological-type

  • Chondrites that are characterized by abundant chondrules, low degrees of aqueous alteration, and unequilibrated mineral assemblages. Many of the low-Ca pyroxene grains are monoclinic and exhibit polysynthetic twinning. The type 3 chondrites may be divided into subtypes ranging from 3.00 (least metamorphosed) to 3.9 (nearly metamorphosed to type 4 levels). If primary igneous glass occurs in the chondrules, it belongs to type 3.

  • Concept URI token: petrologic-type-3-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.3.174 Petrologic Type 4 chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: chondrite-meteorite-by-petrological-type

  • Chondrites that are characterized by abundant chondrules, and have been metamorphosed under conditions sufficient to homogenize olivine compositions and recrystallise fine-grained matrix. Some of the low-Ca pyroxene grains may be monoclinic and exhibit polysynthetic twinning. Primary igneous chondrule glass is absent.

  • Concept URI token: petrologic-type-4-chondrite-meteorite

  • Child of: chondrite-meteorite-by-petrological-type

  • Chondrites that have been metamorphosed under conditions sufficient to homogenize olivine and pyroxene, convert all low-Ca pyroxene to orthopyroxene, cause the growth of various secondary minerals, and blur chondrule outlines.

1.2.4.3.1.3.273 Petrologic Type 6 chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: chondrite-meteorite-by-petrological-type

  • Chondrites that have been metamorphosed under conditions sufficient to homogenize all mineral compositions, convert all low-Ca pyroxene to orthopyroxene, coarsen secondary phases such as feldspar to sizes ‰¥50 µm, and obliterate many chondrule outlines; no melting has occurred.

  • Concept URI token: petrologic-type-6-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.4 Enstatite chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: chondrite-meteorite

  • A major class of chondrites that mostly have sub-solar Mg/Si and refractory/Si ratios, oxygen isotope compositions that plot near the terrestrial fractionation line, and highly reduced mineral assemblages (containing little FeO, Si-bearing metal, and sulfides of elements normally considered lithophile.

  • Concept URI token: enstatite-chondrite-meteorite

  • An E chondrite that is anomalous and for which the petrologic type has not been determined. Meteoritical Society Code: E-an

  • Concept URI token: anomalous-e-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.4.9 EH chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: enstatite-chondrite-meteorite

  • The high-iron (EH) chemical group of enstatite chondrites, distinguished by small chondrules (0.2 mm), abundant metal (~10 vol%) that is rich in Si (~3 wt%), and an extremely reduced mineral assemblage including niningerite (MgS) and perryite (Fe-Ni silicide)Meteoritical Society Code: EH

  • Concept URI token: eh-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.4.22 EL chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: enstatite-chondrite-meteorite

  • The low-iron (EL) chemical group of enstatite chondrites, distinguished by moderately large chondrules (0.6 mm), abundant metal (~10 vol%) that is Si-bearing (~1 wt%), and an extremely reduced mineral assemblage containing ferroan alabandite ((Fe,Mn)S)

  • Concept URI token: el-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.5 K chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: chondrite-meteorite

  • A chondrite characterised by large amounts of dusty matrix and oxygen isotope compositions similar to carbonaceous chondrites, highly reduced mineral compositions and high metal abundances (6% to 10% by volume) that are most like enstatite chondrites, and concentrations of refractory lithophile elements that are most like ordinary chondrites. Meteoritical Society Code: K

  • Concept URI token: k-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.5.1 K3 chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: k-chondrite-meteorite petrologic-type-3-chondrite-meteorite

  • Concept URI token: k3-chondrite-meteorite

  • Child of: k-chondrite-meteorite petrologic-type-4-chondrite-meteorite

  • A K chondrite that is petrologic type 4. Meteoritical Society Code: K4

  • Concept URI token: k4-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.6 Ordinary chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: chondrite-meteorite

  • A major class of chondrites, distinguished by sub-solar Mg/Si and refractory/Si ratios, oxygen isotope compositions that plot above the terrestrial fractionation line, and a large volume percentage of chondrules, with only 10-15 vol% fine-grained matrix. Meteoritical Society Code: OC

  • Concept URI token: ordinary-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.6.1 H chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: ordinary-chondrite-meteorite

  • The high-iron (H) chemical group of ordinary chondrites, distinguished by their high siderophile element content, relatively small chondrules (~0.3 mm), and oxygen isotope compositions that are closer to the terrestrial fractionation line than those of other ordinary chondrites. Meteoritical Society Code: H

  • Concept URI token: h-chondrite-meteorite

  • Concept URI token: h-5unk-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.6.73 L chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: ordinary-chondrite-meteorite

  • The low-iron (L) chemical group of ordinary chondrites, distinguished by their relatively low siderophile element content, moderate sized chondrules (~0.7 mm), and oxygen isotope compositions that intermediate between H chondrites and LL chondrites. Parent body is possibly 433 Eros, 8 Flora or the Flora family as a wholeMeteoritical Society Code: L

  • Concept URI token: l-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.6.193 LL chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: ordinary-chondrite-meteorite

  • The low-iron, low metal (LL) chemical group of ordinary chondrites, distinguished by their low siderophile element content, fairly large chondrules (~0.9 mm), and oxygen isotope compositions that are further above the terrestrial fractionation line than those of other ordinary chondrites. Meteoritical Society Code: LL

  • Concept URI token: ll-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.6.270 LL7 chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: ll-chondrite-meteorite

  • An ordinary chondrite from the LL group that is petrologic type 7. Note: Type 7 designates chondrites which have been metamorphosed to nearly the point of melting. Minerals are equilibrated and chondrules are indistinct or absent. This term is not used consistently or widely accepted in the literature. Meteoritical Society Code: LL7

  • Concept URI token: ll7-chondrite-meteorite

  • Concept URI token: ll7-unk-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.1.7 R chondrite meteorite

  • Child of: chondrite-meteorite

  • A chondrite, different from ordinary chondrite in having a more dusty matrix (about 50% of the rock), more oxidized, containing little metallic Fe-Ni and with a higher 17O ratio. Most of the metal is in the form of sulfides. They appear to come from an asteroid regolith. Meteoritical Society Code: R

  • Concept URI token: r-chondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.2 Differentiated achondrite meteorite

  • Child of: meteorite

  • A stony meteorite that lacks chondrules and originated on a differentiated parent body.

  • Concept URI token: differentiated-achondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.2.1 Asteroidal achondrite meteorite

  • Child of: differentiated-achondrite-meteorite

  • A stony meteorite that lacks chondrules and originated on an asteroid.

  • Concept URI token: asteroidal-achondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.2.1.1 Angrite meteorite

  • Child of: asteroidal-achondrite-meteorite

  • Angrites, named after the Angra dos Reis, Brazil, fall of 1869, are a relatively rare type of basaltic achondrite with low alkali contents, high Ca/Al ratios, and a distinctive mineral assemblage, generally including Al-Ca-Ti-rich pyroxene, Ca-rich plagioclase, and Ca-rich olivine that may have exsolved the mineral kirschsteinite. Meteoritical Society Code: Angrite

  • Concept URI token: angrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.2.1.2 Aubrite meteorite

  • Child of: asteroidal-achondrite-meteorite

  • Aubrites, named after the Aubres, France, fall of 1836, are enstatite achondrites. Most are breccias (Shallowater being a notable exception) containing igneous and impact-melted clasts. Like enstatite chondrites, aubrites have highly reduced mineralogy, but they probably do not come from the same parent asteroid as either EH or EL chondrites. Meteoritical Society Code: Aubrite

  • Concept URI token: aubrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.2.1.3 Anomalous aubrite meteorite

  • Child of: aubrite-meteorite

  • An aubrite with certain anomalous properties. Meteoritical Society Code: Aubrite-an

  • Concept URI token: anomalous-aubrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.2.1.4 Brachinite meteorite

  • Child of: asteroidal-achondrite-meteorite primitive-achondrite-meteorite

  • Almost entirely made from olivine, the parent body might be the Nenetta Asteroid (289 Nenetta)Meteoritical Society Code: Brachinite

  • Concept URI token: brachinite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.2.1.5 HED achondrite meteorite

  • Child of: asteroidal-achondrite-meteorite

  • A group of meteorites believed to have come from asteroid 4 Vesta.

  • Concept URI token: hed-achondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.2.1.6 Diogenite meteorite

  • Child of: hed-achondrite-meteorite

  • Diogenites are an abundant type of achondrite, linked by geochemical traits such as oxygen isotopic ratios and certain elemental ratios, of which Fe/Mn is the most widely cited. The dominant mineral in diogenites is orthopyroxene. The diogenites are strongly linked with two other achondrite groups: eucrites and howardites; the three groups are collectively known as HED meteorites and may come from asteroid 4 Vesta. Meteoritical Society Code: Diogenite

  • Concept URI token: diogenite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.2.1.7 Anomalous diogenite meteorite

  • Child of: diogenite-meteorite

  • A diogenite which has anomalous properties. Meteoritical Society Code: Diogenite-an

  • Concept URI token: anomalous-diogenite-meteorite

  • Concept URI token: dunitic-diogenite-meteorite

  • A diogenite composed of 40-90 vol% olivine.

  • Concept URI token: harzburgitic-diogenite-meteorite

  • A pyroxene-rich diogenite with >10% vol% plagioclase.

  • Concept URI token: noritic-diogenite-meteorite

  • Child of: diogenite-meteorite

  • A diogenite which is a polymict breccia. Meteoritical Society Code: Diogenite-pm

  • Concept URI token: polymict-breccia-diogenite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.2.1.14 Eucrite meteorite

  • Child of: hed-achondrite-meteorite

  • Eucrites are the most abundant type of basaltic achondrite, linked by geochemical traits such as oxygen isotopic ratios and certain elemental ratios, of which Fe/Mn is the most widely cited. The main minerals in eucrites are Fe-rich pyroxene and Na-poor plagioclase. The eucrites are strongly linked with the diogenites and howardites; the three groups are collectively known as HED meteorites and may come from asteroid 4 Vesta.

  • Concept URI token: eucrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.2.1.15 Anomalous eucrite meteorite

  • An anomalous Eucrite. Meteoritical Society Code: Eucrite-an

  • Concept URI token: anomalous-eucrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.2.1.23 Howardite meteorite

  • Child of: hed-achondrite-meteorite

  • Howardites are an abundant group of polymict-breccia achondrites that appear to represent mixtures of eucrites + diogenites (these three linked groups are collectively known as HED meteorites and may come from asteroid 4 Vesta). The main minerals in howardites are pyroxene (largely orthopyroxene) and Na-poor plagioclase. A minority of howardites are rich in solar-wind noble gases and thus inferred to be regolith brecciasMeteoritical Society Code: Howardite

  • Concept URI token: howardite-meteorite

  • Concept URI token: anomalous-howardite-meteorite
