1.2.4.3.2.6 Pallasite meteorite

  • Child of: differentiated-achondrite-meteorite stony-iron-meteorite

  • A stony-iron meteorite composed essentially of large single glassy crystals of olivine embedded in a network of nickel-iron. Pallasites are believed to have been formed at the interface of the stony mantle and metal core of a layered planetoid. Meteoritical Society Code: Pallasite

  • Concept URI token: pallasite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.2.6.1 PES pallasite meteorite

  • Child of: pallasite-meteorite

  • A grouplet named for a pallasite that was found near Eagle Station, Kentucky, in 1880. They all contain highly fragmented olivines, intermixed with small, irregular olivine splinters, in a nickel-iron matrix. The olivine is extraordinarily iron-rich, and the metal consists of higher nickel content than any other pallasites. Meteoritical Society Code: Pallasite, PES

  • Concept URI token: pes-pallasite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.2.6.2 PMG pallasite meteorite

  • Child of: pallasite-meteorite

  • A pallasite belonging to the main chemical group. Meteoritical Society Code: Pallasite, PMG

  • Concept URI token: pmg-pallasite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.2.6.3 Anomalous PMG pallasite meteorite

  • Child of: pmg-pallasite-meteorite

  • A PMG pallasite with anomalous properties. Meteoritical Society Code: Pallasite, PMG-an

  • Concept URI token: anomalous-pmg-pallasite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.2.6.4 Pyroxene pallasite meteorite

  • Child of: pallasite-meteorite

  • A pallasite containing pyroxene as inclusions in the olivine crystals, as large grains in the nickel-iron matrix and as grains bordering the olivines.

  • Concept URI token: pyroxene-pallasite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.2.6.5 Ungrouped pallasite meteorite

  • Child of: pallasite-meteorite

  • A pallasite that is neither a member of the main group nor the Eagle Station grouplet, and is therefore ungrouped. Meteoritical Society Code: Pallasite, ungrouped

  • Concept URI token: ungrouped-pallasite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.2.7 Ungrouped Achondrite meteorite

  • Child of: differentiated-achondrite-meteorite

  • A stony meteorite that lacks chondrules and originated on a differentiated parent body, which has been well-enough characterized to determine that it does not fit into any of the established groups. Meteoritical Society Code: Achondrite-ung

  • Concept URI token: ungrouped-achondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.2.8 Ungrouped enstatite-rich achondrite meteorite

  • Child of: differentiated-achondrite-meteorite

  • An enstatite-rich achondrite that is ungrouped. Meteoritical Society Code: Enst achon-ung

  • Concept URI token: ungrouped-enstatite-rich-achondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.3 Iron meteorite

  • Child of: meteorite

  • Meteorites composed primarily of meteoritic iron - this is an alternative classification category. Meteoritical Society Code: Iron

  • Concept URI token: iron-meteorite

1.2.4.3.3.1 Ataxite

  • Child of: iron-meteorite

  • Ataxites are a structural class of iron meteorites with a high nickel content and show no Widmanstatten patterns upon etching. Ataxites usually contain over 18% nickel.

  • Concept URI token: ataxite

1.2.4.3.3.2 catarinite

  • Child of: iron-meteorite

  • An obsolete term for an iron meteorite remarkable for a high proportion of nickel.

  • Concept URI token: catarinite

1.2.4.3.3.3 Iron group meteorite

  • Child of: differentiated-achondrite-meteorite iron-meteorite

  • A meteorite that is dominantly composed of Fe-Ni metal and that crystallised from a melt.

  • Concept URI token: iron-group-meteorite

1.2.4.3.3.3.1 IC iron meteorite

  • Child of: iron-group-meteorite magmatic-iron-meteorite

  • An iron group meteorite of chemical group IC. Meteoritical Society Code: Iron, IC

  • Concept URI token: ic-iron-meteorite

1.2.4.3.4 Primitive achondrite meteorite

  • Child of: meteorite

  • A meteorite that has lost its chondritic texture due to heating and partial melting, but still has nearly chondritic composition. Meteoritical Society Code: Achondrite-prim

  • Concept URI token: primitive-achondrite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.4.1 Acapulcoite meteorite

  • Child of: primitive-achondrite-meteorite

  • Acapulcoites, named after the Acapulco, Mexico, fall of 1913, and lodranites, named after the Lodran, Pakistan, fall of 1868, are closely related, equigranular meteorites; acapulcoites are finer grained than lodranites and contain rare, relict chondrules, and there are transitional meteorites between the two types (e.g., EET 84302, GRA 95209). Mineral assemblages are similar to, but distinct from those of ordinary chondrites. Meteoritical Society Code: Acapulcoite

  • Concept URI token: acapulcoite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.4.1.1 Acapulcoite-lodranite meteorite

  • Child of: acapulcoite-meteorite lodranite-meteorite

  • A transitional type between acapulcoite and lodranite. Meteoritical Society Code: Acapulcoite/lodranite

  • Concept URI token: acapulcoite-lodranite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.4.2 Brachinite meteorite

  • Child of: asteroidal-achondrite-meteorite primitive-achondrite-meteorite

  • Almost entirely made from olivine, the parent body might be the Nenetta Asteroid (289 Nenetta)Meteoritical Society Code: Brachinite

  • Concept URI token: brachinite-meteorite

  • Concept URI token: anomalous-iab-slm-iron-meteorite

1.2.4.3.4.3.10 Possible IAB complex iron meteorite

  • Child of: iab-complex-iron-meteorite

  • An iron meteorite that may belong to the IAB complex. Meteoritical Society Code: Iron, IAB?

  • Concept URI token: possible-iab-complex-iron-meteorite

1.2.4.3.4.3.11 Ungrouped IAB iron meteorite

  • Child of: iab-complex-iron-meteorite

  • An iron meteorite belonging to the IAB complex that does not fit into the known subgroups. Meteoritical Society Code: Iron, IAB-ung

  • Concept URI token: ungrouped-iab-iron-meteorite

1.2.4.3.4.4 IIICD iron meteorite

  • Child of: primitive-achondrite-meteorite primitive-iron-meteorite

  • Composed dominantly of meteoritic iron and silicate inclusions.

  • Concept URI token: iiicd-iron-meteorite

1.2.4.3.4.5 Lodranite meteorite

  • Child of: primitive-achondrite-meteorite

  • Lodranites can be described as chondrites that were heated to the point where FeNi and FeS reach an eutectic point. At this point partial melting occurred and some of the metal and silica melt was removed. Meteoritical Society Code: Lodranite

  • Concept URI token: lodranite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.4.5.1 Acapulcoite-lodranite meteorite

  • Child of: acapulcoite-meteorite lodranite-meteorite

  • A transitional type between acapulcoite and lodranite. Meteoritical Society Code: Acapulcoite/lodranite

  • Concept URI token: acapulcoite-lodranite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.4.5.2 Lodranite-an meteorite

  • Child of: lodranite-meteorite

  • An lodranite that has anomalous properties. Meteoritical Society Code: Lodranite-an

  • Concept URI token: lodranite-an-meteorite

1.2.4.3.4.6 Ureilite meteorite

  • Child of: primitive-achondrite-meteorite

  • Ureilites, named after the Novo-Urei, Russia, fall of 1886, are ultramafic achondrites that contain interstitial carbon as graphite or diamond. The majority consist of olivine + uninverted pigeonite. In a few, the pyroxene is augite and/or orthopyroxene instead. In addition, about 10% of ureilites are polymict breccias, containing a few percent of feldspathic material in addition to typical ureilitic components. Meteoritical Society Code: Ureilite

  • Concept URI token: ureilite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.4.6.1 Anomalous ureilite meteorite

  • Child of: ureilite-meteorite

  • An achondrite belonging to the ureilite group with anomalous properties. Meteoritical Society Code: Ureilite-an

  • Concept URI token: anomalous-ureilite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.4.6.2 Polymict ureilite meteorite

  • Child of: ureilite-meteorite

  • A polymict ureilite meteorite. Meteoritical Society Code: Ureilite- pmict

  • Concept URI token: polymict-ureilite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.4.7 Winonaite meteorite

  • Child of: primitive-achondrite-meteorite

  • Winonaites, named after the Winona, Arizona, find of 1928, are equigranular rocks, some of which may contain relict chondrules, that have mineralogy and composition that are similar to chondrites.The mineral assemblage is more reduced than that of H chondrites. Winonaites are related to the silicate inclusions found in IAB complex irons. Meteoritical Society Code: Winonaite

  • Concept URI token: winonaite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.5 Relict meteorite

  • Child of: meteorite

  • A highly altered object that is likely to have a meteoritic origin. These are dominantly (>95%) composed of secondary minerals formed from alteration after it landed. Meteoritical Society Code: Relict meteorite

  • Concept URI token: relict-meteorite

1.2.4.3.5.1 Relict H meteorite

  • Child of: relict-meteorite

  • A relict meteorite that originated as an H group ordinary chondrite. Meteoritical Society Code: Relict H

  • Concept URI token: relict-h-meteorite

1.2.4.3.5.2 Relict iron meteorite

  • Child of: relict-meteorite

  • A relict meteorite that originated as an iron meteorite. Meteoritical Society Code: Relict iron

  • Concept URI token: relict-iron-meteorite

1.2.4.3.5.3 Relict OC meteorite

  • Child of: relict-meteorite

  • A relict meteorite that originated as an ordinary chondrite. Meteoritical Society Code: Relict OC

  • Concept URI token: relict-oc-meteorite

1.2.4.3.5.4 Relict ureilite meteorite

  • Child of: relict-meteorite

  • A relict meteorite that originated as a ureilite. Meteoritical Society Code: Relict ureilite

  • Concept URI token: relict-ureilite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.6 Stony-iron meteorite

  • Child of: meteorite

  • A Stony-iron meteorite.

  • Concept URI token: stony-iron-meteorite

1.2.4.3.6.1 Pallasite meteorite

  • Child of: differentiated-achondrite-meteorite stony-iron-meteorite

  • A stony-iron meteorite composed essentially of large single glassy crystals of olivine embedded in a network of nickel-iron. Pallasites are believed to have been formed at the interface of the stony mantle and metal core of a layered planetoid. Meteoritical Society Code: Pallasite

  • Concept URI token: pallasite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.6.1.1 PES pallasite meteorite

  • Child of: pallasite-meteorite

  • A grouplet named for a pallasite that was found near Eagle Station, Kentucky, in 1880. They all contain highly fragmented olivines, intermixed with small, irregular olivine splinters, in a nickel-iron matrix. The olivine is extraordinarily iron-rich, and the metal consists of higher nickel content than any other pallasites. Meteoritical Society Code: Pallasite, PES

  • Concept URI token: pes-pallasite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.6.1.2 PMG pallasite meteorite

  • Child of: pallasite-meteorite

  • A pallasite belonging to the main chemical group. Meteoritical Society Code: Pallasite, PMG

  • Concept URI token: pmg-pallasite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.6.1.3 Anomalous PMG pallasite meteorite

  • Child of: pmg-pallasite-meteorite

  • A PMG pallasite with anomalous properties. Meteoritical Society Code: Pallasite, PMG-an

  • Concept URI token: anomalous-pmg-pallasite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.6.1.4 Pyroxene pallasite meteorite

  • Child of: pallasite-meteorite

  • A pallasite containing pyroxene as inclusions in the olivine crystals, as large grains in the nickel-iron matrix and as grains bordering the olivines.

  • Concept URI token: pyroxene-pallasite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.6.1.5 Ungrouped pallasite meteorite

  • Child of: pallasite-meteorite

  • A pallasite that is neither a member of the main group nor the Eagle Station grouplet, and is therefore ungrouped. Meteoritical Society Code: Pallasite, ungrouped

  • Concept URI token: ungrouped-pallasite-meteorite

1.2.4.3.7 Unclassified stony meteorite

  • Child of: meteorite

  • A stony meteorite that has not yet been classified. Meteoritical Society Code: Stone-uncl

  • Concept URI token: unclassified-stony-meteorite

1.2.5 Ore

  • Child of: rock

  • A general term for a rock/mineral containing an economic quantity of extractable metals or other elements.

  • Concept URI token: ore

1.2.5.1 Aluminium ore

  • Child of: ore

  • An ore of the metal aluminium (aluminum). Most frequently this is bauxite.

  • Alternate labels: Aluminum ore

  • Concept URI token: aluminium-ore

1.2.5.2 Arsenic ore

  • Child of: ore

  • An ore containing commercially workable quantities of arsenic.

  • Concept URI token: arsenic-ore

1.2.5.3 Bismuth ore

  • Child of: ore

  • An ore of bismuth.

  • Concept URI token: bismuth-ore

1.2.5.4 Cadmium ore

  • Child of: ore

  • An ore of cadmium. This is frequently a by-product of the production of other metals, in particular zinc, so cadmium ore may also be zinc ore.

  • Concept URI token: cadmium-ore

1.2.5.5 Caesium ore

  • Child of: ore

  • An ore of caesium. The primary ore mineral for caesium is pollucite.

  • Concept URI token: caesium-ore

1.2.5.6 Chromium ore

  • Child of: ore

  • An ore of the metal chromium, usually the principal ore mineral is chromite.

  • Concept URI token: chromium-ore

1.2.5.7 Cobalt ore

  • Child of: ore

  • An ore of cobalt.

  • Concept URI token: cobalt-ore

1.2.5.8 Copper ore

  • Child of: ore

  • An undifferentiated copper ore.

  • Concept URI token: copper-ore

1.2.5.8.1 Copper carbonate ore

  • Child of: copper-ore

  • A copper ore where the primary copper ore mineral is carbonate.

  • Concept URI token: copper-carbonate-ore

1.2.5.8.2 Copper oxide ore

  • Child of: copper-ore

  • A copper ore where the primary copper ore minerals are oxides.

  • Concept URI token: copper-oxide-ore

1.2.5.8.3 Copper sulfide ore

  • Child of: copper-ore

  • A copper ore where the primary copper ore minerals are sulfides.

  • Concept URI token: copper-sulfide-ore

1.2.5.9 Gold ore

  • Child of: ore

  • An ore of gold, often very low grade gold ore can be commercially viable to process.

  • Concept URI token: gold-ore

1.2.5.10 Iron ore

  • Child of: ore

  • Ferruginous rock containing one or more minerals from which metallic iron may be profitably extracted. The most common iron ores are largely the oxides: hematite Fe2O3; goethite alpha -FeO(OH); magnetite Fe3O4; and siderite FeCO3.

  • Concept URI token: iron-ore

1.2.5.10.1 Iron oxide ore

  • Child of: iron-ore

  • An iron ore where the primary ore minerals are iron oxides.

  • Concept URI token: iron-oxide-ore

1.2.5.10.2 Iron sulfide ore

  • Child of: iron-ore

  • An iron ore where the primary ore minerals are iron sulfides.

  • Concept URI token: iron-sulfide-ore

1.2.5.11 Lead ore

  • Child of: ore

  • An ore of lead. Usually galena.

  • Concept URI token: lead-ore

1.2.5.12 Lithium ore

  • Child of: ore

  • An ore of the metal lithium. Two subvarieties depending on whether the ore is a salt (halide/carbonate) or silicate in nature.

  • Concept URI token: lithium-ore

1.2.5.12.1 Lithium salt ore

  • Child of: lithium-ore

  • A lithium ore which is either a halide, sulphate or carbonate.

  • Concept URI token: lithium-salt-ore

1.2.5.12.2 Lithium silicate ore

  • Child of: lithium-ore

  • An ore of lithium where the primary ore minerals are silicate minerals.

  • Concept URI token: lithium-silicate-ore

1.2.5.13 Mercury ore

  • Child of: ore

  • An ore of the metal mercury, most often the ore mineral is cinnabar although native mercury and calomel may be important components.

  • Concept URI token: mercury-ore

1.2.5.14 Nickel ore

  • Child of: ore

  • Rocks rich in extractable nickel minerals.

  • Concept URI token: nickel-ore

1.2.5.14.1 Nickel laterite

  • Child of: nickel-ore

  • Lateritic rocks with nickel present in silicates and oxides

  • Concept URI token: nickel-laterite

1.2.5.14.2 Nickel sulfide ore

  • Child of: nickel-ore

  • Ores with economic nickel in sulphide minerals (most commonly pentlandite).

  • Concept URI token: nickel-sulfide-ore

1.2.5.15 Silver ore

  • Child of: ore

  • A generic term for ore containing commercial quantities of silver. This may be in the form of native silver, silver sulphides or chlorides, or it may even be silver-rich galena or other minerals containing a workable percentage of silver.

  • Concept URI token: silver-ore

1.2.5.16 Sulfide ore

  • Child of: ore

  • An ore composed of mixed or undifferentiated sulfide minerals.

  • Alternate labels: Massive sulfide ore, Massive sulfides, Massive sulphide ore, Massive sulphides, Sulfides, massive, Sulphide ore, Sulphides, massive,

  • Concept URI token: sulfide-ore

1.2.5.17 Tin ore

  • Child of: ore

  • A generic term for an ore of tin.

  • Concept URI token: tin-ore

1.2.6 Sedimentary rock and sediment

  • Child of: rock

  • Sediments are the collective names for minerals and/or organic detritus that have settled in place, and sedimentary rocks are the lithified equivalents of these.

  • Concept URI token: sedimentary-rock-and-sediment

1.2.6.1 Fossil Bed

  • Child of: sedimentary-rock-and-sediment

  • A stratigraphic layer dominated by fossilised remains, such as bones, teeth, coprolites, and other organic remains.

  • Alternate labels: Bone Bed

  • Concept URI token: fossil-bed

1.2.6.2 Sediment

  • Child of: sedimentary-rock-and-sediment

  • Unconsolidated sediments. Solid fragmental material that originates from weathering of rocks and is transported or deposited by air, water, or ice, or that accumulates by other natural agents, such as chemical precipitation from solution or secretion by organisms, and that forms in layers on the Earth’s surface at ordinary temperatures in a loose, unconsolidated form; e.g., sand, gravel, silt, mud, alluvium.

  • Alternate labels: Grains, Miscellaneous unconsolidated sediments, Poor consolidated sediments, Quaternary sediment, Quaternary sediments, Tertiary sediment, Tertiary sediments, Unconsolidated sediments, unclassified sediment,

  • Concept URI token: sediment

1.2.6.2.1 Carbonate sediment

  • Child of: sediment

  • Sediments where the carbonate component forms more than 50% of the sediment.

  • Concept URI token: carbonate-sediment

1.2.6.2.1.1 Dolomite-sediment

  • Child of: carbonate-sediment

  • Unconsolidated dolomite-sediment, dolostone and magnesite where the dominant carboante mineral is dolomite, ankerite and/or magnesite.

  • Concept URI token: dolomite-sediment

1.2.6.2.1.1.1 Ankerite-gravel

  • Child of: dolomite-sediment phosphate-gravel

  • a dolomite-sediment with over 25% of clasts larger than 2mm and composition dominantey ankerite

  • Concept URI token: ankerite-gravel

1.2.6.2.1.1.2 Ankerite-mud

  • Child of: dolomite-sediment mud

  • a dolomite-sediment with over 75% of the clasts smaller than 32µm, and composition dominantey ankerite.

  • Concept URI token: ankerite-mud

1.2.6.2.1.1.3 Ankerite-sand

  • Child of: dolomite-sediment sand

  • a dolomite-sediment with clasts predominantly 32µm to 2mm, with less than 75% of the clasts smaller than 32µm and less than 25% larger than 2mm, and composition dominantey ankerite.

  • Concept URI token: ankerite-sand

1.2.6.2.1.1.4 Dolomite-gravel

  • Child of: dolomite-sediment gravel

  • a dolomite-sediment with over 25% of clasts larger than 2mm and composition dominantey dolomite

  • Concept URI token: dolomite-gravel

1.2.6.2.1.1.5 Dolomite-mud

  • Child of: dolomite-sediment mud

  • a dolomite-sediment with over 75% of the clasts smaller than 32µm, and composition dominantey dolomite.

  • Concept URI token: dolomite-mud

1.2.6.2.1.1.6 Dolomite-sand

  • Child of: dolomite-sediment sand

  • a dolomite-sediment with clasts predominantly 32µm to 2mm, with less than 75% of the clasts smaller than 32µm and less than 25% larger than 2mm, and composition dominantey dolomite.

  • Concept URI token: dolomite-sand

1.2.6.2.1.1.7 Impure dolomite-sediment

  • Child of: dolomite-sediment

  • Carbonate sediment in with between 50 and 90 percent of the constituents are composed of one (or more) of the carbonate minerals in particles of intrabasinal origin, and the ratio of magnesium carbonate to calcite (plus aragonite) greater than 1 to 1.

  • Alternate labels: dolomitic marl

  • Concept URI token: impure-dolomite-sediment

1.2.6.2.1.1.8 Pure dolomite-sediment

  • Child of: dolomite-sediment

  • Carbonate sediment in with greater than 90 percent of the constituents are composed of one (or more) of the carbonate minerals in particles of intrabasinal origin, and a ratio of magnesium carbonate to calcite (plus aragonite) greater than 1 to 1.

  • Concept URI token: pure-dolomite-sediment

1.2.6.2.1.2 Impure carbonate sediment

  • Child of: carbonate-sediment

  • Carbonate sediment in with between 50 and 90 percent of the constituents are composed of one (or more) of the carbonate minerals in particles of intrabasinal origin.

  • Concept URI token: impure-carbonate-sediment

1.2.6.2.1.3 Lime-sediment

  • Child of: carbonate-sediment

  • Unconsolidated carbonate sediment and sedimentary rock where the dominant carboante mineral is calcite, aragonite and/or vaterite.

  • Concept URI token: lime-sediment

1.2.6.2.1.3.1 Crinoid-lime-sediment

  • Child of: lime-sediment

  • A lime-sediment composed almost entirely of crinoid fragoments.

  • Concept URI token: crinoid-lime-sediment

1.2.6.2.1.3.2 Impure lime-sediment

  • Child of: lime-sediment

  • Carbonate sediment in which between 50 and 90 percent of the constituents are composed of one (or more) of the carbonate minerals in particles of intrabasinal origin, and a calcite (plus aragonite) to dolomite ratio greater than 1 to 1.

  • Concept URI token: impure-lime-sediment

1.2.6.2.1.3.3 Lime-gravel

  • Child of: gravel lime-sediment

  • A lime-sediment with over 25% of the clasts larger than 2mm.

  • Concept URI token: lime-gravel

1.2.6.2.1.3.4 Aragonite-gravel

  • Child of: lime-gravel

  • A lime-gravel where the dominant calcium carbonate is aragonite

  • Concept URI token: aragonite-gravel

1.2.6.2.1.3.5 Calcite-gravel

  • Child of: lime-gravel

  • A lime-gravel where the dominant calcium carbonate is calcite

  • Concept URI token: calcite-gravel

1.2.6.2.1.3.6 Lime-mud

  • Child of: lime-sediment mud

  • A lime-sediment containing more than 50% siliciclastic fragments, of which at least 75% should be less than 32µm.

  • Concept URI token: lime-mud

1.2.6.2.1.3.7 Aragonite-mud

  • Child of: lime-mud

  • A lime-mud where the dominant calcium carbonate is aragonite

  • Concept URI token: aragonite-mud

1.2.6.2.1.3.8 Calcite-mud

  • Child of: lime-mud

  • A lime-mud where the dominant calcium carbonate is calcite

  • Concept URI token: calcite-mud

1.2.6.2.1.3.9 Lime ooze

  • Child of: lime-mud ooze

  • An ooze comprised primarily of calcium carbonate.

  • Alternate labels: calcareous ooze

  • Concept URI token: lime-ooze

1.2.6.2.1.3.10 Marl

  • Child of: lime-mud

  • A calcium-carbonate rich mud containing variable amounts of clays and silt. This may be defined either as calcite-mud or lime-rich silicate-mud depending on the proportion of carbonate to clay.

  • Alternate labels: Bog lime, carbonate rich mud,

  • Concept URI token: marl

1.2.6.2.1.3.11 Sapropelic lime-mud

  • Child of: lime-mud

  • A lime-mud with up to 3% sapropelic organic matter. Compare with sapropel which contains over 3%.

  • Concept URI token: sapropelic-lime-mud

1.2.6.2.1.3.12 Lime-sand

  • Child of: lime-sediment sand

  • A lime-sediment with clasts predominantly in the 32µm to 2mm range, with less than 75% of the clasts smaller than 32µm and less than 25% of the clasts larger than 2mm.

  • Concept URI token: lime-sand

1.2.6.2.1.3.13 Aragonite-sand

  • Child of: lime-sand

  • A lime-sand where the dominant calcium carbonate is aragonite

  • Concept URI token: aragonite-sand

1.2.6.2.1.3.14 Calcite-sand

  • Child of: lime-sand

  • A lime-sand where the dominant calcium carbonate is calcite

  • Concept URI token: calcite-sand

1.2.6.2.1.3.15 Ooid-lime-sand

  • Child of: lime-sand

  • A lime-sand composed almost entirely of ooids.

  • Concept URI token: ooid-lime-sand

1.2.6.2.1.3.16 Pure lime-sediment

  • Child of: lime-sediment

  • Carbonate sediment in which greater than 90 percent of the constituents are composed of one (or more) of the carbonate minerals in particles of intrabasinal origin, and a calcite (plus aragonite) to dolomite ratio greater than 1 to 1.

  • Concept URI token: pure-lime-sediment

1.2.6.2.1.3.17 Shell-lime-sediment

  • Child of: lime-sediment

  • A lime-sediment composed almost entirely of shell fragoments.

  • Concept URI token: shell-lime-sediment

1.2.6.2.1.4 Pure carbonate sediment

  • Child of: carbonate-sediment

  • Carbonate sediment in with greater than 90 percent of the constituents are composed of one (or more) of the carbonate minerals in particles of intrabasinal origin.

  • Concept URI token: pure-carbonate-sediment

1.2.6.2.2 Clastic-sediment

  • Child of: sediment

    1. Clastic sediments where the composition is unknown.ii. Sediment in which at least 50 percent of the constituent particles were derived from erosion, weathering, or mass-wasting of pre-existing earth materials, and transported to the place of deposition by mechanical agents such as water, wind, ice and gravity.

  • Alternate labels: Clast

  • Concept URI token: clastic-sediment

1.2.6.2.2.1 Diamicton

  • Child of: clastic-sediment

  • A poorly-sorted clastic-sediment containing a wide range of clast sizes.

  • Concept URI token: diamicton

1.2.6.2.2.1.1 Silicate-diamicton

  • Child of: diamicton siliciclastic-sediment

  • A poorly-sorted siliclastic-sediment containing a wide range of clast sizes.

  • Concept URI token: silicate-diamicton

1.2.6.2.2.1.2 Till

  • Child of: diamicton glacigenic-deposit

  • Unsorted clastic sediment, often full of boulders, sand, silt and clay, formed from the ground moraine material of glaciers. A stiff, hard, and usually unstratified clay or Glacial drift that contains boulders scattered through it. Also called boulder clay; hardpan; drift clay.

  • Alternate labels: Boulder clay, glacial till, ice-laid drift,

  • Concept URI token: till

1.2.6.2.2.2 Gravel

  • Child of: clastic-sediment

  • A gravel-grade clastic-sediment.

  • Alternate labels: Gravel-grade-sediment, lag,

  • Concept URI token: gravel

1.2.6.2.2.2.1 Boulders

  • Child of: gravel

  • A boulder-grade clastic-sediment.

  • Alternate labels: Boulder, Boulder-grade-sediment,

  • Concept URI token: boulders

1.2.6.2.2.2.2 Cobbles

  • Child of: gravel

  • A cobble-grade clastic-sediment.

  • Alternate labels: Cobble-grade-sediment

  • Concept URI token: cobbles

1.2.6.2.2.2.3 Dolomite-gravel

  • Child of: dolomite-sediment gravel

  • a dolomite-sediment with over 25% of clasts larger than 2mm and composition dominantey dolomite

  • Concept URI token: dolomite-gravel

1.2.6.2.2.2.4 Granules

  • Concept URI token: granules

1.2.6.2.2.2.5 Iron-gravel

1.2.6.2.2.2.15 Pebbles

  • Concept URI token: pebbles

1.2.6.2.2.2.16 Phosphate-gravel

1.2.6.2.2.2.17 Ankerite-gravel

1.2.6.2.2.2.18 Sandy gravel

  • Child of: gravel

  • A gravel containing sand

  • Concept URI token: sandy-gravel

1.2.6.2.2.2.19 Silicate-gravel

  • Child of: gravel siliciclastic-sediment

  • A sediment made up of at least 50% clastic fragments derived from pre-existing siliceous rocks, where at least 25% of the fragments are coarser than 2mm.

  • Concept URI token: silicate-gravel

1.2.6.2.2.2.20 Flint-gravel

  • Child of: silicate-gravel

  • A silicate-gravel composted almost entirely of flint.

  • Concept URI token: flint-gravel

1.2.6.2.2.3 Mud

  • Child of: clastic-sediment

  • A mud-grade clastic-sediment or a liquid or semi-liquid mixture of water and soil. It comprises mostly clay and silt.

  • Alternate labels: Mud-grade-sediment

  • Concept URI token: mud

1.2.6.2.2.3.1 Ankerite-mud

  • Child of: dolomite-sediment mud

  • a dolomite-sediment with over 75% of the clasts smaller than 32µm, and composition dominantey ankerite.

  • Concept URI token: ankerite-mud

1.2.6.2.2.3.2 Clay

  • Child of: mud

  • A clay-grade clastic-sediment.Clay is a fine-grained natural sediment, soil or rock component that comprises mostly one or more clay minerals or clays (hydrous phyllosilicates: mostly smectite, illite, chlorite and kandite) normally with trace to major amounts of quartz, iron and aluminium oxy-hydroxides (mostly goethite and gibbsite) and organic matter. Clay is classified by geologists at a particle size less than 2 µm, sedimentologists often use 4-5 µm, and colloid chemists use 1 µm.

  • Alternate labels: Clay-grade-sediment

  • Concept URI token: clay

1.2.6.2.2.3.3 Clay-with-flints

  • Child of: clay residual-deposit

  • The name given by W. Whitaker in 1861 to a peculiar deposit of stiff red, brown or yellow clay containing unworn whole flints as well as angular shattered fragments, also with a variable admixture of rounded flint, quartz, quartzite and other pebbles.

  • Concept URI token: clay-with-flints

1.2.6.2.2.3.4 Glacialite

  • Child of: clay

  • Trade name for a white clay from Enid, OK., marketed as a fuller’s earth. Ref: English

  • Concept URI token: glacialite

1.2.6.2.2.3.5 Illite-clay

  • Child of: clay

  • A clay rich in illite.

  • Concept URI token: illite-clay

1.2.6.2.2.3.6 Kaolinite-clay

  • Child of: clay

  • A clay rich in kaolinite.

  • Alternate labels: China Clay

  • Concept URI token: kaolinite-clay

1.2.6.2.2.3.7 Ooze

  • Child of: clay

  • A fine-grained pelagic sediment consisting dominantly of calcareous or siliceous organic remains

  • Alternate labels: biogenic mud

  • Concept URI token: ooze

1.2.6.2.2.3.8 Lime ooze

  • Child of: lime-mud ooze

  • An ooze comprised primarily of calcium carbonate.

  • Alternate labels: calcareous ooze

  • Concept URI token: lime-ooze

1.2.6.2.2.3.9 Silicate-clay

  • Child of: clay

  • A silicate-mud where at least 50% of the siliciclastic fragments are of clay grade (<4µm.)

  • Concept URI token: silicate-clay

  • Child of: lime-mud

  • A lime-mud where the dominant calcium carbonate is aragonite

  • Alternate labels: calcareous ooze

  • Concept URI token: lime-ooze

1.2.6.2.2.3.23 Marl

  • Child of: lime-mud

  • A calcium-carbonate rich mud containing variable amounts of clays and silt. This may be defined either as calcite-mud or lime-rich silicate-mud depending on the proportion of carbonate to clay.

  • Alternate labels: Bog lime, carbonate rich mud,

  • Concept URI token: marl

1.2.6.2.2.3.24 Sapropelic lime-mud

  • Child of: lime-mud

  • A lime-mud with up to 3% sapropelic organic matter. Compare with sapropel which contains over 3%.

  • Concept URI token: sapropelic-lime-mud

1.2.6.2.2.3.25 Phosphate-mud

  • Child of: mud phosphate-sediment

  • A phosphate-sediment with over 75% of the clasts smaller than 32µm.

  • Concept URI token: phosphate-mud

1.2.6.2.2.3.26 Sandy mud

  • Child of: mud

  • A mud containing sand.

  • Alternate labels: Sandy Clay

  • Concept URI token: sandy-mud

1.2.6.2.2.3.27 Silicate-mud

  • Child of: mud siliciclastic-sediment

  • A siliciclastic-sediment containing more than 50% siliciclastic fragments, of which at least 75% should be less than 32µm.

  • Alternate labels: Siliclastic-mud

  • Concept URI token: silicate-mud

1.2.6.2.2.3.28 Lime-rich silicate-mud

  • Child of: silicate-mud

  • A mud containing variable amounts of clays, silt and calcium carbonate. This is the mud-dominant end of what is known as marl.

  • Concept URI token: lime-rich-silicate-mud

1.2.6.2.2.3.29 Sapropelic silicate-mud

  • Child of: silicate-mud

  • A silicate-mud with up to 3% sapropelic organic matter. Compare with sapropel which contains over 3%.

  • Concept URI token: sapropelic-silicate-mud

1.2.6.2.2.3.30 Silt

  • Child of: mud

  • A silt-grade clastic-sediment, that is nonplastic or very slightly plastic and that exhibits little or no strength when air-dried. The term is also used for a soil or rock component between clay and sand in particle size.In the Udden-Wentworth scale silt particles range between 0.0039 and 0.0625 mm, larger than clay but smaller than sand particles. ISO 14688 grades silts between 0.002 mm and 0.063 mm.

  • Alternate labels: Silt-grade-sediment

  • Concept URI token: silt

1.2.6.2.2.3.31 Silicate-silt

  • Child of: silt

  • A silicate-mud where at least 50% of the siliciclastic fragments are of silt grade (>4µm.)

  • Concept URI token: silicate-silt

1.2.6.2.2.4 Red bed

  • Child of: clastic-sediment

  • A sequence of sedimentary rocks consisting of sandstone, siltstone and shale amongst others that are predominantly red in colour due to the presence of ferric oxides.

  • Alternate labels: Red Rock, Redbed Sandstone, Redbed Siltstone, Redbed, Redrock,

  • Concept URI token: red-bed

1.2.6.2.2.5 Sand

  • Child of: clastic-sediment

  • A sand-grade clastic-sediment. Note: the majority of sand can be classed as silicate-sand.A rock fragment or detrital particle smaller than a granule and larger than a coarse silt grain, having a diameter in range of 1/16 to 2 mm (4 to 1 phi units), or a size between that at the lower limit of visibility of an individual particle with the unaided eye and that of the head of a small wooden match), being somewhat rounded by abrasion in the course of transport. In Great Britain, the range of 0.1 to 1 mm has been used.

  • Alternate labels: Sand-grade-sediment

  • Concept URI token: sand

1.2.6.2.2.5.1 Ankerite-sand

  • Child of: dolomite-sediment sand

  • a dolomite-sediment with clasts predominantly 32µm to 2mm, with less than 75% of the clasts smaller than 32µm and less than 25% larger than 2mm, and composition dominantey ankerite.

  • Concept URI token: ankerite-sand

1.2.6.2.2.5.2 Bituminous-sand

  • Child of: organic-rich-sediment sand

  • Loose or partially consolidated sands saturated with bitumen.

  • Alternate labels: Oil sand, Oil sands, Tar Sand, Tar sands,

  • Concept URI token: bituminous-sand

1.2.6.2.2.5.3 Blown sand

  • Child of: aeolian-deposit sand

  • Aeolian sands are primarliy wind-blown fine to medium, non-plastic and uniformly graded materials present in many sandy sites, mainly in desert areas.

  • Alternate labels: Aeolian Sand, Aeolian Sands, Eolian Sand, Eolian Sands,

  • Concept URI token: blown-sand

1.2.6.2.2.5.4 Beach dune sand

  • Child of: blown-sand

  • Unconsolidated sand resulting from accumulation in a beach dune system.

  • Alternate labels: Dune Sand

  • Concept URI token: beach-dune-sand

1.2.6.2.2.5.5 Coversand

  • Child of: blown-sand

  • Layers of sand deposited by wind action across areas of countryside to provide a cover deposit over any exposed ground surface or vegetation. Source: Oxford Reference.

  • Concept URI token: coversand

1.2.6.2.2.5.6 Niveo-aeolian sand

  • Child of: blown-sand

  • Snow- and wind-driven sand.

  • Concept URI token: niveo-aeolian-sand

  • Child of: silicate-sand

1.2.6.2.3 Hybrid-sediment

  • Child of: sediment

  • A sediment comprising three or more components, each of which form more than 5% but less than 50% of the total.

  • Concept URI token: hybrid-sediment

1.2.6.2.3.1 Ferruclastic, calciclastic, siliciclastic hybrid-sediment

  • Child of: hybrid-sediment

  • A hybrid-sediment containing, in increasing order, iron clasts, lime clasts and siliclastic casts, with at least 5% iron clasts and less than 50% siliciclastic clasts.

  • Concept URI token: ferruclastic-calciclastic-siliciclastic-hybrid-sediment

  • Child of: iron-sand limonite-sediment

  • An iron-sand composed primarily of limonite.

1.2.6.2.5 Organic-rich-sediment

  • Child of: sediment

  • Sediments rich in organic-matter.Sedimentary rock with color, composition, texture and apparent density indicating greater than 50 percent organic content by weight on a moisture-free basis.

  • Concept URI token: organic-rich-sediment

1.2.6.2.5.1 Bituminous-sand

  • Child of: organic-rich-sediment sand

  • Loose or partially consolidated sands saturated with bitumen.

  • Alternate labels: Oil sand, Oil sands, Tar Sand, Tar sands,

  • Concept URI token: bituminous-sand

1.2.6.2.5.2 Coorongite

  • Child of: organic-rich-sediment

  • A rubber-like, elastic, highly resilient structureless bituminous material derived from algae. Ref: Schieferdecker ii. A boghead coal in the peat stage. See Also: Elaterite Ref: Stutzer

  • Concept URI token: coorongite

1.2.6.2.5.3 Muddy-peat

  • Child of: organic-rich-sediment

  • An impure peat containing mud grade mineral impurities.

  • Concept URI token: muddy-peat

1.2.6.2.5.4 Peat

  • Child of: organic-deposit organic-rich-sediment

  • An unlithified heterogeneous mixture of a wide range of plant debris. It has a carbon content of less than 60% dry ash free and a volatile content of greater than 63%.

  • Concept URI token: peat

1.2.6.2.5.4.1 Basin peat

  • Child of: peat

  • A peat derived from an inundated basin.

  • Concept URI token: basin-peat

1.2.6.2.5.4.2 Birch bog peat

  • Child of: peat

  • A peat derived from a birch dominated bog.

  • Concept URI token: birch-bog-peat

1.2.6.2.5.4.3 Blanket peat

  • Child of: peat

  • A peat derived from a blanket bog, an area of peatland, forming where there is a climate of high rainfall and a low level of evapotranspiration, allowing peat to develop not only in wet hollows but over large expanses of undulating ground.

  • Concept URI token: blanket-peat

1.2.6.2.5.4.4 Cladium peat

  • Child of: peat

  • A peat derived from a Cladium dominated ecosystem.

  • Concept URI token: cladium-peat

1.2.6.2.5.4.5 Fen peat

  • Child of: peat

  • A peat derived from a fen.

  • Concept URI token: fen-peat

1.2.6.2.5.4.6 Fen-wood peat

  • Child of: peat

  • A peat derived from a fen-wood.

  • Concept URI token: fen-wood-peat

1.2.6.2.5.4.7 Gyttja

  • Child of: peat

  • Sediment rich in organic matter deposited at the bottom of a eutrophic lake.

  • Alternate labels: Shell-rich gyttja

  • Concept URI token: gyttja

1.2.6.2.5.4.8 Hill peat

  • Child of: peat

  • Peat formed in mountainous districts and characterized by the presence of Sphagnum, Andromeda, heath, pine trees, etc. Ref: Tomkeieff

  • Concept URI token: hill-peat

1.2.6.2.5.4.9 Magnocaricetum peat

  • Child of: peat

  • Peat derived from Magnocaricetum sedges.

  • Concept URI token: magnocaricetum-peat

1.2.6.2.5.4.10 Moss peat

  • Child of: peat

  • Peat derived from water-loving mosses, chiefly sphagnum. See Also: highmoor peat

  • Concept URI token: moss-peat

1.2.6.2.5.4.11 Parvocaricetum peat

  • Child of: peat

  • A peat produced from the Parvocaricetum plant type.

  • Concept URI token: parvocaricetum-peat

1.2.6.2.5.4.12 Phragmites peat

  • Child of: peat

  • Peat composed of reed grass and other grasses. Ref: Tomkeieff

  • Concept URI token: phragmites-peat

1.2.6.2.5.4.13 Raised bog peat

  • Child of: peat

  • A peat that was produced from a raised bog.

  • Concept URI token: raised-bog-peat

1.2.6.2.5.4.14 Shrub bog peat

  • Child of: peat

  • A peat produced from a shrub bog.

  • Concept URI token: shrub-bog-peat

1.2.6.2.5.4.15 Sphagnum cuspidatum peat

  • Child of: peat

  • A peat produced from a Sphagnum cuspidatum plant type.

  • Concept URI token: sphagnum-cuspidatum-peat

1.2.6.2.5.5 Sandy-peat

  • Child of: organic-rich-sediment

  • An impure peat containing sand grade mineral impurities.

  • Concept URI token: sandy-peat

1.2.6.2.5.6 Sapropel

  • Child of: organic-rich-sediment

  • An organic mud containing concentrations of miospores (spores and pollen) and/or alginite. i. An aquatic ooze or sludge rich in organic (carbonaceous or bituminous) matter.ii. A fluid organic slime originating in swamps as a product of putrification. In its chemical composition, it contains more hydrocarbon than peat. When dry, it is a lusterless, dull, dark, and extremely tough mass that is hard to break up.

  • Concept URI token: sapropel

1.2.6.2.5.6.1 Alga sapropel

  • Child of: sapropel

  • A sapropel dominant in alginite. Equivalent to peat of the humic coal series. Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: alga-sapropel

1.2.6.2.5.6.2 Misporal sapropel

  • Child of: sapropel

  • A sapropel dominant in miospores.

  • Concept URI token: misporal-sapropel

1.2.6.2.6 Phosphate-sediment

  • Child of: sediment

  • Sediments which have more than 50% phosphate minerals.

  • Concept URI token: phosphate-sediment

1.2.6.2.6.1 Phosphate-gravel

  • Child of: gravel phosphate-sediment

  • A phosphate-sediment with over 25% of clasts larger than 2mm.

  • Concept URI token: phosphate-gravel

1.2.6.2.6.1.1 Ankerite-gravel

  • Child of: dolomite-sediment phosphate-gravel

  • a dolomite-sediment with over 25% of clasts larger than 2mm and composition dominantey ankerite

  • Concept URI token: ankerite-gravel

1.2.6.2.6.2 Phosphate-mud

  • Child of: mud phosphate-sediment

  • A phosphate-sediment with over 75% of the clasts smaller than 32µm.

  • Concept URI token: phosphate-mud

1.2.6.2.6.3 Phosphate-sand

  • Child of: phosphate-sediment sand

  • A phosphate-sediment with clasts predominantly 32µm to 2mm, with less than 75% of the clasts smaller than 32µm and less than 25% larger than 2mm.

  • Concept URI token: phosphate-sand

1.2.6.2.7 Siliceous-ooze

  • Child of: sediment

  • Non-clastic siliceous sediments composed of more than 50% silica of biogenic or chemical origin.

  • Concept URI token: siliceous-ooze

  • Concept URI token: sponge-spicular-ooze

1.2.6.2.8 Volcanic sediment

  • Child of: sediment

  • Unconsolidated clastic deposits including >10% volcanic fragments.

  • Child of: volcanic-sediment volcaniclastic-sedimentary-rock-and-sediment

  • Unconsolidated clastic deposits consisting of between 10% and 25% by volume of pyroclastic fragments.

  • Alternate labels: Volcaniclastic Sediment

  • Concept URI token: volcaniclastic-sediment

  • Concept URI token: volcaniclastic-sand

1.2.6.3 Sedimentary rock

  • Child of: sedimentary-rock-and-sediment

  • A rock resulting from the consolidation of loose sediment that has accumulated in layers; e.g., a clastic rock (such as conglomerate or tillite) consisting of mechanically formed fragments of older rock transported from its source and deposited in water or from air or ice; or a chemical rock (such as rock salt or gypsum) formed by precipitation from solution; or an organic rock (such as certain limestones) consisting of the remains or secretions of plants and animals.

  • Alternate labels: Sedimentary Rock, undifferentiated, Sedimentary, derivative rock, stratified rock,

  • Concept URI token: sedimentary-rock

1.2.6.3.1 Biochemical and chemical sedimentary rock

  • Child of: sedimentary-rock

  • A sedimentary rock that has been primarily deposited due to chemical deposition and/or the action of biological organisms.

  • Concept URI token: biochemical-and-chemical-sedimentary-rock

1.2.6.3.1.1 Boundstone

  • Child of: biochemical-and-chemical-sedimentary-rock

  • A rock where the original components were bound and encrusted together by the action of plants and/or animals in the position of growth.

  • Concept URI token: boundstone

1.2.6.3.1.1.1 Ankerite-boundstone

  • Child of: boundstone dolostone

  • A dolostone where the original components were bound and encrusted together by the action of plants and/or animals in the position of growth, and ankerite is the predominate carbonate mineral.

  • Concept URI token: ankerite-boundstone

1.2.6.3.1.1.2 Dolomite-boundstone

  • Child of: boundstone dolostone

  • A dolostone where the original components were bound and encrusted together by the action of plants and/or animals in the position of growth, and dolomite is the predominate carbonate mineral.

  • Concept URI token: dolomite-boundstone

1.2.6.3.1.1.3 Iron-boundstone

  • Child of: boundstone evaporite

  • An ironstone where the original components were bound and encrusted together by the action of plants and/or animals in the position of growth.

  • Concept URI token: iron-boundstone

1.2.6.3.1.1.4 Lime-boundstone

  • Child of: boundstone limestone

  • A limestone where the original components were bound and encrusted together by the action of plants and/or animals in the position of growth.

  • Concept URI token: lime-boundstone

1.2.6.3.1.1.5 Aragonite-boundstone

  • Child of: lime-boundstone

  • A lime-boundstone where the dominant calcium carbonate mineral is aragonite.

  • Concept URI token: aragonite-boundstone

1.2.6.3.1.1.6 Calcite-boundstone

  • Child of: lime-boundstone

  • A lime-boundstone where the dominant calcium carbonate mineral is calcite.

  • Concept URI token: calcite-boundstone

1.2.6.3.1.1.7 Phosphate-boundstone

  • Child of: boundstone phosphorite

  • A phosphorite where the original components were bound and encrusted together by the action of plants and/or animals in the position of growth.

  • Concept URI token: phosphate-boundstone

1.2.6.3.1.2 Carbonate rock

  • Child of: biochemical-and-chemical-sedimentary-rock

  • Sedimentary rocks where the carbonate component forms more than 50% of the sediment. For a rock to be termed a carbonate sedimentary rock the 50% carbonate should not include any carbonate cement in an originally non-carbonate rock.

  • Alternate labels: CARBONATES (LIMESTONE OR DOLOMITE), Carbonate,

  • Concept URI token: carbonate-rock

1.2.6.3.1.2.1 Biocarbonate

  • Child of: carbonate-rock

  • A fossiliferous carbonate rock with an unspecified matrix

  • Alternate labels: fossiliferous carbonate, fossiliferous carbonates, fossiliferous limestone,

  • Concept URI token: biocarbonate

1.2.6.3.1.2.2 Biomicrite

  • Child of: biocarbonate

  • A fossiliferous carbonate rock with a predominantly micrite matrix

  • Concept URI token: biomicrite

1.2.6.3.1.2.3 Biointramicrite

  • Child of: biomicrite

  • A fossiliferous carbonate rock with a predominantly micrite matrix and secondary eroded limestone (intraclast) allochems

  • Concept URI token: biointramicrite

1.2.6.3.1.2.4 Biooomicrite

  • Child of: biomicrite

  • A fossiliferous carbonate rock with a predominantly micrite matrix and secondary ooid allochems

  • Concept URI token: biooomicrite

1.2.6.3.1.2.5 Biopelmicrite

  • Child of: biomicrite

  • A fossiliferous carbonate rock with a predominantly micrite matrix and secondary pellet allochems

  • Concept URI token: biopelmicrite

1.2.6.3.1.2.6 Biosparite

  • Child of: biocarbonate

  • A fossiliferous carbonate rock with a predominantly sparite matrix

  • Concept URI token: biosparite

1.2.6.3.1.2.7 Biointrasparite

  • Child of: biosparite

  • A fossiliferous carbonate rock with a predominantly sparite matrix and secondary eroded limestone (intraclast) allochems

  • Concept URI token: biointrasparite

1.2.6.3.1.2.8 Biooosparite

  • Child of: biosparite

  • A fossiliferous carbonate rock with a predominantly sparite matrix and secondary ooid allochems

  • Concept URI token: biooosparite

1.2.6.3.1.2.9 Biopelsparite

  • Child of: biosparite

  • A fossiliferous carbonate rock with a predominantly sparite matrix and secondary pellet allochems

  • Concept URI token: biopelsparite

1.2.6.3.1.2.10 Caliche

  • Child of: carbonate-rock duricrust

  • A reddish brown to white calcareous material of secondary accumulation, commonly found in layers on or near the surface of stony soils of arid and semiarid regions, but also occurring as a subsoil deposit in subhumid climates. It may occur as a thin, friable horizon within the soil, but more commonly it is up to a metre or more in thickness, impermeable and strongly indurated. It is composed largely of a calcareous cement, in addition to such materials as gravel sand and mud.

  • Concept URI token: caliche

1.2.6.3.1.2.11 Calcrete

  • Child of: caliche conglomerate

  • Etymol: ‘cal’careous + con’crete.’ .A calcareous duricrust, caliche or calcitic conglomerate consisting of surficial sand and gravel cemented into a hard mass by calcium carbonate precipitated from solution and redeposited through the agency of infiltrating waters, or deposited by the escape of carbon dioxide from vadose water.ii. A calcareous duricrust; caliche. Compare with: silcrete, ferricrete

  • Alternate labels: Kunkar

  • Concept URI token: calcrete

1.2.6.3.1.2.12 Dolostone

  • Child of: carbonate-rock

  • A carbonate sedimentary rock where the dominant carbonate mineral is dolomite or ankerite.

  • Alternate labels: Dolomite

  • Concept URI token: dolostone

1.2.6.3.1.2.13 Ankerite-boundstone

  • Child of: boundstone dolostone

  • A dolostone where the original components were bound and encrusted together by the action of plants and/or animals in the position of growth, and ankerite is the predominate carbonate mineral.

  • Concept URI token: ankerite-boundstone

1.2.6.3.1.2.14 Ankerite-framestone

  • Child of: dolostone framestone

  • A dolostone consiting of a rigid framework of colonies, shells and/or skeletons. Internal cavities are filled with fine sediment. Ankerite is the predominant carbonate mineral.

  • Concept URI token: ankerite-framestone

1.2.6.3.1.2.15 Ankerite-grainstone

  • Child of: dolostone grainstone

  • A grain-supported dolostone with little matrix and ankerite is the predominant carbonate mineral.

  • Concept URI token: ankerite-grainstone

1.2.6.3.1.2.16 Ankerite-microsparstone

  • Child of: dolostone microsparstone

  • A dolostone composed of obliterative sparry carbonate crystals, typically in inequant, blocky mosaics, with crystal size in the 4-32µm range and ankerite is the predominate carbonate mineral.

  • Concept URI token: ankerite-microsparstone

1.2.6.3.1.2.17 Ankerite-microstone

  • Child of: dolostone microstone

  • A dolostone composed of obliterative sparry carbonate crystals, typically in inequant, blocky mosaics, with crystal size in the 4-32µm range and ankerite is the predominante carbonate mineral.

  • Concept URI token: ankerite-microstone

1.2.6.3.1.2.18 Ankerite-mudstone

  • Child of: dolostone mudstone

  • A dolostone with at least 75% mud grade (< 32µm) carbonate with ankerite as the dominant carbonate mineral.

  • Concept URI token: ankerite-mudstone

1.2.6.3.1.2.19 Ankerite-packstone

  • Child of: dolostone packstone

  • A grain-supported dolostone with intergranular spaces filled by matrix and ankerite is the predominate carbonate mineral.

1.2.6.3.1.2.20 Ankerite-pseudosparstone

  • Child of: dolostone pseudosparstone

  • A dolostone composed almost totally of a divergent radial fibrous carbonate cement in which grains or in-situ biogenic material do not constitute a framework and ankerite is the predominant carbonate mineral.

  • Concept URI token: ankerite-pseudosparstone

1.2.6.3.1.2.21 Ankerite-sparstone

  • Child of: dolostone sparstone

  • A dolostone composed of obliterative sparry carbonate crystals, typically in inequant, blocky mosaics, with crystal size larger than 32µm and ankerite is the predominate carbonate mineral.

1.2.6.3.1.2.22 Ankerite-wackestone

  • Child of: dolostone wackestone

  • Concept URI token: ankerite-wackestone

1.2.6.3.1.2.23 Calcareous dolostone

1.2.6.3.1.2.36 Impure dolostone

  • Child of: dolostone

  • Sedimentary rock in with between 50 and 90 percent of the primary and/or recrystallised constituents are composed of carbonate minerals with a ratio of magnesium carbonate to calcite (plus aragonite) greater than 1 to 1.

1.2.6.3.1.2.37 Microoncoid-dolostone

1.2.6.3.1.2.38 Mud-grade dolostone

1.2.6.3.1.2.39 Oncoid-dolostone

1.2.6.3.1.2.43 Pure dolostone

  • Child of: dolostone

  • Sedimentary rock in with greater than 90 percent of the primary and/or recrystallised constituents are composed of carbonate minerals with a ratio of magnesium carbonate to calcite (plus aragonite) greater than 1 to 1.

  • Concept URI token: pure-dolostone

1.2.6.3.1.2.44 Sand-grade dolostone

  • Child of: dolostone

  • A dolostone with average grain or crystal size predominantly in the 32µm to 2mm range, with less than 75% smaller than 32µm and less than 25% larger than 2mm.

  • Alternate labels: Dolomitic Sandstone

  • Concept URI token: sand-grade-dolostone

1.2.6.3.1.2.45 Framestone

  • Child of: carbonate-rock

  • A rock consiting of a rigid framework of colonies, shells and/or skeletons. Internal cavities are filled with fine sediment.

  • Concept URI token: framestone

1.2.6.3.1.2.46 Ankerite-framestone

  • Child of: dolostone framestone

  • A dolostone consiting of a rigid framework of colonies, shells and/or skeletons. Internal cavities are filled with fine sediment. Ankerite is the predominant carbonate mineral.

  • Concept URI token: ankerite-framestone

  • Concept URI token: intrapelsparite

1.2.6.3.1.2.61 Limestone

  • Child of: carbonate-rock

  • A sedimentary rock composed dominantly of calcium carbonate (more than 50% by weight or by areal percentages under the microscope). Common minor constituents include silica (chalcedony), feldspar, clays, pyrite, and siderite. Limestones are formed by either organic or inorganic processes, and may be detrital, chemical, oolitic, earthy, crystalline, or recrystallised. Limestones include chalk, calcarenite, coquina, and travertine, and they effervesce freely with any common acid.

  • Concept URI token: limestone

1.2.6.3.1.2.62 Argillaceous limestone

  • Child of: limestone

  • A limestone containing an appreciable amount (but less than 50%) of clay; e.g., cement rock.

  • Alternate labels: Earthy lime

  • Concept URI token: argillaceous-limestone

1.2.6.3.1.2.63 Beachrock

  • Child of: limestone

  • A friable to well-cemented sedimentary rock that consists of a variable mixture of gravel, sand, and silt-sized sediment that is cemented with carbonate minerals and has formed along a shoreline.

  • Alternate labels: Beach rock

  • Concept URI token: beachrock

1.2.6.3.1.2.64 Chalk

  • Child of: limestone

  • Colour:White, GreyA limestone which is friable and porous.

  • Alternate labels: Alm

  • Concept URI token: chalk

1.2.6.3.1.2.65 Chalk-with-flints

  • Child of: chalk

  • A chalk containing a large number of flints.

  • Concept URI token: chalk-with-flints

1.2.6.3.1.2.66 Foraminiferal Chalk

  • Child of: chalk

  • A chalk composed predominantely of foraminifera.

  • Concept URI token: foraminiferal-chalk

  • Child of: limestone

  • A limestone composed almost entirely of crinoid fragments.

  • Concept URI token: crinoid-limestone

1.2.6.3.1.2.68 Gravel-grade limestone

  • Child of: limestone

  • A limestone with over 25% of grains or crystals larger than 2mm.

  • Alternate labels: Calcirudite, Rudaceous limestone,

  • Concept URI token: gravel-grade-limestone

1.2.6.3.1.2.69 Impure limestone

  • Child of: limestone

  • Sedimentary rock in with between 50 and 90 percent of the primary and/or recrystallised constituents are composed of carbonate minerals with a calcite (plus aragonite) to dolomite ratio greater than 1 to 1.

  • Alternate labels: Muddy Limestone, Sandy Limestone,

  • Concept URI token: impure-limestone

1.2.6.3.1.2.70 Kerogenic limestone

  • Child of: limestone

  • A limestone containing 1-8% of organic sapropelic matter rich in algae.

  • Concept URI token: kerogenic-limestone

1.2.6.3.1.2.71 klintite

  • A reef limestone, particularly the massive core.

  • Concept URI token: klintite

1.2.6.3.1.2.90 Impure lime-mudstone

  • Child of: lime-mudstone

  • Mudstone that consists of between 50 and 90 percent carbonate minerals of intrabasinal orign in the mud fraction, and contains less than 10 percent allochems. The original depositional texture is preserved and fabric is matrix supported.

  • Concept URI token: impure-lime-mudstone

1.2.6.3.1.2.91 Marlstone

  • Child of: lime-mudstone silicate-mudstone

  • A lithified marl. An indurated rock of about the same composition as marl.

  • Alternate labels: carbonate rich mudstone, marlite,

  • Concept URI token: marlstone

1.2.6.3.1.2.92 Lime-rich silicate-mudstone

  • Child of: marlstone

  • A silicate-mudstone containing variable amounts of clays, silt and calcium carbonate. This is the mud-dominant end of what is known as marlstone.

  • Concept URI token: lime-rich-silicate-mudstone

1.2.6.3.1.2.93 Pure lime-mudstone

1.2.6.3.1.2.110 Ooid-limestone

  • Child of: limestone

  • A limestone composed almost entirely of ooids. An even-textured limestone composed almost wholly of relatively uniform calcareous ooliths, with virtually no interstitial material. It is locally an important oil reservoir (such as the Smackover Formation in Arkansas), and is also quarried for building stone.

  • Alternate labels: Ammite, Ooite, Oolitic limestone, oolite,

  • Concept URI token: ooid-limestone

1.2.6.3.1.2.113 Pure limestone

  • Child of: limestone

  • Concept URI token: pure-limestone

1.2.6.3.1.2.114 Sand-grade limestone

  • Child of: limestone

  • A limestone with average grain or crystal size predominantly in the 32µm to 2mm range, with less than 75% smaller than 32µm and less than 25% larger than 2mm.

  • Alternate labels: Arenaceous limestone, Calcarenite, calc-arenite, calcareous arenite, calcareous sandstone,

  • Concept URI token: sand-grade-limestone

1.2.6.3.1.2.115 Shell-limestone

  • Child of: limestone

  • A limestone composed almost entirely of shell fragments.

  • Alternate labels: Coquina, Coquinite,

  • Concept URI token: shell-limestone

1.2.6.3.1.2.116 Travertine

  • Child of: chemical-deposit limestone

  • A limestone formed by hot mineral springs.

  • Concept URI token: travertine

1.2.6.3.1.2.117 Tufa

  • Child of: chemical-deposit limestone

  • A limestone formed when carbonate minerals precipitate out of ambient temperature water. A chemical sedimentary rock composed of calcium carbonate, formed by evaporation as a surficial, spongy, porous, semifriable incrustation around the mouth of a hot or cold spring or seep, or along a stream carrying calcium carbonate in solution, and exceptionally as a thick, bulbous, concretionary or compact deposit in a lake or along its shore. It may also be precipitated by algae or bacteria. The hard, dense variety is travertine.

  • Concept URI token: tufa

1.2.6.3.1.2.118 Magnesite-stone

  • Child of: carbonate-rock

  • A sedimentary rock composed of magnesite, some are formed as primary precipitates, some as diagentic replacement.

  • Alternate labels: Magnesite

  • Concept URI token: magnesite-stone

  • Concept URI token: aragonite-pseudosparstone

1.2.6.3.1.3 Evaporite

  • Child of: biochemical-and-chemical-sedimentary-rock

  • Sedimentary rocks containing non-carbonate salts. The term ‘evaporite’ is more strictly a genetic term and sometimes these can be formed through other means. A nonclastic sedimentary rock composed primarily of minerals produced from a saline solution as a result of extensive or total evaporation of the water. Examples include gypsum, anhydrite, rock salt, and various nitrates and borates. The term sometimes includes rocks developed by metamorphism or transport of other evaporites.

  • Alternate labels: Non-carbonate salt, dolomite and anhydrite and halite, halite and anhydrite,

  • Concept URI token: evaporite

1.2.6.3.1.3.1 Banded iron formation

  • Child of: evaporite

  • Iron-rich rocks almost always of Precambrian age, predominantly associated with the great oxygenation event (GOE) about 2.3-2.8 billion years ago. They typically consist of repeated, thin iron oxide layers. The oxide bands are dark grey to to black magnetite (Fe3O4) or hematite (Fe2O3), alternating with bands of iron-poor shales and cherts, usually red in color, of similar thickness, or iron rich silicates and carbonates, including siderite, ankerite, riebeckite etc.

  • Alternate labels: B.I.F., BIF, Banded-Iron-Formation, Carbonate Iron Formation, Magnetite Iron Formation, Oxide iron formation,

  • Concept URI token: banded-iron-formation

1.2.6.3.1.3.2 Banded-ferruginous chert

  • Child of: banded-iron-formation chert

  • A silica-rich rock, part of the banded iron formation.

  • Concept URI token: banded-ferruginous-chert

1.2.6.3.1.3.3 Banded-siliceous ironstone

  • Child of: banded-iron-formation

  • A iron-rich banded ironstone, part of the banded iron formation series. See also banded-ferruginous chert.

  • Concept URI token: banded-siliceous-ironstone

1.2.6.3.1.3.4 Itabirite

  • Child of: banded-iron-formation

  • A laminated, metamorphosed oxide-facies iron formation in which (1) the original chert or jasper bands have been recrystallised into megascopically distinguishable grains of quartz and (2) the iron is present as thin layers of hematite, magnetite, or martite (Dorr & Barbosa, 1963). The term was originally applied in Itabira, Brazil, to a high-grade, massive specular-hematite ore (66% iron) associated with a schistose rock composed of granular quartz and scaly hematite. The term is now widely used outside Brazil.

  • Concept URI token: itabirite

1.2.6.3.1.3.5 Jaspillite

  • Child of: banded-iron-formation

  • A siliceous or metamorphosed banded ironstone, including iron-rich quartzites, interbedded jasper and iron oxides. They are usually mixtures of quartz and magnetite and/or hematite. They constitute many low grade iron ore deposits, collectively forming the largest accumulations of iron on the Earth (hundreds of megatons and more).Also a trade name for red, hematitized varieties of jasper.

  • Alternate labels: Jaspilite

  • Concept URI token: jaspillite

1.2.6.3.1.5 Ironstone

  • Child of: biochemical-and-chemical-sedimentary-rock

  • Lithified iron-rich sediments. Any rock containing a substantial proportion of an iron compound, or any iron ore from which the metal may be smelted commercially.

  • Alternate labels: iron formation

  • Concept URI token: ironstone

1.2.6.3.1.5.1 argillaceous hematite

  • Child of: ironstone

  • A brown to deep-red variety of natural ferric oxide containing an appreciable portion of clay (or sand). Synonym of: ironstone clay

  • Concept URI token: argillaceous-hematite

1.2.6.3.1.5.2 Bog ironstone

  • Child of: chemical-deposit ironstone

  • A soft and porous deposit of limonite, impregnated with plant debris, clay and clastic material. It is formed in bogs, marshes and shallow lakes by precipitation from iron-bearing waters and by the oxidising action of algae, iron bacteria or the atmosphere. Sometimes used as an iron ore. Ref: Pryor, Schieferdecker

  • Concept URI token: bog-ironstone

  • Concept URI token: calciclastic-ironstone

1.2.6.3.1.8 Siliceous-rock

  • Child of: biochemical-and-chemical-sedimentary-rock

  • Concept URI token: siliceous-rock

1.2.6.3.1.8.1 Biogenic siliceous-rock

  • Child of: siliceous-rock

  • Sedimentary rock that consists of at least 50 percent silicate mineral material, deposited directly by biological processes at the depositional surface, or in particles formed by biological processes within the basin of deposition.

  • Concept URI token: biogenic-siliceous-rock

1.2.6.3.1.8.2 Diatomite

  • Child of: biogenic-siliceous-rock biological-deposit

  • A siliceous-rock composed predominantly of diatoms and with porosity greater than 50%.

  • Alternate labels: Diatomaceous Earth

  • Concept URI token: diatomite

1.2.6.3.1.8.3 Radiolarite

  • Child of: biogenic-siliceous-rock

  • A siliceous-rock composed predominantly of radiolaria and with porosity greater than 50%.

  • Concept URI token: radiolarite

1.2.6.3.1.8.4 Spiculite

  • Child of: biogenic-siliceous-rock

  • A siliceous-rock composed predominantly of sponge spicules and with porosity greater than 50%.

  • Concept URI token: spiculite

1.2.6.3.1.8.5 Chert

  • Child of: siliceous-rock

  • A dense, hard siliceous-rock with low porosity composed mainly of microcrystalline quartz and varying amounts of impurities. The quartz occurs as randomly interlocked, microscopic quartz grains (microquartz) or fibrous chalcedony.

  • Alternate labels: Hornstone, Massive silica, Mozarkite,

  • Concept URI token: chert

1.2.6.3.1.8.6 Banded-ferruginous chert

  • Child of: banded-iron-formation chert

  • A silica-rich rock, part of the banded iron formation.

  • Concept URI token: banded-ferruginous-chert

1.2.6.3.1.8.7 Novaculite

  • Child of: chert

  • Novaculite is a uniform, fine-grained hard rock mostly composed of extremely fine-grained to cryptocrystalline quartz. It may be white, gray, or black due to impurities.

  • Concept URI token: novaculite

1.2.6.3.1.8.8 Opaline-chert

  • Child of: chert

  • A chert where the silica content is opal-A, opal-CT, opal-C.

  • Concept URI token: opaline-chert

1.2.6.3.1.8.9 Quartzose-chert

  • Child of: chert

  • A chert where the silica content is predominantly quartz (88-98%).

  • Alternate labels: Silica - White chert

  • Concept URI token: quartzose-chert

1.2.6.3.1.8.10 Flint

  • Child of: quartzose-chert

  • A nodular chert, often grey/black, formed as nodules in Creataceous chalk.

  • Concept URI token: flint

1.2.6.3.1.8.11 Radiolarian chert

  • Child of: chert

  • A chert with a significant amount of radiolaria.

  • Concept URI token: radiolarian-chert

1.2.6.3.1.8.12 Ribbonstone

  • Child of: chert

  • A banded variety of chert.

  • Concept URI token: ribbonstone

1.2.6.3.1.8.13 Silexite

  • Child of: chert quartzolite

    1. An igneous rock composed essentially of primary quartz (60% to 100%), e.g., a quartz dike, segregation mass, or inclusion inside or outside its parent rock.Ref: AGIii. The French term for chert; specif. chert occurring in calcareous beds.See Also: Chert

  • Concept URI token: silexite

1.2.6.3.1.8.14 Taconite

  • Child of: chert

  • The cherty or jaspery rock that enclosed the Mesabi iron ores in Minnesota. In a somewhat more general sense, it designates any bedded ferruginous chert of the Lake Superior district. [Stokes and Varnes, 1955.] In Minnesota practice, it is any grade of extremely hard, lean iron ore that has its iron either in banded or well disseminated form and which may be hematite or magnetite, or a combination of the two within the same or body. [Cumming]

  • Alternate labels: taconyte

  • Concept URI token: taconite

1.2.6.3.1.8.15 Porcellanite

  • Child of: siliceous-rock

  • A group of siliceous-rocks that have the texture, lustre and conchoidal fracture of porcelain. A dense siliceous rock having the texture, dull luster, hardness, conchoidal fracture, and general appearance of unglazed porcelain; it is less tough, dense, and vitreous than chert.

  • Alternate labels: Porcelainite, Porcelanite,

  • Concept URI token: porcellanite

1.2.6.3.1.8.16 Opaline-porcellanite

  • Child of: porcellanite

  • A porcelllanite where the silica content is mostly opal-A, opal-CT, low-cristobalite or tridymite.

  • Concept URI token: opaline-porcellanite

1.2.6.3.1.8.17 Quartzose-porcellanite

  • Child of: porcellanite

  • A porcelllanite where the silica content is predominantly quartz.

  • Concept URI token: quartzose-porcellanite

1.2.6.3.1.8.18 Sinter

  • Child of: chemical-deposit siliceous-rock

  • Also used for any chemical sedimentary rock deposited as a hard incrustation on rocks or on the ground by precipitation from hot or cold mineral waters in springs, lakes, or streams; specif. siliceous sinter and calcareous sinter (travertine). The term is indefinite and should be modified by the proper compositional adj., although when used alone it usually signifies siliceous sinter.

  • Concept URI token: sinter

1.2.6.3.1.8.19 Geyserite

  • Child of: sinter

  • An opaline sinter that is often found around hot springs and geysers.

  • Alternate labels: Terpizite

  • Concept URI token: geyserite

1.2.6.3.1.8.20 Fiorite

  • Child of: geyserite

  • A botryoidal form of geyserite.

  • Concept URI token: fiorite

1.2.6.3.1.8.21 Siliceous sinter

  • Child of: sinter

  • A silica rock deposited from rapidly cooling watery solutions. Often irregularily laminated, but also sponge-like or massive. May form contiguous crusts or isolated, often rounded bodies. Usually made of opal (opal-AG, opal-CT), but may also contain or be exclusively made of chalcedony. Silicious sinter forms at hot springs, but silicious rocks of similar texture and composition can form under comparable conditions in subsurface veins and are sometimes also called silicious sinter.

  • Concept URI token: siliceous-sinter

1.2.6.3.2 Clastic sedimentary rock

  • Child of: sedimentary-rock

  • Clastic sedimentary rock, composed of clasts of detrital rock and mineral fragments.

  • Alternate labels: clasolite

  • Concept URI token: clastic-sedimentary-rock

1.2.6.3.2.1 Conglomerate

  • Child of: clastic-sedimentary-rock

  • A gravel-grade clastic-sedimentary-rock.A coarse-grained clastic sedimentary rock, composed of rounded to subangular fragments larger than 2 mm in diameter (granules, pebbles, cobbles, boulders) set in a fine-grained matrix of sand or silt, and commonly cemented by calcium carbonate, iron oxide, silica, or hardened clay; the consolidated equivalent of gravel. The rock or mineral fragments may be of varied composition and range widely in size and are usually rounded and smoothed from transportation by water or from wave action.

  • Alternate labels: Arenite-Rudite, Gravel-grade-sedimentary-rock, Mudrock-rudite, Rudite,

  • Concept URI token: conglomerate

1.2.6.3.2.1.1 Breccio-conglomerate

  • Child of: conglomerate

  • A gravel-grade clastic-sedimentary-rock with both rounded and angular fragments.

  • Concept URI token: breccio-conglomerate

1.2.6.3.2.1.2 Calcrete

  • Child of: caliche conglomerate

  • Etymol: ‘cal’careous + con’crete.’ .A calcareous duricrust, caliche or calcitic conglomerate consisting of surficial sand and gravel cemented into a hard mass by calcium carbonate precipitated from solution and redeposited through the agency of infiltrating waters, or deposited by the escape of carbon dioxide from vadose water.ii. A calcareous duricrust; caliche. Compare with: silcrete, ferricrete

  • Alternate labels: Kunkar

  • Concept URI token: calcrete

1.2.6.3.2.1.3 Conglomerite

  • Child of: conglomerate

  • A conglomerate that has reached the same state of induration as a quartzite.

  • Concept URI token: conglomerite

1.2.6.3.2.1.4 Monomitic conglomerate

  • Child of: conglomerate

  • A conglomerate consisting of fragments of a single rock or mineral.

  • Concept URI token: monomitic-conglomerate

1.2.6.3.2.1.5 Orthoconglomerate

  • Child of: conglomerate

  • A conglomerate where the gravel-size clasts are in contact with each other.

  • Concept URI token: orthoconglomerate

1.2.6.3.2.1.6 Paraconglomerate

  • Child of: conglomerate

  • A term proposed by Pettijohn (1957) for a conglomerate that is not a product of normal aqueous flow, but is deposited by such agents as subaqueous turbidity slides and glacier ice; it contains more matrix than gravel-sized fragments (pebbles may form less than 10% of the rock). Examples include tillites, pebbly mudstones, and relatively structureless clay or shale bodies in which pebbles or cobbles are randomly distributed.A conglomerate where the gravel-size clasts are separated from each other by an abundance of matrix.

  • Alternate labels: conglomerate mudstone

  • Concept URI token: paraconglomerate

1.2.6.3.2.1.7 Puddingstone

  • Child of: conglomerate

  • A local name for a conglomerate with contrasting colours between the stones and the finer-grained matrix.

  • Concept URI token: puddingstone

1.2.6.3.2.1.8 Sedimentary breccia

  • Child of: breccia conglomerate

  • A gravel-grade clastic-sedimentary-rock with angular fragments.

  • Alternate labels: Flake Breccia, Siltstone/sandstone breccia, sandstone breccia, siltstone breccia,

  • Concept URI token: sedimentary-breccia

1.2.6.3.2.1.9 Silicate-conglomerate

  • Child of: conglomerate siliclastic-sedimentary-rock

  • A sedimentary rock made up of at least 50% clastic fragments derived from pre-existing siliceous rocks, where at least 25% of the fragments are coarser than 2mm.

  • Concept URI token: silicate-conglomerate

1.2.6.3.2.1.10 Conglomeratic arkose

  • Child of: silicate-conglomerate

  • A silicate-conglomerate containing at least 25% feldspar.

  • Concept URI token: conglomeratic-arkose

1.2.6.3.2.1.11 Silica-cemented silicate-conglomerate

  • Child of: silicate-conglomerate

  • A silicate-conglomerate consisting of sand and gravel cemented into a hard mass by silica.

  • Concept URI token: silica-cemented-silicate-conglomerate

1.2.6.3.2.2 Monomict Breccia

  • Child of: clastic-sedimentary-rock

  • A gravel-grade clastic-sedimentary-rock with angular clasts of predominantly a single rock type.

  • Alternate labels: Monomictic Breccia

  • Concept URI token: mono-breccia

  • Child of: clastic-sedimentary-rock

  • Child of: mudstone

  • A mudstone with variable amounts of silt-sized particles composed predominantly of indurated clay particles.A compact rock derived either from mudstone (claystone or siltstone), or shale, that has undergone a somewhat higher degree of induration than mudstone or shale but is less clearly laminated and without its fissility, and that lacks the cleavage distinctive of slate.

  • Concept URI token: argillite

1.2.6.3.2.4.6 Bentonite

  • Child of: claystone

  • Concept URI token: bentonite

1.2.6.3.2.4.7 alkali sub-bentonite

  • Child of: bentonite

  • A bentonite containing easily replaceable alkali bases but having original properties that are destroyed by acid treatment. Ref: Davis

  • Concept URI token: alkali-sub-bentonite

1.2.6.3.2.4.8 magnesium bentonite

  • Child of: bentonite

  • A bentonite or smectite-rich rock with exchangeable magnesium.

  • Concept URI token: magnesium-bentonite

1.2.6.3.2.4.9 Metabentonite

  • Child of: bentonite

    1. Metamorphosed, altered, or somewhat indurated bentonite; characterized by clay minerals (esp. illite), that no longer has the property of absorbing or adsorbing large quantities of water; nonswelling bentonite, or bentonite that swells no more than do ordinary clays. The term has been applied to certain Ordovician clays of the Appalachian region and upper Mississippi River Valley. See Also: potassium bentonite ii. A mineral of the montmorillonite group with SiO2 layers in the montmorillonite structure. Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: metabentonite

1.2.6.3.2.4.10 potassium bentonite

  • Child of: bentonite

  • A clay of the illite group, formed by the alteration of volcanic ash; a metabentonite. Synonym of: K-bentonite

  • Concept URI token: potassium-bentonite

1.2.6.3.2.4.15 Lithomarge

  • Child of: kaolinite-claystone

  • A compact, massive form of kaolin; perhaps used more as a mineral than rock name, but may include halloysite. Commonly considered to be a variety of claystone, though its not clear that its always sedimentary. An early name for several soft clay-like minerals.

  • Concept URI token: lithomarge

1.2.6.3.2.4.16 Tonstein

  • Child of: kaolinite-claystone

  • A hard, compact sedimentary rock that is composed mainly of kaolinite or, less commonly, other clay minerals such as montmorillonite and illite. A compact argillaceous rock containing the clay mineral kaolinite in a variety of forms together with occasional detrital and carbonaceous material, commonly occurring as a thin band in a Carboniferous coal seam (or locally in the roof of a seam), often used as an aid in correlating European strata of Westphalian age.

  • Concept URI token: tonstein

1.2.6.3.2.4.35 Impure lime-mudstone

  • Child of: lime-mudstone

  • Mudstone that consists of between 50 and 90 percent carbonate minerals of intrabasinal orign in the mud fraction, and contains less than 10 percent allochems. The original depositional texture is preserved and fabric is matrix supported.

  • Concept URI token: impure-lime-mudstone

1.2.6.3.2.4.36 Marlstone

  • Child of: lime-mudstone silicate-mudstone

  • A lithified marl. An indurated rock of about the same composition as marl.

  • Alternate labels: carbonate rich mudstone, marlite,

  • Concept URI token: marlstone

1.2.6.3.2.4.37 Lime-rich silicate-mudstone

  • Child of: marlstone

  • A silicate-mudstone containing variable amounts of clays, silt and calcium carbonate. This is the mud-dominant end of what is known as marlstone.

  • Concept URI token: lime-rich-silicate-mudstone

1.2.6.3.2.4.38 Pure lime-mudstone

  • Child of: lime-mudstone

  • Mudstone that consists of greater than 90 percent carbonate minerals of intrabasinal orign in the mud fraction, and contains less than 10 percent allochems. The original depositional texture is preserved and fabric is matrix supported.

  • Concept URI token: pure-lime-mudstone

1.2.6.3.2.4.39 Phosphate-mudstone

  • Child of: mudstone

  • A phosphorite with at least 75% mud grade (< 32µm) phosphate.

  • Concept URI token: phosphate-mudstone

1.2.6.3.2.4.40 Shale

  • Child of: mudstone

  • A fine-grained detrital sedimentary rock, formed by the consolidation (esp. by compression) of clay, silt, or mud. It is characterized by finely laminated structure, which imparts a fissility approx. parallel to the bedding, along which the rock breaks readily into thin layers, and by an appreciable content of clay minerals and detrital quartz; a thinly laminated or fissile claystone, siltstone, or mudstone.

  • Alternate labels: Schluffstein

  • Concept URI token: shale

1.2.6.3.2.4.41 Black shale

  • Child of: shale

  • A shale with at least 1% carbonaceous material indicating a reducing environment. A dark, thinly laminated carbonaceous shale, exceptionally rich in organic matter (5% or more carbon content) and sulfide (esp. iron sulfide, usually pyrite), and often containing unusual concentrations of certain trace elements (U, V, Cu, Ni).

  • Alternate labels: biopelite

  • Concept URI token: black-shale

1.2.6.3.2.4.42 Alum Shale

  • Child of: black-shale

  • An argillaceous sedimentary rock, often a variety of Black shale, containing pyrite or marcasite. Decomposition of the pyrite and marcasite by weathering forms sulfuric acid which reacts with aluminous minerals in the rock to form alum and other aluminum sulfates. Synonym of: alum earth, alum schist, alum slate

  • Concept URI token: alum-shale

1.2.6.3.2.4.43 Ampelite

  • Child of: black-shale

  • An obsolete term for a black carbonaceous or bituminous shale.

  • Concept URI token: ampelite

1.2.6.3.2.4.44 sulphidic shale

  • Child of: black-shale

  • A black shale with a high sulphur content. Typically recognisable by a noticably sulphorous odour.

  • Alternate labels: Sulfer Shale, Sulfidic Shale, Sulpher Shale,

  • Concept URI token: sulphidic-shale

1.2.6.3.2.4.45 Carbonaceous Shale

  • Child of: carbonaceous-sedimentary-rock shale

  • Shale with a significant carbonaceuous fraction excluding coal fragments

  • Concept URI token: carbonaceous-shale

  • Concept URI token: sapropelite

1.2.6.3.2.4.51 Silicate-mudstone

  • Child of: mudstone siliclastic-sedimentary-rock

  • Concept URI token: silicate-mudstone

1.2.6.3.2.4.52 Calci-pebbly silicate-mudstone

  • Child of: silicate-mudstone

  • A silicate-mudstone containing calcaerous pebbly clasts.
