1.2.6.3.2.4.55 Kerogenic silicate-mudstone

  • Child of: silicate-mudstone

  • A silicate-mudstone containing up to 8% sapropelic matter rich in algae.

  • Concept URI token: kerogenic-silicate-mudstone

1.2.6.3.2.4.56 Marlstone

  • Child of: lime-mudstone silicate-mudstone

  • A lithified marl. An indurated rock of about the same composition as marl.

  • Alternate labels: carbonate rich mudstone, marlite,

  • Concept URI token: marlstone

1.2.6.3.2.4.57 Lime-rich silicate-mudstone

  • Child of: marlstone

  • A silicate-mudstone containing variable amounts of clays, silt and calcium carbonate. This is the mud-dominant end of what is known as marlstone.

  • Concept URI token: lime-rich-silicate-mudstone

1.2.6.3.2.4.58 Sapropelic silicate-mudstone

  • Child of: silicate-mudstone

  • A silicate-mudstone containing up to 8% sapropelic matter rich in miospores.

  • Concept URI token: sapropelic-silicate-mudstone

1.2.6.3.2.4.59 Silicate-claystone

  • Child of: claystone silicate-mudstone

  • A silicate-mudstone where at least 50% of the siliciclastic fragments are of clay grade (<4µm.)

  • Concept URI token: silicate-claystone

1.2.6.3.2.4.60 Silicate-siltstone

  • Child of: silicate-mudstone siltstone

  • A silicate-mudstone where at least 50% of the siliciclastic fragments are of silt grade (>4µm.)

  • Concept URI token: silicate-siltstone

1.2.6.3.2.4.61 Silici-pebbly silicate-mudstone

  • Child of: silicate-mudstone

  • A silicate-mudstone with siliciclastic pebbles.

  • Alternate labels: Pebbly Mudstone, Pellet Claystone,

  • Concept URI token: silici-pebbly-silicate-mudstone

1.2.6.3.2.4.62 Siltstone

  • Child of: mudstone

  • A mudstone with silt-grade clasts. An indurated silt having the texture and composition of shale but lacking its fine lamination or fissility; a massive mudstone in which the silt predominates over clay; a nonfissile silty shale. It tends to be flaggy, containing hard, durable, generally thin layers, and often showing various primary current structures.

  • Alternate labels: Siltite

  • Concept URI token: siltstone

1.2.6.3.2.4.63 calcisiltite

  • Child of: siltstone

  • A limestone consisting predominantly of detrital calcite particles of silt size; a consolidated calcareous silt.

  • Alternate labels: Calcareous Silt, Calcareous siltstone,

  • Concept URI token: calcisiltite

1.2.6.3.2.4.64 Carbonaceous Siltstone

  • Child of: carbonaceous-sedimentary-rock siltstone

  • Siltstone with a significant carbonaceuous fraction excluding coal fragments

  • Concept URI token: carbonaceous-siltstone

  • Child of: coaly-sedimentary-rock siltstone

  • Concept URI token: coaly-siltstone

1.2.6.3.2.4.66 Silicate-siltstone

  • Child of: silicate-mudstone siltstone

  • A silicate-mudstone where at least 50% of the siliciclastic fragments are of silt grade (>4µm.)

  • Concept URI token: silicate-siltstone

1.2.6.3.2.5 Olistostrome

  • Child of: clastic-sedimentary-rock

  • A sedimentary deposit composed of a chaotic mass of heterogeneous material, such as blocks and mud, known as olistoliths, that accumulates as a semifluid body by submarine gravity sliding or slumping of the unconsolidated sediments.

  • Concept URI token: olistostrome

1.2.6.3.2.6.15 Humic coal series

  • Child of: organic-rich-rock

  • The humic coal series develops from peat. Humic coals have a low hydrogen content.

  • Concept URI token: humic-coal-series

1.2.6.3.2.6.16 Coal

  • Child of: humic-coal-series

  • An organic-rich-rock with less than 50% ash (by weight air dried) or more than 50% organic matter.A sedimentary rock of organic origin consisting predominantly of carbonised plant remains.

  • Concept URI token: coal

1.2.6.3.2.6.17 Anthracite

  • Child of: coal

  • A coal with greater than 90% carbon content dry ash free and less than 14% volatiles.

  • Alternate labels: Anthracolite, Vitrite,

  • Concept URI token: anthracite

1.2.6.3.2.6.18 Bituminous-coal

  • Child of: coal

  • Colour:BlackA coal with between 75-90% carbon content dry ash free and between 14-46% volatiles.A ‘soft’ coal, often containing substantial admixed sulfur.It is of higher quality than lignite coal but of poorer quality than anthracite. The colour ranges from black to dark brown.

  • Alternate labels: Pechkohle

  • Concept URI token: bituminous-coal

1.2.6.3.2.6.19 Banded-bright-coal

  • Child of: bituminous-coal

  • A bright banded bituminous-coal.

  • Concept URI token: banded-bright-coal

1.2.6.3.2.6.20 Banded-coal

  • Child of: bituminous-coal

  • A banded bituminous-coal.

  • Concept URI token: banded-coal

1.2.6.3.2.6.21 Banded-dull-coal

  • Child of: bituminous-coal

  • A dull banded bituminous-coal.

  • Concept URI token: banded-dull-coal

1.2.6.3.2.6.22 Bright-coal

  • Child of: bituminous-coal

  • A bright bituminous-coal.

  • Concept URI token: bright-coal

1.2.6.3.2.6.23 Clarain

  • Child of: bituminous-coal

  • A finely laminated bituminous-coal with bright to semi-bright bands. Overall it has a silky lustre, often containing fine vitrain bands alternating with a duller attrital groundmass. It has a sheetlike, irregular fracture. It is distinguished from vitrain by containing fine intercalations of a duller lithotype, durain. Its characteristic microlithotype is clarite. Compare with: clarite, fusain, Vitrain

  • Concept URI token: clarain

1.2.6.3.2.6.24 Dull-coal

  • Child of: bituminous-coal

  • A dull bituminous-coal.

  • Concept URI token: dull-coal

1.2.6.3.2.6.25 Durain

  • Child of: bituminous-coal

  • Dark grey to black bands of bituminous-coal with a rough surface and a dull to slightly greasy lustre. In humic coals, durain occurs in bands up to many centimeters in thickness. Widely distributed, but with exceptions not abundant.

  • Concept URI token: durain

1.2.6.3.2.6.26 Fusain

  • Child of: bituminous-coal

  • A black, soft, friable bituminous-coal which closely resembles charcoal. A coal lithotype characterized macroscopically by its silky luster, fibrous structure, friability, and black color. It occurs in strands or patches and is soft and dirty where not mineralised. Its characteristic microlithotype is fusite. Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: fusain

1.2.6.3.2.6.27 Vitrain

  • Child of: bituminous-coal

  • A black, glassy vitreous bituminous-coal. It occurs as thin (usually 6-8mm) bands, closely jointed and breaks into cubic pieces with a conchoidal fracture.

  • Concept URI token: vitrain

1.2.6.3.2.6.28 carbankerite

  • Child of: coal

  • Any coal microlithotype containing 20% to 60% by volume of carbonate minerals (calcite, siderite, dolomite, and ankerite). Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: carbankerite

1.2.6.3.2.6.29 carbargilite

  • Child of: coal

  • Any coal microlithotype containing 20% to 60% by volume of clay minerals, mica, and in lesser proportions, quartz.

  • Concept URI token: carbargilite

1.2.6.3.2.6.30 gagatite

  • Child of: coal

  • A Jetlike coalified plant material preserving cellular structures.

  • Concept URI token: gagatite

1.2.6.3.2.6.31 Lignite

  • Child of: coal

  • A consolidated, dull, soft brown to black coal with visible plant fragments set in a finer grained matrix. 60-75% carbon content dry ash free, 46-63% volatiles.A carbon-poor and humidity-rich variety of coal which retains the structure of the original wood.It is often referred to as brown coal, and is considered the lowest rank of coal (carbon content is only around 25-35%).

  • Alternate labels: Brown Coal, fulvurite,

  • Concept URI token: lignite

1.2.6.3.2.6.32 Black-lignite

  • Child of: lignite

  • A dark brown to black lignite with a silky lustre. It is much harder than brown-lignite.

  • Concept URI token: black-lignite

1.2.6.3.2.6.33 Jet

  • Child of: black-lignite

  • A hard black-lignite regarded as a gemstone. Formed by decomposition of wood under extreme pressure.

  • Concept URI token: jet

1.2.6.3.2.6.34 Hard jet

  • Child of: jet

  • A harder form of jet, derived from carbon compression with salt water.

  • Concept URI token: hard-jet

1.2.6.3.2.6.35 Soft jet

  • Child of: jet

  • A softer form of jet, derived from carbon compression with fresh water.

  • Concept URI token: soft-jet

1.2.6.3.2.6.36 Brown-lignite

  • Child of: lignite

  • A brown lignite with a dull or earthy lusture; many are banded with a fibrous structure.

  • Concept URI token: brown-lignite

1.2.6.3.2.6.37 Quisqueite

  • Child of: lignite

  • A vanadium-rich variety of lignite. Also ‘a highly sulphurous asphaltum’ (spelling ‘Quiscqueite’). Originally described from Quisque District, Cerro de Pasco, Alcides Carrion Province, Pasco Department, Peru.

  • Concept URI token: quisqueite

1.2.6.3.2.6.38 Stipite

  • Child of: coal

  • An impure, pyritiferous coal.

  • Concept URI token: stipite

1.2.6.3.2.6.39 Impure-coal

  • Child of: humic-coal-series

  • An impure coal containing 15 to 50% ash (or 50 to 85% organic matter.) The lithified analogue of sandy-peat or muddy-peat.

  • Concept URI token: impure-coal

1.2.6.3.2.6.40 Bone-coal

  • Child of: impure-coal

  • An impure-coal with clay disseminated throughout the organic matter. It can be recognised by its dull appearance and grey streak.

  • Concept URI token: bone-coal

1.2.6.3.2.6.41 Sapropelic coal series

  • Child of: organic-rich-rock

  • A series of rocks developed from sapropel and with a high hydrogen content.

  • Concept URI token: sapropelic-coal-series

1.2.6.3.2.6.42 Canel-mudstone

  • Child of: sapropelic-coal-series

  • An inorganic sedimentary rock with between 8-50% sapropelic matter rich in miospores

  • Concept URI token: canel-mudstone

1.2.6.3.2.6.43 Sapropelic-coal

  • Child of: sapropelic-coal-series

  • Fine grained coal, faintly bedded to homogeneous and massive.

  • Concept URI token: sapropelic-coal

1.2.6.3.2.6.44 Boghead-cannel-coal

  • Child of: sapropelic-coal

  • An intermediate between cannel-coal and boghead-coal with miospores > alginite.

  • Concept URI token: boghead-cannel-coal

1.2.6.3.2.6.45 Boghead-coal

  • Child of: sapropelic-coal

  • A browner sapropelic-coal rich in alginite with little miospores.

  • Alternate labels: Torbanite, boghedite,

  • Concept URI token: boghead-coal

1.2.6.3.2.6.46 Cannel-boghead-coal

  • Child of: sapropelic-coal

  • An intermediate between cannel-coal and boghead-coal with alginite > miospores.

  • Concept URI token: cannel-boghead-coal

1.2.6.3.2.6.47 Cannel-coal

  • Child of: sapropelic-coal

  • A dull black, waxy lustre, homogeneous sapropelic-coal rich in miospores with very little alginite.

  • Concept URI token: cannel-coal

1.2.6.3.2.6.48 Sideritic cannel-coal

  • Child of: cannel-coal

  • A cannel-coal with abundant siderite (exceeding the clay minerals.)

  • Concept URI token: sideritic-cannel-coal

1.2.6.3.2.6.49 Wollongongite

  • Child of: cannel-coal

  • A name given by Professor Silliman (Yale College) to a variety of cannel-coal.

  • Concept URI token: wollongongite

1.2.6.3.2.6.50 Sapropelic-lignite

  • Child of: sapropelic-coal-series

  • Visually similar to lignite but with a higher hydrogen content.

  • Concept URI token: sapropelic-lignite

1.2.6.3.2.6.51 Sapropelite

  • Child of: sapropelic-coal-series shale

  • An inorganic sedimentary rock with between 8-50% sapropelic matter rich in alginite.

  • Alternate labels: Oil shale, Tar shale, hartleyite,

  • Concept URI token: sapropelite

1.2.6.3.2.6.52 Lamalginite

  • Child of: sapropelite

  • A sapropelite whrere algal matter occurs in very thin laminae cryptically interbedded with mineral matter.

  • Concept URI token: lamalginite

1.2.6.3.2.6.53 Telaginite

  • Child of: sapropelite

  • A sapropelite where organic matter is present in large discretely occurring algal bodies.

  • Concept URI token: telaginite

1.2.6.3.2.7 Polymict Breccia

  • Child of: clastic-sedimentary-rock

  • A gravel-grade clastic-sedimentary-rock with angular clasts of various rock types.

  • Alternate labels: Polymictic Breccia

  • Concept URI token: poly-breccia

1.2.6.3.2.8 Polymict Conglomerate

  • Child of: clastic-sedimentary-rock

  • Alternate labels: Poly conglomerate, Poly-conglomerate, Polymictic Conglomerate,

  • Concept URI token: poly-conglomerate

1.2.6.3.2.9 Sandstone

  • Child of: clastic-sedimentary-rock

  • A sand-grade clastic-sedimentary-rock.

  • Alternate labels: Sand-grade-sedimentary-rock

  • Concept URI token: sandstone

1.2.6.3.2.9.1 Aeolinite

  • Child of: aeolian-deposit sandstone

  • A cemented aeolian blown sand. consolidated sedimentary rock consisting of clastic material deposited by the wind; e.g., dune sand cemented below ground-water level by calcite. Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: aeolinite

1.2.6.3.2.9.2 Arenite

  • Child of: sandstone

  • A sandstone with less than 15% of fine-grained interstitial material. i. A general name for sedimentary rocks composed of sand- sized fragments irrespective of composition; ii. A clean sandstone that is well sorted, contains little or no matrix material, and has a relatively simple mineralogic composition; specif. a pure or nearly pure, chemically cemented sandstone containing less than 10% argillaceous matrix.

  • Alternate labels: Subgreywacke

  • Concept URI token: arenite

1.2.6.3.2.9.3 Silicate-arenite

  • Child of: arenite silicate-sandstone

  • A silicate-sandstone with less than 15% of fine-grained interstitial material.

  • Concept URI token: silicate-arenite

1.2.6.3.2.9.4 Feldspathic-arenite

  • Child of: silicate-arenite

  • An arenite where at least 25% of the interstitial material is feldspar and feldspar > rock fragments with the rest consiting of quartz.

  • Alternate labels: arkosic arenite

  • Concept URI token: feldspathic-arenite

1.2.6.3.2.9.5 Lithic-arenite

  • Child of: silicate-arenite

  • An arenite where at least 25% of the interstitial material is rock fragments and rock fragments > feldspar with the rest consiting of quartz.

  • Alternate labels: Lithic arenite, lithic sandstone,

  • Concept URI token: lithic-arenite

1.2.6.3.2.9.6 Quartz-arenite

  • Child of: silicate-arenite

  • An arenite where there is no more than 5% of feldspar and no more than 5% of rock fragments and the rest is quartz.

  • Alternate labels: Quartz arenite

  • Concept URI token: quartz-arenite

1.2.6.3.2.9.7 Subfeldspathic-arenite

  • Child of: silicate-arenite

  • An arenite where between 5% and 25% of the interstitial material is feldspar and feldspar > rock fragments and the rest made up of quartz.

  • Alternate labels: Subarkose

  • Concept URI token: subfeldspathic-arenite

1.2.6.3.2.9.8 Sublithic-arenite

  • Child of: silicate-arenite

  • An arenite where between 5% and 25% of the interstitial material is rock fragments and rock fragments > feldspar and the rest made up of quartz.

  • Alternate labels: sublith arenite, sublithic arenite,

  • Concept URI token: sublithic-arenite

1.2.6.3.2.9.9 Asphaltic sandstone

  • Child of: sandstone

  • A sandstone containing asphalt.

1.2.6.3.2.9.10 Argulite

1.2.6.3.2.9.11 Calcite-cemented sandstone

1.2.6.3.2.9.12 Carbonaceous Sandstone

  • Child of: carbonaceous-sedimentary-rock sandstone

1.2.6.3.2.9.13 Coaly Sandstone

  • Child of: coaly-sedimentary-rock sandstone

  • Sandstone with a significant fraction of coal fragments

  • Concept URI token: coaly-sandstone

1.2.6.3.2.9.14 Itacolumite

  • Child of: quartzite sandstone

  • A micaceous sandstone or a schistose quartzite that contains interstitial, loosely interlocking grains of mica, chlorite, and talc; exhibits flexibility when split into thin slabs. Type locality is Itacolumi Mountain in Minas Gerais, Brazil. Synonym of: flexible sandstone, articulite Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: itacolumite

1.2.6.3.2.9.15 Flexible sandstone

  • Child of: itacolumite

  • A fine-grained, thin-layered variety of itacolumite. Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: flexible-sandstone

1.2.6.3.2.9.16 Metaxite

  • Child of: sandstone

  • A micaceous sandstone

  • Alternate labels: Metaxite (of AGI)

  • Concept URI token: metaxite

1.2.6.3.2.9.17 Pebbly sandstone

  • Child of: sandstone

  • A sandstone containing pebbles.

  • Concept URI token: pebbly-sandstone

1.2.6.3.2.9.18 Sandrock

  • Child of: sandstone

  • A field term for a sandstone that is not firmly cemented. Mostly used in southern England for a sandstone that crumbles between the fingers. Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: sandrock

1.2.6.3.2.9.19 Silicate-sandstone

  • Child of: sandstone siliclastic-sedimentary-rock

  • A Siliclastic-sedimentary-rock with siliceous clasts predominantly in the 32µm to 2mm range, with less than 75% of the clasts smaller than 32µm and less than 25% of the clasts larger than 2mm.

  • Concept URI token: silicate-sandstone

1.2.6.3.2.9.20 Arkose

  • Child of: silicate-sandstone

  • A silicate-sandstone containing at least 25% feldspar derived from arkosic sand. A typically coarse-grained and pink or reddish feldspar- rich sandstone composed of angular to subangular grains that are poorly to moderately well sorted. Quartz is usually the dominant mineral, with feldspar (chiefly microcline) constituting at least 25%. Cement (silica or calcite) is commonly rare, and matrix material (usually less than 15%) includes clay minerals (esp. kaolinite), mica, and iron oxide; fine-grained rock fragments are often present.

  • Alternate labels: arcose

  • Concept URI token: arkose

1.2.6.3.2.9.21 Calcite-cemented silicate-sandstone

  • Child of: silicate-sandstone

  • A silicate-sandstone cemented by calcite

  • Concept URI token: calcite-cemented-silicate-sandstone

1.2.6.3.2.9.22 Feldspathic-sandstone

  • Child of: silicate-sandstone

  • A silicate-standstone where less than 75% of the siliclastic material is quartz, and the remainder is predominantly feldspar.

  • Concept URI token: feldspathic-sandstone

1.2.6.3.2.9.23 Gritstone

  • Child of: silicate-sandstone

  • A hard, coarse-grained, siliceous sandstone.

  • Alternate labels: Grits

  • Concept URI token: gritstone

1.2.6.3.2.9.24 Orthoquartzite

  • Child of: quartzite silicate-sandstone

  • An indurated silicate-sandstone that is made up almost exclusively of quartz sand (with or without chert), that is relatively free of or lacks a fine-grained matrix; a hard but unmetamorphosed ‘pure quartz sandstone’, derived by secondary silicification; a quartzite of sedimentary origin, or a pure quartz sandstone. Typically a sandstone comprising more than 90% to 95% detrital quartz and chert grains that are well-sorted, well-rounded, and cemented primarily with secondary quartz (sometimes with carbonate).

  • Concept URI token: orthoquartzite

1.2.6.3.2.9.25 Poorly-sorted silicate-sandstone

  • Child of: silicate-sandstone

  • A silicate-sandstone containing a wide range of grain sizes within the 32µm to 2mm range.

  • Concept URI token: poorly-sorted-silicate-sandstone

1.2.6.3.2.9.26 Quartzose sandstone

  • Child of: silicate-sandstone

  • A silicate-sandstone composed primarily of quartz.

  • Alternate labels: Quartz Sandstone

  • Concept URI token: quartzose-sandstone

1.2.6.3.2.9.27 Silica-cemented silicate-sandstone

  • Child of: silicate-sandstone

  • A silicate-sandstone cemented by silica.

  • Concept URI token: silica-cemented-silicate-sandstone

1.2.6.3.2.9.28 Silicate-arenite

  • Child of: arenite silicate-sandstone

  • A silicate-sandstone with less than 15% of fine-grained interstitial material.

  • Concept URI token: silicate-arenite

1.2.6.3.2.9.29 Feldspathic-arenite

  • Child of: silicate-sandstone wacke

  • A silicate-sandstone with 15% to 75% fine-grained interstitial material.

  • Concept URI token: silicate-wacke

1.2.6.3.2.9.35 Feldspathic-wacke

  • Concept URI token: feldspathic-wacke

1.2.6.3.2.9.36 Greywacke

  • Child of: silicate-wacke

  • A wacke generally consisting of poorly sorted angular grains of quartz, feldspar and lithic fragments set in a compact clay-rich matrix. Commonly applied to dark gray, firmly indurated, coarse- grained sandstone that consists of poorly sorted, angular to subangular grains of quartz and feldspar, with a variety of dark rock and mineral fragments embedded in a compact clayey matrix having the general composition of slate and containing an abundance of very fine- grained illite/sericite, and chlorite.

  • Alternate labels: Graywacke

  • Concept URI token: greywacke

1.2.6.3.2.9.39 Quartz-wacke

  • Alternate labels: Quartz wacke

  • Concept URI token: quartz-wacke

1.2.6.3.2.9.40 Wacke

  • Child of: sandstone

  • A sandstone with 15% to 75% fine-grained interstitial material.A dirty sandstone that consists of a mixed variety of angular and unsorted or poorly sorted mineral and rock fragments, and of an abundant matrix of clay and fine silt; specif. an impure sandstone containing more than 10% argillaceous matrix. The term is used for a major category of sandstone, as distinguished from arenite.

  • Alternate labels: clayey sandstone, vake,

  • Concept URI token: wacke

  • Concept URI token: volcaniclastic-wacke

1.2.6.3.2.10 Siliclastic-sedimentary-rock

  • Child of: clastic-sedimentary-rock

  • A clastic-sedimentary-rock derived from fragments of pre-existing siliceous rocks. They are mostly quartz-rich, but can be dominated by feldspar and lithic rock fragments. Lithic rocks are usually silica- rich, eg. siltstone, slate, etc.

  • Concept URI token: siliclastic-sedimentary-rock

1.2.6.3.2.10.1 Silicate-conglomerate

  • Child of: conglomerate siliclastic-sedimentary-rock

  • A sedimentary rock made up of at least 50% clastic fragments derived from pre-existing siliceous rocks, where at least 25% of the fragments are coarser than 2mm.

  • Concept URI token: silicate-conglomerate

1.2.6.3.2.10.2 Conglomeratic arkose

  • Child of: silicate-conglomerate

  • A silicate-conglomerate containing at least 25% feldspar.

  • Concept URI token: conglomeratic-arkose

1.2.6.3.2.10.3 Silica-cemented silicate-conglomerate

  • Child of: silicate-conglomerate

  • A silicate-conglomerate consisting of sand and gravel cemented into a hard mass by silica.

  • Concept URI token: silica-cemented-silicate-conglomerate

1.2.6.3.2.10.4 Silicate-diamictite

  • Child of: diamictite siliclastic-sedimentary-rock

  • A poorly-sorted siliclastic sedimentary rock containing a wide range of clast sizes.

  • Concept URI token: silicate-diamictite

1.2.6.3.2.10.5 Silicate-mudstone

  • Child of: mudstone siliclastic-sedimentary-rock

  • Siliciclastic sedimentary rock containing more than 50% siliciclastic fragments, of which at least 75% should be less than 32µm.

  • Concept URI token: silicate-mudstone

1.2.6.3.2.10.6 Calci-pebbly silicate-mudstone

  • Child of: silicate-mudstone

  • A silicate-mudstone containing calcaerous pebbly clasts.

  • Concept URI token: calci-pebbly-silicate-mudstone

1.2.6.3.2.10.7 Calciclastic silicate-mudstone

  • Child of: silicate-mudstone

  • A silicate-mudstone with calcite clasts.

  • Concept URI token: calciclastic-silicate-mudstone

1.2.6.3.2.10.8 Fissile silicate-mudstone

  • Child of: silicate-mudstone

  • A thin-laminated silicate-mudstone.

  • Concept URI token: fissile-silicate-mudstone

1.2.6.3.2.10.9 Kerogenic silicate-mudstone

  • Child of: silicate-mudstone

  • A silicate-mudstone containing up to 8% sapropelic matter rich in algae.

  • Concept URI token: kerogenic-silicate-mudstone

1.2.6.3.2.10.10 Marlstone

  • Child of: lime-mudstone silicate-mudstone

  • A lithified marl. An indurated rock of about the same composition as marl.

  • Alternate labels: carbonate rich mudstone, marlite,

  • Concept URI token: marlstone

1.2.6.3.2.10.11 Lime-rich silicate-mudstone

  • Child of: marlstone

  • A silicate-mudstone containing variable amounts of clays, silt and calcium carbonate. This is the mud-dominant end of what is known as marlstone.

  • Concept URI token: lime-rich-silicate-mudstone

1.2.6.3.2.10.12 Sapropelic silicate-mudstone

  • Child of: silicate-mudstone

  • A silicate-mudstone containing up to 8% sapropelic matter rich in miospores.

  • Concept URI token: sapropelic-silicate-mudstone

1.2.6.3.2.10.13 Silicate-claystone

  • Child of: claystone silicate-mudstone

  • A silicate-mudstone where at least 50% of the siliciclastic fragments are of clay grade (<4µm.)

  • Concept URI token: silicate-claystone

1.2.6.3.2.10.14 Silicate-siltstone

  • Child of: silicate-mudstone siltstone

  • A silicate-mudstone where at least 50% of the siliciclastic fragments are of silt grade (>4µm.)

  • Concept URI token: silicate-siltstone

1.2.6.3.2.10.15 Silici-pebbly silicate-mudstone

  • Child of: silicate-mudstone

  • A silicate-mudstone with siliciclastic pebbles.

  • Alternate labels: Pebbly Mudstone, Pellet Claystone,

  • Concept URI token: silici-pebbly-silicate-mudstone

1.2.6.3.2.10.16 Silicate-sandstone

  • Child of: sandstone siliclastic-sedimentary-rock

  • A Siliclastic-sedimentary-rock with siliceous clasts predominantly in the 32µm to 2mm range, with less than 75% of the clasts smaller than 32µm and less than 25% of the clasts larger than 2mm.

  • Concept URI token: silicate-sandstone

1.2.6.3.2.10.17 Arkose

  • Child of: silicate-sandstone

  • A silicate-sandstone containing at least 25% feldspar derived from arkosic sand. A typically coarse-grained and pink or reddish feldspar- rich sandstone composed of angular to subangular grains that are poorly to moderately well sorted. Quartz is usually the dominant mineral, with feldspar (chiefly microcline) constituting at least 25%. Cement (silica or calcite) is commonly rare, and matrix material (usually less than 15%) includes clay minerals (esp. kaolinite), mica, and iron oxide; fine-grained rock fragments are often present.

  • Alternate labels: arcose

  • Concept URI token: arkose

1.2.6.3.2.10.18 Calcite-cemented silicate-sandstone

  • Child of: silicate-sandstone

  • A silicate-sandstone cemented by calcite

  • Concept URI token: calcite-cemented-silicate-sandstone

1.2.6.3.2.10.19 Feldspathic-sandstone

  • Child of: silicate-sandstone

  • A silicate-standstone where less than 75% of the siliclastic material is quartz, and the remainder is predominantly feldspar.

  • Concept URI token: feldspathic-sandstone

1.2.6.3.2.10.20 Gritstone

  • Child of: silicate-sandstone

  • A hard, coarse-grained, siliceous sandstone.

  • Alternate labels: Grits

  • Concept URI token: gritstone

1.2.6.3.2.10.21 Orthoquartzite

  • Child of: quartzite silicate-sandstone

  • An indurated silicate-sandstone that is made up almost exclusively of quartz sand (with or without chert), that is relatively free of or lacks a fine-grained matrix; a hard but unmetamorphosed ‘pure quartz sandstone’, derived by secondary silicification; a quartzite of sedimentary origin, or a pure quartz sandstone. Typically a sandstone comprising more than 90% to 95% detrital quartz and chert grains that are well-sorted, well-rounded, and cemented primarily with secondary quartz (sometimes with carbonate).

  • Concept URI token: orthoquartzite

1.2.6.3.2.10.22 Poorly-sorted silicate-sandstone

  • Child of: silicate-sandstone

  • A silicate-sandstone containing a wide range of grain sizes within the 32µm to 2mm range.

  • Concept URI token: poorly-sorted-silicate-sandstone

1.2.6.3.2.10.23 Quartzose sandstone

  • Child of: silicate-sandstone

1.2.6.3.2.12 Volcaniclastic-conglomerate

  • Child of: clastic-sedimentary-rock volcaniclastic-sedimentary-rock

  • Concept URI token: volcaniclastic-conglomerate

1.2.6.3.3 Hybrid-sedimentary-rock

  • Child of: sedimentary-rock

  • A sedimentary rock comprising three or more components, each of which form more than 5% but less than 50% of the total.

  • Concept URI token: hybrid-sedimentary-rock

1.2.6.3.4 Volcaniclastic rock

  • Child of: sedimentary-rock

  • Rocks composed in part or entirely of volcanic fragments, formed by any particle-forming mechanism (e.g. pyroclastic, hydroclastic, epiclastic, autoclastic, transported by any mechanism, deposited in any physiogeographic environment or mixed with any other volcaniclastic type or with any nonvolcanic fragment types in any proportion. Typically a volcaniclastic rock or sediment must have more than 10% by volume of volcanic debris. Volcanic debris is defined as fragments originating by volcanic processes, either primary or after redeposition.

  • Alternate labels: Volcaniclastic, Volcaniclastics,

  • Concept URI token: volcaniclastic-rock

1.2.6.3.4.1 Tuffaceous-sedimentary-rock

  • Child of: tuffite volcaniclastic-rock

  • Lithified volcaniclastic rock consisting of between 25% and 75% by volume of pyroclastic fragments.

  • Concept URI token: tuffaceous-sedimentary-rock

1.2.6.3.4.1.1 Tuffaceous-breccia

  • Child of: breccia tuffaceous-sedimentary-rock

  • A gravel-grade tuffaceous-rock with mostly angular clasts.

  • Concept URI token: tuffaceous-breccia

1.2.6.3.4.1.2 Tuffaceous-conglomerate

  • Child of: clastic-sedimentary-rock tuffaceous-sedimentary-rock

  • A gravel-grade tuffaceous-rock with mostly rounded clasts.

  • Concept URI token: tuffaceous-conglomerate
