1.2.7 Superficial deposit

  • Child of: rock

  • The most recent of geological formations; unconsolidated detrital material lying on or near the surface, generally unstratified.

  • Alternate labels: Grus, Sheetwash,

  • Concept URI token: superficial-deposit

1.2.7.1 Aeolian deposit

  • Child of: superficial-deposit

  • The most recent of geological formations; unconsolidated detrital material lying on or near the surface, generally unstratified.

  • Concept URI token: aeolian-deposit

1.2.7.1.1 Aeolinite

  • Child of: aeolian-deposit sandstone

  • A cemented aeolian blown sand. consolidated sedimentary rock consisting of clastic material deposited by the wind; e.g., dune sand cemented below ground-water level by calcite. Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: aeolinite

1.2.7.1.2 Blown sand

  • Child of: aeolian-deposit sand

  • Aeolian sands are primarliy wind-blown fine to medium, non-plastic and uniformly graded materials present in many sandy sites, mainly in desert areas.

  • Alternate labels: Aeolian Sand, Aeolian Sands, Eolian Sand, Eolian Sands,

  • Concept URI token: blown-sand

1.2.7.1.2.1 Beach dune sand

  • Child of: blown-sand

  • Unconsolidated sand resulting from accumulation in a beach dune system.

  • Alternate labels: Dune Sand

  • Concept URI token: beach-dune-sand

1.2.7.1.2.2 Coversand

  • Child of: blown-sand

  • Layers of sand deposited by wind action across areas of countryside to provide a cover deposit over any exposed ground surface or vegetation. Source: Oxford Reference.

  • Concept URI token: coversand

1.2.7.1.2.3 Niveo-aeolian sand

  • Child of: blown-sand

  • Snow- and wind-driven sand.

  • Concept URI token: niveo-aeolian-sand

1.2.7.1.3 Loess

  • Child of: aeolian-deposit

  • A clastic, predominantly silt-sized sediment that is formed by the accumulation of wind-blown dust. A widespread, nonstratified, porous, friable, usually highly calcareous, blanket deposit (generally less than 30 m thick), consisting predominantly of silt with subordinate grain sizes ranging from clay to fine sand.

  • Concept URI token: loess

1.2.7.1.3.1 Non-glacial loess

  • Child of: loess

  • Non-glacial loess can originate from deserts, dune fields, playa lakes, and volcanic ash.

  • Concept URI token: non-glacial-loess

1.2.7.1.3.2 Periglacial loess

  • Child of: loess

  • A loess deposited under cold, dry, peri- or postglacial conditions.

  • Concept URI token: periglacial-loess

1.2.7.2 Alluvial deposit

  • Child of: superficial-deposit

  • A term encompassing unconsolidated detrital material, deposited during comparatively recent geologic time by a stream or other body of running water, and A driller’s term for the broken, earthy rock material directly below the soil layer and above the solid, unbroken bed or ledge rock. Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: alluvial-deposit

1.2.7.2.1 Alluvium

  • Child of: alluvial-deposit

  • A general term for clay, silt, sand, gravel, or similar unconsolidated detrital material, deposited during comparatively recent geologic time by a stream or other body of running water, (1) as sediment in the bed of the stream or on its flood plain or delta,

  1. as a cone or fan at the base of a mountain slope; esp., such a deposit of fine-grained texture (silt or silty clay) deposited during time of flood. Ref: AGI

  • Alternate labels: alluvion

  • Concept URI token: alluvium

1.2.7.2.1.1 Geest

  • Child of: alluvium

  • Alluvial material that is not of recent origin lying on the surface. An example is the sandy region of the North Sea coast in Germany. Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: geest

1.2.7.3 Biological deposit

  • Child of: superficial-deposit

  • A superficial deposit of Biological origin.

  • Concept URI token: biological-deposit

1.2.7.3.1 Diatomite

  • Child of: biogenic-siliceous-rock biological-deposit

  • A siliceous-rock composed predominantly of diatoms and with porosity greater than 50%.

  • Alternate labels: Diatomaceous Earth

  • Concept URI token: diatomite

1.2.7.3.2 Shell marl

  • Child of: biological-deposit

    1. A sandy, clayey, or limy deposit, loose or weakly consolidated, containing abundant molluscan shells; a common term in the coastal plain of the Southeastern United States. Ref: AGI ii. A light-colored calcareous deposit formed on the bottoms of small freshwater lakes, composed largely of uncemented mollusk shells and precipitated calcium carbonate, along with the hard parts of minute organisms. Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: shell-marl

1.2.7.4 Chemical deposit

  • Child of: superficial-deposit

  • A superfical desposit of chemically derived origin.

  • Concept URI token: chemical-deposit

1.2.7.4.1 Bog ironstone

  • Child of: chemical-deposit ironstone

  • A soft and porous deposit of limonite, impregnated with plant debris, clay and clastic material. It is formed in bogs, marshes and shallow lakes by precipitation from iron-bearing waters and by the oxidising action of algae, iron bacteria or the atmosphere. Sometimes used as an iron ore. Ref: Pryor, Schieferdecker

  • Concept URI token: bog-ironstone

1.2.7.4.2 Sinter

  • Child of: chemical-deposit siliceous-rock

  • Also used for any chemical sedimentary rock deposited as a hard incrustation on rocks or on the ground by precipitation from hot or cold mineral waters in springs, lakes, or streams; specif. siliceous sinter and calcareous sinter (travertine). The term is indefinite and should be modified by the proper compositional adj., although when used alone it usually signifies siliceous sinter.

  • Concept URI token: sinter

1.2.7.4.2.1 Geyserite

  • Child of: sinter

  • An opaline sinter that is often found around hot springs and geysers.

  • Alternate labels: Terpizite

  • Concept URI token: geyserite

1.2.7.4.2.1.1 Fiorite

  • Child of: geyserite

  • A botryoidal form of geyserite.

  • Concept URI token: fiorite

1.2.7.4.2.2 Siliceous sinter

  • Child of: sinter

  • A silica rock deposited from rapidly cooling watery solutions. Often irregularily laminated, but also sponge-like or massive. May form contiguous crusts or isolated, often rounded bodies. Usually made of opal (opal-AG, opal-CT), but may also contain or be exclusively made of chalcedony. Silicious sinter forms at hot springs, but silicious rocks of similar texture and composition can form under comparable conditions in subsurface veins and are sometimes also called silicious sinter.

  • Concept URI token: siliceous-sinter

1.2.7.4.3 Travertine

  • Child of: chemical-deposit limestone

  • A limestone formed by hot mineral springs.

  • Concept URI token: travertine

1.2.7.4.4 Tufa

  • Child of: chemical-deposit limestone

  • A limestone formed when carbonate minerals precipitate out of ambient temperature water. A chemical sedimentary rock composed of calcium carbonate, formed by evaporation as a surficial, spongy, porous, semifriable incrustation around the mouth of a hot or cold spring or seep, or along a stream carrying calcium carbonate in solution, and exceptionally as a thick, bulbous, concretionary or compact deposit in a lake or along its shore. It may also be precipitated by algae or bacteria. The hard, dense variety is travertine.

  • Concept URI token: tufa

1.2.7.5 Coastal zone deposit

  • Child of: superficial-deposit

  • A superficial, unconsolidated deposit occuring in a coastal zone.

  • Concept URI token: coastal-zone-deposit

1.2.7.5.1 Beach sand

  • Child of: coastal-zone-deposit

  • A coastal sand often composed of both rock and shell fragments.

  • Concept URI token: beach-sand

1.2.7.6 Colluvium

  • Child of: superficial-deposit

  • Loose, unconsolidated sediments that have been deposited at the base of hillslopes by either rainwash, sheetwash, slow continuous downslope creep, or a variable combination of these processes.

  • Alternate labels: Scree

  • Concept URI token: colluvium

1.2.7.7 Glacigenic deposit

  • Child of: superficial-deposit

  • A superficial deposit of Glacial origin.

  • Concept URI token: glacigenic-deposit

1.2.7.7.1 Glacitectonite

  • Child of: glacigenic-deposit

  • Rock or sediment that has been deformed by subglacial shearing/deformation but retains some of the structural characteristics of the parent material.

  • Concept URI token: glacitectonite

1.2.7.7.2 Till

  • Child of: diamicton glacigenic-deposit

  • Unsorted clastic sediment, often full of boulders, sand, silt and clay, formed from the ground moraine material of glaciers. A stiff, hard, and usually unstratified clay or Glacial drift that contains boulders scattered through it. Also called boulder clay; hardpan; drift clay.

  • Alternate labels: Boulder clay, glacial till, ice-laid drift,

  • Concept URI token: till

1.2.7.8 Lacustrine deposit

  • Child of: superficial-deposit

  • Unconsolidated detrital sedimentary material deposited in a lake environment

  • Alternate labels: Lacustrine sediments, lake sediment,

  • Concept URI token: lacustrine-deposit

1.2.7.9 Organic deposit

  • Child of: superficial-deposit

  • A rock or other deposit formed by organisms or their remains.

  • Concept URI token: organic-deposit

1.2.7.9.1 Peat

  • Child of: organic-deposit organic-rich-sediment

  • An unlithified heterogeneous mixture of a wide range of plant debris. It has a carbon content of less than 60% dry ash free and a volatile content of greater than 63%.

  • Concept URI token: peat

1.2.7.9.1.1 Basin peat

  • Child of: peat

  • A peat derived from an inundated basin.

  • Concept URI token: basin-peat

1.2.7.9.1.2 Birch bog peat

  • Child of: peat

  • A peat derived from a birch dominated bog.

  • Concept URI token: birch-bog-peat

1.2.7.9.1.3 Blanket peat

  • Child of: peat

  • A peat derived from a blanket bog, an area of peatland, forming where there is a climate of high rainfall and a low level of evapotranspiration, allowing peat to develop not only in wet hollows but over large expanses of undulating ground.

  • Concept URI token: blanket-peat

1.2.7.9.1.4 Cladium peat

  • Child of: peat

  • A peat derived from a Cladium dominated ecosystem.

  • Concept URI token: cladium-peat

1.2.7.9.1.5 Fen peat

  • Child of: peat

  • A peat derived from a fen.

  • Concept URI token: fen-peat

1.2.7.9.1.6 Fen-wood peat

  • Child of: peat

  • A peat derived from a fen-wood.

  • Concept URI token: fen-wood-peat

1.2.7.9.1.7 Gyttja

  • Child of: peat

  • Sediment rich in organic matter deposited at the bottom of a eutrophic lake.

  • Alternate labels: Shell-rich gyttja

  • Concept URI token: gyttja

1.2.7.9.1.8 Hill peat

  • Child of: peat

  • Peat formed in mountainous districts and characterized by the presence of Sphagnum, Andromeda, heath, pine trees, etc. Ref: Tomkeieff

  • Concept URI token: hill-peat

1.2.7.9.1.9 Magnocaricetum peat

  • Child of: peat

  • Peat derived from Magnocaricetum sedges.

  • Concept URI token: magnocaricetum-peat

1.2.7.9.1.10 Moss peat

  • Child of: peat

  • Peat derived from water-loving mosses, chiefly sphagnum. See Also: highmoor peat

  • Concept URI token: moss-peat

1.2.7.9.1.11 Parvocaricetum peat

  • Child of: peat

  • A peat produced from the Parvocaricetum plant type.

  • Concept URI token: parvocaricetum-peat

1.2.7.9.1.12 Phragmites peat

  • Child of: peat

  • Peat composed of reed grass and other grasses. Ref: Tomkeieff

  • Concept URI token: phragmites-peat

1.2.7.9.1.13 Raised bog peat

  • Child of: peat

  • A peat that was produced from a raised bog.

  • Concept URI token: raised-bog-peat

1.2.7.9.1.14 Shrub bog peat

  • Child of: peat

  • A peat produced from a shrub bog.

  • Concept URI token: shrub-bog-peat

1.2.7.9.1.15 Sphagnum cuspidatum peat

  • Child of: peat

  • A peat produced from a Sphagnum cuspidatum plant type.

  • Concept URI token: sphagnum-cuspidatum-peat

1.2.7.10 Residual deposit

  • Child of: superficial-deposit

  • Rocks formed by the pedogenic weathering of primary rock.

  • Alternate labels: Eluvium

  • Concept URI token: residual-deposit

1.2.7.10.1 Clay-with-flints

  • Child of: clay residual-deposit

  • The name given by W. Whitaker in 1861 to a peculiar deposit of stiff red, brown or yellow clay containing unworn whole flints as well as angular shattered fragments, also with a variable admixture of rounded flint, quartz, quartzite and other pebbles.

  • Concept URI token: clay-with-flints

1.2.7.10.2 Duricrust

  • Child of: residual-deposit

  • A general term for a hard crust on the surface of, or layer in the upper horizons of, a soil in a semiarid climate. It is formed by the accumulation of soluble minerals deposited by mineral-bearing waters that move upward by capillary action and evaporate during the dry season.

  • Alternate labels: Billy

  • Concept URI token: duricrust

1.2.7.10.2.1 Caliche

  • Child of: carbonate-rock duricrust

  • A reddish brown to white calcareous material of secondary accumulation, commonly found in layers on or near the surface of stony soils of arid and semiarid regions, but also occurring as a subsoil deposit in subhumid climates. It may occur as a thin, friable horizon within the soil, but more commonly it is up to a metre or more in thickness, impermeable and strongly indurated. It is composed largely of a calcareous cement, in addition to such materials as gravel sand and mud.

  • Concept URI token: caliche

1.2.7.10.2.1.1 Calcrete

  • Child of: caliche conglomerate

  • Etymol: ‘cal’careous + con’crete.’ .A calcareous duricrust, caliche or calcitic conglomerate consisting of surficial sand and gravel cemented into a hard mass by calcium carbonate precipitated from solution and redeposited through the agency of infiltrating waters, or deposited by the escape of carbon dioxide from vadose water.ii. A calcareous duricrust; caliche. Compare with: silcrete, ferricrete

  • Alternate labels: Kunkar

  • Concept URI token: calcrete

1.2.7.10.2.2 Ferricrete

  • Child of: duricrust laterite

  • A laterite or conglomerate consisting of surficial sand and gravel cemented into a hard mass by iron oxide derived from the oxidation of percolating solutions of iron salts. Also see duricrust. i. A conglomerate consisting of surficial sand and gravel cemented into a hard mass by iron oxide derived from the oxidation of percolating solutions of iron salts.ii. A ferruginous duricrust.

  • Concept URI token: ferricrete

1.2.7.10.2.3 Gossan

  • Child of: duricrust

  • An iron and manganese-bearing weathered product overlying a sulfide deposit. It is formed by the oxidation and leaching-out of sulfides and carbonates, with the loss of the sulfur and most metals, leaving hydrated iron and manganese oxides, quartz and relatively insoluble minerals. Also spelled gozzan.

  • Concept URI token: gossan

1.2.7.10.2.4 Silcrete

  • Child of: duricrust

  • A conglomerate or sandstone consisting of surficial sand and gravel cemented into a hard mass by silica. A siliceous duricrust.

  • Concept URI token: silcrete

1.2.7.10.3 Laterite

  • Child of: residual-deposit

  • A highly weathered, generally indurated, red subsoil nearly devoid of primary silicates, rich in hydrous iron oxides, +/- kaolinite +/- quartz +/- gibbsite.Red residual soil developed in humid, tropical, and subtropical regions of good drainage. It is leached of silica and contains concentrations particularly of iron oxides and hydroxides and aluminum hydroxides. It may be an ore of iron, aluminum, manganese, or nickel. Adj. lateritic.

  • Alternate labels: latosol

  • Concept URI token: laterite

1.2.7.10.3.1 Bauxite

  • Child of: laterite

  • Named after the locality at Baux (or Beaux), near St. Reny, Bouches- du-Rhone, France. Predominantly hydrated aluminium oxides with iron oxides, kaolinite and other impurities; almost always a residual soil rather than a sediment. A mixture, and rock, comprised of iron and aluminium Hydroxides/Oxides. The primary ore of aluminium.

  • Alternate labels: Alcrete, Beauxite, Cliachite, Kliachite, Kljakite, Wocheinite,

  • Concept URI token: bauxite

1.2.7.10.3.1.1 Bauxitic soil

  • Child of: bauxite

  • A residual soil formed through lateritic processes rich in aluminium and iron oxides.

  • Alternate labels: bauxite soil, bauxite-soil, bauxitic soil,

  • Concept URI token: bauxitic-soil

1.2.7.10.3.1.2 Karst bauxite

  • Child of: bauxite

  • Formed in karst depressions in limestone plateaux, aluminium hydroxides are derived from altered bentonitic clays.

  • Concept URI token: karst-bauxite

1.2.7.10.3.2 Ferricrete

  • Child of: duricrust laterite

  • A laterite or conglomerate consisting of surficial sand and gravel cemented into a hard mass by iron oxide derived from the oxidation of percolating solutions of iron salts. Also see duricrust. i. A conglomerate consisting of surficial sand and gravel cemented into a hard mass by iron oxide derived from the oxidation of percolating solutions of iron salts.ii. A ferruginous duricrust.

  • Concept URI token: ferricrete

1.2.7.10.4 manganolite

  • Child of: residual-deposit

  • A general term for rocks composed of manganese minerals, esp. manganese oxides such as wad and psilomelane.

  • Concept URI token: manganolite

1.2.7.10.5 Palaeosol

  • Child of: residual-deposit

  • A fossil soil horizon found in sedimntary rocks

  • Alternate labels: Paleosol

  • Concept URI token: palaeosol

1.2.7.10.5.1 Seat earth

  • Child of: palaeosol

  • A bed of rock underlying a coal seam, representing an old soil that supported the vegetation from which the coal was formed; specif. underclay. A highly siliceous seat earth is known locally as ganister. Ref: AGI

  • Alternate labels: Seat-earth, seatearth,

  • Concept URI token: seat-earth

1.2.7.10.5.1.1 Ganister

  • Child of: seat-earth

  • A hard, fine-grained, quartz-arenite, cemented with silica and possessing a splintery fracture, used in the manufacture of silica brick. Ganister is distinguished from chert by its more granular texture and by the relatively small quantity of chalcedonic or amorphous silica. Ref.: Chambers s Mineralogical Dictionary (1964) Chemical Publishing Co., Inc., New York, NY, USA (reprint).

  • Concept URI token: ganister

1.2.7.10.6 Regolith

  • Child of: residual-deposit

  • The layer or mantle of loose incoherent rock material, of whatever origin, that nearly everywhere underlies the surface of the land and rests on solid bedrock. It comprises: volcanic ash, glacial drift, alluvium, windblown deposits, organic accumulations, soils and rock waste.

  • Alternate labels: Blanket head, Mantle rock,

  • Concept URI token: regolith

1.2.7.10.6.1 Saprolite

  • Child of: regolith

  • A highly to completely weathered rock which has been altered and decomposed by chemical processes but retains textural and structural features of the parent material. A soft, earthy, typically clay-rich, thoroughly decomposed rock, formed in place by chemical weathering of igneous, sedimentary, and metamorphic rocks. Saprolite is characterized by preservation of structures that were present in the unweathered rock.

  • Alternate labels: Saprock, Saprolith, sathrolith,

  • Concept URI token: saprolite

1.2.7.11 Soil

  • Child of: superficial-deposit

    1. All unconsolidated materials above bedrock. This is the meaning of the term as used by early geologists and in some recent geologic reports, and has been vigorously advocated by Legget (1967, 1973). It is the common usage among engineering geologists (see, e.g., compaction; soil mechanics). In recent years the approx. syn. regolith has come into wide geological use.ii. The natural medium for growth of land plants.

  • Concept URI token: soil

1.2.7.11.1 Alfisol

  • Child of: soil

  • A USDA soil classification: Must have argillic, natric, or kandic horizon; High-to-medium base saturation; Moderately weathered; Commonly form under boreal or broadleaf forests; Rich in iron and aluminum. It is common in humid areas, semi-tropics, and mediterranean climates.

  • Concept URI token: alfisol

1.2.7.11.2 Andisol

  • Child of: soil

  • Form from volcanic ejecta, dominated by allophane or Al-humic complexes; Must have andic soil properties: high in poorly crystalline Fe and Al minerals, high in phosphorus, low bulk density, and high proportions of glass and amorphous colloidal materials, such as allophane, imogolite and ferrihydrite; High Organic Matter content, sometimes melanic epipedon.

  • Concept URI token: andisol

1.2.7.11.3 Anthroposol

  • Child of: soil

  • Soils resulting from human activities. Australian Soil Classification - CSIRO.

  • Concept URI token: anthroposol

1.2.7.11.4 Aridisol

  • Child of: soil

  • Dry soil (i.e., must have aridic moisture regime); Ochric epipedon is common; Sometimes argillic or natric horizon; Must have some diagnostic subsurface horizon; Commonly in deserts.

  • Concept URI token: aridisol

1.2.7.11.5 Calcarosol

  • Child of: soil

  • Non-chromosol soils that are either calcareous throughout the solum

  • or calcareous at least directly below the A1 or Ap horizon, or within a depth of 0.2 m (whichever is shallower). Carbonate accumulations must be judged to be pedogenic, ie. are a result of soil forming processes in situ (either current or relict) in contrast to fragments of calcareous rock such as limestone or shell fragments. Australian Soil Classification - CSIRO.

  • Concept URI token: calcarosol

1.2.7.11.6 Chromosol

  • Child of: soil

  • Non-sodosol soils with a clear or abrupt textural B horizon and in which the major part1 of the upper 0.2 m of the B2 horizon (or the major part of the entire B2 horizon if it is less than 0.2 m thick) is not strongly acid. Australian Soil Classification - CSIRO.

  • Concept URI token: chromosol

1.2.7.11.7 Clay loam

  • Child of: soil

    1. A fine-textured soil that breaks into clods or lumps that are hard when dry. When the moist soil is pinched between the thumb and finger, it will form a thin ribbon that will break readily, barely sustaining its own weight. The moist soil is plastic and will form a cast that will bear much handling. When kneaded in the hand, it does not crumble readily but tends to work into a heavy compact mass. Ref: Stokes ii. A soil containing 27% to 40% clay, 20% to 45% sand, and the remainder silt. (Ref. Soil Texture types (USDA))

  • Concept URI token: clay-loam

1.2.7.11.8 Clay soil

  • Child of: soil

  • A soil containing over 25% clay. A fine-grained soil, made up largely of clay or silt. Ref: Nichols, 1

  • Concept URI token: clay-soil

1.2.7.11.9 Dermosol

  • Child of: soil

  • Non-Ferrosols with B2 horizons that have structure more developed than weak throughout the major part of the horizon. Australian Soil Classification - CSIRO.

  • Concept URI token: dermosol

1.2.7.11.10 Entisol

  • Child of: soil

  • Least soil profile development; Ochric epipedon is common; No B horizons; most common order by surface area.

  • Concept URI token: entisol

1.2.7.11.11 Ferrosol

  • Child of: soil

  • Non-calcarosols with B2 horizons in which the major part has a free iron oxide content greater than 5% Fe in the fine earth fraction (<2 mm). Soils with a B2 horizon in which at least 0.3m has vertic properties are excluded. Australian Soil Classification - CSIRO.

  • Concept URI token: ferrosol

1.2.7.11.12 Gelisol

  • Child of: soil

  • Soils with permafrost within 100 cm or cryoturbation (frost churning) within 100 cm plus permafrost within 200 cm; Commonly at high latitudes and elevations;

  • Concept URI token: gelisol

1.2.7.11.13 Histosol

  • Child of: soil

  • Must have histic epipedon; Usually aquic soil moisture regime; No diagnostic subsurface horizons; Rapid decomposition when aerated; Peat or bog; >20% organic matter; Organic soil materials extending down to an impermeable layer or with an organic layer that is more than 40 cm thick and without andic properties Commonly in wetlands (swamps, marshes, etc.).

  • Concept URI token: histosol

1.2.7.11.14 Hydrosol

  • Child of: soil

  • Non-vertosol soils that are saturated in the major part of the solum for at least 2-3 months in most years (ie. includes tidal waters). Australian Soil Classification - CSIRO.

  • Concept URI token: hydrosol

1.2.7.11.15 Inceptisol

  • Child of: soil

  • Similar to Entisol, but beginning of a B horizon is evident; No diagnostic subsurface horizons; On landscapes continuously eroded or young deposits; Cambic, sulfuric, calcic, gypsic, petrocalcic, or petrogypsic horizon, or with a mollic, umbric, or histic epipedon, or with an exchangeable sodium percentage of >15% or fragipan;

  • Concept URI token: inceptisol

1.2.7.11.16 Kandosol

  • Child of: soil

  • Non-dermosols that, a) Have well-developed B2 horizons in which the major part1 is massive or has only a weak grade of structure, (compare with tenic B horizon and cemented pans), and b) have a maximum clay content in some part of the B2 horizon which exceeds 15% (ie. heavy sandy loam, SL+). Australian Soil Classification - CSIRO.

  • Concept URI token: kandosol

1.2.7.11.17 Kurosol

  • Child of: soil

  • Non-hydrosol soils with a clear or abrupt textural B horizon and in which the major part1 of the upper 0.2 m of the B2 horizon (or the major part of the entire B2 horizon if it is less than 0.2 m thick) is strongly acid. Australian Soil Classification - CSIRO.

  • Concept URI token: kuroosol

1.2.7.11.18 Lime-rich soil

  • Child of: soil

  • A synonym of Chalky soil.

  • Concept URI token: lime-rich-soil

1.2.7.11.19 Loam

  • Child of: soil

  • Loam is soil composed mostly of sand, silt, and a smaller amount of clay. By weight, its mineral composition is about 40-40-20% concentration of sand-silt-clay, respectively.

  • Concept URI token: loam

1.2.7.11.20 Loamy sand

  • Child of: soil

  • This soil type is normally made up of sand mixed with a majority of silt and clay. It consists of less than 50 percent of fine or very fine particles, more than 25 percent of medium particles, and less than 25 percent of the two coarsest particle types..

  • Concept URI token: loamy-sand

1.2.7.11.21 Mollisol

  • Child of: soil

  • Must have mollic epipedon; High base saturation of >50%; Dark soils; Some with argillic or natric horizons; Common in grasslands.

  • Concept URI token: mollisol

1.2.7.11.22 Organosol

  • Child of: soil

  • Soils that are not regularly inundated by saline tidal waters and either: a) Have more than 0.4 m of organic materials within the upper 0.8 m. The required thickness may either extend down from the surface or be taken cumulatively within the upper 0.8 m; or b) Have organic materials extending from the surface to a minimum depth of 0.1 m; these either directly overlie rock or other hard layers, partially weathered or decomposed rock or saprolite, or overlie fragmental material such as gravel, cobbles or stones in which the interstices are filled or partially filled with organic material. In some soils there may be layers of humose and/or melacic horizon material underlying the organic materials and overlying the substrate. Australian Soil Classification - CSIRO.

  • Concept URI token: organosol

1.2.7.11.23 Oxisol

  • Child of: soil

  • Most soil profile development; Must have oxic horizon within 150 cm of soil surface; Low nutrient availability; No argillic horizon; Highly weathered; Dominated by end-member clays, Al and Fe oxides; Commonly in old landscapes in tropics. Most bauxite deposits are found in this type of soil.

  • Concept URI token: oxisol

1.2.7.11.24 Podosol

  • Child of: soil

  • Non-organosol soils that have a Bs, Bhs or Bh horizon.Australian Soil Classification - CSIRO.

  • Concept URI token: podosol

1.2.7.11.25 Rudosol

  • Child of: soil

  • Non-Kandosols with negligible (rudimentary) pedological organisation apart from the minimal development of an A1 horizon or the presence of less than 10% of B horizon material (including pedogenic carbonate) in fissures in the parent rock or saprolite. The soils are apedal or only weakly structured in the A1 horizon and show no pedological colour change apart from darkening of an A1 horizon. There is little or no texture or colour change with depth unless stratified or buried soils are present. Cemented pans may be present as a substrate material. Australian Soil Classification - CSIRO.

  • Concept URI token: rudosol

1.2.7.11.26 Sandy clay loam

  • Child of: soil

  • A soil with between 20 and 35% clay, less than 30% silt, and 60 to 90% sand.

  • Concept URI token: sandy-clay-loam

1.2.7.11.27 Sandy clay soil

  • Child of: soil

  • A soil with high porportions of sand and clay.

  • Concept URI token: sandy-clay-soil

1.2.7.11.28 Sandy loam

  • Child of: soil

  • A soil with predominantly sand relative to clay and silt portions.

  • Concept URI token: sandy-loam

1.2.7.11.29 Sandy soil

  • Child of: soil

  • Soil containing sand.

  • Alternate labels: Light soil, Soil, sandy,

  • Concept URI token: sandy-soil

1.2.7.11.30 Silt loam

  • Child of: soil

  • A soil type with greater than 50% silt and lesser amounts of clay and sand.

  • Concept URI token: silt-loam

1.2.7.11.31 Silty clay loam

  • Child of: soil

  • A soil with relatively equal amounts of clay and silt with lesser amounts of sand.

  • Concept URI token: silty-clay-loam

1.2.7.11.32 Silty clay soil

  • Child of: soil

  • A soil with relatively equal amounts of clay and silt with lesser amounts of sand.

  • Concept URI token: silty-clay-soil

1.2.7.11.33 Silty soil

  • Child of: soil

  • A soil with a high proportion of silt.

  • Concept URI token: silty-soil

1.2.7.11.34 Sodosol

  • Child of: soil

  • Non-Kurosol soils with a clear or abrupt textural B horizon and in which the major part1 of the upper 0.2 m of the B2 horizon (or the major part of the entire B2 horizon if it is less than 0.2 m thick) is sodic and is not strongly subplastic. Australian Soil Classification - CSIRO.

  • Concept URI token: sodosol

1.2.7.11.35 Spodosol

  • Child of: soil

  • Also called podzol or podosol. This is a soil type commonly found in coniferous or boreal forests. The name comes from a russian term podzolistaya pochva or ‘under-ashed soil’) due to the experience in Russia of farmers ploughing up an apparent under-layer of ash when ploughing the soil for the first time. It must have spodic horizon within 2 m of soil surface and without andic properties; Usually have albic horizon; High in Fe, Al oxides and humus accumulation; Acidic soils;

  • Concept URI token: spodosol

1.2.7.11.36 Stony Soil

  • Child of: soil

  • Soil containing clasts of gravel size or larger.

  • Alternate labels: Soil, Stoney

  • Concept URI token: stony-soil

1.2.7.11.37 Tenosol

  • Child of: soil

  • All other soils that do not meet the Rudosol classification. Australian Soil Classification - CSIRO.

  • Concept URI token: tenosol

1.2.7.11.38 Ulitisol

  • Child of: soil

  • Must have argillic or kandic horizon; Low base saturation of <35% at 2 m depth or 75 cm below a fragipan; Common in subtropical regions; often known as red clay soils.

  • Concept URI token: ulitisol

1.2.7.11.39 Vertisol

  • Child of: soil

  • Usually mollic epipedon; High in shrinking and swelling clays; >30% clay to a depth of 50 cm; Deep cracks (called gilgai) form when soil dries; Form from parent material high in clay (e.g., shales, basins, exposed Bt horizons of old soils).

  • Concept URI token: vertisol

1.2.7.11.40 Vertosol

  • Child of: soil

  • Non-podosol soils that: a) Have a clay field texture or 35% or more clay throughout the solum except for thin, surface crusty horizons 0.03 m or less thick, and b) Unless too moist, have open cracks at some time in most years that are at least 5 mm wide and extend upward to the surface or to the base of any plough layer, peaty horizon, self-mulching horizon, or thin, surface crusty horizon, and c) At some depth in the solum, have slickensides and/or lenticular peds. Australian Soil Classification - CSIRO.

  • Concept URI token: vertosol

1.2.8 Non-specific rocks

  • Child of: rock

  • Rock that is not specific to a single category categories. ie a generalised rock type that may describe rocks belonging to different classifications e.g. igneous and sedimentary.

  • Concept URI token: unclassified-rock

1.2.8.1 Breccia

  • Child of: unclassified-rock

  • A coarse-grained clastic rock, composed of angular broken rock fragments held together by a mineral cement or in a fine-grained matrix; it differs from conglomerate in that the fragments have sharp edges and unworn corners. Breccia may originate as a result of talus accumulation, explosive igneous processes, collapse of rock material, or faulting.

  • Alternate labels: melange

  • Concept URI token: breccia

1.2.8.1.1 Agmatite

  • Child of: breccia migmatite

  • A migmatite with a breccia-like structure.

  • Concept URI token: agmatite

1.2.8.1.2 Brecciated granite

  • Child of: breccia granite

  • A granite that has been brecciated, usually as part of a fault or shear zone.

  • Concept URI token: brecciated-granite

1.2.8.1.3 Fault-breccia

  • Child of: breccia cataclasite

  • A medium-to-carse grained cataclasite containing >30% visible fragments.

  • Alternate labels: Cataclastic breccia, Coarse-grained cataclasite, Crush breccia, Fault Breccia, Milled breccia, Shear zone, breccia, fault,

  • Concept URI token: fault-breccia

1.2.8.1.3.1 Cohesive fault-breccia

  • Child of: cohesive-cataclasite fault-breccia

  • A fault-breccia showing cohesion.

  • Alternate labels: Mosaic breccia

  • Concept URI token: cohesive-fault-breccia

1.2.8.1.4 Hybrid igneous rock and intrusive breccia

  • Child of: breccia normal-crystalline-igneous-rock

  • Mixed rocks including xenoliths and and breccias formed where igneous rocks intrude, vein, metamorphose and assimilate preexisting igneous rocks and other rocks.

  • Concept URI token: hybrid-igneous-rock-and-intrusive-breccia

1.2.8.1.4.1 Intrusive breccia

  • Child of: hybrid-igneous-rock-and-intrusive-breccia

  • A breccia of intrusive rock. Intrusive rocks can become brecciated in appearance by multiple stages of intrusion, especially if fresh magma is intruded into partly consolidated or solidified magma.

  • Alternate labels: Gabbroic breccia, Granite breccia,

  • Concept URI token: intrusive-breccia

1.2.8.1.4.2 Peperite

  • Child of: hybrid-igneous-rock-and-intrusive-breccia

  • Most commonly used to refer to breccias, clastic rocks comprising both igneous and sedimentary components, which were generated by intrusive processes, or along the basal contacts of lava flows or hot volcaniclastic deposits with unconsolidated, typically wet, sediments (Skilling et al, 2002). It usually consists of highly irregular fragments of glassy igneous rock within sediments and/or the opposite. Formed essentially in situ by disintegration of magma intruding and mingling with typically wet sediments.

  • Alternate labels: Pepperite

  • Concept URI token: peperite

1.2.8.1.5 Hydrothermal breccia

  • Child of: breccia metasomatic-rock

  • Breccias comprising largely hydrothemal minerals, cementing clasts.

  • Alternate labels: breccia, hydrothermal, siliceous breccia,

  • Concept URI token: hydrothermal-breccia

1.2.8.1.6 Monomict impact breccia

  • Child of: breccia single-impact-impactite

  • Impact breccia from a single lithology target.

  • Concept URI token: monomict-impact-breccia

1.2.8.1.7 Ophicarbonate

  • Child of: breccia metacarbonate-rock

  • A rock consisting of serpentine and carbonate; the serpentine is commonly fragmented or brecciated, and veined and impregnated by the carbonate material (calcite, dolomite or magnesite). It forms by the serpentinisation of ultramafic rocks and their reaction with CO2-bearing solutions.

  • Concept URI token: ophicarbonate

1.2.8.1.7.1 Ophicalcite

  • Child of: ophicarbonate

  • Strictly an ophicarbonate where calcite is the predominant carbonate, but it has been traditionally used as a synonym of ophicarbonate. A recrystallised metamorphic rock composed of calcite and serpentine, commonly formed by dedolomitisation of a siliceous dolostone. Some ophicalcites are highly veined and brecciated and are associated with serpentinite.

  • Concept URI token: ophicalcite

1.2.8.1.7.2 Ophidolomite

  • Child of: ophicarbonate

  • A ophicarbonate where dolomite is the predominant carbonate.

  • Concept URI token: ophidolomite

1.2.8.1.7.3 Ophimagnesite

  • Child of: ophicarbonate

  • A ophicarbonate where magnesite is the predominant carbonate.

  • Concept URI token: ophimagnesite

1.2.8.1.8 Orthobreccia

  • Child of: breccia

  • A breccia where the gravel-size clasts are in contact with each other.

  • Alternate labels: Clast supported breccia

  • Concept URI token: orthobreccia

1.2.8.1.9 Parabreccia

  • Child of: breccia

  • A breccia where the gravel-size clasts are separated from each other by an abundant matrix.

  • Alternate labels: Matrix supported breccia

  • Concept URI token: parabreccia

1.2.8.1.10 Polymict impact breccia

  • Child of: breccia single-impact-impactite

  • Impact breccia from a complex lithology target.

  • Concept URI token: polymict-impact-breccia

1.2.8.1.10.1 Lithic impact breccia

  • Child of: polymict-impact-breccia

  • An impact breccia that contains shocked and unshocked clasts in a clastic matrix but lacks cogenetic melt particles.

  • Concept URI token: lithic-impact-breccia

1.2.8.1.10.2 Suevite

  • Child of: polymict-impact-breccia

  • An impact breccia that contains shocked and unshocked clasts in a clastic matrix along with cogenetic melt particles. Suevite is one of the diagnostic rock-types for large impact structures. It has been described from many of the larger impact structures identified on earth.

  • Concept URI token: suevite

1.2.8.1.11 Sedimentary breccia

  • Child of: breccia conglomerate

  • A gravel-grade clastic-sedimentary-rock with angular fragments.

  • Alternate labels: Flake Breccia, Siltstone/sandstone breccia, sandstone breccia, siltstone breccia,

  • Concept URI token: sedimentary-breccia

1.2.8.1.12 Shock lithified impact regolith breccia

  • Child of: breccia shock-lithified-impact-regolith

  • Consolidated clastic impact debris breccia.

  • Alternate labels: Shatter Breccia

  • Concept URI token: shock-lithified-impact-regolith-breccia

1.2.8.1.12.1 Lithic breccia

  • Child of: shock-lithified-impact-regolith-breccia

  • Consolidated clastic impact debris without matrix melt or melt particles.

  • Concept URI token: lithic-breccia

1.2.8.1.12.2 Regolith breccia

  • Child of: shock-lithified-impact-regolith-breccia

  • Consolidated clastic impact debris with matrix melt and melt particles.

  • Concept URI token: regolith-breccia

1.2.8.1.13 Tuffaceous-breccia

  • Child of: breccia tuffaceous-sedimentary-rock

  • A gravel-grade tuffaceous-rock with mostly angular clasts.

  • Concept URI token: tuffaceous-breccia

1.2.8.1.14 Volcanic breccia

  • Child of: breccia fragmentalovervolcaniclastic-igneous-rock-and-sediment

  • A general or field term applying to all coarse-grained rocks containing abundant (>10%) angular volcanic fragments.

  • Alternate labels: alloclastic breccia, lava breccia, trachyte breccia,

  • Concept URI token: volcanic-breccia

1.2.8.1.14.1 Agglomerate

  • Child of: pyroclastic-rock volcanic-breccia

  • A pyroclastic rock in which more than 75% of the pyroclastic fragments exceed 64mm and at least 50% of these are rounded.

  • Concept URI token: agglomerate

1.2.8.1.14.1.1 Agglutinate

  • Child of: agglomerate

  • A welded pyroclastic deposit or agglomerate where the ejecta (sintered vitric pyroclasts) were plastic when emplaced and are cemented together by thin skins of glass. Also spelled agglutinite.

  • Concept URI token: agglutinate

1.2.8.1.14.1.2 Pyroclastic-breccia

  • Child of: agglomerate

  • An agglomerate in which more than 75% of the pyroclastic fragments exceed 64mm and at least 50% of these are angular.

  • Alternate labels: Pyroclastic breccia

  • Concept URI token: pyroclastic-breccia

1.2.8.1.14.2 Ash-breccia

  • Child of: ash-breccia-bomb-or-block-tephra volcanic-breccia

  • A tephra where there is at least 25% of each of the main fragment size divisions (i.e. block/bomb, lapilli and ash.)

  • Concept URI token: ash-breccia

1.2.8.1.14.3 Tuff-breccia

  • Child of: pyroclastic-rock volcanic-breccia

  • A pyroclastic-rock where there is at least 25% of each of the main fragment size divisions (i.e. block/bomb, lapilli and ash.)

  • Alternate labels: Brecciated Tuff, Tuff breccia,

  • Concept URI token: tuff-breccia

1.2.8.1.15 Volcaniclastic-breccia

  • Child of: breccia volcaniclastic-sedimentary-rock

  • Volcaniclastic-sedimentary-rock consisting of between 10% and 25% by volume of pyroclastic fragments, average >2mm, with more than 50% angular.

  • Concept URI token: volcaniclastic-breccia

1.2.8.1.15.1 Basaltic-volcaniclastic-breccia

  • Child of: volcaniclastic-breccia

  • A volcaniclastic-breccia containing significant andesitic compositon clasts.

  • Concept URI token: basaltic-volcaniclastic-breccia

1.2.8.1.15.2 Pillowed-volcaniclastic-breccia

  • Child of: volcaniclastic-breccia

  • A volcaniclastic-breccia formed from pillow lavas spalling from a volcanic vent and being recemented.

  • Concept URI token: pillowed-volcaniclastic-breccia

1.2.8.1.15.3 Rhyolitic-volcaniclastic-breccia

  • Child of: volcaniclastic-breccia

  • A volcaniclastic-breccia containing significant rhyolitic compositon clasts.

  • Concept URI token: rhyolitic-volcaniclastic-breccia

1.2.8.1.15.4 Volcaniclastic-megabreccia

  • Child of: volcaniclastic-breccia

  • A volcaniclastic-breccia with fragments of rock in excess of 1m as conspicuous components.

  • Concept URI token: volcaniclastic-megabreccia

1.2.8.1.15.5 Volcaniclastic-mesobreccia

  • Child of: volcaniclastic-breccia

  • A volcaniclastic-breccia in the mesocratic ramge of M’ (35-65% dark minerals.)

  • Concept URI token: volcaniclastic-mesobreccia

1.2.8.2 Dimension Stone

  • Child of: unclassified-rock

  • A general term for quarried and cut building stone.

  • Alternate labels: Building Stone, Commercial Rock,

  • Concept URI token: dimension-stone

1.2.8.3 Glassy rock

  • Child of: unclassified-rock

  • Glassy igneous rocks not otherwise classifiedIgneous rock that contains greater than 50 percent massive glass.

  • Alternate labels: Glass

  • Concept URI token: glassy-rock

1.2.8.3.1 Contact metamorphic glassy rock

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-rock glassy-rock

  • Rocks heated to very high temperatures in a very short time followed by rapid cooling, forming vitreous or semivitreous materials.

  • Concept URI token: contact-metamorphic-glassy-rock

1.2.8.3.1.1 Buchite

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-glassy-rock

  • A compact, vesicular or slaggy metamorphic rock of any composition containing more than 20% vol. of glass, either produced by contact metamorphism in volcanic to subvolcanic settings or generated by combustion metamorphism.

  • Concept URI token: buchite

1.2.8.3.1.1.1 Clinker

  • Child of: buchite

  • Fused or partly fused coal ash, a byproduct of combustion. Characteristic features of clinkers is its resemblance to pavement brick (klinkaerd) and a ‘metallic’ sound when hit by a hammer. Clinkers are the most common rocks found in burning coal mining dumps and are usually red or pink, hard, having well preserved shaly texture. They are usually composed of quartz, partially/fully dehydrated clay minerals, and minor mullite. ref: ACSG, 2

  • Concept URI token: clinker

1.2.8.3.1.1.2 Combustion buchite

  • Child of: buchite

  • A buchite formed through combustion metamorphism.

  • Concept URI token: combustion-buchite

1.2.8.3.1.1.3 Contact buchite

  • Child of: buchite

  • A buchite formed through contact metamorphism.

  • Concept URI token: contact-buchite

1.2.8.3.1.1.4 Systil

  • Child of: contact-buchite

  • A dull, hard rock with a conchoidal to splintery fracture derived from contact metamorphism of claystone or marly sandstone by basalt. Also used as a synonym of basalt jasper.

  • Concept URI token: systil

1.2.8.3.1.2 Fritted-rock

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-glassy-rock

  • A compact, vesicular or slaggy metamorphic rock of any composition with a glass content ranging from a few percent up to a maximum of 20% vol., and either produced by contact metamorphism in volcanic to subvolcanic settings or generated by combustion metamorphism.

  • Concept URI token: fritted-rock

1.2.8.3.1.2.1 Combustion fritted-rock

  • Child of: fritted-rock

  • A fritted-rock formed through combustion metamorphism.

  • Concept URI token: combustion-fritted-rock

1.2.8.3.1.2.2 Contact fritted-rock

  • Child of: fritted-rock

  • A fritted-rock formed through contact metamorphism.

  • Concept URI token: contact-fritted-rock

1.2.8.3.1.3 Fulgurite

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-glassy-rock

  • Natural silica-rich glass formed by lightning striking and melting sands or bare rock (colour is therefore variable, depending on the chemical composition of these sands and rocks.) They form hollow tubes that are often irregular and branched. Originally described from Senne plateau, Gutersloh, Eastern Westphalia, North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany.

  • Concept URI token: fulgurite

1.2.8.3.1.4 Glassy hornfels

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-glassy-rock hornfels

  • A hornfels with a vitreous or subvitreous texture.

  • Concept URI token: glassy-hornfels

1.2.8.3.1.5 Parabasalt

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-glassy-rock

  • A type of pyrometamorphic rock derived from complete-to-near- complete melting and recrystallisation of sedimentary rocks.

  • Alternate labels: Paralava

  • Concept URI token: parabasalt

1.2.8.3.1.6 Pseudotachylite

  • Child of: cohesive-cataclasite contact-metamorphic-glassy-rock

  • A cohesive cataclasite in which fragments occur in a glassy groundmass produced by frictional melting.

  • Concept URI token: pseudotachylite

1.2.8.3.1.6.1 Brecciated pseudotachylite

  • Child of: pseudotachylite

  • A Pseudotachylite that has been brecciated.

  • Concept URI token: brecciated-pseudotachylite

1.2.8.3.1.7 Tektite

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-glassy-rock impact-melt-rock

  • A natural glass formed from a meteorite impact melting the local rock. Depending on the nature of the latter, the composition of tektites is variable.

  • Concept URI token: tektite

1.2.8.3.1.7.1 Australite

  • Child of: tektite

  • A tektite variety from the Australasian strewnfield. Dark, mostly black. The crater of this strewnfield has not be located, but is assumed to lie in Southeast Asia.

  • Concept URI token: australite

1.2.8.3.1.7.2 Bediasite

  • Child of: tektite

  • A black tektite variety from North American strewnfield (Chesapeake Bay impact crater), found in Texas, USA.

  • Concept URI token: bediasite

1.2.8.3.1.7.3 Bikolite

  • Child of: tektite

  • A name given to tektites from the Bikol area of the Philippines.

  • Concept URI token: bikolite

1.2.8.3.1.7.4 Billitonite

  • Child of: tektite

  • A tektite material found on Billiton Island, between Sumatra and Borneo. Compare indochinite.

  • Concept URI token: billitonite

1.2.8.3.1.7.5 Chinite

  • Child of: tektite

  • A black tektite variety found in Chinafrom the Australasian strewnfield.

  • Concept URI token: chinite

1.2.8.3.1.7.6 Darwin Glass

  • Child of: tektite

  • A variety of Tektite From Tasmania, Australia.

  • Concept URI token: darwin-glass

1.2.8.3.1.7.7 Georgiaite

  • Child of: tektite

  • A green tektite variety from North American strewnfield (Chesapeake Bay impact crater), found in Georgia, USA.

  • Concept URI token: georgiaite

1.2.8.3.1.7.8 Indochinite

  • Child of: tektite

  • A tektite variety from the Australasian strewnfield. Dark, mostly black. The crater of this strewnfield has not be located, but is assumed to lie in Southeast Asia.

  • Concept URI token: indochinite

1.2.8.3.1.7.9 Irghizite

  • Child of: tektite

  • Tektite from the Zhamanshin meteor crater in Kazakhstan (latitude: 48° 24’ North, longitude: 60° 58’ East).

  • Concept URI token: irghizite

1.2.8.3.1.7.10 Ivorite

  • Child of: tektite

  • A black tektite variety from the Ivory Coast strewnfield (Lake Bosumtwi Crater, Ghana). Found in the Cote d’Ivoire (Ivory Coast).NOTE: Some tectites from the large Australasian field are fraudulently sold in Ivory Coast as being Ivory Coast tektites (the latter are extremely rare).

  • Concept URI token: ivorite

1.2.8.3.1.7.11 Microtektite

  • Child of: tektite

  • Milimeter-size tektites.

  • Concept URI token: microtektite

1.2.8.3.1.7.12 Uruguaite

  • Child of: tektite

  • Black tektites from a new strewn field discovered in 2016 (Ferriare et al., 2017).

  • Concept URI token: uruguaite

1.2.8.3.1.7.13 Zhamanshinite

  • Child of: tektite

  • Tektites from the Zhamanshin meteor crater.

  • Concept URI token: zhamanshinite

1.2.8.3.2 Glassy igneous rock

  • Child of: glassy-rock igneous-rock

  • I. Glassy igneous rocks not otherwise classifiedii. Igneous rock that consists of greater than 80 percent massive glass.

  • Alternate labels: Volcanic Glass

  • Concept URI token: glassy-igneous-rock

1.2.8.3.2.1 Basaltic glass

  • Child of: glassy-igneous-rock

  • Glassy, fresh varieties of basalt, often contain microscopic crystals, or the interstital glass found in partly crystallised basalts.

  • Concept URI token: basaltic-glass

1.2.8.3.2.1.1 Hyaloclastite

  • Child of: basaltic-glass

  • A volcanic breccia composed almost entirely of basaltic glass.

  • Alternate labels: Hyaloclastite Breccia

  • Concept URI token: hyaloclastite

1.2.8.3.2.1.2 Pele’s hair

  • Child of: basaltic-glass

  • Threads or fibers of volcanic glass, usually basaltic. A natural spun glass formed by blowing-out during quiet fountaining of fluid lava, cascading lava falls, or turbulent flows, sometimes in association with Pele’s tear pyroclast. A single strand, with a diameter of less than 1/2 mm, may be as long as 2 m. Etymol: Pele, Hawaiian goddess of fire. Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: peles-hair

1.2.8.3.2.1.3 Pele’s tears

  • Child of: basaltic-glass

  • Tear-like drops of volcanic glass, usually basaltic

  • Concept URI token: peles-tears

1.2.8.3.2.1.4 Scoria

  • Child of: basaltic-glass pyroclastic-rock

  • Highly vesicular, basaltic glass. Bomb-size pyroclast that is irregular in form and generally very vesicular. In less restricted usage, a vesicular cindery crust on the surface of andesitic or basaltic lava, the vesicular nature of which is due to the escape of volcanic gases before solidification; it is usually heavier, darker, and more crystalline than pumice. The adj. form, scoriaceous, is usually applied to pyroclastic ejecta. Cinder is sometimes used synonymously.

  • Concept URI token: scoria

1.2.8.3.2.1.5 Sideromelane

  • Child of: basaltic-glass

  • The extremely common yellow or brown translucent glass in many basalts formed during submarine eruption or any magma/water interaction. Commonly occurring in palagonite tuff, for which it is characteristic. The term may refer to an interstitial glass or a rock composed mostly of such glass.

  • Concept URI token: sideromelane

1.2.8.3.2.1.6 Tachylite

  • Child of: basaltic-glass

  • Black or dark brown, opaque basaltic glass. The term may refer to an interstitial glass or a rock composed mostly of such glass.

  • Concept URI token: tachylite

1.2.8.3.2.2 Perlite

  • Child of: glassy-igneous-rock

  • An amorphous volcanic glass with a relatively high water content, frequently formed by the hydration of obsidian.

  • Concept URI token: perlite

1.2.8.3.2.3 Silicic volcanic glass

  • Child of: glassy-igneous-rock

  • Silica-rich volcanic glass

  • Concept URI token: silicic-volcanic-glass

1.2.8.3.2.3.1 Obsidian

  • Child of: silicic-volcanic-glass

  • Fresh igneous rocks with a high silica content and conchoidal fracture. Volcanic glass - a rock rather than a mineral, it is a mixture of cryptocrystalline grains of silica minerals in a glass-like suspension, a super-cooled liquid.

  • Alternate labels: Bergmahogany, Black Lava Glass, Hyalopsite, Isophyre,

  • Concept URI token: obsidian

1.2.8.3.2.3.2 Apache Tears

  • Child of: obsidian

  • ‘Apache tears’ originate from siliceous lava flows, lava domes or ash-flow tuffs, often in close association with or embedded in, gray perlite. The spherules occur as cores within perlite masses that typically exhibit concentrically curved, onion-skin fractures. Their formation is apparently related to differential cooling and differing alkali and water contents.

  • Concept URI token: apache-tears

1.2.8.3.2.3.3 Fire Obsidian

  • Child of: obsidian

  • An iridescent variety of obsidian. Its ‘fire’ is caused by thin layers of microcrystals of magnetite (which are approximately the thickness of a wavelength of light). The colour of Rainbow Obsidian occurs from a much thicker volume of the specimen (Nadin, 2007).

  • Concept URI token: fire-obsidian

1.2.8.3.2.3.4 Macusanite

  • Child of: obsidian

  • A natural glass of composition similar to some granite pegmatites. Most typically found as pale yellow-green transparent alluvial pebbles. The glass usually has abundant well developed micro crystals floating in it, including the rare quartz-like mineral Virgilite for which this is the type locality.

  • Alternate labels: Macusani glass

  • Concept URI token: macusanite

1.2.8.3.2.3.5 Mahogany Obsidian

  • Child of: obsidian

  • A mahogany coloured variety of Obsidian

  • Concept URI token: mahogany-obsidian

1.2.8.3.2.3.6 Marekanite

  • Child of: obsidian

  • Obsidian that occurs as rounded to subangular bodies, usually less than 2 inches (5.1 cm) in diameter and having indented surfaces. These bodies occur in masses of perlite and are of special interest because of their low water content as compared with the surrounding perlite. The name is from the Marekanka River, Okhotsk, Siberia, Russia. Marekanite (obsidian balls) have also been found at Cerro Tijerina, central Nicaragua and appear identical to apache tears. Compare with apache tears.

  • Concept URI token: marekanite

1.2.8.3.2.3.7 Rainbow Obsidian

  • Child of: obsidian

  • Obsidian with multicolored iridescence caused by inclusions of magnetite nanoparticles (Nadin, 2007).

  • Concept URI token: rainbow-obsidian

1.2.8.3.2.3.8 Sheen Obsidian

  • Child of: obsidian

  • A variety of obsidian exhibiting a golden sheen effect.

  • Concept URI token: sheen-obsidian

1.2.8.3.2.3.9 Snowflake Obsidian

  • Child of: obsidian

  • A natural volcanic glass containing white ‘snowflake’ crystal patterns of the mineral cristobalite, originated due to partial crystallisation of the glass.

  • Concept URI token: snowflake-obsidian

1.2.8.3.2.3.10 Stigmite

  • Child of: obsidian

  • An obsolete name for a porphyritic variety of pitchstone or obsidian.

  • Concept URI token: stigmite

1.2.8.3.2.3.11 Pitchstone

  • Child of: silicic-volcanic-glass

  • Glassy silicic igneous rocks lacking a conchoidal fracture. A dark, resinous volcanic glass.

  • Concept URI token: pitchstone

1.2.8.3.2.3.12 Pumice

  • Child of: silicic-volcanic-glass

  • Glassy, highly vesicular, mostly silicic igneous rocks.

  • Alternate labels: Bimsstein, Bymsftein, Bynftein, Spumulite,

  • Concept URI token: pumice

1.2.8.3.2.3.13 Reticulite

  • Child of: pumice

  • An extremely vesiculated variety of pumice consisting of a broken network of glass threads which join a series of points forming a polyhedral space lattice. It is formed from pumice by the collapse of the walls of adjacent vesicles and the retraction of the liquid into threads which form the perimeters of the former polygonal faces. The threads are usually of triangular cross section, indicating chilling, before rounding could take place. Such rock has generally been known by Dana’s name, thread-lace scoria.

  • Concept URI token: reticulite

1.2.8.4 Quartzite

  • Child of: unclassified-rock

  • Usually a regionally metamorphosed quartz-sandstone, but the term is commonly also used as a field term for orthoquartzite (a sedimentary rock), secondary quartzite and paraquartzite.

  • Concept URI token: quartzite

1.2.8.4.1 Belocherite

  • Child of: quartzite

  • A Precambrian quartzite from the Central and Southern Urals, Russia.

  • Concept URI token: belocherite

1.2.8.4.2 Grunerite quartzite

  • Child of: quartzite

  • A quartzite containing grunerite.

  • Concept URI token: grunerite-quartzite

1.2.8.4.3 Itacolumite

  • Child of: quartzite sandstone

  • A micaceous sandstone or a schistose quartzite that contains interstitial, loosely interlocking grains of mica, chlorite, and talc; exhibits flexibility when split into thin slabs. Type locality is Itacolumi Mountain in Minas Gerais, Brazil. Synonym of: flexible sandstone, articulite Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: itacolumite

1.2.8.4.3.1 Flexible sandstone

  • Child of: itacolumite

  • A fine-grained, thin-layered variety of itacolumite. Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: flexible-sandstone

1.2.8.4.4 Metaquartz-sandstone

  • Child of: metasilicate-sandstone quartzite

  • A metamorphosed quartz-sandstone.

  • Concept URI token: metaquartz-sandstone

1.2.8.4.4.1 Meta-arkose

  • Child of: metaquartz-sandstone

  • A metamorphosed arkose. Arkose that has been welded or recrystallised by metamorphism so that it resembles a granite or a granitized sediment. Compare with: recomposed granite. Ref: AGI

  • Concept URI token: meta-arkose

1.2.8.4.4.1.1 Arkose quartzite

  • Child of: meta-arkose

  • Quartzitic arkose and/or arkosic quartzite

  • Concept URI token: arkose-quartzite

1.2.8.4.4.2 Meta-orthoquartzite

  • Child of: metaquartz-sandstone

  • A metamorphosed orthoquartzite.

  • Concept URI token: meta-orthoquartzite

1.2.8.4.5 Orthoquartzite

  • Child of: quartzite silicate-sandstone

  • An indurated silicate-sandstone that is made up almost exclusively of quartz sand (with or without chert), that is relatively free of or lacks a fine-grained matrix; a hard but unmetamorphosed ‘pure quartz sandstone’, derived by secondary silicification; a quartzite of sedimentary origin, or a pure quartz sandstone. Typically a sandstone comprising more than 90% to 95% detrital quartz and chert grains that are well-sorted, well-rounded, and cemented primarily with secondary quartz (sometimes with carbonate).

  • Concept URI token: orthoquartzite

1.2.8.4.6 Paraquartzite

  • Child of: contact-metamorphic-rock quartzite

  • A quartzite formed by contact metamorphism.

  • Concept URI token: paraquartzite

1.2.8.4.7 Secondary-quartzite

  • Child of: metasomatic-rock quartzite

  • A medium to low-temperature metasomatic rock mainly composed of quartz with subsidiary high-alumina minerals, such as pyrophyllite, diaspore, alunite and kaolinite. Common accessories include fluorite, dumortierite and lazulite. Secondary-quartzites are associated with volcanic and subvolcanic rocks of rhyolitic to andesitic composition. Normally they form as replacements of acid igneous rocks and more rarely of sedimentary rocks. They may host mineral deposits of alunite, pyrophyllite, Au, Cu, Sb and Hg.

  • Concept URI token: secondary-quartzite

1.2.8.5 tectonite

  • Child of: unclassified-rock

  • In modern usage tectonites are metamorphic or tectonically deformed rocks whose fabric reflects the history of their deformation, or rocks with a penetrative fabric that clearly displays coordinated geometric features that indicate continuous solid (ductile) flow during formation.

  • Concept URI token: tectonite

1.2.9 Wood

  • Child of: rock

  • Wood is a porous and fibrous structural tissue found in the stems and roots of trees and other woody plants.

  • Concept URI token: wood

1.2.9.1 Charcoal

  • Child of: wood

  • Formula:C Colour:black Crystal System:Amorphous Not a true mineral species, but rather a term used in old geological literature for carbon produced by the incomplete burning (pyrolysis) of trees and other vegetation in lava and pyroclastic flows (especially in Japan). Occasionally also used (especially in the USA) for carbonized vegetable matter in sedimentary rocks, where it may be associated with lignite or silicified wood.

  • Alternate labels: Burnt Wood/Charcoal, Burnt wood,

  • Concept URI token: charcoal

1.2.9.2 Petrified Wood

  • Child of: wood

  • A type of fossil wood where the original organic material has been replaced - usually by chalcedony or agate (cryptocrystalline quartz), but sometimes by opal, coal, pyrite, calcite and others. Colors red and green are usually caused by iron, but a few of the more brightly colored green woods may be colored by chromium.

  • Alternate labels: Agatised wood, Agatized Wood, Fossil Wood,

  • Concept URI token: petrified-wood
